[White "Introduction"]
[Black "Introduction"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6
{ Hello everyone! Thank you for showing interest in this course on the Ruy Lopez Exchange Variation aka the RLE! Before we get started, let me say a few words about myself. My name is Jan Werle, I'm from the Netherlands, and I became a grandmaster in 2006. I reached my peak rating of 2607 in 2009, around the time when I won the European Championship in Liverpool. When Chessable first approached me to do a course about the RLE, I wasn't sure whether I would get excited by such a positional and solid line. However, after delving into the theory and examining the positions, I found that there are lots of entertaining lines and a lot of unexplored territory. After I picked up splendid moves and plans from the games of unconventional elite players like Bobby Fischer, Garry Kasparov and Shakhriyar Mamedyarov, I was hooked. Furthermore, strong engines like Leela Lc0 and Stockfish found many novelties and creative ideas to make Black's life highly unpleasant. However, at the root of this is our convenient starting point that we obtain on move four 4. Bxc6 and due to the damaged pawn structure of Black our play is mostly risk-free. }
3. Bb5
{ This is the Ruy Lopez aka the Spanish Opening. Black has a wide range of responses he can choose from, amongst others besides the main move 3...a6. First, there is 3...Nf6 - the Berlin Defense, which is the second most popular line. Former world champion Vladimir Kramnik boosted its popularity by beating Garry Kasparov in the world championships in London @@StartBracket@@2000@@EndBracket@@ with this tenacious line. The Berlin Defense will be covered in Volume 2 of this series, whereas the other main Black's defenses, amongst others: - 3...Nge7 - the Cozio Defense; - 3...g6 - the Smyslov Defense; - 3...Nd4 - the Bird Defense; -3...d6 - the Steinitz Defense; - 3...f5 - the Schliemann Defense, and; - 3...Bc5 - the Classical Defense will be covered in Volume 3. This will give you a complete repertoire in the Spanish Opening. }
3... a6
{ This is the so-called 'Morphy Defense'. There is instant tension on the board, as our opponent challenges our bishop to make up its mind. The most common move is 4.Ba4, after which the opening will branch into countless variations like the Chigorin, Breyer, Ragozin and Marshall. Black will find his move 3...a6 useful in all of these variations, as he can chase the bishop from a4 with tempo, unpinning himself in the process while also taking space on the queenside. However, completely different positions occur after our move in this course: 4. Bxc6, aka the Ruy Lopez: Exchange Variation. At the same time, uncompromising and attacking players, such as the world champions Bobby Fischer and Garry Kasparov, as well as the current elite player Shakhriyar Mamedyarov from time to time let off steam in this very entertaining line. }
4. Bxc6
{ Black can take back with either the b-pawn or d-pawn, but only the last move has gained popularity as after  4...bxc6  he faces a hard time completing his development - see Chapter 1.   4.Ba4  The main concept of Morphy's Defense materializes when White falls for the 'Noah's Ark Trap'. This happened in 1929 when Steiner got ambushed in his game against Capablanca, but the current elite grandmaster Nepomniachtchi was similarly caught in it in a recent online game.  4...d6  5.d4  b5  6.Bb3  exd4  7.Nxd4  Nxd4  8.Qxd4  c5!  All of a sudden, White's bishop is caught after c5-c4.  9.Qd5  threatening Qxf7+  Be6  10.Qc6+  The check will not help Black.  10...Bd7  11.Qd5  c4  0-1 @@StartBracket@@55@@EndBracket@@ Nepomniachtchi,I 2784-Demchenko,A 2641 chess.com INT 2020 }
4... dxc6
{ The contours of the RLE position are there. White gave up his light-squared bishop and the bishop pair, leaving Black with doubled c-pawns and behind in development. White has many options here. Lasker's main choice was 5. d4, but 5. d3 and 5. Nc3 have also been tried, remaining flexible and not committing the king to g1 yet. }
5. O-O
{ The most ambitious move! White stays flexible, keeping open the options of: 1. d3 or d4, 2. whether the knight should be moved to d2, c3 or a3. The American world-class grandmaster Robert Byrne named 5.O-O is after the Dutch IM John Barendregt, who played this move a couple of times in the 60's. White has already castled while Black's pieces are all on the back rank. Moreover, Black must make an important choice as to how to protect his central pawn since White has renewed the threat of Nxe5 after castling. }
5... f6
{ This move will be covered in the last chapter of the theoretical section, Chapter 12. From a historical perspective, this is the main move. Besides one game in a simultaneous exhibition, Fischer faced this move in all of his RLE games! I am going to call it ' The Classical Variation'. The more aggressive-looking line 5...Bg4 has a similarly rich history and can be considered the second main line. We're going to call it 'The Pin Variation', a name coined by another GM from the small town of Woerden: Erwin l'Ami. Especially 6. h3 h5!? is often seen in practice, but 6...Bh5 and 6...Bxf3 have also gained some popularity. Please note that most of Black's main moves protect the pawn on e5 directly or indirectly, for instance, 5...f6, 5...Bg4, 5...Qd6, 5...Qf6, 5...Qe7 and 5... Bd6. The only moves that don't are 5...Be6, 5...Be7 and 5...Ne7. These 'odd ducks' block the e-file and enable Black to regain his pawn back with 6...Qd4.   In naming the variations I wanted to pay homage to Mackenzie, Smyslov, Bronstein, and Morozevich, in naming the chapters after them. Here's an overview of what's to come:    •  5...Be6  See Chapter 2,   •  5...Ne7  See Chapter 3,   •  5...Be7  See Chapter 4,   •  5...Qe7  See Chapter 5: The Smyslov Variation,   •  5...Qf6  See Chapter 6: The Morozevich Variation,   •  5...Qd6  See Chapter 7: The Bronstein Variation,   •  5...Bd6  See Chapter 8: The Mackenzie Variation.   5...Bg4  6.h3  The Pin Variation:   •  6...Bh5  See Chapter 9: Pin Variation I,   •  6...Bxf3  See Chapter 10: Pin Variation II,   •  6...h5  See Chapter 11: Pin Variation III. }
6. d4
{ The quick pawn push to d4 grabs our opponent immediately by the throat and is most dangerous for Black. }
6... exd4 7. Nxd4 c5
{ In order to get acquainted with the aspects of the position, we should be aware of the opponent's plans. This quick preview of the major line of 5...f6 reveals this. }
8. Nb3 Qxd1 9. Rxd1
{ Black intends to swap queens and hopes to rely on his bishop pair. } 9... Bd7
{ Black wants to castle long, so he blocks the d-file with his bishop. } 10.
Bf4
{ The rest of this old game of Barendregt from 1960 gives you a quick peek into where the sore points in Black's position lie. Please enjoy the game and good luck with your training! }
10... O-O-O 11. Nc3 Re8 12. Nd5 Bc6 13. Nxc7 Rxe4 14. f3
{ White's trickery box is to be revealed. Here are other very promising moves, but - fortunately - in this case, the strongest one is the most beautiful as well. }
14... Re2
{ After  14...Rxf4  15.Ne6  Black is lost because of the mating threat on  d8  . }
15. Na8 { White is threatening a mate on b6. } 15... b5
{ Remarkably, this is the only move that keeps Black in the game. He vacates the square for the king, avoiding mate after Nb6. }
16. Nb6+ Kb7 17. Nd7
{ Black couldn't keep the gates closed. The Black king has got enemies on all sides, e.g. Na5 or Nxc5, Nxf8, and a rook invasion along the d-file are all threatened. }
17... Bxd7 18. Rxd7+
{ The White army is marching forward. It seems that the White pieces are unstoppable. }
18... Kc6 19. Rc7+ Kb6 20. Rc8 Nh6 21. Rb8+
{ Black resigned, as after  21...Kc6  22.Rd1  White threatens mate with  Na5  .  Barendregt,J-Sliwa,B Marianske Lazne 1961: 1-0  (21)  . }
*

