[White "Introduction"]
[Black "Endgame Strategy #1: Pawn Majority Advantage"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "4k3/ppp2ppp/2p5/8/4P3/8/PPP2PPP/4K3 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ This is the basic pawn structure of the Ruy Lopez Exchange. We can consider this structure as the skeleton of the entire line arising after 4.Bxc6 bxc6. In many lines, sooner or later, White will create a 4 vs 3 pawn majority on the kingside after d2 to d4, exd4, Qxd4 or Nxd4. We can base our planning on our pawn majority which is our main strength. In the following introductory 'Endgame and Middlegame Strategy' examples, I try to shed some preliminary light on plans which we will repeatedly see in the upcoming theoretical lines. }
1. -- *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Introduction"]
[Black "Endgame Strategy #2: Winning the Pawn Endgame"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "8/2p2p2/ppp1kp1p/7P/3KPPP1/P7/1PP5/8 w - - 0 34"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ White's king is ruling on the strong central square d4. However, there is not yet an entrance square in Black's position and Black wants to push our king back by means of c6-c5+. }
34. b4
{ White fixes the Black pawn majority: c6-c5+ is no longer possible. Black is out of moves and is forced to move his king backwards. }
34... Ke7 35. e5 { Without hesitation, White grabs the space given by Black. }
35... Ke6 36. exf6
{ Simplifying the position by exchanging Black's pawns. The remaining kingside pawns will weigh more heavily. }
36... Kxf6
{ Let's take a moment to look deeper at this position. Did White make progress here with the exchange of pawns? Actually, yes, he did. The 3 vs 2 majority prevails over the 4 vs 3 pawn majority, as the breakthrough or creation of a passed pawn is likelier here. On top of that, the White king has more space @@StartBracket@@e.g. via e4@@EndBracket@@ to find a passage to Black's kingside. }
37. Ke4
{ White is using the idea of 'Zugzwang'. Black cannot move his pawn majority on the queenside as it's fixed. For instance, }
37... Kg7
{ 37...b5  renounces the c5-square.  38.Kd4 !  The king is grateful to find an entrance on c5.  38...Ke6  The Black king is moving along with White's king in order to protect the c6-pawn.  39.Kc5  Hitting the pawn on c6. The lack of mobility of Black's majority becomes unequivocally visible here.  39...Kd7  So the Black king is tied to the defense of the queenside pawns. Now White exploits this with a breakthrough on the other wing.  40.g5 !  White is winning. }
38. Kf5
{ Sad but true for the Black player, White is gaining more and more ground. }
38... c5 39. bxc5 bxc5 40. c4
{ This move is not necessary for conducting the winning plan, but this sadistic move, fastening Black to the max, is part of our key endgame strategy. }
40... a5 41. a4 Kh7
{ Black's king is compelled to retreat.  41...c6  leaving the d6-square unprotected, inviting an unwelcome guest.  42.Ke5  The king is going to eat them all, poor souls. }
42. Kf6 Kg8 43. g5
{ Black is totally helpless against White's overwhelming initiative on the kingside. White's footsoldiers are marching forward and there is no way that they can be stopped. }
43... hxg5 44. fxg5 c6 45. h6 Kh7 46. Kxf7 Kh8 47. h7 Kxh7 48. g6+ Kh8 49. g7+
Kh7 50. g8=Q+ Kh6 51. Qg6#
{ Nayak, R-Biswa,PR Osidha-ch 60th Balasore @@StartBracket@@1@@EndBracket@@ 01.10.2019. An instructive game which should keep us faith in the resulting ending from the Ruy Lopez Exchange variation! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Introduction"]
[Black "Endgame Strategy #3 vs. Winning the Knight Ending"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "8/1pp1kpp1/p1p1n2p/4P3/7P/4K1P1/PPP1NP2/8 w - - 0 29"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ Let's find a sound plan in this ending arising from the Ruy Lopez Exchange  (RLE)  . Are you with me? }
29. Nd4
{ The superior pawn advantage comes unequivocally to the fore in the pawn ending.  29.h5 !?  was a satisfactory alternative gaining ground on the kingside, but why not reap the fruits when the opportunity occurs? }
29... Nxd4 30. Kxd4 Ke6
{ Black would like to move his king to f5, in order to block White's pawns and in line with this, stop them from advancing. }
31. Ke4
{ White will follow up with f4-f5.   31.h5  Kf5  White should watch out here not to get in zugzwang: in that case he should move his king, losing the e5-pawn. }
31... f6
{ 31...c5  32.f4  threatening f5+, when the e- and f-pawn will eventually be converted into a single passed pawn.  32...g6  White is winning after g4 and f5+. On the contrary, White is having problems when he plays c4.  33.c4 ??  h5 !  Now Black is fixing the White pawn majority.. Don't forget this in your upcoming RLE-endings: never let your majority be fixed!  34.Kf3  Kf5  White should start all over again here, regaining ground on the Black king who settled on the excellent outpost on f5. }
32. exf6
{ Like in the previous RLE-endgame, we benefit from the shape-shifting pawn structure. Our 3 vs 2 - in relation to 4 vs 3 - gives us more chances to create a passed pawn and allows our king more manoeuvring space on the kingside @@StartBracket@@e.g. squares e5, f5 etc.@@EndBracket@@. }
32... Kxf6 33. g4 { There is nothing what White's pawns can stop now. } 33...
g6 34. f4 h5 35. gxh5 gxh5 36. c4
{ Before White undertakes action on the kingside, he provides himself with the convenient thought that Black's pawn majority can not move. }
36... c5 37. b3 a5 38. f5
{ Using the idea of Zugzwang. Black's king is compelled to retreat. } 38... Kf7
39. Ke5 Ke7 40. f6+ Kf7 41. Kf5 { Once again, Black should withdraw. } 41... b6
42. Kg5 c6 43. Kf5 a4 44. Kg5 b5
{ A final convulsion from Black's pawns. The thing is that he can never create a passed pawn due to the fixed doubled pawns on c5 and c6. }
45. Kf5 a3 46. Kg5 b4 47. Kf5
{ Black resigned in the game Prins, L - Stalda, G, Venice 1949, @@StartBracket@@1-0@@EndBracket@@. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Introduction"]
[Black "Endgame Strategy #4 vs. Winning the Rook Ending"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "2k4r/2pr1pp1/ppp2np1/4p3/4P3/P1KPBP1P/1PP3P1/3R3R w - - 0 17"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ We witness the model game in the Ruy Lopez Exchange  (RLE)   between the specialist GM Solak, and Cubas, played in Rio Janeiro  (2000)  . Can you find a promising plan for White? }
17. b4
{ Meanwhile, after studying the previous introductory examples of 'Endgame Strategy', we are acquainted with this move fixing Black's pawn majority. Hereafter, Black can forget about getting his queenside pawns roll forward, for example by means of c6-c5. }
17... Kb7 18. d4
{ One of the experts of this line knew at a young age already that White's chances lie in the far ending. }
18... Rhd8 19. Rd2
{ The start of the winning plan. White doubles his rooks, pushing for the mass exchange of pieces. }
19... exd4+
{ What else, White also menaced to take on e5 now that the d-pawn was no longer pinned. }
20. Rxd4 Nh5 21. Rhd1 { We don't mind swapping all of the rooks. } 21... Rxd4
22. Rxd4 Rd6
{ Black is not intending to lose without a fight and avoids the situation with all rooks off the board. }
23. Rd3
{ 23.Rxd6 ?!  can't be recommended since after  23...cxd6  Black's weak doubled pawns and problems have vanished as snow in the sun. White can no longer capitalize on his kingside majority. }
23... Ng3 24. Kd2
{ Solak invites his opponent for a rook ending, in which he has the better odds because of his better pawns. }
24... Nf1+ 25. Ke2 Nxe3 26. Kxe3
{ This ending is not at all a picnic for Black. He is going to suffer due to his doubled c-pawns and immobile queenside majority. Especially now that there is so limited material on the board, this weakness can no longer be concealed. }
26... Kc8 { This is the real mistake, allowing White's superb retort. } 27. e5
{ In the arising pawn ending, Black's chances on half a point are quickly reduced. }
27... Rxd3+
{ Black has fallen in the trick with the eyes wide open. Nonetheless, there is not much that he can do. For example,   27...Rd5  28.Ke4 !  threatening to win a pawn, Black is forced to enter the pawn ending after all.   27...Re6  Now the king on c8 is cut off along the d-file.  28.Ke4  White will gradually move his pawns forward. }
28. Kxd3 { White has an easy plan at his disposal, moving the pawns forward. }
28... g5 { Using all of his resources, Black attempts to stop White's pawns. }
29. Ke4
{ When the king enters f5, hitting g5, it would mean the end of the game. }
29... g6 30. f4 { The time is ripe to run with the pawns! } 30... gxf4 31. Kxf4
Kd7 32. h4 { Of course, why don't we use our trump if we can? } 32... Ke6 33.
g4 { White is intending to create a far passed h-pawn. } 33... f6
{ 33...c5  a desperate attempt to create something out of his pawn majority. The thing is that the doubled pawns don't sort any serious danger as they are unwieldy.  34.bxc5  bxc5  35.h5  gxh5  36.gxh5 }
34. exf6 Kxf6
{ White's kingside strategy unfolds like the transformation of water into wine: his promising 4 vs 3 majority has been turned into an even more promising 3 vs 2, and then - the best is yet to come - into a 2 vs 1 majority! }
35. c4
{ Black realised that he is out of moves, not that his queenside pawns are fastened.   35.h5  would deploy another well known plan in the pawn ending: White's far passed pawn lures the hostile king to the h-file, rolling out the carpet for the ravenous White king towards the tasty, unprotected queenside pawns.  35...gxh5  36.gxh5  Kg7  37.Kf5  The predatory White king is on its way to the abandoned c-pawns.  37...Kh6  38.Ke6  Kxh5  39.Kd7  c5  40.bxc5  bxc5  41.Kxc7  Kg5  42.Kb6  Black's king is just too far away from the fray. Time to resign. Solak,D-Cubas, 2000, WchT U20 3rd, @@StartBracket@@1-0@@EndBracket@@. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Introduction"]
[Black "Endgame Strategy #5: Solak, Dragan vs. Nikolov, Sasho"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "3r4/2p4P/pp2Kbk1/2pP2p1/2P5/P3B3/1P6/7R w - - 0 35"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ This position arising from the Ruy Lopez Exchange  (RLE)   is another fine example of how White can convert his pawn majority. Here he obtained a far passed h-pawn deflecting Black's pieces. And more important, as so often goes in the RLE, the White king is the piece that decides for 'us' the game. }
35. Rh6+
{ Though White is forced to play it, it doesn't call into question the beauty of this move  35.Rh2 ??  can't be recommended, due to  35...Rd6 }
35... Kxh6 36. Kxf6 Rf8+ 37. Ke7 Rh8 38. Kf6
{ One may wonder: how is Black going to convert his material advantage into a full point here? In reality, Black must fight his way off in order to survive. }
38... Rxh7
{ An exquisite defense was  38...Kxh7 !  running along g8, f8 to e8 to the aid of the pawns.  39.Bxg5  Kg8  40.Bf4  Rh7  41.Ke6  Kf8  due to the approaching king, Black is saved.   Another defense was:  38...Rf8+  39.Ke7  Rh8  and would be sufficient for a draw as well, now that Black doesn't give up on his g5-pawn. }
39. Bxg5+ Kh5
{ White could go here for Bf4 and Bxc7, entering a drawn ending. However, Solak tries to test his opponent one more time. }
40. Kf5 a5
{ And not without success! You may not say so beforehand, but this is losing while Black is a full exchange up!  40...b5 !  gaining counterplay, would be much stronger. }
41. a4 Rg7 42. Bd8
{ After  42.Bf6  Rh7  43.Be5  the Black king can't get closer to the queenside, and White intends again to sac the bishop on c7 to let the d-pawn run. }
42... Rd7
{ Black cannot activate the rook as all the pawns will be taken off the board as dropping like flies. }
43. Bf6 Rf7
{ Black's king is stuck on the edge of the board. He should watch out he is not tipping over. Surprisingly,  43...Rh7  44.b3  is winning as well  44...Kh6  45.Ke6  Kg6  46.Be5 }
44. Ke6
{ The game unfolds in a dramatic course of events. Even with an exchange down, White is winning here because of his strong king and bishop. }
44... Kg6 45. Be5
{ Aiming for the sacrifice Bxc7, after which the d-pawn has free passage. }
45... Rh7 46. b3
{ 46.Bxc7  Would have been winning as well, for instance  46...Rxc7  47.d6  Rc8  48.d7  Rh8  49.Ke7  The thing is that Black's king is too far off from the queenside.  49...Kf5  50.d8=Q  Rxd8  51.Kxd8  When White as first reaches the pawns. But this doesn't spoil anything. After the text move Black cannot move and Bxc7 is about to come. In other words: Black is a sitting duck here. }
