[White "Introduction"]
[Black "Endgame Strategy #6: Adorjan, Andras vs. Nicevski, Risto"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "8/2p3p1/2p5/p1k4p/PpP4P/1PbK2P1/5P2/5N2 w - - 0 37"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ Black couldn't do anything with his doubled pawns: they are all stuck on the queenside. }
37. g4
{ White is using the pawn majority optimally in his favor. Time to create a passer! }
37... hxg4 38. Ne3 { From 3 vs 2, it turned into a 2 vs 1 pawn majority. }
38... g3
{ When Black walks to the center with  38...Kd6  39.Ke4  g6  40.Nxg4  Ke6  41.f4  Bb2  42.c5  Bc3  43.Ne3  the a5-pawn can't be saved any longer. }
39. fxg3 Be1
{ Black cant' save the game with  39...Kd6  40.c5+  Kxc5  41.h5  Kd6  42.Nc4+  as White obtains another wing passer. }
40. Nf5 g6
{ White can encounter  40...Bc3  with  41.h5!  fixing the g7-pawn.  Bf6  42.g4  Be5  43.g5  when White is winning. }
41. Ne7 Kd6 42. Nxg6 *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Introduction"]
[Black "Middlegame Strategy #1: Stellwagen, Daniel vs. Werle, Jan"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r3r1k1/1ppbbqpp/p1p1np2/5N2/1P2P3/1Q6/PBPN1PPP/4RRK1 w - - 0 18"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ The following game was played in the final round of the Dutch Championships in 2005. It still is giving me the shivers, as the gradually expanded overwhelming positional advantage by White made me chanceless the entire game. Now showing you the typical middlegame plans of RLE with White - and so with reversed colours - gives me much more joy! }
18. e5
{ White exploits his pawn majority to the bone, by opening the diagonal for his bishop. }
18... fxe5 19. Nxe7+ Rxe7 20. Rxe5
{ Considering the colour of the bishops, White is a piece up on the black squares, Black on the light squares. However, Black's bishop is of no use as it has no targets on the light squares, the White king is securely protected by his 3 pawns. On the contrary, White's bishop is firing along the long diagonal on g7 - a clear target of attack. }
20... Rae8 21. Rfe1 Rf8 22. Nf3 Ree8 23. R5e2
{ The pressure on Black is massive. Black is missing his 3rd kingside pawn excessively and White's control over e5 is giving him a large advantage. }
23... Qf5 24. h3 Kh8 25. Qc3 Qf6 26. Qd2
{ Showing true understanding of the characteristics of the position. Of course, White was slightly better in the ending after Qxf6, gxf6, but keeping the heavy pieces on the board provides him with superior pieces pointed at White's king, and so, an irresistible attack!   26.Qxf6 ?  gxf6  27.Nd2  Kg7  Black has chances to hold the ending, though it won't be a picnic. }
26... Qe7 27. Nd4 Qf7 28. Nxe6
{ An exclamation mark for my opponent's understanding, aiming for a position in which the contrast between the bishops couldn't be any stronger.   28.Nf5 !  would even be stronger here:  28...Qxf5  29.Qxd7  Like toppling dominoes, Black's position collapses. }
28... Rxe6 29. Rxe6 Bxe6 30. Re3
{ Black is defenseless against the threat of Rg3 and taking on g7. } 30... Rg8
31. Rg3 Bxa2 32. h4
{ How torturous is the slow advance of the h-pawn to h6. There is nothing I can do! }
32... Qh5 33. Qd7
{ After  33.Qd4 !  Qf7  34.h5  with h6 next to come, White is winning.  34...h6  35.Rg6  Kh7  36.Qe4 !  threatening a discovered check.  36...Kh8  37.Rxh6 }
33... Qf7 34. Qd2 Qd5 35. Qh6 Qe6
{ Neither would help Black  35...Qf7  36.h5  Bd5  37.Qg5  and there is NOTHING Black can do against h6. White is winning. }
36. Bxg7+
{ Could there be a stronger contrast conceivable between the light and dark squared bishops? }
