{ Black can take back with either the b-pawn or d-pawn, but only the last move has gained popularity as after 4...bxc6 he faces a hard time completing his development.   4.Ba4  The main concept of Morphy's Defense materializes when White falls for the 'Noah's Ark Trap'. This happened in 1929 when Steiner got ambushed in his game against Capablanca, but the current elite grandmaster Nepomniachtchi was similarly caught in it in a recent online game.  4...d6  5.d4  b5  6.Bb3  exd4  7.Nxd4  Nxd4  8.Qxd4  c5!  All of a sudden, White's bishop is caught after c5-c4.  9.Qd5  threatening Qxf7+  Be6  10.Qc6+  The check will not help Black.  10...Bd7  11.Qd5  c4  0-1 @@StartBracket@@55@@EndBracket@@ Nepomniachtchi,I 2784-Demchenko,A 2641 chess.com INT 2020 }
4... dxc6
{ The contours of the RLE position are there. White gave up his light-squared bishop and the bishop pair, leaving Black with doubled c-pawns and behind in development. White has many options here. Lasker's main choice was 5. d4, but 5. d3 and 5. Nc3 have also been tried, remaining flexible and not committing the king to g1 yet. }
5. O-O
{ The most ambitious move! White stays flexible, keeping open the options of: 1. d3 or d4, 2. whether the knight should be moved to d2, c3 or a3. The American world-class grandmaster Robert Byrne named 5.O-O is after the Dutch IM John Barendregt, who played this move a couple of times in the 60's. White has already castled while Black's pieces are all on the back rank. Moreover, Black must make an important choice as to how to protect his central pawn since White has renewed the threat of Nxe5 after castling. }
5... Be7
{ Let me begin by telling you that in case you are not familiar yet with the 'queen desperado' you ought to examine this variation in which this concept appears abundantly. Furthermore, like the mysterious 5th queen's move to e7, 5...Be7 should neither be underestimated. It has been used in practice several times with success by Aronian, as well as Grischuk, Ponomariov and Svidler. }
6. Nxe5
{ The only move which tests Black to the bone. From scratch we put a knife to our opponent's throat. }
6... Qd4
{ Like in the 5...Be6 variation, because of the block on the e-file, Black hopes to regain the e-pawn. }
7. Qh5 Be6 8. d3
{ We are up a pawn for the moment, but our queen is tied to the knight, which will lead to some very nice queen desperados regaining back the pawn. }
8... Qc5
{ This move has appeared 8 times in practice. Due to the inconvenient pin on the 5th rank, White should sac his pawn on c2 back. }
9. Be3 Qxc2 10. Nd2
{ A strong novelty over Nakamura-Aronian. The knight is heading for c4. After  10.Nc3  Nf6  11.Qf3  Qxb2  12.Rfc1  Qa3  13.Rab1  Bd6  14.Nc4  Bxc4  15.dxc4  Be5  Black was doing fine. ½-½ @@StartBracket@@57@@EndBracket@@ Nakamura, H @@StartBracket@@2777@@EndBracket@@ - Aronian, L @@StartBracket@@2767@@EndBracket@@ chess.com INT 2018 }
10... Nf6
{ We take that hit and retreat to  f3  . It doesn't mean that our opponent can lay back and relax. After  10...Qxb2 ?!  11.Rab1  Qxa2  12.Rxb7  leaves White on top. }
11. Qf3
{ The Queen is well placed on f3. She is active, keeping an eye  (indirectly)  on f7 and making it possible to harrass the Black queen with Rfc1 and Ndc4. }
11... Qxb2
{ 11...O-O-O  In case Black doesn't accept White's Greek gift on b2, White doesn't slow down his active play.  12.Rfc1  Qa4  13.Ndc4  Nd7  14.Nxd7  Rxd7  15.b3  Qb5  16.d4  Kb8   16...Rhd8  17.d5  cxd5  18.Nb6+  White is winning the exchange and has a small advantage afterwards.  17.a4 !  Qxb3   17...Qb4  18.Bd2  When the queen is captured.  18.Na5 !  Qb4  19.Nxc6+  bxc6  20.Rab1  Bb3  21.Bd2 !  White's attacking prospects are more than promising. }
12. Ndc4
{ The queen on b2 is abandoned to her fate, roaming in no man's land. } 12...
Bxc4 13. Nxc4 Qc2 14. Bd4
{ I truly believe in White's position here, and probably there are more promising continuations. I was enchanted by the next line, illuminating White's potential. }
14... O-O-O
{ If Black refuses to castle it doesn't change much  14...Rd8  15.Rfc1  Qa4  16.Be5!  A recurring theme in the RLE: the weak pawn on c7. }
15. Rfc1
{ The idea behind White's bishop move is that it indirectly protects d3 for the moment - giving us the time to play Rfc1. }
15... Qa4 16. Be5 Rd7
{ Black preemptively defends c7 from a future Qg3, but this runs into a nice tactic. }
17. Bxc7
{ The entire point of White's play is that if  17...Rxc7??  18.Nb6+  winning the queen. }
17... Kxc7 18. Qg3+
{ Black better refrain from  18...Kc8  , because of  19.Nb6+  . But  18...Kd8  is even worse. }
18... Kd8
{ 18...Bd6  19.Nxd6  Rxd6  20.e5  when White will win an exchange in the worst-case scenario. }
19. Qb8# *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "5...Qe7, The Smyslov Variation"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5
{ This is the Ruy Lopez aka the Spanish Opening. Black has a wide range of responses he can choose from, amongst others besides the main move 3...a6. First, there is 3...Nf6 - the Berlin Defense, which is the second most popular line. Former world champion Vladimir Kramnik boosted its popularity by beating Garry Kasparov in the world championships in London @@StartBracket@@2000@@EndBracket@@ with this tenacious line. The Berlin Defense will be covered in Volume 2 of this series, whereas the other main Black's defenses, amongst others: - 3...Nge7 - the Cozio Defense; - 3...g6 - the Smyslov Defense; - 3...Nd4 - the Bird Defense; -3...d6 - the Steinitz Defense; - 3...f5 - the Schliemann Defense, and; - 3...Bc5 - the Classical Defense will be covered in Volume 3. This will give you a complete repertoire in the Spanish Opening. }
3... a6
{ This is the so-called 'Morphy Defense'. There is instant tension on the board, as our opponent challenges our bishop to make up its mind. The most common move is 4.Ba4, after which the opening will branch into countless variations like the Chigorin, Breyer, Ragozin and Marshall. Black will find his move 3...a6 useful in all of these variations, as he can chase the bishop from a4 with tempo, unpinning himself in the process while also taking space on the queenside. However, completely different positions occur after our move in this course: 4. Bxc6, aka the Ruy Lopez: Exchange Variation. At the same time, uncompromising and attacking players, such as the world champions Bobby Fischer and Garry Kasparov, as well as the current elite player Shakhriyar Mamedyarov from time to time let off steam in this very entertaining line. }
4. Bxc6
{ Black can take back with either the b-pawn or d-pawn, but only the last move has gained popularity as after 4...bxc6 he faces a hard time completing his development.   4.Ba4  The main concept of Morphy's Defense materializes when White falls for the 'Noah's Ark Trap'. This happened in 1929 when Steiner got ambushed in his game against Capablanca, but the current elite grandmaster Nepomniachtchi was similarly caught in it in a recent online game.  4...d6  5.d4  b5  6.Bb3  exd4  7.Nxd4  Nxd4  8.Qxd4  c5!  All of a sudden, White's bishop is caught after c5-c4.  9.Qd5  threatening Qxf7+  Be6  10.Qc6+  The check will not help Black.  10...Bd7  11.Qd5  c4  0-1 @@StartBracket@@55@@EndBracket@@ Nepomniachtchi,I 2784-Demchenko,A 2641 chess.com INT 2020 }
4... dxc6
{ The contours of the RLE position are there. White gave up his light-squared bishop and the bishop pair, leaving Black with doubled c-pawns and behind in development. White has many options here. Lasker's main choice was 5. d4, but 5. d3 and 5. Nc3 have also been tried, remaining flexible and not committing the king to g1 yet. }
5. O-O
{ The most ambitious move! White stays flexible, keeping open the options of: 1. d3 or d4, 2. whether the knight should be moved to d2, c3 or a3. The American world-class grandmaster Robert Byrne named 5.O-O is after the Dutch IM John Barendregt, who played this move a couple of times in the 60's. White has already castled while Black's pieces are all on the back rank. Moreover, Black must make an important choice as to how to protect his central pawn since White has renewed the threat of Nxe5 after castling. }
5... Qe7
{ This move appeared in practice in 1960 and was repeated in 1971 by Zaitsev. The greatest pioneer of this variation is the former World Champion Vassily Smyslov. In the period of 1972-1973 Smyslov used 5...Qe7 no less than 4 times! From all the unnatural moves we consider none are anything like 5...Qe7! Playing with the queen so early in the game, blocking the knight and bishop - do I need to say more? In fact, this move is not that strange since like 5...Qf6 and 5...Qd6 - it prepares long castling. Ivanchuk, Svidler, and Firouzja have all played this way. }
6. d4 { We cannot allow our opponent to play ...Bg4 and ...0-0-0. } 6... exd4
7. Qxd4 Bg4 { By far the most popular move from Black's perspective. } 8. Bf4
{ Black's 'threat' of delivering White a doubled f-pawn is simply ignored. Our opponent's development lags so much behind that the doubling of the f-pawns is insignificant. }
8... Bxf3 9. gxf3 Nf6
{ Black solved the position of his knight, but what about his bishop and king? }
10. Nc3
{ White relies upon his faster development and his enemy's vulnerable king. }
10... Nh5 { Probably best, to release the tension somewhat. } 11. Bg3 Nxg3
{ The swap of knight against bishop is beneficial for Black in terms of simplification, but it has a detrimental effect on him due to White's improved pawn structure.   11...Rd8  The former world champion Valery Smyslov and the Swedish grandmaster Johnny Hector have tried this move, but unfortunately without great success. It tells us that Black's position is not enviable.  12.Qe3  Nxg3  13.hxg3  Qc5  What else should Black play else here? The king can't stay forever in the open field.  14.Rad1  Qxe3  15.Rxd8+  Kxd8  16.Rd1+  Kc8  Black players have tried all of the three plausible moves ...Qd4, ...Kc8 and ...Ke8 here. For the game Dvoretsky - Smyslov, I'd like to refer you to the model game section.  17.fxe3  1-0 @@StartBracket@@28@@EndBracket@@ Dvoretsky, M - Smyslov, V Odessa 1973 }
12. hxg3
{ We take back towards the center. After 12. fxg3, Black would be happy to swap queens with 12...Qc5. }
12... h5
{ How else could Black get his rook on h8 involved?   12...Qc5  aiming for simplifications.  13.Rad1  White shouldn't run from this, as he maintains the better odds in the ending. ½-½ @@StartBracket@@27@@EndBracket@@ Santos Ruiz, M @@StartBracket@@2484@@EndBracket@@ - Romanov, E @@StartBracket@@2622@@EndBracket@@ Sitges 2016. }
13. Rad1
{ We control the open d-file and are ready for the exchanges. Please take a close look at the model game Dvoretsky-Smyslov from the main course, in which the former world champion was left without any chance in the ending. }
*

