exd4 7. Qxd4
{ The queen is attacking the g7-pawn, as a result of which Black cannot move his knight out. }
7... f6
{ Blocking the diagonal, Black is now ready for Ne7 and Ng6, and evt. Be6. Black is very flexible, as he can switch plans of short and long castling. }
8. Be3
{ The bishop is positionally better placed on e3, compared to fianchettoing it on b2. From e3 it reaches both flanks. }
8... Ne7 9. Nbd2
{ This is the right square for the Knight. It goes to c4 from where it hits Black d6-bishop. }
9... Be6 { Temporarily preventing the White knight from moving to c4. } 10. Qc3
{ A delicate move. The queen makes place for the knight and prevents any tactical threats such as ...Bxh2. }
10... Qd7
{ Throughout the latest years this move gained more followers as compared to the other competitor 10... Ng6. Here, I'd like to step off the main paths of 11. Nd4 or 11. Nc4, not merely to surprise our opponent, but because I truly believe in the proposed moves. We have arrived at a crossroads. This is one of the most critical positions in the entire Ruy Lopez Exchange Variation and Black's set-up is a tough nut to crack. I wanted to provide you with a wide variety of moves and plans which all prove to be very dangerous for Black in my opinion. You can choose between 11. Rad1, 11. a4 and 11. Rfd1. }
11. Rad1
{ This move has been played over 20 times, but not yet combined with the new idea of regrouping the knight to e1 and d3. }
11... Ng6
{ This move, like 0-0-0 should be played. As both of the moves are useful for Black, we can only guess his move order. }
12. Nb3
{ sidestepping the main line after 12.Nd4. As Black's position is a tough nut to crack, I'd suggest deviating from the main theory to confuse our opponent. }
12... Bxb3
{ This panicking move happened twice in practice is the only move played so far in this position. Black players well prepared will likely come up with improvements fighting for equality.   12...O-O-O !?  N  hasn't been played yet, but is an interesting alternative. And ultimately fit for the daredevils amongst us.  13.Na5  is resulting in very sharp lines, after  13...Bg4   13...Bh3  14.Qb3  b6  15.Bxb6 !?  Qg4  16.g3  Bxf1  17.Rxf1  cxb6  18.Qxb6  Kd7  is very unclear and needs to be tested in practice, also because of the many interesting sidetracks for both sides. }
13. Qxb3 { Preventing short castling, attacking b7. } 13... O-O-O 14. Nd4 Rhe8
{ This direct move, attacking e4 has merely appeared in this position. } 15. f3
{ A main pillar of our strategy in this line. White is fortifying his center, before undertaking ensuing operations on the queenside @@StartBracket@@by means of a minority pawn attack@@EndBracket@@. }
15... c5 { is far too optimistic, underestimating White's initiative. } 16. Nf5
{ Where should the Black queen go to in order to unpin herself. } *

