[White "1. 4... bxc6"]
[Black "4â¦ bxc6: Introduction"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5
{ This is the Ruy Lopez aka the Spanish Opening. Black has a wide range of responses he can choose from, amongst others besides the main move 3...a6. First, there is 3...Nf6 - the Berlin Defense, which is the second most popular line. Former world champion Vladimir Kramnik boosted its popularity by beating Garry Kasparov in the world championships in London @@StartBracket@@2000@@EndBracket@@ with this tenacious line. The Berlin Defense will be covered in Volume 2 of this series, whereas the other main Black's defenses, amongst others: - 3...Nge7 - the Cozio Defense; - 3...g6 - the Smyslov Defense; - 3...Nd4 - the Bird Defense; -3...d6 - the Steinitz Defense; - 3...f5 - the Schliemann Defense, and; - 3...Bc5 - the Classical Defense will be covered in Volume 3. This will give you a complete repertoire in the Spanish Opening. }
3... a6
{ This is the so-called 'Morphy Defense'. There is instant tension on the board, as our opponent challenges our bishop to make up its mind. The most common move is 4.Ba4, after which the opening will branch into countless variations like the Chigorin, Breyer, Ragozin and Marshall. Black will find his move 3...a6 useful in all of these variations, as he can chase the bishop from a4 with tempo, unpinning himself in the process while also taking space on the queenside. However, completely different positions occur after our move in this course: 4. Bxc6, aka the Ruy Lopez: Exchange Variation. At the same time, uncompromising and attacking players, such as the world champions Bobby Fischer and Garry Kasparov, as well as the current elite player Shakhriyar Mamedyarov from time to time let off steam in this very entertaining line. }
4. Bxc6
{ Black can take back with either the b-pawn or d-pawn, but only the last move has gained popularity as after 4...bxc6 he faces a hard time completing his development.   4.Ba4  The main concept of Morphy's Defense materializes when White falls for the 'Noah's Ark Trap'. This happened in 1929 when Steiner got ambushed in his game against Capablanca, but the current elite grandmaster Nepomniachtchi was similarly caught in it in a recent online game.  4...d6  5.d4  b5  6.Bb3  exd4  7.Nxd4  Nxd4  8.Qxd4  c5!  All of a sudden, White's bishop is caught after c5-c4.  9.Qd5  threatening Qxf7+  Be6  10.Qc6+  The check will not help Black.  10...Bd7  11.Qd5  c4  0-1 @@StartBracket@@55@@EndBracket@@ Nepomniachtchi, I 2784-Demchenko, A 2641 chess.com INT 2020 }
4... bxc6
{ The recapture with the b-pawn, taking towards the center, makes at least some sense. The move appeared twice on the board in the 19th century, however, the line is named after the Austro-Hungarian chess master Carl Schlechter who played and popularized this move in February 1904. Only 2 months later, world champion Emanuel Lasker repeated 4...bxc6 in the Cambridge Springs tournament, while the fourth world champion Alexander Alekhine tried this line in 1914. One of the key ideas is that White doesn't get an advantage after the obvious 5. Nxe5, as Black can then counterpunch with 5...Qg5. Presently, the line doesn't have a following amongst the top players, though it should be taken seriously as Black's position remains quite sturdy. Having said that, when White knows what to do, he gets smooth piece play and Black can never truly disentangle himself. }
5. d4
{ White - not resting on his laurels - hits immediately in the center. Our adversary should not get the chance to solve his opening troubles i.e. being behind in development too easily!   5.Nxe5  is less convincing for White, and was played in the key game of this line.  5...Qg5  !? The point: Black hits both the knight on e5 and the pawn on g2. 0-1 @@StartBracket@@26@@EndBracket@@ Marco, G - Schlechter, C Monte Carlo 1904, see the next informational line. }
5... exd4 6. Qxd4
{ Black still has a lot to accomplish. He is way behind in development and his bishop cannot move, since then g7 would hang, while a knight on f6 can be harassed by e5. }
6... Qf6
{ 6...Ne7  The knight will be moved to g6, out of range of the e4-e5 pawn push. The only problem is that it takes 2 moves, wasting valuable time.  7.Nc3  Rb8  1-0 @@StartBracket@@36@@EndBracket@@ Yandemirov, V @@StartBracket@@2481@@EndBracket@@- Sitnikov, A @@StartBracket@@2509@@EndBracket@@ Alushta 2009  8.b3  This can be considered a novelty. The plan is clear: White fianchettoes his bishop, preparing long castling.  8...Ng6  9.Bb2  It becomes apparent that Black wasted too much time in the opening, while his king is still on e8.  9...Nf4  10.O-O-O  Black can't move his bishop and is having problems with his development. White is much better here.   6...d6  A sound and necessary move in Black's development.  7.O-O  c5  The long diagonal is opened for the bishop.   7...Nf6  Black exposes himself to e5.  8.e5  c5  9.Qe3  ! The best place for the queen.  9...dxe5  What else?  10.Nxe5  Black's dreadful queenside pawns should raise concerns.  8.Qd3  White has a huge lead in development. One way or another, he should be able to capitalize on this.  8...Ne7   8...Be7  this move has appeared 10 times in practice.  9.Nc3  Black cannot allow the knight to come to d5.  9...Nf6  But the f6-knight is a target for the e4-pawn.  10.e5  ! Black is forced to take  10...dxe5   10...Nd7  is from bad to worse, since after  11.exd6  cxd6  12.Nd5  It becomes clear that 10...Nd7, allowing our knight to d5, turns out badly for Black.  11.Qxd8+  Bxd8  12.Nxe5  After the exchange of queens, Black has to worry about his pawn structure.  9.Nc3  The knight is heading towards d5.  9...Ng6  10.Nd5  The knight is very powerful on d5, and Black needs to concede something drive it off. For instance, after ...c6, Black's d6-pawn will become White's prey. However, after ...Be6, Bxd5, Black gives up his bishop pair.  10...Be7  11.Bd2  ! This is an important idea to remember. The bishop on a5 will exert full pressure on c7 and entails that Black will find himself 'squeezed' .  11...Be6  12.Ba5  This is a new move and idea, as the only move played here was b2-b4. After Ba5 we hit c7, hence Black is kind of forced to take the knight.  12...Bxd5  Giving up his good bishop, is not something we object to.  13.exd5  The bishop on a5 is exerting annoying pressure on c7.  13...O-O  14.Rae1  It's time to conquer the e-file. Black gets squeezed more and more.  14...Qd7  15.b3  Prophylaxis against any counterattack on the b-file.  15...Rfe8  16.Re4  ! Black should do something against the doubling of the rooks on the e-file.  16...Bf6  So, our opponent swaps one pair of rooks. But it won't ease their pain much since the e-file remains in our possession.  17.Rxe8+  Qxe8  18.Re1  Qd7  19.h3  ! A small and useful move, since White creates a hideaway square on h2 for his king. White maintains the initiative and a pleasant edge in the ensuing ending, as Black cannot easily get rid of his 2 weak pawns on a6 and c7.   6...Nf6  This move has its drawbacks since White can harass the knight.  7.e5  ! Space in the center is taken, while the knight has to move.  7...Nd5  8.c4  ! This position resembles the Scotch Opening. However, here White has a much better version of it.  8...Nb6  9.c5  Just grabbing space.  9...Nd5  10.Nc3  Qe7   10...Nxc3  Like in the main line, White is much better due to his space advantage.  11.Qxc3  Be7  12.Bf4  Black is in a squeeze.  11.Ne4  To tighten the screws even harder.  11...Qe6  12.O-O  Be7  13.Bg5  The dark-squared bishops are swapped, so that Black gets stuck with a weak bishop on c8. }
7. Qa4
{ For our inspiration in this particular line, we follow the Serbian GM Solak in his game against Sanal. Please be aware that there are several playable alternatives for White on the 7th move. The queen on f6 is misplaced now, and surprisingly, our queen on a4 hampers Black's development. }
7... Bc5 8. O-O Ne7
{ Compared to Nf6, the knight cannot be harassed by e4-e5. Furthermore, after ... d7-d6, the c6-pawn is no longer hanging. }
9. Nc3 h6 { Preventing Bg5 once and for all. } 10. Re1
{ Supporting a possible e4-e5 thrust and preparing for the exchange of bishops with Be3. }
10... Rb8
{ Exerting pressure on b2, and threatening Rb4.   10...d6  ? Here comes evidently to light the point of Qa4.  11.Nd5  !! The pawn on c6 is pinned, and the king is trapped in the center. By the way, e4-e5, with the idea of ...dxe5, Ne4, would be winning as well.  11...Nxd5  12.Qxc6+  When Black's position falls apart. }
11. Qc4
{ The queen, having conducted her task of preventing d7-d6, moves back to more fertile soil. }
11... Ba7
{ 11...d6  this line manifests the concealed dangers for Black.  12.e5  ! The e-file will be opened; with the king still seeking for a shelter.  12...Qg6  13.exd6  We should not spare the Black king nor our opponent. Let's hit him in his weakest spot.  13...cxd6  14.Ne4  ! The tricky part revolving around this 'knight to e4 concept', is that White doesn't just want to take on c5.  14...Bb4  15.Nh4  ! As a Dutch saying goes: now the monkey gets out of the sleeve - meaning: now we get to the point!  15...Qg4  Pinning the e4-knight, endeavoring to save his skin by a swap of queens.   15...Qh5 ?  16.Nxd6+  Bxd6  17.Qxc6+  +-   15...Qe6  16.Nxd6+ !  Qxd6  17.Bf4  ±  16.h3  Qd7  17.Qd4  ! This very strong move decides the game. The problem for Black is that he cannot castle. }
12. b3
{ A multi-purpose move, since White might want to fianchetto, or go for Be3 without giving Black the chance to take on b2. }
12... O-O
{ Our opponent cannot be allowed to complete his development with ...d6 and ...Ng6. A proven strategy is to exchange the opponent's best pieces. }
13. Be3 { Black will regret giving up his bishop pair. } 13... Bxe3 14. Rxe3
{ Let's take stock of the position. We are almost done with developing our pieces whereas Black, on the contrary, is stuck with a passive bishop on c8 and a weak pawn on a6. Taken together, this means that White is better here. }
14... d5
{ A drastic measure, leaving weaknesses behind.   14...d6  The phenomenon of doubled pawns: are they good or bad? Here they are good because they control a lot of the central squares, but bad because...  15.e5  ! ...they are not flexible. When the pawn on d6 moves to d5 or takes on e5, the coherence is torn apart and two silly pawns on c6 and c7 are all what is left. }
15. Qc5 { The aforementioned weakness is being occupied. } 15... dxe4 16. Rxe4
{ Black has a worse pawn structure, so he wishes to create confusion by means of 16...Nd5. }
16... Nd5
{ Until here we've been following Solak, D @@StartBracket@@2607@@EndBracket@@-Sanal, V @@StartBracket@@2460@@EndBracket@@, 1-0 34, Jerusalem 2015. White could have obtained a large advantage by }
17. Rae1
{ This is an improvement over Solak's game. White is menacing to take on f8, followed by Re8 mate. White has a much better position. }
