5... exd4 6. Qxd4
{ Black has a lot to accomplish yet. He is way behind in development and his bishop cannot move, since then g7 would hang, while a knight on f6 can be harrassed by e5. }
6... Ne7
{ The knight will be moved to g6, out of range of the e4-e5 pawn push. The only problem is that it takes 2 moves, wasting valuable time. }
7. Nc3 Rb8
{ Taking the semi-open b-file, and restricting the development of the c1 bishop for the moment.  1-0 @@StartBracket@@36@@EndBracket@@ Yandemirov, V @@StartBracket@@2481@@EndBracket@@-Sitnikov, A @@StartBracket@@2509@@EndBracket@@ Alushta 2009 }
8. b3
{ This can be considered a novelty. The plan is clear: White fianchettoes his bishop, preparing long castling. }
8... Ng6 9. Bb2
{ It becomes apparent that Black wasted too much time in the opening, while his king is still on e8. }
9... Nf4 10. O-O-O
{ Black can't move his bishop and has problems with his development. White is much better here.  For instance when Black gets too greedy and takes on g2 White will capture the knight after   10...Nxg2  11.Qe5+  followed by 12. Qg3. }
