14... d5 { A drastic measure, leaving weaknesses behind. } 15. Qc5
{ The weaknesses that the doubled pawns left behind  (in this case, the c5 square)  are being put to good use. }
15... dxe4 16. Rxe4
{ Black has a worse pawn structure, so he wishes to create confusion by means of 16...Nd5. }
16... Nd5
{ Until here we've been following Solak,D @@StartBracket@@2607@@EndBracket@@-Sanal,V @@StartBracket@@2460@@EndBracket@@, 1-0 @@StartBracket@@34@@EndBracket@@, Jerusalem 2015. How could White have obtained a large advantage? }
17. Nxd5
{ This was Solak's move, which seems to work for White. Notwithstanding, Black has a strong intermediate tactic by which he manages to equalize. }
17... Qxa1+
{ Cold-bloodedly, Black can take the rook while dealing with the nasty threat of Ne7+.   17...cxd5 ?    this was the move played by Sanal, leaving him without any hopes after  18.Ree1  Rb5  19.Qxc7  Winning a pawn and leaving Black without the slightest hope of any counterplay. }
18. Re1 Rb5
{ The way out for Black! This move defuses the idea of Ne7+ and Nxc6. When White takes on b5, Black can take on e1 before he takes back the queen on b5.   18...Qb2  This must have been the position which Solak must have been considering in his calculations. And indeed, White would have won here with a 'petite combinaison'.  19.Ne7+ !  Kh7  20.Nxc6  The 2 Black rooks are hanging here. Undoubtedly, this was Solak's intention when he went for  17.Nxd5  . }
19. Qxf8+
{ One after the other a beautiful 'desperado' is played, it should become illegal! }
19... Kxf8 20. Rxa1 cxd5
{ After the dust has settled, Black got rid of the doubled pawns and would be doing fine. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1. 4... bxc6"]
[Black "6...Qf6 #7"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5
{ This is the Ruy Lopez aka the Spanish Opening. Black has a wide range of responses he can choose from, amongst others besides the main move 3...a6. First, there is 3...Nf6 - the Berlin Defense, which is the second most popular line. Former world champion Vladimir Kramnik boosted its popularity by beating Garry Kasparov in the world championships in London @@StartBracket@@2000@@EndBracket@@ with this tenacious line. The Berlin Defense will be covered in Volume 2 of this series, whereas the other main Black's defenses, amongst others: - 3...Nge7 - the Cozio Defense; - 3...g6 - the Smyslov Defense; - 3...Nd4 - the Bird Defense; -3...d6 - the Steinitz Defense; - 3...f5 - the Schliemann Defense, and; - 3...Bc5 - the Classical Defense will be covered in Volume 3. This will give you a complete repertoire in the Spanish Opening. }
3... a6
{ This is the so-called 'Morphy Defense'. There is instant tension on the board, as our opponent challenges our bishop to make up its mind. The most common move is 4.Ba4, after which the opening will branch into countless variations like the Chigorin, Breyer, Ragozin and Marshall. Black will find his move 3...a6 useful in all of these variations, as he can chase the bishop from a4 with tempo, unpinning himself in the process while also taking space on the queenside. However, completely different positions occur after our move in this course: 4. Bxc6, aka the Ruy Lopez: Exchange Variation. At the same time, uncompromising and attacking players, such as the world champions Bobby Fischer and Garry Kasparov, as well as the current elite player Shakhriyar Mamedyarov from time to time let off steam in this very entertaining line. }
4. Bxc6
{ Black can take back with either the b-pawn or d-pawn, but only the last move has gained popularity as after 4...bxc6 he faces a hard time completing his development.   4.Ba4  The main concept of Morphy's Defense materializes when White falls for the 'Noah's Ark Trap'. This happened in 1929 when Steiner got ambushed in his game against Capablanca, but the current elite grandmaster Nepomniachtchi was similarly caught in it in a recent online game.  4...d6  5.d4  b5  6.Bb3  exd4  7.Nxd4  Nxd4  8.Qxd4  c5!  All of a sudden, White's bishop is caught after c5-c4.  9.Qd5  threatening Qxf7+  Be6  10.Qc6+  The check will not help Black.  10...Bd7  11.Qd5  c4  0-1 @@StartBracket@@55@@EndBracket@@ Nepomniachtchi, I 2784-Demchenko, A 2641 chess.com INT 2020 }
4... bxc6
{ The recapture with the b-pawn, taking towards the center, makes at least some sense. The move appeared twice on the board in the 19th century, however the line is named after the Austro-Hungarian chess master Carl Schlechter who played and popularized this move in February 1904. Only 2 months later, world champion Emanuel Lasker repeated 4...bxc6 in the Cambridge Springs tournament, while the fourth world champion Alexander Alekhine tried this line in 1914. One of the key ideas is that White doesn't get an advantage after the obvious 5. Nxe5, as Black can then counterpunch with 5...Qg5. Presently, the line doesn't have a following amongst the top players, though it should be taken seriously as Black's position remains quite sturdy. Having said that, when White knows what to do, he gets smooth piece play and Black can never truly disentangle himself. }
5. d4
{ White - not resting on his laurels - hits immediately in the center. Our adversary should not get the chance to solve his opening troubles @@StartBracket@@i.e. being behind in development@@EndBracket@@ too easily! }
5... exd4 6. Qxd4
{ Black has a lot to accomplish yet. He is way behind in development and his bishop cannot move, since then g7 would hang, while a knight on f6 can be harrassed by e5. }
6... Qf6 7. Qa4
{ For our inspiration in this particular line, we follow the Serbian GM Solak in his game against Sanal. Please be aware that there are several playable alternatives for White on the 7th move. The queen on f6 is misplaced now, and surprisingly, our queen on a4 hampers Black's development. }
7... Bc5 8. O-O Ne7
{ Compared to Nf6, the knight can not be harrassed by e4-e5. Furthermore, after ...d7-d6, the c6-pawn is no longer hanging. }
9. Nc3 h6 { Preventing Bg5 once and for all. } 10. Re1
{ Supporting a possible e4-e5 thrust, and preparing for the exchange of bishops with Be3. }
10... Rb8 { Exerting pressure on b2, and threatening Rb4. } 11. Qc4
{ The queen, having conducted her task of preventing d7-d6, moves back to more fertile soil. }
11... Ba7 12. b3
{ A multi-purpose move, since White might want to fianchetto, or go for Be3 without giving Black the chance to take on b2. }
12... O-O
{ Our opponent cannot be allowed to complete his development with ...d6 and ...Ng6. A proven strategy is to exchange the opponent's best pieces. }
13. Be3 { Black will regret giving up his bishop pair. } 13... Bxe3 14. Rxe3
{ Let's take stock of the position. We are almost done with developing our pieces whereas Black, on the contrary, is stuck with a passive bishop on c8 and a weak pawn on a6. Take together, this means that White is better here. }
14... d5 { A drastic measure, leaving weaknesses behind. } 15. Qc5
{ The aforementioned weakness is being occupied. } 15... dxe4 16. Rxe4
{ Black has a worse pawn structure, so he wishes to create confusion by means of 16...Nd5. }
16... Nd5
{ Until here we've been following Solak,D @@StartBracket@@2607@@EndBracket@@-Sanal,V @@StartBracket@@2460@@EndBracket@@, 1-0 @@StartBracket@@34@@EndBracket@@, Jerusalem 2015. How could White have obtained a large advantage? }
17. Rae1 Be6 { If  17...Qxc3?  18.Qxf8+  Kxf8  19.Re8# } 18. Nd4
{ White is much better here due to his strongly mobilized pieces and Black's weak pawns. }
