{ Here it is, the pawn on e4 can be taken as the e6-bishop prevents any heavy material losses after Re1. }
8. Ng5
{ But White can inflict serious damage to Black's pawn structure! Why does Black allow this terrible weakening? }
8... Qg6 { was played by a young Magnus Carlsen, with a 'low' rating of 2646. }
9. Nxe6 fxe6 10. d3 O-O-O 11. Qe2 { This position resembles our main line. }
11... Bd6 12. Nd2 Nf6
{ Black is not in a generous mood in leaving the e-pawn undefended since 13. Qxe6+ leads to a lot of counterplay. }
13. Qxe6+ { accepting the gift is dangerous. } 13... Kb8
{ White is about to lose valuable time while retreating the queen. } 14. Qe2
{ Otherwise Black will be able to misplace the queen with Rhe8. } 14... Rhe8
{ When the queen should go all the way go back to d1. Black has enough compensation for the sacrificed pawn. }
15. Qf3
{ If  15.Qd1  Bc5  and Black's rook will join the attack, by  means of Rd8-d5-h5. }
15... Ng4 16. g3
{ The only move, as after  16.h3  Black wins the exchange with  16...Nh2! }
16... Qh5 { Threatening mate on h2. } 17. Qg2
{ One step back, but not two forward. Black can intrude as the square on e2 is no longer covered by the queen. }
17... Re2
{ White ended up on a slippery slope, his position deteriorating with each move. }
