{ The most ambitious move! White stays flexible, keeping open the options of: 1. d3 or d4, 2. whether the knight should be moved to d2, c3 or a3. The American world-class grandmaster Robert Byrne named 5.O-O is after the Dutch IM John Barendregt, who played this move a couple of times in the 60's. White has already castled while Black's pieces are all on the back rank. Moreover, Black must make an important choice as to how to protect his central pawn since White has renewed the threat of Nxe5 after castling. }
5... Be6
{ Most of Black's 5th moves - 5...f6, 5...Bg4, 5...Qd6, 5...Qf6 and 5...Bd6 protect the pawn on e5 directly or indirectly. The only moves that don't are 5...Be6, 5...Be7, and 5...Ne7. These 'odd ducks' block the e-file and enable 6... Qd4. The text move is not as innocent as it may seem and shouldn't be underestimated! Black leaves the e5 pawn 'en prise', but White cannot immediately take profit in terms of gaining a pawn, as Black can take back on e4 since the bishop on e6 blocks the e-file. It was first put in practice in 1972, but it was only in 1994 that it was played on the highest level by my countryman Jan Timman. }
6. Nxe5
{ This move makes clear that we will get an open position with sharp play. }
6... Qd4 7. Nf3 Qxe4
{ Here it is, the pawn on e4 can be taken as the e6-bishop prevents any heavy material losses after Re1. }
8. Ng5
{ But White can inflict serious damage to Black's pawn structure! Why does Black allow this terrible weakening? }
8... Qg6 { was played by a young Magnus Carlsen, with a 'low' rating of 2646. }
9. Nxe6 fxe6 10. d3
{ This move is preferred over d4 as here, the pawn will not come under fire, enabling us to focus on development. Compare to when the d4 pawn is going to come under pressure.   10.d4  O-O-O }
10... O-O-O 11. Qe2
{ This position resembles our main line. This is the most natural square for the queen, hitting the weak e6 pawn. }
11... Bd6 12. Nd2 Nf6
{ Black is not in a generous mood in leaving the e-pawn undefended since 13. Qxe6+ leads to a lot of counterplay. }
13. Nc4
{ Is my favorite move here: White is keeping an eye on the dangerous bishop on d6  (hitting h2)  . Please take a look at the model game Rozentalis-Stevic.   13.Ne4  This was played by Naiditsch in his game against a young Carlsen.  13...Nxe4  14.Qxe4  Naiditsch was wise to swap the queens. Not merely because it was Carlsen on the other side of the board, but because of the following line:   14.dxe4  Qf6  a strong move hindering White's development.  15.c3   15.Be3  is not possible, on account of  15...Qe5  g5  There is not much that White can do here to stop the Black pawns from advancing.  16.Bd2  h5  ! Black's attack begins to take shape, whereas White can't place a counterpunch; too bad for us that the c3-pawn is standing in the way of the d2-bishop.  14...Qxe4  15.dxe4  But here White is slightly better as a result of his better structure.  15...Bc5  16.Bg5  Rd7  17.Rad1  Naturally, White tries to exchange a pair of rooks to make the better pawn structure count in this ending with same-colored bishops.  17...Rxd1  18.Rxd1  Rf8  19.Bh4  There is still a lot of music in this ending. By slow means White can try to exploit his potential, although against Carlsen it wasn't easy. ½-½, @@StartBracket@@58@@EndBracket@@ Naiditsch, A @@StartBracket@@2664@@EndBracket@@ - Carlsen, M @@StartBracket@@2646@@EndBracket@@ Sarajevo 2006 }
13... e5
{ 13...Rhe8  Black is preparing e6-e5. However, the pawn is not yet there and this gives White an extra opportunity to fix e6.  14.f4 !  this is a pleasant option for White when Black refrains from an early e6-e5. The pawn on e6 will be stuck and is an easy target for our heavy pieces. }
14. Qe3
{ White is aiming for 15. Qa7, and I believe out of a sense of danger, most of our opponents will try to prevent this with the obvious 14...Kb8. Secondarily, we offer the exchange of Queens, exposing the sole e5-pawn even more.  For   14.f3 !?  , which also secures a small advantage fixing the weak e-pawn. Please have a look at the aforementioned game Rozentalis-Stevic for further moves and plans. }
14... Kb8
{ This is an interesting move for Black, though in the arising positions there can be only 2 results: a win for White or a draw.   14...e4  15.Nxd6+   15.Qa7 !?  This may well be even stronger, threatening Qa8+ and Qxb7.  15...exd3  16.Qa8+  Kd7  17.Qxb7  Black has to cope with the threat of Nxd6, when it is no picnic to take back with the king. In a word, you have a very pleasant option on move 15 between the sharp 15.Qxa7 and the solid 15.Nxd6.  15...cxd6  16.dxe4  Qxe4  17.Qxe4  Nxe4  White is having the best chances here, though Black's position is a tough nut to crack. A sample line could be  18.b3  White is taking profit of his better minor piece in these types of positions.  18...Rhe8  19.Bb2  g6  20.f3  Nc5  21.Bf6  Rd7  22.Rfe1  White is aiming to take over the e-file. Maybe your engine will grant us merely a very little plus, but practically I wouldn't be glad at all to defend this position with Black. }
15. Qg5 { Aiming for simplifications after the queen swap. } 15... Qxg5 16.
Bxg5
{ White has a stable and lasting advantage here. Black cannot move his e-pawn which can be considered a liability for the remainder of the game. }
