1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5
{ This is the Ruy Lopez aka the Spanish Opening. Black has a wide range of responses he can choose from, amongst others besides the main move 3...a6. First, there is 3...Nf6 - the Berlin Defense, which is the second most popular line. Former world champion Vladimir Kramnik boosted its popularity by beating Garry Kasparov in the world championships in London @@StartBracket@@2000@@EndBracket@@ with this tenacious line. The Berlin Defense will be covered in Volume 2 of this series, whereas the other main Black's defenses, amongst others: - 3...Nge7 - the Cozio Defense; - 3...g6 - the Smyslov Defense; - 3...Nd4 - the Bird Defense; -3...d6 - the Steinitz Defense; - 3...f5 - the Schliemann Defense, and; - 3...Bc5 - the Classical Defense will be covered in Volume 3. This will give you a complete repertoire in the Spanish Opening. }
3... a6
{ This is the so-called 'Morphy Defense'. There is instant tension on the board, as our opponent challenges our bishop to make up its mind. The most common move is 4.Ba4, after which the opening will branch into countless variations like the Chigorin, Breyer, Ragozin and Marshall. Black will find his move 3...a6 useful in all of these variations, as he can chase the bishop from a4 with tempo, unpinning himself in the process while also taking space on the queenside. However, completely different positions occur after our move in this course: 4. Bxc6, aka the Ruy Lopez: Exchange Variation. At the same time, uncompromising and attacking players, such as the world champions Bobby Fischer and Garry Kasparov, as well as the current elite player Shakhriyar Mamedyarov from time to time let off steam in this very entertaining line. }
4. Bxc6
{ Black can take back with either the b-pawn or d-pawn, but only the last move has gained popularity as after 4...bxc6 he faces a hard time completing his development.   4.Ba4  The main concept of Morphy's Defense materializes when White falls for the 'Noah's Ark Trap'. This happened in 1929 when Steiner got ambushed in his game against Capablanca, but the current elite grandmaster Nepomniachtchi was similarly caught in it in a recent online game.  4...d6  5.d4  b5  6.Bb3  exd4  7.Nxd4  Nxd4  8.Qxd4  c5!  All of a sudden, White's bishop is caught after c5-c4.  9.Qd5  threatening Qxf7+  Be6  10.Qc6+  The check will not help Black.  10...Bd7  11.Qd5  c4  0-1, @@StartBracket@@55@@EndBracket@@ Nepomniachtchi, I @@StartBracket@@2784@@EndBracket@@ - Demchenko, A @@StartBracket@@2641@@EndBracket@@ chess.com INT 2020 }
4... dxc6
{ The contours of the RLE position are there. White gave up his light-squared bishop and the bishop pair, leaving Black with doubled c-pawns and behind in development. White has many options here. Lasker's main choice was 5. d4, but 5. d3 and 5. Nc3 have also been tried, remaining flexible and not committing the king to g1 yet. }
5. O-O
{ The most ambitious move! White stays flexible, keeping open the options of: 1. d3 or d4, 2. whether the knight should be moved to d2, c3 or a3. The American world-class grandmaster Robert Byrne named 5.O-O is after the Dutch IM John Barendregt, who played this move a couple of times in the 60's. White has already castled while Black's pieces are all on the back rank. Moreover, Black must make an important choice as to how to protect his central pawn since White has renewed the threat of Nxe5 after castling. }
5... Ne7
{ The sideline 5... Ne7 should be taken seriously, not in the least because Magnus Carlsen played it twice. The move was first seen in 1967, when it was played by Book. It was then played by Paul Keres against Dutch IM Hans Ree four years later. Way ahead of his time, Keres used this creative move to obtain a draw without much effort . }
6. Nxe5 { Let's take the opportunity to open up the position! } 6... Qd4 7. Qh5
{ We cannot play at half speed here. Therefore, we should go all-in with 7. Qh5, when Black will not get the chance to castle long, reaching a decent position.   7.Nf3  The following line illustrates why we should play in a powerful manner with 7. Qh5.  7...Qxe4  8.Re1  Qg6  9.Ne5  Qf5   9...Qf6  Played by Keres in 1971, followed up 40 years later by Bacrot and Tari, resp. in 2010 and 2017, see the next informational line  10.d4  Be6  when Black can castle on the next move and is doing fine. }
7... g6
{ White's choice of moves has been reduced here to 8. Qg5 and 8. Nf3.   7...Be6  allows White to stabilize his center by means of  8.d3  g6  9.Nf3 !  when White remains a pawn up. }
8. Nf3
{ Combined with the next move, this is a useful move to aim for a quick development of pieces and to open the e-file. }
8... Qxe4 9. Nc3
{ Time is of crucial importance in this position, not letting Black consolidate! The e-file is cleared for the White rook, in the meantime developing our pieces by chasing the queen.   9.Qa5  Hitting c7.  9...Bg4  Hitting f3, Black has not been idle either  10.Re1  Qd5  11.Qxc7  Unfortunately, Black can liquidate into a perpetual check.   11.Qxd5  cxd5  12.Ne5  Be6  13.d4  Nf5  14.c3  Bg7  15.Nd2  O-O  16.Ndf3  Nd6  17.Bf4  Rac8  18.Nd3  Ne4  19.Ng5  Nxg5  20.Bxg5  b6  21.Nf4  Rce8  22.Nxe6  Rxe6  23.Bf4  Rc8  24.f3  c5  25.dxc5  bxc5  26.Rad1  a5  27.Kf2  d4  From a seemingly equal position, Carlsen managed @@StartBracket@@don't ask me how!@@EndBracket@@ to gain a considerable advantage. 0-1 @@StartBracket@@64@@EndBracket@@ Naiditsch, A @@StartBracket@@2689@@EndBracket@@-Carlsen, M @@StartBracket@@2801@@EndBracket@@ Moscow 2009   11...Bxf3  12.gxf3   12.Nc3 ??  Qg5  Qxf3  13.Qxb7   13.Nc3  Qg4+  14.Kh1  Qf3+  15.Kg1  Qg4+  16.Qg3  Qxg3+  17.hxg3  Kd7  18.d3  Nd5  19.Ne4  f5  when the world champion was @@StartBracket@@up to this moment@@EndBracket@@ fine. ½-½ @@StartBracket@@44@@EndBracket@@ Hammer, J @@StartBracket@@2588@@EndBracket@@-Carlsen, M @@StartBracket@@2801@@EndBracket@@ Oslo 2009  Qg4+  forcing a perpetual check.  14.Kf1  Qh3+  15.Kg1   15.Ke2  does not change anything after  15...Qg4+ =  Qg4+  No way to hide, and we should bury the hatchet. }
9... Qf5
{ All the time, White's queen couldn't be taken.   9...gxh5 ?!  10.Nxe4  White's pawn structure is impeccable whereas Black's is all scattered and shattered.   9...Qxc2 ?  Black's greed doesn't go without impunity.  10.Qe5 !  Hitting the rook and attacking c7.  10...Rg8  11.d3 !  Now our bishop can be moved while Black can't move the queen to f5.  11...Qxd3  12.Rd1 !  As usual in these kinds of situations with Black's king in the middle, time is more important than material.  12...Qf5  13.Qxc7  White is winning, as the king will never ever find a shelter anymore. }
10. Qh4
{ Black's main problem in this line comes to light. Even after 10...Bg7, Black cannot castle because of the attacked knight. }
10... Bg7
{ 10...Be6  11.d3  Clearing the path for the bishop to come to g5, or f4.  11...Nd5   11...O-O-O  12.Bg5 !  Also, here, the knight on e7 can be considered as the problem child.  12...Re8  13.Qd4 !  Simultaneously threatening Qxh8 and Qa7.  13...Rg8  14.Qa7  Black is helpless against the intruder.  12.Nxd5  Qxd5  13.Re1  Bg7  14.Bf4  Not merely hitting c7, but also keeping g5 for the knight.  14...O-O  : the correspondence game went on with:   14...Bxb2  15.Rab1  Bc3  16.Bxc7  b5  17.Be5  Bxe1  18.Rxe1  when Blacks king will not find any shelter for the rest of the game. 1-0 @@StartBracket@@64@@EndBracket@@ Davidson, J @@StartBracket@@2092@@EndBracket@@- Knol, E @@StartBracket@@2223@@EndBracket@@ ICCF email 2015   15.Ng5 !  Will Black's king ever find any rest? White is clearly better here. }
11. Re1
{ 11.d4 ?!  seems like a normal move, but it has its flaws.  11...Be6  Of course, Black wishes to close the e-file.  12.Bf4  O-O-O !  Black is fine  13.Bxc7  Kxc7  14.Qxe7+  Rd7  Black's strong bishops and rooks compensate for the lost pawn. }
11... Be6 12. d3 Qg4 13. Qg5
{ This oddity has appeared in practice no less than 13 times!   13.Qxg4  Bxg4  leads to unclear play. }
13... Qxg5 14. Nxg5
{ The point behind 13.Qg5 is revealed. After the bishop moves, White clings to the knight on e7. In summary, we are glad to be capable of taking back on g5 with the knight! For the rest, see the trainable lines. }
