5. O-O
{ The most ambitious move! White stays flexible, keeping open the options of: 1. d3 or d4, 2. whether the knight should be moved to d2, c3 or a3. The American world-class grandmaster Robert Byrne named 5.O-O is after the Dutch IM John Barendregt, who played this move a couple of times in the 60's. White has already castled while Black's pieces are all on the back rank. Moreover, Black must make an important choice as to how to protect his central pawn since White has renewed the threat of Nxe5 after castling. }
5... Ne7
{ The sideline 5... Ne7 should be taken seriously, not in the least because Magnus Carlsen played it twice. The move was first seen in 1967, when it was played by Book. It was then played by Paul Keres against Dutch IM Hans Ree four years later. Way ahead of his time, Keres used this creative move to obtain a draw without much effort . }
6. Nxe5 { Let's take the opportunity to open up the position! } 6... Qd4 7. Nf3
{ The following line illustrates that we should play in a powerful manner with 7.Qh5. }
7... Qxe4 8. Re1 Qg6 9. Ne5 Qf6
{ Played by Keres in 1971, followed up 40 years later by Bacrot and Tari , resp. in 2010 and 2017.  Or   9...Qf5  10.d4  Be6  when Black can castle on the next move and is doing fine. }
10. d4 Bf5 11. Nc3 O-O-O 12. Qh5 Bg6 13. Qh3+ Qf5 14. Nxg6 fxg6 15. Qxf5+ gxf5
16. Bg5 Rd7
{ After a couple of piece trades, White is still a little better  (a nagging edge)  due to his lead in development. Black is solid though, and shouldn't have that hard of a task consolidating. }
17. Rad1 h6 18. Bf4 g5 19. Be5 Rh7 20. f3 Ng6 21. Bg3 Rhe7
{ After this little maneuver with the knight and rook, Black has neutralized White's pressure and possibly is a little better! }
22. Bf2 Bg7 23. Kf1 Kd8 24. Ne2 Rf7 25. c3 Bf8 { The knight is heading to e5. }
26. Nc1 Bd6 27. Nd3 Rfe7 28. Bg3 Ke8 29. Rxe7+ Kxe7 30. Re1+ Kf7 31. Ne5+ Bxe5
32. Bxe5 h5 33. h3 h4 { Making a sort-of 'clamp' on the kingside. } 34. Bh2 f4
{ Now, White's bishop is quite pathetic, locked behind the pawns. } 35. Bg1 Ne7
36. Re5 Kf6 37. Ke2 b6 38. Re4 Rd8 39. Bf2 Nf5 40. b3 Nd6
{ It's astounding that both players missed here a tactic  (see next move) } 41.
Re5
{ White could've played  41.Rxf4  gxf4  42.Bxh4+!  winning the rook back with interest. }
41... c5 42. Kd3 Nf5 43. Ke4
{ ½-½,  Ree, H - Keres, P Amsterdam 1971 @@StartBracket@@43@@EndBracket@@ } *

