{ We cannot play at half speed here. Therefore, we should go all-in with 7.Qh5, when Black will not get the chance to castle long, reaching a decent position. }
7... g6 { White's choice of moves has been reduced here to 8.Qg5 and 8.Nf3. }
8. Nf3
{ Combined with the next move, this is a useful move to aim for a quick development of pieces and to open the e-file. }
8... Qxe4 9. Nc3
{ Time is of crucial importance in this position, not letting Black consolidate! The e-file is cleared for the White rook, in the meantime developing our pieces by chasing the queen. }
9... Qf5 { All the time, White's queen couldn't be taken. } 10. Qh4
{ Black's main problem in this line comes to light. Even after 10...Bg7, Black cannot castle because of the attacked knight. }
10... Be6
{ Blocking the e-file. If  10...Qxc2  11.d3 !  the queen will be trapped after Nf3-e1, so she is left without any choice but taking on d3  11...Qxd3  12.Rd1  We get to the point! After a double pawn sacrifice, the position is opened up dramatically  12...Qf5  13.Bg5  Black cannot get out with his king, while the queen got led astray on the middle of the board. What follows is gallery play from our side  13...Be6  14.Nd4  Qa5  There was no convenient place for the queen. After ...Qg4 we can play 15.Nxe6 threatening  Nxc7  mate  15.b4  Qb6  After ...Qxb4 we follow up with the same idea as in the stem line with 16.Nxe6  16.Na4  Qxb4  17.Nxe6  Qxh4  18.Nxc7# }
11. d3 { Clearing the path for the bishop to come to g5, or f4. } 11... O-O-O
12. Bg5
{ Also, here, the knight on e7 can be considered as the problem child. } 12...
Re8 { Getting out of the pin, but Black is still in a world of hurt after } 13.
Qd4 { Simultaneously threatening Qxh8 and Qa7. } 13... Rg8 14. Qa7
{ Black is helpless against the intruder. } *

