{ We of course do not trade queens as with a lead in development, we want to attack. Black's main problem in this line comes to light. Even after 10...Bg7, Black cannot castle because of the attacked knight. }
10... Bg7
{ This is the main move. Black intends to play Be6, and castle. Our queen on h4 really puts a dent in Black's plan, though. }
11. Re1
{ 11.d4 ?!  seems like a normal move, but it has its flaws.  11...Be6  Of course, Black wishes to close the e-file.  12.Bf4  O-O-O !  Black is fine  13.Bxc7  Kxc7  14.Qxe7+  Rd7  Black's strong bishops and rooks compensate for the lost pawn. }
11... Be6 { Of course, blocking the e-file. } 12. d3 Qg4
{ While this may seem a bit weird, the idea is clear. Black wants to trade off the annoying queen on  h4  so he can castle. Black could also try  12...Bf6  13.Bg5  Bxg5  14.Qxg5  Qxg5  15.Nxg5  when Black's position is coming under pressure. }
13. Qg5
{ This oddity has appeared in practice no less than 13 times! The main idea of this move is shown after  13...Qxg5  14.Nxg5  . }
13... Qxg5
{ The most common response to 13.Qg5, although 13...h6 may be considered stronger. }
14. Nxg5
{ The point behind 13.Qg5 is revealed. After the bishop moves, White clings to the knight on e7. In summary, we are glad to be capable taking back on g5 with the knight! }
14... Bf5
{ Saving his pawn structure at the cost of development. If  14...Nd5  We can 'mutilate' Black's pawn structure severely, by  15.Nxe6  fxe6  I believe that we don't necessarily have to take on  e6  , giving some counterplay to Black along the e-file after Kd7 and Re8.  16.Ne4  when Black can't be happy with the outcome of the opening. }
15. Bf4
{ As seen often, the Black sheep of the doubled c-brothers is the latter one on c7. }
15... h6
{ This is practically forced, as Black has to start development, and there are not many other useful moves. }
16. Nf3 Rc8
{ After all, the problem of the king on  e8  hasn't quite been solved. If  16...Bg4  17.Bxc7  Bxf3  18.Bd6  Bf6  19.gxf3  Kd7  20.Ne4  when White is better as well. }
17. Re2 Be6
{ Another attempt to castle!  17...g5 !?  is an interesting alternative, given by Stockfish. However, Lc0 comes up with a nice idea to put our opponent under heavy pressure. When our opponent gives up the right to castle, in certain lines we can exploit the 2 weaknesses of Black:  (1)  (the pawn on c7, and)  (2)  the back rank.  18.Bg3  Kd7  19.h4 !  This is a highly inconvenient position for Black. How should he handle the attack on  g5?  For instance, after  19...f6  , we will play  20.Nd4  and 21. Ne6, giving us a large advantage. In the following correspondence game, White won impressively 1-0 @@StartBracket@@56@@EndBracket@@ Rodolfo Masera, L @@StartBracket@@2127@@EndBracket@@-Koelewijn, A @@StartBracket@@2161@@EndBracket@@ ICCF email 2016 }
18. Be5
{ A new move after which our opponent is balancing on a chord.  18.Rae1  is a quite harmless move for Black. After  18...O-O  Adhiban, aka 'The Beast', made an easy draw here. ½-½ @@StartBracket@@53@@EndBracket@@ Solak, D @@StartBracket@@2613@@EndBracket@@ -Adhiban, B @@StartBracket@@2561@@EndBracket@@ Moscow 2012 }
18... Bxe5
{ Seemingly, a very normal move. But in chess, 'nothing' is what it seems. }
19. Nxe5
{ Our knight is very active now, and Rae1 is coming fast. Note that some Nxf7 sacrifices are in the air. }
19... O-O
{ 19...g5  will not change the balance of the position  20.Rae1  Black is defenseless against the idea of  Nxf7  .  20...Nf5  21.Nxf7 !  Kxf7  22.Rxe6  A winning position has arisen on the board. }
20. Nxf7 { Optimally exploiting the pressure along the e-file. } 20... Kxf7 21.
Rae1
{ Black is losing material. Please note that after  21...Nd5  22.Rxe6  Rce8  White is completely winning due to the idea of creating a passed pawn decoy on the kingside. }
*

