15... h6 16. Nf3 Rc8
{ After all, the problem of the king on e8 hasn't quite been solved. } 17. Re2
Be6 { Another attempt to castle! } 18. Be5
{ A new move after which our opponent is balancing on a chord. } 18... Nf5
{ This is Black's most resilient move, and one which makes us work to prove our edge. }
19. Bxg7 Nxg7
{ After the doubling of the rooks, the knight on g7 fulfills an important defensive task of safeguarding the e6-stronghold. }
20. Rae1
{ White is now fully developed and ready to pounce on Black's position with the knights. }
20... O-O { A seemingly regular move which is likely to be played. } 21. Ne4
{ White intends to go c5 or f6. } 21... b6
{ Advice is hard to give for Black. White's position is much better overall. }
22. Nf6+
{ 22.b4!?  Is a sound alternative, displaying White's dominance. The positional idea is to fix the  c6  pawn. Black better not take on a2:  22...Bxa2?  23.Nf6+  Kh8  24.c4  The bishop is secluded from the game.  24...Bb3  25.Nd7  An odd-looking move; White is targeting  f7  .  25...Rfe8  26.Nfe5  This line reveals the superiority of the White knights. Black went astray after only a couple of normal looking moves!   26...Kh7  is even a mate after  27.Nf6+  Kh8  28.Nxf7# }
22... Kh8 { These kinds of positions are difficult to play, being so passive. }
23. Ne5
{ Likewise, the unprotected pawn on c6 needs our opponent's fullest attention. }
23... c5 24. g4
{ Note how every one of White's pieces are better than their Black counterparts. Black is getting 'squeezed', especially due to the fact that the square f5 is no longer available. White can gradually improve his position by, for instance, Kg1-g2-g3  (due to the fact that the king is a strong piece in the endings)  , f3 and h4. etc.   24.g4  Bxa2 ??  Leaves Black with the Fischer-bishop  (in his '72 Wch-game against Spassky)  .  25.b3 !  The bishop is incarcerated - after Ra1 it will inevitably be lost. }
