20... O-O { A seemingly regular move which is likely to be played. } 21. Ne4
Nf5 { Is maybe better than the stem line, but will definitely not equalize. }
22. g4 Nd6 23. Nd4 Bd5
{ The best under the given circumstances, but the positions arising for Black here are not a picnic.   23...Bd7  24.Nf6+   23...Nxe4  24.Nxe6  fxe6  25.Rxe4 }
24. Nf6+ { White aims for total domination. } 24... Kg7 25. Nd7 Rfd8 26. Re7
{ Black's position is entirely cramped:  (1)  his knight can't be moved to f5 due to the g4-pawn,  (2)  the rooks have not any apt squares,  (3)  the bishop cannot be moved to e6  (because of R1xe6)  and c4 is coming. The rest is provided for illustration. }
26... Nb5 { Looking for simplification but in vain. } 27. Ne6+ Bxe6 28. R1xe6
Nd4 { A cat-and-mouse-game follows. } 29. Rf6 Rf8
{ For the moment, Black defends f7: after Nxf8, Black can take on f6. } 30. Rf4
Ne6 { Hitting the rook, but the knight is not invincible. } 31. Re4
{ After a ludicrous maneuver R1e6-f6-f4-e4 Black is on the verge of defeat. White threatens both R1xe6 and Nxf8. }
31... Ng5 32. Re3
{ Keeping control, there is no need to change the balance of the position. }
32... Rfd8 33. h4 Nh7 34. Rf3
{ And after a long and tiring trajectory with the rook, f7 is undefendable. } *

