8. Nf3
{ Combined with the next move, this is a useful move to aim for a quick development of pieces and to open the e-file. }
8... Qxe4 9. Nc3
{ Time is of crucial importance in this position, not letting Black consolidate! The e-file is cleared for the White rook, in the meantime developing our pieces by chasing the queen. }
9... Qf5 { All the time, White's queen couldn't be taken. } 10. Qh4
{ Black's main problem in this line comes to light. Even after 10...Bg7, Black cannot castle because of the attacked knight. }
10... Bg7 11. Re1 Be6 12. d3 Qg4 13. Qg5
{ This oddity has appeared in practice no less than 13 times! } 13... h6
{ On the highest level, this move appears critical. However, after the novelty 15.Rb1, there are still plenty of problems for Black to solve. }
14. Qc5 g5
{ A good attempt to equalize the game, that happened in two correspondence games. The g5-pawn restricts our bishop and the e7-knight can be moved to g6. However, in order to castle Black is dependant on b6 and c5 to lock the a3-f8 diagonal for our Queen. Hence, with the king stuck in the center, he is still in danger and should be utterly accurate as each small misstep could lead to disaster. }
15. Rb1
{ A mysterious, innocent looking move - but with a lot of potential hidden within. It's a prophylaxis against Black's plan of secluding the queen with b6 and c5. The rook steps away from the diagonal of the g7-bishop and prepares the break with b4 after Black's aforementioned plan.   15.Ne5  Qf5  16.g4  Qh7  17.Bd2  b6  18.Qe3  O-O  19.h4  Rfe8  20.hxg5  hxg5  21.Qg3  Qh4  22.Qxh4  gxh4  23.f3  b5  24.Re2  b4  25.Na4  Bd5  26.Rae1  Ng6  27.f4  a5  28.Nc5  Re7  29.d4  Rae8  30.g5  h3  31.Kh2  Nh4  32.Rf2  Bxe5  ½-½ @@StartBracket@@32@@EndBracket@@ Vorontsov, G @@StartBracket@@2024@@EndBracket@@ - Cornelisse, J @@StartBracket@@2217@@EndBracket@@ ICCF email 2016    15.Ne4  Qf5  16.Qb4  Qb5  17.Qa3  g4  18.Nh4  Nd5  19.Rb1  Qb4  20.Bd2  Qxa3  21.bxa3  O-O-O  22.Nc5  Rde8  23.c4  Nb6  24.Ng6  fxg6  25.Nxe6  Bf6  26.Re4  h5  The position became very double-edged in ½-½ @@StartBracket@@57@@EndBracket@@ Stukalov, M @@StartBracket@@2244@@EndBracket@@- Kirsanov, V @@StartBracket@@2193@@EndBracket@@ ICCF email 2018 }
15... b6
{ Black is continuing with his plan closing the diagonal for our queen by  c5  .  15...Qf5!?  needs further practice. After  16.Ne4  Qxc5  17.Nxc5  Bc8  18.b3  we reach a double-edged position, but nonetheless I prefer White's chances slightly after the exchange of bishops.   15...Ng6 ?  would be good news for us: there is no way to close the diagonal with b6 and c5, since c6 is hanging with the knight on g6. }
16. Qa3
{ The normal square for our queen in these lines, keeping an eye on the e7 knight. }
16... Ng6 17. Re4
{ Testing our opponent to the bone! The queen has to be moved, after which White follows up with Be3 and Nd4. }
17... Qh5
{ Note that  17...Nf4  18.Bxf4  and Ne2 is coming next. The text move is dangerous because of... }
18. Ne2
{ when the queen starts a long and tiring journey across the board to find shelter. }
