{ The sideline 5... Ne7 should be taken seriously, not in the least because Magnus Carlsen played it twice. The move was first seen in 1967, when it was played by Book. It was then played by Paul Keres against Dutch IM Hans Ree four years later. Way ahead of his time, Keres used this creative move to obtain a draw without much effort . }
6. Nxe5 { Let's take the opportunity to open up the position! } 6... Qd4 7. Qh5
{ We cannot play at half speed here. Therefore, we should go all-in with 7.Qh5, when Black will not get the chance to castle long, reaching a decent position. }
7... g6 { White's choice of moves has been reduced here to 8.Qg5 and 8.Nf3. }
8. Nf3
{ Combined with the next move, this is a useful move to aim for a quick development of pieces and to open the e-file. }
8... Qxe4 9. Nc3
{ Time is of crucial importance in this position, not letting Black consolidate! The e-file is cleared for the White rook, in the meantime developing our pieces by chasing the queen. }
9... Qf5 { All the time, White's queen couldn't be taken. } 10. Qh4
{ Black's main problem in this line comes to light. Even after 10...Bg7, Black cannot castle because of the attacked knight. }
10... Bg7 11. Re1 Be6 12. d3 Qg4 13. Qg5
{ This oddity has appeared in practice no less than 13 times! } 13... h6
{ On the highest level, this move appears critical. However, after the novelty 15.Rb1, there are still plenty of problems for Black to solve. }
14. Qc5 g5
{ A good attempt to equalize the game, as happened in two correspondence games. However, Black should be utterly accurate as each small misstep could lead to disaster. Remember: his king is still in the center! }
15. Rb1
{ A mysterious, innocent looking move - but with a lot of potential hidden within. It's a prophylaxis against Black's plan of secluding the queen with b6 and c5. The rook steps away from the diagonal of the g7-bishop and prepares the break with b4 after Black's aforementioned plan.   15.Ne5  Qf5  16.g4  Qh7  17.Bd2  b6  18.Qe3  O-O  19.h4  Rfe8  20.hxg5  hxg5  21.Qg3  Qh4  22.Qxh4  gxh4  23.f3  b5  24.Re2  b4  25.Na4  Bd5  26.Rae1  Ng6  27.f4  a5  28.Nc5  Re7  29.d4  Rae8  30.g5  h3  31.Kh2  Nh4  32.Rf2  Bxe5  ½-½ @@StartBracket@@32@@EndBracket@@ Vorontsov, G @@StartBracket@@2024@@EndBracket@@ - Cornelisse, J @@StartBracket@@2217@@EndBracket@@ ICCF email 2016    15.Ne4  Qf5  16.Qb4  Qb5  17.Qa3  g4  18.Nh4  Nd5  19.Rb1  Qb4  20.Bd2  Qxa3  21.bxa3  O-O-O  22.Nc5  Rde8  23.c4  Nb6  24.Ng6  fxg6  25.Nxe6  Bf6  26.Re4  h5  The position became very double-edged in ½-½ @@StartBracket@@57@@EndBracket@@ Stukalov, M @@StartBracket@@2244@@EndBracket@@- Kirsanov, V @@StartBracket@@2193@@EndBracket@@ ICCF email 2018 }
15... b6 16. Qa3 Ng6 17. Re4
{ Testing our opponent to the bone! The queen has to be moved, after which White follows up with Be3 and Nd4. }
17... Qf5 18. Be3 { Where should the Black king hide? } 18... c5 19. b4
{ The true idea behind 15.Rb1 is divulged. } 19... O-O
{ This is Black's best move, and the only one which really poses us some problems. }
20. bxc5 { Free pawn? Of course we grab it. } 20... Bxc3
{ Black doesn't give up his strong bishop for nothing. He wants to eliminate the knight in order to play Bd5 on the next move. After  bxc5  the square  d4  became ours. For that reason, Black better refrain from  20...b5  because of  21.Nd4  Bxd4  22.Bxd4  White's bishop rules the board  22...Nf4  This active move will not come to Black's rescue.  23.Be5 !  After taking, Black is left with ugly pawns scattered all over the board. }
21. Qxc3 Bd5
{ So here it is, Black defended well, gave his king a shelter, and is about to win an exchange. Didn't we let him come too far? }
22. Nd2
{ Black cannot really take on e4, since then Nxe4 @@StartBracket@@with Nf6+ to follow@@EndBracket@@ lead to highly promising positions for White. }
22... Bxe4 { It reflects back on Black when he is too greedy. } 23. Nxe4 Rfd8
{ Freeing up the f8 square in case the king needs to run.  23...f6  does not keep White's pieces out  24.cxb6  cxb6  25.Rxb6  Kg7  Defending f6, but Black can't defend the 7th rank.  26.Rb7+ !  Rf7 ?  27.Rxf7+  Kxf7  28.Nd6+   23...Ne5  This blocks the long diagonal, and 'seems' to hold things together for the time being  24.Bd4 !  But nothing is as it seems...White does a dirty trick.  Rfe8  25.cxb6  cxb6  26.Nd6 }
24. Nf6+ { White doesn't hold back and finds a way to invade. } 24... Kf8 25.
h4
{ Menacing  25...--  26.hxg5  hxg5  27.Bxg5  as Black cannot take back the bishop due to Nh7+   Also winning should be @@StartFEN@@r2r1k2/2p2p2/pp3Nnp/2P2qp1/8/2QPB3/P1P2PPP/1R4K1 w - - 3 25@@EndFEN@@  25.cxb6  cxb6  26.Rxb6  threatening  26...--  27.Bc5+  Kg7  28.Nh5+  and Qg7 mate. }
25... Nxh4
{ The knight is lured to h4. Now Black can no longer set a block on e5.   25...Qe5 ?!  will not save Black either  26.Qxe5  Nxe5  27.hxg5  hxg5  28.Bxg5  b5  29.Re1 !  even leads to a mate, after  29...Nc6  30.Bh6#   25...Nxh4  26.cxb6  cxb6  27.Rxb6  Black is defenceless against White's pieces closing in on him. }
26. cxb6 cxb6 27. Rxb6
{ Black is defenseless against White's pieces closing in on him. For example  27...Rac8  28.Qb4+  Kg7  29.Nh5+  Kh7  30.Qb2  because of the knight on h4, ...Qe5 can't be played. Black is helpless against the mating threat on g7. }
