5. O-O
{ The most ambitious move! White stays flexible, keeping open the options of: 1. d3 or d4, 2. whether the knight should be moved to d2, c3 or a3. The American world-class grandmaster Robert Byrne named 5.O-O is after the Dutch IM John Barendregt, who played this move a couple of times in the 60's. White has already castled while Black's pieces are all on the back rank. Moreover, Black must make an important choice as to how to protect his central pawn since White has renewed the threat of Nxe5 after castling. }
5... Be7
{ Let me begin by telling you that in case you are not familiar yet with the 'queen desperado' you ought to examine this variation in which this concept appears abundantly. Furthermore, like the mysterious 5th queen's move to e7, 5...Be7 should neither be underestimated. It has been used in practice several times with success by Aronian, as well as Grischuk, Ponomariov and Svidler. }
6. Nxe5
{ The only move which tests Black to the bone. From scratch we put a knife to our opponent's throat. }
6... Qd4
{ Like in the 5...Be6 variation, because of the block on the e-file, Black hopes to regain the e-pawn. }
7. Qh5
{ Black is at crossroads here, he can play @@StartBracket@@A@@EndBracket@@ 7..Be6, which is considered as the main line, and @@StartBracket@@B@@EndBracket@@ 7..g6, which is not as popular as @@StartBracket@@A@@EndBracket@@ but should be taken seriously! }
7... Be6
{ 7...g6  Another way to deal with the threat on f7.  8.Nf3  In all 15 games which have been played in this line, Black always took on e5. And rightly so, as 8... gxh5 clearly favors White.  8...Qxe4   8...gxh5  ?  9.Nxd4  +-  9.Qa5  The pawn on c7 is hanging here. By bothering our opponent with such a small threats, he won't have time to bringing his king into safety.  9...b6  10.Qc3  This time it is the rook on h8..  10...Bf6  11.d4  One way or another, Black should block the e-file in order to avoid material losses.  11...Be6  12.Re1  Qd5  Evidently, our opponent should not allow Qxc6.  13.Qd3  ! A move to remember. White not only makes room for the knight, but also prevents long castling. }
8. d3 Nf6
{ 8...Qc5  This move has appeared 8 times in practice. Due to the inconvenient pin on the 5th rank, White should sac his pawn on c2 back.  9.Be3  Qxc2  10.Nd2  ! A strong novelty over Nakamura-Aronian. The knight is heading for c4. After }
9. Nf3
{ The Tabiya in this variation. It's fascinating and astounding that Black can try so many queen sacrifices here. }
9... Qxf2+ 10. Rxf2
{ Black wins the pawn back in this line. As a result of the check, we can't execute a queen desperado of our own with Qxf7+. }
