{ Stopping the threat, and gaining time.   9...Bg4 !?  Not as often played as 9...b6, but a plausible alternative. Black simply wants to take on f3 and castle long.   9...Qxc2  10.Qxc7  Qd3  This position appeared 3 times in practice.  11.Re1  Qd8  12.Qe5 !  Our queen is like a fly in the ointment. Black's success of taking on c2 and bringing the queen safely home, is nothing compared to the problems he has to solve regarding the security of his king.  f6  13.Qf4  Kf8  14.b3 !  From all sides Black's king is bombarded.  Kg7  15.Bb2  Bd6  16.Qc4  Bf5  It's an illusion to think that the bishop can keep its post, because of  17.h3 !  h5   17...Bd3  doesn't solve Black's problems.  18.Qc3 !  with Nd4-Ne6+ to come.  18.Nc3  Ne7  19.Ng5 !  Rf8  Black cannot take, because of   19...fxg5 ?  20.Ne4+  Kh6  21.Bxh8  Bxe4  22.Bf6  Bf5  23.Qf7  Back is undeniably losing his e7-knight.  20.g4  hxg4  21.hxg4  b5  22.Qe2  Bc8  23.Nce4  Nd5  24.Rac1  Black can no longer keep it dry, since after Bd7 we take on d6 and after Bb7 we go Ne6+  (1-0 @@StartBracket@@49@@EndBracket@@ Kolcak, M @@StartBracket@@2546@@EndBracket@@ - Nicholson, M @@StartBracket@@2478@@EndBracket@@ ICCF email 2008)  .  10.Re1  Qd5  11.Qxc7  Bxf3  12.Re5 !  Surprise, surprise.. we are forcing the exchange of queens.  Qd7  13.Qxd7+  Kxd7  14.gxf3  It the ensuing ending, it won't be easy to compensate entirely for the sacced pawn.  Bd6  15.Re1  Nf6  16.d4  Rhe8  1/2-1/2 @@StartBracket@@73@@EndBracket@@ Skoberne,J @@StartBracket@@2479@@EndBracket@@-Borisek,J @@StartBracket@@2506@@EndBracket@@ Ljubljana 2007  17.Rd1 !  This novelty holds the gates closed.  Re2  18.Bd2  As we all know, the rook on the 2nd rank is strong. Fortunately, we have the means to expel from its dominant post.  Rae8  19.Nc3  kicking the intruder out. After the retreat Black has to show whether he has sufficient compensation. }
10. Qc3 { This time it is the rook on h8.. } 10... f6
{ was played by the twofold Dutch champion Jan Smeets, but he didn't obtain a position he would've had liked to repeat. }
11. d3 { Aiming for Bf4. } 11... Qd5 12. Bf4
{ When Black is urged to move his king to  d8  , like in the game Van Osch-Smeets, Leiden 2014, we know that we are doing fine. Black could also try  12...Bg4  but after  13.Nbd2  White remains on top. }
