4. Bxc6
{ Black can take back with either the b-pawn or d-pawn, but only the last move has gained popularity as after 4...bxc6 he faces a hard time completing his development.   4.Ba4  The main concept of Morphy's Defense materializes when White falls for the 'Noah's Ark Trap'. This happened in 1929 when Steiner got ambushed in his game against Capablanca, but the current elite grandmaster Nepomniachtchi was similarly caught in it in a recent online game.  4...d6  5.d4  b5  6.Bb3  exd4  7.Nxd4  Nxd4  8.Qxd4  c5!  All of a sudden, White's bishop is caught after c5-c4.  9.Qd5  threatening Qxf7+  Be6  10.Qc6+  The check will not help Black.  10...Bd7  11.Qd5  c4  0-1, @@StartBracket@@55@@EndBracket@@ Nepomniachtchi, I @@StartBracket@@2784@@EndBracket@@ - Demchenko, A @@StartBracket@@2641@@EndBracket@@ chess.com INT 2020 }
4... dxc6
{ The contours of the RLE position are there. White gave up his light-squared bishop and the bishop pair, leaving Black with doubled c-pawns and behind in development. White has many options here. Lasker's main choice was 5. d4, but 5. d3 and 5. Nc3 have also been tried, remaining flexible and not committing the king to g1 yet. }
5. O-O
{ The most ambitious move! White stays flexible, keeping open the options of: 1. d3 or d4, 2. whether the knight should be moved to d2, c3 or a3. The American world-class grandmaster Robert Byrne named 5.O-O is after the Dutch IM John Barendregt, who played this move a couple of times in the 60's. White has already castled while Black's pieces are all on the back rank. Moreover, Black must make an important choice as to how to protect his central pawn since White has renewed the threat of Nxe5 after castling. }
5... Be7
{ Let me begin by telling you that in case you are not familiar yet with the 'queen desperado' you ought to examine this variation in which this concept appears abundantly. Furthermore, like the mysterious 5th queen's move to e7, 5...Be7 should neither be underestimated. It has been used in practice several times with success by Aronian, as well as Grischuk, Ponomariov and Svidler. }
6. Nxe5
{ The only move which tests Black to the bone. From scratch we put a knife to our opponent's throat. }
6... Qd4
{ Like in the 5...Be6 variation, because of the block on the e-file, Black hopes to regain the e-pawn. }
7. Qh5 Be6 8. d3 Nf6 9. Nf3
{ The Tabiya in this variation. It's fascinating and astounding that Black can try so many queen sacrifices here. }
9... Qxe4
{ Queen desperado number 2! Compared to 9...Qxf2, here Black doesn't give a check making it possible for White to play a queen desperado himself! }
10. Qxf7+ { White is aiming to open up the position. } 10... Bxf7 11. dxe4 Nxe4
{ Black got all he dreamt of - the two bishops in an open position - didn't he? }
12. Re1 { Black is 'e-filed', the poor king won't be able find a safe haven. }
12... Bg6
{ 12...Nf6  13.Bf4  Nd5  14.Bg5  doesn't solve Black's problems - not even close. }
13. Nbd2
{ Calm before the storm. White is trying to clear the e-file, making Black's inability to castle really felt. }
13... Nf6
{ 13...Nxd2  doesn't solve all of Black's problems.  14.Bxd2  Kf8  What else? Black can not castle and has to unpin himself one way or another.  15.c4  Preventing, after  Bxc2  , the loss of a pawn.  15...Re8  16.Ne5  Bf5  17.Re3  If Black doesn't react, White wins a piece with  Rf3  .  17...Bf6  18.Bc3  White's position is just more solid. He consolidated on square  e5  and will try to push his pawns forward by means of f3/h3-g4. }
14. Nc4
{ We are following the game between the Swedish grandmasters Brynell vs Hector. From this moment on Black should be on alert about all the possible knight intrusions. }
14... Bxc2
{ At least Black now has a pawn for his troubles. If instead,  14...Be4  in order to lock the e-file, in the meantime aiming to take on  f3  , White plays  15.Bg5!  After all, Black should lift his blockade, since  Bxf6  and  Rxe4  is a threat here.  15...Bxf3  16.gxf3  White allowed doubled pawns, but Black's king is not safe yet. He cannot castle and after Kf7, the knight comes with force to e5.  16...Rd8  17.Re2!  Doubling the rooks, leaves White in the driver's seat. }
15. Nd4 { Let's not forget about the other knight, being on its way to e6. }
15... Be4
{ is another option, but it doesn't prevent the knight leap to e6. It seems like this move just makes Black's position looser, as now there are ideas of Bg5xf6 winning the e4 bishop }
16. Bg5 O-O-O
{ The only move, the king had to be moved from the center.  16...Bd5 ?  17.Nf5 !  Bxc4  18.Rxe7+  is winning for White. }
17. Ne6 { leaves White in the driver's seat. } *

