17... Bd6
{ 1-0 @@StartBracket@@46@@EndBracket@@ Brynell, S @@StartBracket@@2489@@EndBracket@@ - Hector, J @@StartBracket@@2546@@EndBracket@@ Linkoping 2001 }
18. Nxg7+
{ Winning the pawn back, whereas the Black king cannot really get away. } 18...
Kf8
{ the best option, as 18...Ke7 loses on the spot.   18...Ke7  19.Bg5  Bxe5  20.Rxe4  is winning for White. }
19. Ne6+ { Now, White gains a tempo by retreating his knight with a check. }
19... Ke7 20. Ng5 Bxe5 21. Nxe4
{ Two major advantages stand out here for White, @@StartBracket@@1@@EndBracket@@ the more dangerous 3 vs 1 pawn majority on the kingside, and @@StartBracket@@2@@EndBracket@@ the exposed Black king, who still didn't succeed in finding a shelter.   For instance,  21...Rhe8  22.Bg5  Kf7  23.Bxf6  Bxf6  24.Kf1  Rad8  25.Re2  White consolidated his central knight, and is now ready for pushing his kingside pawns forward. }
