4... dxc6
{ The contours of the RLE position are there. White gave up his light-squared bishop and the bishop pair, leaving Black with doubled c-pawns and behind in development. White has many options here. Lasker's main choice was 5. d4, but 5. d3 and 5. Nc3 have also been tried, remaining flexible and not committing the king to g1 yet. }
5. O-O
{ The most ambitious move! White stays flexible, keeping open the options of: 1. d3 or d4, 2. whether the knight should be moved to d2, c3 or a3. The American world-class grandmaster Robert Byrne named 5.O-O is after the Dutch IM John Barendregt, who played this move a couple of times in the 60's. White has already castled while Black's pieces are all on the back rank. Moreover, Black must make an important choice as to how to protect his central pawn since White has renewed the threat of Nxe5 after castling. }
5... Be7
{ Let me begin by telling you that in case you are not familiar yet with the 'queen desperado' you ought to examine this variation in which this concept appears abundantly. Furthermore, like the mysterious 5th queen's move to e7, 5...Be7 should neither be underestimated. It has been used in practice several times with success by Aronian, as well as Grischuk, Ponomariov and Svidler. }
6. Nxe5
{ The only move which tests Black to the bone. From scratch we put a knife to our opponent's throat. }
6... Qd4
{ Like in the 5...Be6 variation, because of the block on the e-file, Black hopes to regain the e-pawn. }
7. Qh5 Be6 8. d3 Nf6 9. Nf3
{ The Tabiya in this variation. It's fascinating and astounding that Black can try so many queen sacrifices here. }
9... Qxf2+ { Another mind-boggling queen desperado. } 10. Rxf2
{ Black wins the pawn back in this line. As a result of the check, we can't execute a queen desperado of our own with Qxf7+.   10.Kxf2 !?  Not wasting any time on improving the king's position, is a genuine candidate move.  10...Nxh5  11.h3  Nf6  12.Bf4  O-O-O  13.Nbd2  Nd7  14.Nd4  Bc5  15.Be3  Bxd4  16.Bxd4  f6  1/2-1/2 @@StartBracket@@49@@EndBracket@@ Nakamura, H @@StartBracket@@2746@@EndBracket@@- Aronian, L @@StartBracket@@2765@@EndBracket@@ Kolkata 2018  17.b4 !?  Fixing Black's pawns; White is slightly better.   17.Bc3  c5  18.g4  b5  19.b3  Nb8  20.Kg3  Nc6  when Black was OK.  1/2-1/2 @@StartBracket@@49@@EndBracket@@ Nakamura, H @@StartBracket@@2746@@EndBracket@@- Aronian, L @@StartBracket@@2765@@EndBracket@@ Kolkata 2018 }
10... Nxh5
{ After matters have calmed down, White remains with the superior pawn structure. }
11. Nd4
{ Black is about to lose his bishop pair after Nxe6. After ...Bd7, we can force the exchange by Nf5, ...Bxf5. }
11... Nf6 12. h3 { The square g4 is ours; once and for all. } 12... Nd7
{ The knight is clearing the way for the bishop. } 13. Be3
{ Not attacking anything, but on this central square the bishop is omnipotent. }
13... Bh4
{ When Black just castles with  13...O-O  , then  14.Nxe6  fxe6  15.Nd2  , we follow up on a similar development scheme, like in our main line. }
14. Rf1
{ In the game, White moved his rook to the unnatural square e2. I believe that 14.Rf1 is an improvement after which White can claim an advantage.   14.Re2  Bf6  15.Nd2  c5  16.Nxe6  fxe6  17.Rf1  O-O  18.b3  b6  19.Nf3  Ne5  20.Nxe5  Bxe5  21.Ref2  Rxf2  22.Kxf2  Rf8+  23.Ke2  Rxf1  24.Kxf1  and the ending is drawish.  1/2-1/2 @@StartBracket@@49@@EndBracket@@ Volokitin, A @@StartBracket@@2640@@EndBracket@@- Lenic, L @@StartBracket@@2625@@EndBracket@@ Austria 2016 }
14... c5
{ We follow the similar plan as applied in the game Volokitin - Lenic. } 15.
Nxe6 { Of course, we are depriving Black of his bishop pair. } 15... fxe6 16.
Nd2 { The knight is more flexible on d2, than on c3, reaching b3, c4 and f3. }
16... Bf6 17. Rab1
{ White better refrain from c3 in this early stage, as after Ne5, d3 will be under attack. This pawn move should be played only once our king is on e2. }
17... b6 18. Kf2
{ History will repeat itself in the miscellaneous RLE-lines, the king is so often best placed on e2. From this square, we can start further operations with c3 and evt. d4, as the king does a great job guarding the d3-pawn. }
18... Ne5 19. Ke2 { White is ready for the pawn advance c2-c3. } 19... Ke7 20.
c3
{ White is aiming for the advance in the center, enhancing his influence there. }
20... Nc6 { Understandably, our opponent hinders the pawn advance. } 21. Nf3
{ White renews the positional threat of d3-d4. } 21... Rad8 22. Rbc1
{ An ingenious rook move in order to make the pawn advance d3-d4 work. The point of this move is that White sacrifices the d-pawn in order to invade on c7. He is clearly better in the ensuing positions. }
