{ Black solved the position of his knight, but what about his bishop and king? }
10. Nc3
{ White relies upon his faster development and his enemy's vulnerable king. }
10... Nh5 { Probably best, to release the tension somewhat. } 11. Bg3 Nxg3
{ The swap of knight against bishop is beneficial for Black in terms of simplification, but it has a detrimental effect on him due to White's improved pawn structure. }
12. hxg3
{ We take back towards the center. After 12. fxg3, Black would be happy to swap queens with 12...Qc5. }
12... Qc5
{ aiming for simplifications.   12...Rd8  13.Qe3  Qc5  14.Rad1  Transposes to the model game Dvoretsky-Smyslov after 12... Rd8. }
13. Rad1
{ White shouldn't run from this, as he maintains the better odds in the ending. }
13... Qxd4 14. Rxd4 Bc5 15. Rd3
{ White maintains his trumps in the shape of his strong mass of pawns. } 15...
Rd8
{ Black could as well opt for  15...Ke7  16.Rfd1  Rad8  but that doesn't change White's edge on account of his pawn majority. }
16. Rxd8+ Kxd8 17. f4
{ A plan we are familiar with now. White exploits his majority. } 17... Ke7 18.
Rd1 { White is slightly better because of his better pawn structure. } 18... h5
19. Kg2
{ ½-½ @@StartBracket@@27@@EndBracket@@ Santos Ruiz, M @@StartBracket@@2484@@EndBracket@@-Romanov, E @@StartBracket@@2622@@EndBracket@@ Sitges 2016. White can try to create something out of his pawn majority and move his knight to a better square, for instance via e2 to d4/ g1 and f3. }
