10... Nh5 { Probably best, to release the tension somewhat. } 11. Bg3 Nxg3
{ The swap of knight against bishop is beneficial for Black in terms of simplification, but it has a detrimental effect on him due to White's improved pawn structure. }
12. hxg3
{ We take back towards the center. After 12. fxg3, Black would be happy to swap queens with 12...Qc5. }
12... h5
{ How else could Black get his rook on h8 involved?   12...Qc5  aiming for simplifications.  13.Rad1  White shouldn't run from this, as he maintains the better odds in the ending. ½-½ @@StartBracket@@27@@EndBracket@@ Santos Ruiz, M @@StartBracket@@2484@@EndBracket@@ - Romanov, E @@StartBracket@@2622@@EndBracket@@ Sitges 2016. }
13. Rad1 h4 14. g4
{ This is an improvement over the stem correspondence game, putting the pressure on and giving Black limited space to freely move his pieces.   14.f4  1-0 @@StartBracket@@40@@EndBracket@@ Gaujens, A @@StartBracket@@2565@@EndBracket@@ - Matisson, J @@StartBracket@@2274@@EndBracket@@ ICCF email 2001  14...Rh6  with the idea of  15..Rd6  , Black most likely being able to stand the strain by the exchange of rooks and castling long, is something we don't want! }
14... Rh6 { with the aim of taking back control over the d-file. } 15. e5
{ Preventing Rd6. } 15... g5 { No other idea than ...Bg7. } 16. Ne4 Bg7 17. f4
{ In comparison to the 17.Nf6+ line in which Black will take on f6 and subsequently on f3, Qxf3 is being made impossible now.   17.Nf6+  Bxf6  18.exf6  Qxf6  19.Qc5  Qxf3 !  20.Rfe1+  Re6  21.Rxe6+  fxe6  Black stays in the game because of the hanging rook. Therefore, the intermediate 17. f4! has to be played. }
17... gxf4 18. Nf6+ Bxf6 19. exf6 Qxf6
{ As a result of 17.f4, Black's queen can no longer move to f3. } 20. Qb4
{ The point! The king cannot escape and so our opponent - being on the brink of defeat - has to cope with what turn out to be too many threats. }
20... Qe7 21. Rfe1 Re6 22. Qc3
{ Black found himself in an awful situation because of his weak king's position. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6. 5...Qf6 - the Morozevich Variation"]
[Black "5â¦Qf6, The Morozevich Variation: Introduction"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5
{ This is the Ruy Lopez aka the Spanish Opening. Black has a wide range of responses he can choose from, amongst others besides the main move 3...a6. First, there is 3...Nf6 - the Berlin Defense, which is the second most popular line. Former world champion Vladimir Kramnik boosted its popularity by beating Garry Kasparov in the world championships in London @@StartBracket@@2000@@EndBracket@@ with this tenacious line. The Berlin Defense will be covered in Volume 2 of this series, whereas the other main Black's defenses, amongst others: - 3...Nge7 - the Cozio Defense; - 3...g6 - the Smyslov Defense; - 3...Nd4 - the Bird Defense; -3...d6 - the Steinitz Defense; - 3...f5 - the Schliemann Defense, and; - 3...Bc5 - the Classical Defense will be covered in Volume 3. This will give you a complete repertoire in the Spanish Opening. }
3... a6
{ This is the so-called 'Morphy Defense'. There is instant tension on the board, as our opponent challenges our bishop to make up its mind. The most common move is 4.Ba4, after which the opening will branch into countless variations like the Chigorin, Breyer, Ragozin and Marshall. Black will find his move 3...a6 useful in all of these variations, as he can chase the bishop from a4 with tempo, unpinning himself in the process while also taking space on the queenside. However, completely different positions occur after our move in this course: 4. Bxc6, aka the Ruy Lopez: Exchange Variation. At the same time, uncompromising and attacking players, such as the world champions Bobby Fischer and Garry Kasparov, as well as the current elite player Shakhriyar Mamedyarov from time to time let off steam in this very entertaining line. }
4. Bxc6
{ Black can take back with either the b-pawn or d-pawn, but only the last move has gained popularity as after 4...bxc6 he faces a hard time completing his development.   4.Ba4  The main concept of Morphy's Defense materializes when White falls for the 'Noah's Ark Trap'. This happened in 1929 when Steiner got ambushed in his game against Capablanca, but the current elite grandmaster Nepomniachtchi was similarly caught in it in a recent online game.  4...d6  5.d4  b5  6.Bb3  exd4  7.Nxd4  Nxd4  8.Qxd4  c5!  All of a sudden, White's bishop is caught after c5-c4.  9.Qd5  threatening Qxf7+  Be6  10.Qc6+  The check will not help Black.  10...Bd7  11.Qd5  c4  0-1, @@StartBracket@@55@@EndBracket@@ Nepomniachtchi, I @@StartBracket@@2784@@EndBracket@@ - Demchenko, A @@StartBracket@@2641@@EndBracket@@ chess.com INT 2020 }
4... dxc6
{ The contours of the RLE position are there. White gave up his light-squared bishop and the bishop pair, leaving Black with doubled c-pawns and behind in development. White has many options here. Lasker's main choice was 5. d4, but 5. d3 and 5. Nc3 have also been tried, remaining flexible and not committing the king to g1 yet. }
5. O-O
{ The most ambitious move! White stays flexible, keeping open the options of: 1. d3 or d4, 2. whether the knight should be moved to d2, c3 or a3. The American world-class grandmaster Robert Byrne named 5.O-O is after the Dutch IM John Barendregt, who played this move a couple of times in the 60's. White has already castled while Black's pieces are all on the back rank. Moreover, Black must make an important choice as to how to protect his central pawn since White has renewed the threat of Nxe5 after castling. }
5... Qf6
{ The first game in this line which I retrieved from the database was a pearl of Morozevich, played in 1994 against Spanish GM Magem Badals. At first sight Morozevich's queen move might seem strange. White has already castled, and as a rule of thumb we know that we shouldn't move our queen in the first part of the game. Having said that, the e5-pawn needed protection while the queen makes room for long castling. It's not a miracle that this aggressive move was a choice of Morozevich due to his attacking style. It has also been tried by more sturdy players like Adams, Karjakin and Yu. }
6. d4
{ We can't give Black time to finish his development and initiate a dangerous attack with 6...Bg4 and long castling. This forces Black to react on d4. }
6... exd4 7. Bg5 { With tempo. } 7... Qd6
{ This is the main line with the idea of clinging to the d4 pawn. Now that the position has been opened and he is behind in development, Black wouldn't mind exchanging queens.   7...Qg6  A less popular alternative. Why is made clear in the next lines.  8.Qxd4  Bd6  9.Nbd2  A young MVL played this line with White.  9...f6  ? White can strike hard here and shouldn't let this opportunity pass. 1-0 @@StartBracket@@37@@EndBracket@@ Vachier-Lagrave, M 2458-Le Roux, J 2489 Val d'Isere 2004  10.e5  ! Of course, the center will be torn open!:  1-0 @@StartBracket@@15@@EndBracket@@ 56 Bucek, J 2300 - Svrsek, R 2230 Czech email 2003 }
8. Nxd4
{ Here, in this open position, it's likely that our opponent wants to solve the problem of his insecure king as fast as possible. The fastest way to seek shelter is long castling. We should consider two of Black's main options here: @@StartBracket@@A@@EndBracket@@ the 'old' 8..Bd7, and the recently by Caruana popularized @@StartBracket@@B@@EndBracket@@ 8..Be7. }
8... Be7
{ 8...Bd7  9.Nc3  We complete our development, waiting for Black to do something to oppose our bishop on g5.  9...Ne7  Black gets ready for ...O-O-O.   9...c5  ?? Black has to choose his moves carefully, as a mistake is easy to make. For example, take the not too odd-looking 9...c5.  10.Nd5  !  10...cxd4  11.Bf4  White is winning.  10.Be3  Being at crossroads, Black plays mostly 10...0-0-0, but 10...c5 has also been seen in practice.  10...c5  Aiming for the exchange of queens, relying on the bishop pair.   10...O-O-O  is another sound option.  11.Qe2  Making space for the rook to d1.  11...f5  Fighting back in the center.   11...Qg6  The queen moves from the d-file and prepares f5.  12.Rad1  f5  ½-½ @@StartBracket@@27@@EndBracket@@ Stevic, H 2506- Atalik, S 2584 Vogosca 2007   13.e5  ! A strong novelty. With the knight still on d4, Black has control over the blockade square.  12.Nf3  !?  12...fxe4  This move needs further practical testing.  13.Nxe4  Qg6  This move looks like the most obvious, though Qe6 shouldn't be underestimated.  14.Bg5  ! Pinning the knight. It's hard for Black to get away under the squeeze.  11.Nde2  Black ought to be reluctant to allow a backward pawn on d6.  11...Qxd1  12.Raxd1  Ng6  Of course, it's not easy to break Black's defences here. His position is solid as he has the bishop pair. Albeit all of this, I proudly suggest the following, not the most common, but - in my opinion - the most dangerous move.  13.h4  ! A highly unpleasant continuation for Black: how should he cope with the threat of h4-h5? This aggressive approach also has a positional idea: White is gaining important space on the kingside. }
9. Be3
{ At first sight, this bishop retreat may seem like not the most challenging choice. Besides, wouldn't we be glad to swap off one of Black's bishops, depriving him for the bishop pair a powerful tool in the ending? However, my enthusiasm for my initial choice of 9. Bxe7 quickly vanished after seeing Svidler's masterpiece, completely outplaying Naiditsch with the Black pieces. }
9... Nf6
{ Attacking e4, menacing 9...Ng4 and preparing for short castling. All looks fine for Black here, doesn't it?   9...Nh6  10.Qd2  g5  !? A splendid idea by Caruana. Black launches his attack immediately, not allowing White to grab the initiative in the center.   10...Ng4  This move was recently tried by Adams.  11.Bf4  White doesn't want to lose his bishop, and this also avoids mate.  11...Ne5  12.Nc3  !  12...Nc4  13.Bxd6  Nxd2  14.Bxe7  Kxe7  15.Rfd1  This is an interesting novelty over the game  Naiditsch-Adams, 2020 0-1    10...Qg6  Our opponent's set-up seems illogical. Specifically, the prospects of his knight are gloomy.  11.f3  ! White is stabilizing his central pawn phalanx, meanwhile preventing Ng4.  11.Nc3  !? A novelty and improvement over Naiditsch's play in his game against Caruana.  11...Ng4  Don't let yourself be mated!  12.e5  !! Vacating e4 for the c3-knight.  12...Qg6   12...Qxe5  Leads to disaster for Black, due to the opening of the e-file.  13.Nf3  Qd6  14.Bd4  How should Black cope with the attack on the rook? When he plays 0-0, White will get the upper hand after Rfe1 and Ne4 in a quite similar way to the 14... f6 line.   12...Nxe5  is simply bad, because of Bxg5.   12...Qh6  Hitting h2 and winning e5 but are seeing beyond all of this.  13.h3  Nxe5  14.Rae1 !  we get a very dangerous attack at Black's poorly placed king.  13.Rad1  !? Dear learners, I am pleased to recommend you this venomous concept. The major problem for Black here is that he can't really develop his pieces. Both 13...Bd7 as well as ...Nxe5 are no go's. When Black castles, we will harass the king with f4, opening the f-file.  13...O-O   13...Bd7  ? This is asking for trouble after 13. Rad1.  14.e6  ! A devious concept comprising interception!  14.f4  ! I repeat once again: in for a penny, in for a pound! In the ensuing lines you are going to train on, Black's king will be most of the time be in real danger. }
10. f3
{ This move copes with both of the threats. Maybe even more important is the fact that White sets up a bind against the knight on f6 and the bishop on c8. Where can they be moved at? }
10... O-O
{ This is the Tabiya of the @@StartBracket@@old@@EndBracket@@ 5... Qf6 line. The most popular moves are 11. Nc3 and 11. Nd2.   10...c5  !? This can be considered as a very solid line. I warn you: 10...c5 is a tough nut to crack.  11.Nb3  Black must spend time on defending c5, while White remains flexible. For instance, he can resume with Qe2, Nd2 and Nc4. Or with Qe2, Nc1-d3-f4.  11...b6  12.Nc3  Be6  As said, there are 2 ways to improve the knight on b3.1 Nd2, Qe2 and Nc4, and 2 Nc1, Nd3 and Nf4.  13.Nd2  !? The knight is heading for c4. Option 2:  13...O-O-O  14.Qe2  ! Hitting a6 and preparing for Nc4.  14...Kb7  15.Nc4  We have the better odds here, as the center is ours. }
11. Qe1
{ I'd like to suggest this 'novelty'. It has only been played once in 2009 in a correspondence game but didn't gain any followers. White steps out of the d-file, avoiding any possible queen exchanges after c5. He has a pleasant choice between Nd2 and Nc3, followed by Rd1 when the Queen on d6 is rather silly placed. }
11... c5 12. Ne2
{ Keeping all options open: the knight is heading for f4 or g3. } 12... Be6 13.
Nbc3
{ We are following the correspondence game Kurat-Butov. I believe there are more interesting tries here for White, fighting for the advantage. One of them is instantly playing Nf4. }
13... Rad8 14. Nf4
{ An excellent outpost for the knight. There are 2 strong continuations of which we can choose: 1 taking on e6, with Black giving up on the bishop pair, and 2 maintaining the knight on f4 trying to gain ground on the kingside. }
14... Qc6 15. Nce2
{ I am quite fond of this set-up. The knights are very flexible in picking their favorable squares. White will follow up with taking on e6 and Nf4, possibly Qc3, or even chooses a more aggressive plan with g2-g4 and Ng3 etc. The choice is all yours! }
*

