{ The first game in this line which I retrieved from the database was a pearl of Morozevich, played in 1994 against Spanish GM Magem Badals. At first sight Morozevich's queen move might seem strange. White has already castled, and as a rule of thumb we know that we shouldn't move our queen in the first part of the game. Having said that, the e5-pawn needed protection while the queen makes room for long castling. It's not a miracle that this aggressive move was a choice of Morozevich due to his attacking style. It has also been tried by more sturdy players like Adams, Karjakin and Yu. }
6. d4
{ We can't give Black time to finish his development and initiate a dangerous attack with 6...Bg4 and long castling. This forces Black to react on d4. }
6... exd4 7. Bg5 { With tempo. } 7... Qg6
{ A less popular alternative. Why is made clear in the next lines. } 8. Qxd4
Bd6 9. Nbd2 { A young MVL played this line with White. } 9... f6
{ White can strike hard here and shouldn't let this opportunity pass. 1-0 @@StartBracket@@37@@EndBracket@@ Vachier-Lagrave, M @@StartBracket@@2458@@EndBracket@@-Le Roux, J @@StartBracket@@2489@@EndBracket@@ Val d'Isere 2004 }
10. e5 { Of course, the center will be torn open! } 10... fxe5
{ After 10...fxg5, 11. exd6 Black king can't find shelter either. } 11. Rfe1
Be6 12. Rxe5 { No half measures. } 12... Bxe5 13. Qxe5
{ The bishop on g5 hinders Black's castling. } 13... h6
{ White will keep his bishop on the h4-d8 diagonal, impeding Black's castling. }
14. Bh4 Ne7 15. Re1
{ Simple and strong. Black is losing a piece. 1-0 @@StartBracket@@56@@EndBracket@@ Bucek, J @@StartBracket@@2300@@EndBracket@@ - Svrsek, R @@StartBracket@@2230@@EndBracket@@ Czech email 2003 }
*

