6... exd4 7. Bg5 { With tempo. } 7... Qd6
{ This is the main line with the idea of clinging to the d4 pawn. Now that the position has been opened and he is behind in development, Black wouldn't mind exchanging queens. }
8. Nxd4
{ Here, in this open position, it's likely that our opponent wants to solve the problem of his insecure king as fast as possible. The fastest way to seek shelter is long castling. }
8... Bd7 9. Nc3
{ We complete our development, waiting for Black to do something to oppose our bishop on g5. }
9... Ne7 { Black gets ready for ...O-O-O. } 10. Be3
{ Being at crossroads, Black plays mostly 10...0-0-0, but 10...c5 has also been seen in practice. }
10... O-O-O { is another sound option. } 11. Qe2
{ Making space for the rook to d1. } 11... f5 { Fighting back in the center. }
12. Nf3 f4
{ closing the position, but White finds a strong outpost for his minor pieces. }
13. Rad1 Qf6
{ After  13...Qh6 ?  White is winning easily with  14.Ne5  fxe3  15.Nf7  Qe6  16.Nxh8  g6  17.fxe3  and White maintains his material advantage after Nf7. }
14. Bd4 { with the idea of } 14... Qg6 15. Be5 *

