{ intending 15...g5. } 16. Ng3
{ 16.Qe3 ?!  Interesting but bad.  16...c5 !  We are following a correspondence game. The position is so difficult that even the computers don't know what to do here.   16...Kb8 ?  This was the trap which we set for our naive opponent.  17.Ng3  Qf7  18.Ne5 !  Any sensible advice is hard to give.  18...Qe8  What else?  19.Rad1  We threaten Qd4  (pinning the bishop)  , whilst the bishop can't retreat to c8, due to Rxd8, Qxd8 and Nf7.  17.Qxc5  Qxe4  Black interposed c5, to free the c6-square for his pieces.  18.Qa7  Looks threatening but is it really?  18...Nc6  19.Qa8+  Nb8  Black is fine. 0-1 @@StartBracket@@48@@EndBracket@@ Gaujens, A @@StartBracket@@2264@@EndBracket@@ - Kishkin, S @@StartBracket@@2458@@EndBracket@@ ICCF email 2017 }
16... Qf4 { is probably better, but we won't back down! } 17. Bxe7 Re8 18. Qe5
{ Not giving Black a moment of rest. The exchange of pieces turns out to be favorable. }
18... Qxe5 19. Nxe5 Bxe7 20. Ng6
{ Backed by Lc0's assessment, we can give it a go here. White has the better pawn structure in this interesting ending. }
*

