{ Here, in this open position, it's likely that our opponent wants to solve the problem of his insecure king as fast as possible. The fastest way to seek shelter is long castling. }
8... Be7 9. Be3
{ At first sight, this bishop retreat may seem like not the most challenging choice. Besides, wouldn't we be glad to swap off one of Black's bishops, depriving him for the bishop pair @@StartBracket@@a powerful tool in the ending@@EndBracket@@? However, my enthusiasm for my initial choice of 9. Bxe7 quickly vanished after seeing Svidler's masterpiece, completely outplaying Naiditsch with the Black pieces. }
9... Nh6 10. Qd2 Ng4 { This move was recently tried by Adams. } 11. Bf4
{ White doesn't want to lose his bishop, and this also avoids mate. } 11... Ne5
12. Nc3 Nc4 13. Bxd6 Nxd2 14. Bxe7 Kxe7 15. Rfd1
{ This is an interesting novelty over the game Naiditsch-Adams, 2020 @@StartBracket@@0-1@@EndBracket@@    15.Rfe1  Was the game Naiditsch-Adams, 2020 Biel @@StartBracket@@0-1@@EndBracket@@  15...Nc4  16.b3  Na3  17.Rad1 ?!  Rd8  Black combines 2 strong plans:  (1)  c5 and, subsequently, taking on c2, and  (2)  Nb5.  18.Re2  Nb5  19.Ncxb5  axb5  White is in serious trouble here. The mass of Black pawns is dangerous while a2 is a weak backward pawn. }
15... Nc4 { Hitting b2, moving to a3 or d6, and possibly b5. } 16. b3 Na3
{ Contrary to the game Naiditsch-Adams, White should prevent the exchange of the knights on b5, after which axb5 opens the a-file. }
17. Na4 { The threat of c5 and taking on c2, has been neutralized by Na4. }
17... Nb5
{ If  17...Rd8  18.Rac1  Gradually, White is solidifying the position. He maintains his preferable pawn structure and the better position. He can move his pawn from  c2  to  c4  , making the knight look stupid on  a3  . }
18. Ne2
{ White avoids the exchange of knights and maintains the better pawn structure. He enjoys a pleasant advantage here. }
*

