13... O-O 14. f4 { I repeat once again: in for a penny, in for a pound! } 14...
f6
{ This plan is one of Black's main concepts. Our opponent gets rid of the backward f-pawn and opens the f-file for his rook. }
15. e6 { Very sharp positions are arising now. } 15... f5
{ Is a serious option. The 6th rank is opened so that the queen attacks e6, and f6 is vacated for Black's pieces. }
16. h3 { White wants to get rid of the strong knight on g4. } 16... Nxe3 17.
Qxe3
{ We don't mind playing with the knights here, there is lot of music in it for our knights! }
17... gxf4
{ We don't take back with the queen, since Black will chase it away with Bd6, leading to unclear play. }
18. Rxf4 { We are losing the exchange, but we get so much in return. } 18...
Bg5 19. Nce2
{ The key idea behind White's play. The knights will occupy perfect places on f3 and f4, protecting our passed pawn. }
19... Re8 20. Nf3
{ In case Black accepts our gift on f4, our knight comes in with great force. }
20... Rxe6 { This move has its drawbacks as well. } 21. Qb3
{ The pin causes Black a massive headache. } 21... Bxf4 22. Nxf4
{ Black is hopelessly lost because of all of White's active pieces pointed at his king. }
