11... Ng4 { Don't let yourself be mated! } 12. e5
{ Vacating e4 for the c3-knight. } 12... Qg6 13. Rad1
{ Dear learners, I am pleased to recommend you this venomous concept. The major problem for Black here is that he can't really develop his pieces. Both 13...Bd7 as well as ...Nxe5 are no go's. When Black castles, we will harass the king with f4, opening the f-file. }
13... O-O 14. f4 { I repeat once again: in for a penny, in for a pound! } 14...
Nxe3 15. Qxe3
{ Yes, we gave up our bishop pair, but our knights need outposts and/or targets. Hence, that's what we give them! }
15... gxf4 16. Qxf4 Bh3 { Threatening mate and developing the bishop, but } 17.
Rf2
{ Black should better do something against White's venomous idea of settling on f6. }
17... f6 { A good move, but Black is not out of trouble yet. } 18. e6
{ It's beneficial for the knights that we keep the position closed. White cherishes his strong e-pawn, and our knights support the front-line force. }
18... Bd6 19. Qe3 { White's configuration is harmonious. } 19... Bg4 20. Rdf1
{ We are aiming for the frontal attack on f6 by means of Ne4. } 20... Qg5 21.
Rf4
{ In order to maintain the initiative, avoiding the queen exchange, White sacrifices the exchange. }
21... Bxf4 22. Rxf4
{ White has more than sufficient compensation here. His pieces are very active and his advanced pawn receives the required back-up of the knights. }
22... Kh8 23. Ne4
{ A forced line follows. Black cannot retreat to g7, as White will play h3, Bh5 and Nf5. }
23... Qe5 { Black gives up a piece, but he can take it back after f5. } 24.
Rxg4 f5 25. Rh4 fxe4 26. Rxe4
{ White has a very pleasant position. The well-supported e6-pawn is a thorn in the flesh for Black. }
26... Qf6 27. Nf3 { The knight closes the f-file and intends to hop to g5. }
27... Rae8 28. h4
{ A great move, as Black can hardly parry all the threats coming his way after Ng5. After 28..h6, the hole on g6 can be exploited by  (1)  Nd4-e2-f4 and h6, or, maybe even stronger  (2)  29.h5 and Nh4. Another dangerous idea is to attack by 29.Nh2 and Ng4. These lines exemplify the danger in which Black finds himself. }
*

