10... O-O
{ This is the Tabiya of the 5... Qf6 line. The most popular moves are 11. Nc3 and 11. Nd2. }
11. Qe1
{ I'd like to suggest this 'novelty'. It has only been played once in 2009 in a correspondence game but didn't gain any followers. White steps out of the d-file, avoiding any possible queen exchanges after c5. He has a pleasant choice between Nd2 and Nc3, followed by Rd1 when the Queen on d6 is rather silly placed.  For comparison   11.Nc3   11.Nd2 !?  This game resembles a lot to our main move 11. Qe1 and can serve our purposes as inspiration. It's instructive to see how Naiditsch outplayed Caruana  (up to a certain point)  .  c5  12.Nc4  Qd8  13.Ne2  Qe8  14.Bf4  b5  15.Ne3  c4  This is maybe too opportunistic: 15... Qc6 should have been preferred, although White is still enjoying an edge.  16.Kh1  Qc6  17.Nd4  Qb6  18.Ndf5  0-1 @@StartBracket@@49@@EndBracket@@ Naiditsch, A @@StartBracket@@2716@@EndBracket@@ - Caruana, F @@StartBracket@@2757@@EndBracket@@ Baden-Baden 2013 CBM 153, Andreikin, D  11...c5  12.Nde2  Be6  13.Nf4  Bc4  14.Rf2  Qc6  15.Qe1  Rad8  ½-½ @@StartBracket@@34@@EndBracket@@ Meier, G @@StartBracket@@2558@@EndBracket@@ - Adams, M @@StartBracket@@2734@@EndBracket@@ Kallithea 2008. I don't like the coordination between White's pieces and the rook on f2 blocks the queen. The most logical continuation is Rd1 or Rd2, leading unequivocally to mass exchanges. I would like to keep the rooks for the attack on the kingside. }
11... c5 12. Ne2
{ Keeping all options open: the knight is heading for f4 or g3. } 12... Be6 13.
Nbc3
{ We are following the correspondence game Kurat-Butov. I believe there are more interesting tries here for White, fighting for the advantage. One of them is instantly playing Nf4. }
13... Rad8 14. Nf4
{ An excellent outpost for the knight. There are 2 strong continuations of which we can choose: @@StartBracket@@1@@EndBracket@@ taking on e6, with Black giving up on the bishop pair, and @@StartBracket@@2@@EndBracket@@ maintaining the knight on f4 trying to gain ground on the kingside. }
14... Qc6 15. Nce2
{ I am quite fond of this set-up. The knights are very flexible in picking their favorable squares. }
15... Nd7 16. Rd1
{ Placing the rook on d1 in this position, doesn't lead to the immediate exchange of rooks. White prepares for a possible Nd5. }
16... Ne5 17. Qc3
{ Step by step, White is coming forward, pressing Black backwards. } 17... Bd6
{ 17...Bf6 ?  just loses a pawn, after  18.Qxc5 } 18. b3
{ A positionally sound move, increasing White's influence on the light squares. }
18... Rd7 19. Kh1 { White is not in a hurry and hides his king in the corner. }
19... Re8 20. h3
{ White intends to take on  e6  and occupy  d5  with a rook or queen. Moreover,  h3  creates space for the king. An alternative is  20.Bf2  A flexible move, leaving all options open for White. For Black it is very hard to guess what White's next move will be. White has a wide variety of options. For instance,  Bg3  looks annoying for Black. }
20... h6 { is already close to being lost after } 21. Nh5
{ White can blow Black's kingside up, with Bxh6 and Nf6+. } 21... Kh7 22. Neg3
{ White is now ready for f4. } 22... c4 23. b4
{ Not giving Black even the slightest counterplay. } 23... f6 24. f4
{ Black is being overrun. } *

