5... Qf6 6. d4 exd4 7. Bg5 Qd6 8. Nxd4 Be7 9. Be3 Nf6 10. f3 Qe5
{ a typical computer suggestion which would be a bit nerve-wrecking for us mortals. Black is begging us to push our kingside pawns forward - a plan which was already in the pipeline. }
11. Nc3 Nd5 12. exd5 Qxe3+ 13. Kh1 c5 14. Nb3 O-O
{ 14...Qg5  15.Re1  O-O  16.Ne4  transposes to 14... O-O. } 15. Re1
{ This whole operation is pretty risky for Black and unlikely that our opponent will go for this when he can't remember his lines vividly at the board. }
15... Qg5 16. Ne4 { White, centralizing his knight, wins the pawn on c5. }
16... Qh6 17. Nbxc5 f5
{ 17...b6  18.Nd3 !  I'd rather be White here since Black has to prove his compensation for the pawn - which is far from easy. }
18. d6
{ Knights need strongholds in the center. With this move Black structure is shattered meanwhile we create the so desired central sttongholds for our knights. }
18... cxd6 19. Qd5+
{ Gratefully using the vacant squares in the center. Next is a knight jump to e6. }
19... Kh8 20. Nf2 { Now that Be7 is hanging, Black can't take our knight. }
20... Bh4 21. Ne6
{ in this double-edged position, White is calling the shots. } 21... Bxf2
{ The only move to stay in the game is  21...Rg8  , a difficult move for our opponent. }
22. Nxf8 Bxe1 23. Rxe1
{ A picturesque image of White's dominant strategy with his knights. } *

