[White "7. 5...Qd6 - the Bronstein Variation"]
[Black "5â¦Qd6, The Bronstein Variation: Introduction"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5
{ This is the Ruy Lopez aka the Spanish Opening. Black has a wide range of responses he can choose from, amongst others besides the main move 3...a6. First, there is 3...Nf6 - the Berlin Defense, which is the second most popular line. Former world champion Vladimir Kramnik boosted its popularity by beating Garry Kasparov in the world championships in London @@StartBracket@@2000@@EndBracket@@ with this tenacious line. The Berlin Defense will be covered in Volume 2 of this series, whereas the other main Black's defenses, amongst others: - 3...Nge7 - the Cozio Defense; - 3...g6 - the Smyslov Defense; - 3...Nd4 - the Bird Defense; -3...d6 - the Steinitz Defense; - 3...f5 - the Schliemann Defense, and; - 3...Bc5 - the Classical Defense will be covered in Volume 3. This will give you a complete repertoire in the Spanish Opening. }
3... a6
{ This is the so-called 'Morphy Defense'. There is instant tension on the board, as our opponent challenges our bishop to make up its mind. The most common move is 4.Ba4, after which the opening will branch into countless variations like the Chigorin, Breyer, Ragozin and Marshall. Black will find his move 3...a6 useful in all of these variations, as he can chase the bishop from a4 with tempo, unpinning himself in the process while also taking space on the queenside. However, completely different positions occur after our move in this course: 4. Bxc6, aka the Ruy Lopez: Exchange Variation. At the same time, uncompromising and attacking players, such as the world champions Bobby Fischer and Garry Kasparov, as well as the current elite player Shakhriyar Mamedyarov from time to time let off steam in this very entertaining line. }
4. Bxc6
{ Black can take back with either the b-pawn or d-pawn, but only the last move has gained popularity as after 4...bxc6 he faces a hard time completing his development.   4.Ba4  The main concept of Morphy's Defense materializes when White falls for the 'Noah's Ark Trap'. This happened in 1929 when Steiner got ambushed in his game against Capablanca, but the current elite grandmaster Nepomniachtchi was similarly caught in it in a recent online game.  4...d6  5.d4  b5  6.Bb3  exd4  7.Nxd4  Nxd4  8.Qxd4  c5!  All of a sudden, White's bishop is caught after c5-c4.  9.Qd5  threatening Qxf7+  Be6  10.Qc6+  The check will not help Black.  10...Bd7  11.Qd5  c4  0-1, @@StartBracket@@55@@EndBracket@@ Nepomniachtchi, I @@StartBracket@@2784@@EndBracket@@ - Demchenko, A @@StartBracket@@2641@@EndBracket@@ chess.com INT 2020 }
4... dxc6
{ The contours of the RLE position are there. White gave up his light-squared bishop and the bishop pair, leaving Black with doubled c-pawns and behind in development. White has many options here. Lasker's main choice was 5. d4, but 5. d3 and 5. Nc3 have also been tried, remaining flexible and not committing the king to g1 yet. }
5. O-O
{ The most ambitious move! White stays flexible, keeping open the options of: 1. d3 or d4, 2. whether the knight should be moved to d2, c3 or a3. The American world-class grandmaster Robert Byrne named 5.O-O after the Dutch IM John Barendregt, who played this move a couple of times in the 60's. White has already castled while Black's pieces are all on the back rank. Moreover, Black must make an important choice as to how to protect his central pawn since White has renewed the threat of Nxe5 after castling. }
5... Qd6
{ This is the third most popular move, based on the number of played games. Only 5...f6 and 5...Bg4 have appeared more often in practice. This line hasn't lost any relevance on top level in the last 40 years. The first game with 5...Qd6 I found is dated 1965 in which the legendary GM David Bronstein used this move against Dutch IM John Barendregt. For that reason, I'd like to 'baptize' this line the Bronstein Variation. @@StartBracket@@I couldn't retrieve any older games than Bronstein's. Please correct me when I am wrong@@EndBracket@@. Since then, countless top players have imitated him, amongst them are: Romanishin, Huebner, Kamsky, Leko, Eljanov, Adams, Karpov, Svidler, Anand and Ivanchuk. The queen covers the e5-pawn, but can become vulnerable to a knight leap to c4 @@StartBracket@@Na3-c4@@EndBracket@@. }
6. Na3
{ Renewing the threat of winning the e5-pawn, not giving Black time to improve his pieces with ...Bg4 and ...0-0-0.   6.d4  exd4  7.Qxd4  Qxd4  8.Nxd4  Bd7  9.Bf4  O-O-O  10.Nc3  Ne7  11.Rad1  Ng6  12.Bg3  Bd6  1/2-1/2 @@StartBracket@@12@@EndBracket@@ Barendregt, J - Bronstein, D Hamburg 1965    There are two main moves we need to look at here,  6...Be6  and  6...b5 }
6... Be6
{ Keeping an eye on c4. White should not hesitate and forget about his knight on a3.   6...b5  This is another popular line we should take into consideration.  7.c3  ! White enhances his influence in the center and creates a new route for the knight. After a future d4, exd4, he can now take back with the c-pawn.  7...c5  8.Nc2  ! A delicate Knight-maneuver to boost the d2-d4 advance.  8...Bb7  9.Re1  White has to defend his central e4-pawn, before he undertakes action with d2-d4.  9...Ne7  10.a4  Ng6  From g6 the knight supports the crucial central e5-point.  11.axb5  axb5  12.Rxa8+  Bxa8  13.d4  Black is in danger here, being heavily underdeveloped. }
7. Qe2
{ Nevertheless, the knight is heading to c4. Our opponent is preferably not giving up on his bishop pair in this early stage of the game. }
7... f6
{ The most popular move in modern days.   7...Ne7  Black accepts that he is losing one of his bishops, but thankfully he is using the time to bring his knight to g6 or c6.  8.Nc4  The eagle has landed.  8...Bxc4  9.Qxc4  c5  So, Black is showing his cards: the knight is going to c6.  10.Ng5  ! Not giving Black a moment's respite. The pawn on f7 is under siege, and how should it be protected? Black seems to be limited in his choice and is forced to bring his queen to g6 or f6. White will follow up with d3 and f4, or he can prepare for a queenside-assault preparing b2-b4. }
8. d4
{ We can make use of the fact that the Black king is still in the center, and that we haven't 'wasted' a move on d2-d3. }
8... exd4
{ 8...Bg4  this move has been put in practice by the strong Ukrainian GM Oleg Romanishin, so 8...Be6 can't be underestimated. However, moving twice with the bishop on the first 8 moves with the bishop, can't be 'it'. }
9. Rd1 Bg4
{ This bishop move makes more sense for Black than on the 8th move, since Black sticks to his extra pawn.   9...c5  Holding on to the extra pawn, but for how long?  10.c3  ! White doesn't let the d4-pawn go, naturally. }
10. c3
{ As a result of Black's underdevelopment, White feels the strong desire to act. Moreover, we want our pawn back! }
10... O-O-O
{ 10...Ne7  trying to improve the knight's position via g6 and evt. h4.  11.h3  ! An innocent looking, though cunning move. Black can better not hold on to the pin:  11...Bxf3  All the Black players in this position chose to play Bxf3. Why would they release the tension?   11...Bh5  ?  12.Nc4  White makes ready for a discovered attack.  12...Qe6  13.Nxd4  The gods are with us as the tactics are working! Please train them in the ensuing lines.  12.Qxf3  The queens occupied a strong position, not in the last place to make Bf4 possible.   10...Qe6  Stepping aside from the open d-file makes sense.  11.Nxd4  ! unpinning and attacking the queen and afterward the a8-rook due to: Nxd4xe6xc7 and xa8. ½-½ 26 Kamsky, G @@StartBracket@@2705@@EndBracket@@ - Eljanov, P @@StartBracket@@2761@@EndBracket@@ Plovdiv 2010. }
11. Rxd4
{ Due to our lead in development, we take the pawn back with the rook. The character of the position remains open. There follows a sequence of forced moves. }
11... Qe7 12. Rxd8+ Qxd8 13. Nc4
{ The knight is perfectly placed on c4, hindering Black's development as Bf8-d6 is no longer an option. }
13... Qe8
{ This mysterious queen move is the only one which has been serious tested. }
14. h3
{ Once again - as so often in the RLE - we make good use of this subtle pawn move. The h2-square is of good use for our bishop or king. Moreover, we can unpin ourselves when we feel the time is there. }
14... Bh5 15. Bf4
{ Black should really watch out here, as White is set for the assault. In practice this position appeared twice, when the Black players didn't sense the danger, playing in a too optimistic style. }
*

