7... c5 8. Nc2 { A delicate knight maneuver to boost the d2-d4 advance. } 8...
Bb7 9. Re1
{ White has to defend his central e4-pawn, before he undertakes action with d2-d4. }
9... Ne7 10. a4
{ 10.d4  doesn't lead to an advantage, due to  10...cxd4  11.cxd4  exd4  12.Ncxd4   12.a4  d3 !  When the position becomes double-edged.  12...c5 !  Black is protected against Nf5 and is intending to exchange the queens. The open character of the position favors the bishops. }
10... Ng6 { From g6 the knight supports the crucial central e5-point. } 11.
axb5 axb5 12. Rxa8+ Bxa8 13. d4 { Of course, our pieces need to 'breathe'. }
13... cxd4
{ opening the position, with the king in the middle, is very risky. } 14. cxd4
Be7 15. d5 { The a8-bishop is entombed, and the only way out is c7-c6. } 15...
O-O 16. Ne3
{ The knight is close to its destination @@StartBracket@@f5@@EndBracket@@. }
16... Qd7 17. Nf5
{ The knight's route @@StartBracket@@Nb1-a3-c2-e3-f5@@EndBracket@@ is a long and impressive one. From f5 it paralyzes Black's position. }
17... Bc5 { was played in a correspondence game, but after } 18. h4
{ All lights are green for the final kingside attack. } 18... f6 19. h5 Ne7 20.
N3h4
{ White increased his dominance and went on to win. 1-0 @@StartBracket@@27@@EndBracket@@ Oviedo Araujo, A - De Zavalia, G @@StartBracket@@1818@@EndBracket@@ ICCF email 2016 }
