{ From g6 the knight supports the crucial central e5-point. } 11. axb5 axb5 12.
Rxa8+ Bxa8 13. d4 { Of course, our pieces need to 'breathe'. } 13... Qd7 14. h4
{ The knight is one of Black's main pillars, defending the central point e5. However, it doesn't get any rest after h4-h5.  14.dxe5 ?  This is a positional blunder. The pawn on e4 will be lost and Black enjoys the advantage of the 2 bishops.  14...Qxd1 15.Rxd1 Bxe4 =+ }
14... h5 15. d5 c6 { Of course, Black wants to give life to his a8-bishop. }
16. Ne3 cxd5
{ Here, I would like to suggest a novelty as compared to the correspondence game: ½-½ @@StartBracket@@43@@EndBracket@@ Mager, F @@StartBracket@@2103@@EndBracket@@ - Kotzem, E @@StartBracket@@2238@@EndBracket@@ GER email 2012. }
17. exd5 c4
{ After placing his f8-bishop to the active square c5, he seems to be out of trouble. However, White uses his lead in development to harass Black and attack his queenside pawns. }
18. b3
{ White is not merely intending to rip Black's structure apart, he also wants to 'liberate' his pieces. }
18... cxb3 19. Qxb3 Bc5 20. Ba3
{ The worst piece of White turns into the best. } 20... Bxe3
{ Black can't take on a3, with the king still on e8. } 21. Rxe3 Bxd5
{ If  21...Qxd5  22.Qb1  and Black is in serious trouble since he can't castle. }
22. Qb1
{ White keeps an eye on b5 and g6. Now Black can't castle or bring his king in safety otherwise. After f6 @@StartBracket@@intending Kf7@@EndBracket@@, White can take the knight. }
