{ The most ambitious move! White stays flexible, keeping open the options of: 1. d3 or d4, 2. whether the knight should be moved to d2, c3 or a3. The American world-class grandmaster Robert Byrne named 5.O-O is after the Dutch IM John Barendregt, who played this move a couple of times in the 60's. White has already castled while Black's pieces are all on the back rank. Moreover, Black must make an important choice as to how to protect his central pawn since White has renewed the threat of Nxe5 after castling. }
5... Qd6 6. Na3 b5 7. c3 c5 8. Nc2
{ A delicate knight maneuver to boost the d2-d4 advance. } 8... Bb7 9. Re1 Ne7
10. a4 c4
{ 10...b4  keeping the a-file closed.  11.cxb4   11.Qe2  appeared 28 times in practice, but I couldn't find any advantage after  11...Nc6  11...cxb4  12.d4  exd4  13.Ncxd4  N  c5  14.Nb3  Qxd1  15.Rxd1  15...Bxe4  16.Nxc5  Bxf3  17.gxf3  Nf5  18.Rd5 !  Not merely defending the knight, but working on a serious initiative over the entire board. The rook is excellently placed on d5.  18...Nh4   18...g6  19.Bd2  with the Black king still on e8 and b4 hanging, White is definitely better here.  19.f4  leads to a forced line, after   19.Re5+ !?  Be7  20.Rxe7+  Kxe7  21.Bg5+  Kd6  22.Ne4+  Kd5  23.Bxh4  Kc4 !!  Strangely enough, this exquisite king's run to our weak pawns, keeps our opponent in the game. However, it's not easy to find this and the remaining position is double-edged.  Be7  20.Be3  O-O  21.Nd7  We entered an ending which seems to be very hard to defend for Black. His queenside pawns are weak and White has the more active pieces. }
11. axb5 axb5 12. Rxa8+ Bxa8 13. b3 cxb3 14. Na3 c6 15. Qxb3 Ng6 16. Nc2
{ Peculiarly enough, this strong move only appeared twice in correspondence games. The mainstream theory was 16.c4 or 16. d4. After 16.Nc2, White has two major ideas, first, Nc2-e3-f5, and, second,  Ba3.   16.c4  b4  17.Qa4  Qb8  18.Nc2  Be7  19.d4  O-O  was unclear in ½-½  @@StartBracket@@30@@EndBracket@@ Naiditsch,A @@StartBracket@@2664@@EndBracket@@-Anand,V @@StartBracket@@2803@@EndBracket@@ Turin 2006. }
16... Qe6
{ Apparently 16. Nc2 made the 'computer's blood' run cold, as in both of the correspondence games the players went for this queen exchange. In case Black avoids the exchange of queens, White finds a sound plan in:  16...Be7  17.Ba3  Qd7  18.Ne3 !  Heading for  f5  , not raising the pressure yet with 18.Bxe7  18...O-O  19.Nf5  White has a strong initiative here. }
17. Qxe6+ fxe6
{ 1-0 @@StartBracket@@59@@EndBracket@@ Khromov,S @@StartBracket@@2472@@EndBracket@@ - Simakov,V ICCF email 2007 }
18. h4
{ This is a novelty; we are threatening to chase away the knight with h4-h5 when e5 is hanging. After  18...h5  19.Ng5  White knocks on Black's door. White is much better here. }
