{ The most popular move in modern days. } 8. d4
{ We can make use of the fact that the Black king is still in the center, and that we haven't 'wasted' a move on d2-d3. }
8... exd4 9. Rd1 Bg4
{ This bishop move makes more sense for Black than on the 8th move, since Black sticks to his extra pawn. }
10. c3
{ As a result of Black's underdevelopment, White feels the strong desire to act. }
10... Ne7 { trying to improve the knight's position via g6 and evt. h4. } 11.
h3
{ An innocent looking, though cunning move. Black should not hold on to the pin: }
11... Bh5 12. Nc4 { White makes ready for a discovered attack. } 12... Qe6 13.
Nxd4 Bxe2 14. Nxe6
{ Both the rook and the knight are 'en prise', but it doesn't keep White from breaking in. White menaces to take on c7, subsequently on a8. }
14... Rc8
{ White will lose material, but that doesn't matter because of the following splendid idea. }
15. Nxc7+ Rxc7 16. Nd6+ Kd7
{ Though being a piece down, White can afford a quiet move here. } 17. Rd2
{ Black is in serious trouble. He has to deal with 2 threats: Nf7+ and evt. Rxe2. }
17... Ke6 18. Rxe2 { The knight cannot be taken, surprisingly. } 18... Rd7 19.
Nc4 Rd1+
{ The pin looks threatening, but actually White can chase the rook away from the back rank. }
20. Kh2 Ng6 21. Ne3
{ The Black rook has to retreat from the first rank, after which Black lacks sufficient counterplay for the pawn. }
