h3
{ An innocent looking, though cunning move. Black can better not hold on to the pin: }
11... Bxf3
{ All the Black players in this position chose to play Bxf3. Why would they release the tension? }
12. Qxf3
{ The queens occupied a strong position, not in the last place to make Bf4 possible. }
12... Ng6 13. cxd4 Be7 { Black should have gone for Qe6, not allowing Nc4. }
14. Nc4 { Now things go quickly downhill for Black. } 14... Qe6 15. d5 Qf7
{ 0-1 @@StartBracket@@57@@EndBracket@@ Brynell, S @@StartBracket@@2435@@EndBracket@@ - Sokolov, I @@StartBracket@@2645@@EndBracket@@, Malmo 1995 }
16. Bf4
{ This is a plan to remember. The c7-pawn, last in line, often becomes vulnerable. Black can barely hold the pawn. }
16... Rc8 17. d6 { White breaks through. } 17... cxd6 18. Nxd6+ Bxd6 19. Bxd6
Ne7 20. Bc5
{ When Black would be hopelessly lost, as he can't castle due to Rd7. } *

