{ The queens occupied a strong position, not in the last place to make Bf4 possible. }
12... Qe6 13. Bf4
{ 13.cxd4  doesn't secure our desired opening advantage, since Black can go  O-O-O  14.Nc2  Ng6  Black intends ...Bd6 and ...Rhe8, exerting full pressure on the center. In the meantime, White is not well-coordinated. }
13... dxc3 { This greedy move may well be too risky for Black. } 14. Qxc3 Qxe4
{ Once again Black is too eager to win material. It comes against a too high price. }
15. Rd4
{ Making space for the other rook and not giving Black time to organize. }
15... Qf5 16. g4 Qg6 17. Bxc7
{ The c7-pawn had the important function of protecting d6. The knight on d6 will not be a welcome guest. }
17... Nd5 18. Re1+ Kf7 19. Qb3
{ With the simultaneous threat comprising Qxb7 and Rxd5. } 19... Kg8
{ At least Rxd5 can be dealt with. } 20. Nc4
{ We'd rather involve more of our pieces into play, than win a pawn. } 20...
Qf7 21. Qxb7 Rd8 22. Na5
{ Covering the queen and renewing the threat of 23.Bxd8. } 22... Rd7
{ Black couldn't take the bishop, since the rook would be hanging. } 23. Qxc6
{ When Black can't break out and is in real danger here. } *

