1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5
{ This is the Ruy Lopez aka the Spanish Opening. Black has a wide range of responses he can choose from, amongst others besides the main move 3...a6. First, there is 3...Nf6 - the Berlin Defense, which is the second most popular line. Former world champion Vladimir Kramnik boosted its popularity by beating Garry Kasparov in the world championships in London @@StartBracket@@2000@@EndBracket@@ with this tenacious line. The Berlin Defense will be covered in Volume 2 of this series, whereas the other main Black's defenses, amongst others: - 3...Nge7 - the Cozio Defense; - 3...g6 - the Smyslov Defense; - 3...Nd4 - the Bird Defense; -3...d6 - the Steinitz Defense; - 3...f5 - the Schliemann Defense, and; - 3...Bc5 - the Classical Defense will be covered in Volume 3. This will give you a complete repertoire in the Spanish Opening. }
3... a6
{ This is the so-called 'Morphy Defense'. There is instant tension on the board, as our opponent challenges our bishop to make up its mind. The most common move is 4.Ba4, after which the opening will branch into countless variations like the Chigorin, Breyer, Ragozin and Marshall. Black will find his move 3...a6 useful in all of these variations, as he can chase the bishop from a4 with tempo, unpinning himself in the process while also taking space on the queenside. However, completely different positions occur after our move in this course: 4. Bxc6, aka the Ruy Lopez: Exchange Variation. At the same time, uncompromising and attacking players, such as the world champions Bobby Fischer and Garry Kasparov, as well as the current elite player Shakhriyar Mamedyarov from time to time let off steam in this very entertaining line. }
4. Bxc6
{ Black can take back with either the b-pawn or d-pawn, but only the last move has gained popularity as after 4...bxc6 he faces a hard time completing his development.   4.Ba4  The main concept of Morphy's Defense materializes when White falls for the 'Noah's Ark Trap'. This happened in 1929 when Steiner got ambushed in his game against Capablanca, but the current elite grandmaster Nepomniachtchi was similarly caught in it in a recent online game.  4...d6  5.d4  b5  6.Bb3  exd4  7.Nxd4  Nxd4  8.Qxd4  c5!  All of a sudden, White's bishop is caught after c5-c4.  9.Qd5  threatening Qxf7+  Be6  10.Qc6+  The check will not help Black.  10...Bd7  11.Qd5  c4  0-1, @@StartBracket@@55@@EndBracket@@ Nepomniachtchi, I @@StartBracket@@2784@@EndBracket@@ - Demchenko, A @@StartBracket@@2641@@EndBracket@@ chess.com INT 2020 }
4... dxc6
{ The contours of the RLE position are there. White gave up his light-squared bishop and the bishop pair, leaving Black with doubled c-pawns and behind in development. White has many options here. Lasker's main choice was 5. d4, but 5. d3 and 5. Nc3 have also been tried, remaining flexible and not committing the king to g1 yet. }
5. O-O
{ The most ambitious move! White stays flexible, keeping open the options of: 1. d3 or d4, 2. whether the knight should be moved to d2, c3 or a3. The American world-class grandmaster Robert Byrne named 5.O-O is after the Dutch IM John Barendregt, who played this move a couple of times in the 60's. White has already castled while Black's pieces are all on the back rank. Moreover, Black must make an important choice as to how to protect his central pawn since White has renewed the threat of Nxe5 after castling. }
5... Qd6
{ This is the third most popular move, based on the number of played games. Only 5...f6 and 5...Bg4 have appeared more often in practice. This line hasn't lost any relevance on top level in the last 40 years. The first game with 5...Qd6 I found is dated 1965 in which the legendary GM David Bronstein used this move against Dutch IM John Barendregt. For that reason, I'd like to 'baptize' this line the Bronstein Variation. @@StartBracket@@I couldn't retrieve any older games than Bronstein's. Please correct me when I am wrong@@EndBracket@@. Since then, countless top players have imitated him, amongst them are: Romanishin, Huebner, Kamsky, Leko, Eljanov, Adams, Karpov, Svidler, Anand and Ivanchuk. The queen covers the e5-pawn, but can become vulnerable to a knight leap to c4 @@StartBracket@@Na3-c4@@EndBracket@@. }
6. Na3
{ Renewing the threat of winning the e5-pawn, not giving Black time to improve his pieces with ...Bg4 and ...0-0-0. }
6... Be6
{ Keeping an eye on c4. White should not hesitate and forget about his knight on a3. }
7. Qe2 { Nevertheless, the knight is heading to c4. } 7... f6
{ The most popular move in modern days. } 8. d4
{ We can make use of the fact that the Black king is still in the center, and that we haven't 'wasted' a move on d2-d3. }
8... exd4 9. Rd1 Bg4
{ This bishop move makes more sense for Black than on the 8th move, since Black sticks to his extra pawn. }
10. c3
{ As a result of Black's underdevelopment, White feels the strong desire to act. }
10... O-O-O 11. Rxd4 { There follows a sequence of forced moves. } 11... Qe7
12. Rxd8+ Qxd8 13. Nc4
{ The knight is perfectly placed on c4, hindering Black's development as Bf8-d6 is no longer an option. }
13... Qe8
{ This mysterious queen move is the only one which has been serious tested. }
14. h3 { Once again we make good use of this subtle pawn move. } 14... Bh5 15.
Bf4
{ Black should really watch out here, as White is set for the assault. In practice this position appeared twice, when the Black players didn't sense the danger, playing in a too optimistic style. }
15... g5
{ Seemingly, Black starts an offense on our king with his pieces unemployed. }
16. Bh2 g4
{ Too frivolous. Black is just not ready for the @@StartBracket@@counter@@EndBracket@@attack. Instead, he should have played Bc5.   16...Qe6  this move happened once, in a correspondence game.  17.Qd3  c5  18.Rd1  Be7  19.Ne3  Nh6  20.Nd5  1-0 @@StartBracket@@61@@EndBracket@@ Noble, M - Hassim, U LSS email 2007 }
17. hxg4 Bxg4 18. Qe3
{ The defects of Black's play are manifested. The queen threatens via a7 and f4 to hit his opponents on his most vulnerable places. }
18... Kb8 { Preventing Qa7 but missing another tactic. } 19. Bxc7+
{ White is winning a pawn. } 19... Kxc7 20. Qf4+ *

