4. Bxc6
{ Black can take back with either the b-pawn or d-pawn, but only the last move has gained popularity as after 4...bxc6 he faces a hard time completing his development.   4.Ba4  The main concept of Morphy's Defense materializes when White falls for the 'Noah's Ark Trap'. This happened in 1929 when Steiner got ambushed in his game against Capablanca, but the current elite grandmaster Nepomniachtchi was similarly caught in it in a recent online game.  4...d6  5.d4  b5  6.Bb3  exd4  7.Nxd4  Nxd4  8.Qxd4  c5!  All of a sudden, White's bishop is caught after c5-c4.  9.Qd5  threatening Qxf7+  Be6  10.Qc6+  The check will not help Black.  10...Bd7  11.Qd5  c4  0-1, @@StartBracket@@55@@EndBracket@@ Nepomniachtchi, I @@StartBracket@@2784@@EndBracket@@ - Demchenko, A @@StartBracket@@2641@@EndBracket@@ chess.com INT 2020 }
4... dxc6
{ The contours of the RLE position are there. White gave up his light-squared bishop and the bishop pair, leaving Black with doubled c-pawns and behind in development. White has many options here. Lasker's main choice was 5. d4, but 5. d3 and 5. Nc3 have also been tried, remaining flexible and not committing the king to g1 yet. }
5. O-O
{ The most ambitious move! White stays flexible, keeping open the options of: 1. d3 or d4, 2. whether the knight should be moved to d2, c3 or a3. The American world-class grandmaster Robert Byrne named 5.O-O is after the Dutch IM John Barendregt, who played this move a couple of times in the 60's. White has already castled while Black's pieces are all on the back rank. Moreover, Black must make an important choice as to how to protect his central pawn since White has renewed the threat of Nxe5 after castling. }
5... Bd6
{ Considering the current theory, 5... Bd6 is one of the strongest and most popular responses for Black here. Contrary to all the modern and odd-looking Queen moves 5...Qd6, 5...Qf6 and 5...Qe7, this healthy developing move with the bishop has its roots all the way back in 1867, when Scottish Chess master George Henry Mackenzie used this movem obtaining an equal game. Given its solid reputation, the adepts on top level are countless: Carlsen, Aronian, Svidler, Wojtaszek, Vitiugov, Adams, Fressinet and Vidit etc. It is also GM Jan Gustafsson's recommendation in his lifetime repertoire for Black after 1.e4 e5. }
6. d4 { White opens up the center and develops a dangerous initiative. } 6...
exd4
{ 6...Bg4  is an inaccuracy, allowing White to grab a large advantage.  7.dxe5  Bxf3  8.Qxf3  Black got voluntarily rid of his bishop pair and White is running a smooth development.  8...Bxe5  9.Qb3  ! This unexpected queen shift frees the f3-square for the b1-knight. Meanwhile, Black has to waste time on the defence of b7. }
7. Qxd4
{ The queen is attacking the g7-pawn, as a result of which Black cannot move his knight out. }
7... f6
{ Blocking the diagonal, Black is now ready for Ne7 and Ng6, and evt. Be6. Black is very flexible, as he can switch plans of short and long castling. }
8. Be3
{ The bishop is positionally better placed on e3, compared to fianchettoing it on b2. From e3 it reaches both flanks. White can start with }
8... Ne7
{ 8...Be6  9.Nbd2  Is a transposition to our main line, after  9...Ne7 } 9.
Nbd2
{ This is the right square for the knight. It goes to c4 from where it hits Black d6-bishop. }
9... Be6 { Temporarily preventing the White knight from moving to c4. } 10. Qc3
{ A delicate move. The queen makes place for the knight and prevents any tactical threats such as Bx h2.   10.Nc4  ? comes too early, because of the following discovered check.  10...Bxh2+  !  11.Kxh2  Qxd4  The knight on c4 is missing its defender.  12.Nxd4  Bxc4  =+ }
10... Qd7
{ Throughout the latest years this move gained more followers as compared to the other competitor 10... Ng6. Here, I'd like to step off the main paths of 11.Nd4 or 11. Nc4, not merely to surprise our opponent, but because I truly believe in the proposed moves. We arrived at crossroads. As this is one of the most critical positions in the entire Ruy Lopez Exchange Variation, Black's set-up a tough nut to crack. I wanted to provide you with a wide variety of moves and plans which all prove to be very dangerous for Black in my opinion. You can choose between 11.Rad1, 11.a4 and 11.Rfd1.   10...O-O  is another option but won't make that Black escapes from the pressure.  11.Nc4  !  11...Bxc4   11...Qe8  Black vacates d8 for the rook and anticipating on Nxd6  12.Rad1  Rd8  13.Nxd6  Of course, the bishop pair should be defused.  13...cxd6  14.Rd2  += when White rejoices the better chances due to his space advantage and the weakening on d6.  12.Qxc4+  The White square on e6 is vulnerable: Black is inextricably missing his light-squared bishop.  12...Kh8  13.Rad1  As we have witnessed in so many lines in The Ruy Lopez Exchange, White operates in a harmonious way. 1-0 @@StartBracket@@18@@EndBracket@@ 45 Vecek, M 2278- Blanchard, A ICCF email 2018. White's initiative and better pawn structure make his life easy.   10...Ng6  This move was in common use a decade ago and has been put aside in popularity by 10...Qd7.  11.Nd4  Qe7  Protecting e6 and preparing for long castling.  12.a3 !  O-O-O   12...O-O  If I had to recommend a line for Black, it wouldn't be short castling. White can directly cash in with f4, threatening f5.  13.f4  White is better here due to his strong influence in the center.  13.f4  This move grabs loads of space from Black. And he can't dispose anymore of the e5-square. }
11. Rad1
{ This move has been played over 20 times, but not yet combined with the new idea of regrouping the knight to e1 and d3.   11.Rfd1  !? A strong idea, as White plays a useful move waiting which side Black chooses.  11...Ng6  Black is deferring his choice.  12.Nd4  O-O-O  Ahh.. his Royal Highness opts for the queenside after all.  13.f3  It's always a joy for the eyes to see such a strong pawn chain reaching to the center. Again, Black has plenty of choice in picking a move or plan. The most characterizing plans and positions for both sides are picked in my analysis below.  13...Qf7   13...h5  going out on a long journey in his endeavor to harm the king's position.  14.a4  h4  15.b4  This quick and dangerous attack seems to me as the most promising continuation.  14.Nxe6  Good timing to take just now on e6. Nc4 is no longer possible, and Black is losing a move by our delayed taking Qd7-f7xe6.  14...Qxe6  15.Nc4  The best square for the knight, covering d6 and e5. }
11... O-O-O
{ Gustafsson's sturdy retort to 11.Rad1. Given the solid reputation of the German's opening specialist, we'd better go off the main paths in the quest for an advantage.   11...Ng6  This move, like 0-0-0 should be played. As both of the moves are useful for Black, we can only guess his move order.  12.Nb3  !? sidestepping from the main line after 12.Nd4. As Black's position is a tough nut to crack, I'd suggest deviating from the main theory to confuse our opponent.   12.Nd4  is the main line here. I couldn't find any advantage here for us. ½- @@StartBracket@@16@@EndBracket@@ ½ 41 De Carlos Arregui, I 2433- Bescos Anzano, M 2567 ICCF email 2017  12...Bxb3  This panicking move happened twice in practice is the only move played so far in this position. Black players well prepared will likely come up with improvements fighting for equality.   12...b6  This move is a common theme in the Ruy Lopez Exchange. Black uses his doubled pawns to take important squares under control b6 and c5.  13.Nbd4  ! Now c6 is under attack.  13...c5  A logical continuation, but Black beyond the first doubled pawn we find Black's Achilles heel.  14.Nxe6  Qxe6  15.b4  !! A powerful move, emphasizing the weak doubled pawns on the c-file.   12...Bg4  !? Notwithstanding, there are 0 games in the database to be found with 12..Bg4, this is a serious attempt for Black in the quest for equality. Black should see that Nc5 is not dangerous for him.  13.Bc5   13.Nc5  does resolve the problematic pin, because of  13...Qc8  ! Black is better because he can take on f3 and play Nh4 threatening Qh3.  O-O-O  14.Bxd6  cxd6  The problem in this position is that White cannot drive the bishop off with h3 since he has to take into account Nf4.  15.Rd2  Currently, White is ready to move the f3-knight to make the g4-bishop look stupid.   12...O-O-O  N hasn't been played yet, but is an interesting alternative. And ultimately fit for the daredevils amongst us.  13.Qxb3  Preventing short castling, attacking b7.  13...O-O-O  14.Nd4  Rhe8  This direct move, attacking e4 has merely appeared in this position.   14...Nf4  ?  15.Nf5  ! Black position is torn down, his knight and bishop are both hanging whereas White is about to double his rooks on the d-file.  15.f3  ! A main pillar of our strategy in this line. White is fortifying his center, before undertaking ensuing operations on the queenside by means of a minority pawn attack.  15...Nh4  15..Ng4 is the only tested move. Black takes control over f5, preventing White's knight leap to f5 while aiming to start a minority attack on the kingside. This plan contains some deficiencies as well, though..  16.Qc4  ! This is a novelty. The idea is refreshing and straightforward. The queen makes place for the minority pawn attack b2-b4, a2-a4 and b4-b5. Meanwhile, her Majesty is hitting c6 while after c6-c5, White can now move his knight to b3 when c5 is defenseless. }
12. Ne1
{ Moving the knight to d3, subsequently to c5, or just prepare f4, gives White something to play for and urges Black to play cautiously. This relatively new idea will certainly sort effect to the unprepared opponent.   12.Nd4  Was the only move given by Gustafsson, after which he equalized with Black with  12...Rhe8  13.Nc4  Bxc4  14.Qxc4  c5  15.Nb3  Ng6  16.Nxc5  Qc6  17.f3  f5  as given by Gustafsson, Black is safe here due to his pressure on e4. }
12... Ng6
{ This may well be more testing for White, but it looks not likely that your surprised opponent will risk of stepping into a fork.   12...Be5  May well be a move which could appear on the board when you catch your opponent off guard.  13.Qc5  forcing a weakening to Black's position.  13...b6  Surely, the queen on a7 is an uninvited guest.  14.Qa3  Kb7  The most obvious way to protect the pawn on a6.  15.Nd3  The knight is magnificently placed on d3. }
13. f4
{ avoiding the exchange of the pieces after Nd3, Ne5. Moreover, Black's knight on g6 and bishop on d6 have been degraded to mere spectators. }
13... Bg4
{ The most apparent square for the bishop, avoiding the f4-f5 fork.   13...f5  is another move to create a blockade on the light squares.  14.e5  Be7  15.Nd3  @@StartBracket@@White do all within his power to impede Black from taking in his perfect blockading formation with the bishop on d5 and knight on e6.@@EndBracket@@  15...Bd5  16.Bc5  ! Depriving our opponent of his two bishops. In the meantime, in the battle of e6, we create free passage for the knight to c5. }
14. Rc1
{ A rather mysterious move, but after examining this position at full stretch, I'd say this is the best, notwithstanding Ra1 as Rb1 come into consideration. }
14... Rhe8 15. Rf2
{ Black should be on his'qui vive' after this move, as his bishop can easily be trapped after h3.   15.h3  is not catching the bishop, because of  15...Be2 }
15... Ne7
{ This is defending on a class out of this world. The prophylaxis is against Nd3, against which immediate counteraction should be undertaken.   15...Nf8  is another plausible move for Black the knight is heading to e6, but I still prefer White. }
16. h3
{ 16.Nd3  !? is another razor-sharp continuation after which Black will be tested to the bone.  16...Nd5  17.exd5  Rxe3  18.Qd4  The queen comes in; 19.Qd4-a7 can't be prevented anymore!  18...Qe7  19.dxc6  looks quite dangerous for Black, to say the least. }
16... Bh5
{ Extremely double-edged position is arising now. The Black player should conduct his defensive job close to perfection in order to avoid his position becoming quickly worse. }
17. Nd3
{ Black should act here, otherwise risking that White will pull the strings. In the following lines we will encounter the sharp possibilities our opponent can throw at us. }
*

