exd4 7. Qxd4
{ The queen is attacking the g7-pawn, as a result of which Black cannot move his knight out. }
7... f6
{ Blocking the diagonal, Black is now ready for Ne7 and Ng6, and evt. Be6. Black is very flexible, as he can switch plans of short and long castling. }
8. Be3
{ The bishop is positionally better placed on e3, compared to fianchettoing it on b2. From e3 it reaches both flanks. }
8... Ne7
{ 8...Be6  9.Nbd2  is a transposition to our main line. 1-0 @@StartBracket@@9@@EndBracket@@ Varonen, H @@StartBracket@@1923@@EndBracket@@ - Saarikangas, M @@StartBracket@@1928@@EndBracket@@ ICCF email 2019, after  9...Ne7 }
9. Nbd2
{ This is the right square for the knight. It goes to c4 from where it hits the Black d6-bishop. }
9... Be6 { Temporarily preventing the White knight from moving to c4. } 10. Qc3
{ A delicate move. The queen makes place for the knight and prevents any tactical threats such as ...Bxh2.   10.Nc4 ?  comes too early, because of the following discovered check.  10...Bxh2+ !  11.Kxh2  Qxd4  The knight on c4 is missing its defender.  12.Nxd4  Bxc4  =+ }
10... O-O
{ is another option but it won't allow Black to escape from the pressure. } 11.
Nc4 Qe8 { Black vacates d8 for the rook and anticipating on Nxd6 } 12. Rad1 Rd8
13. Nxd6 { Of course, the bishop pair should be defused. } 13... cxd6 14. Rd2
{ when White has the better chances due to his space advantage and the weak pawn on d6. }
