{ is another option but won't make that Black escapes from the pressure. } 11.
Nc4 Bxc4 12. Qxc4+
{ The White square on e6 is vulnerable: Black is inextricably missing his light squared bishop. }
12... Kh8 13. Rad1
{ As we have witnessed in so many lines in The Ruy Lopez Exchange, White operates in a harmonious way. }
13... Qe8 14. Bc5
{ Wow! What a nice concept. The central bishop on d6 was Black's pivot. Now that it's exchanged, the d-file will fall in White's hands all the possible counterplay and hopes have been smashed. }
14... Bxc5 15. Qxc5
{ Now that the dust has settled, as so many pieces have been swapped, we see that White is on top. Besides his better development, his pawn structure prevails. }
15... b6 16. Qe3 { The best site to proceed with further central operations. }
16... c5 17. e5
{ After the exchange on e5, this square will be usable for White's pieces. }
17... fxe5 18. Qxe5
{ White was clearly better and went on to win in 1-0 @@StartBracket@@45@@EndBracket@@ Vecek, M @@StartBracket@@2278@@EndBracket@@ - Blanchard, A ICCF email 2018. White's initiative and better pawn structure make his life easy. }
