[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "8. 5...Bd6 - the Mackenzie Variation"]
[Black " 11. Rfd1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5
{ This is the Ruy Lopez aka the Spanish Opening. Black has a wide range of responses he can choose from, amongst others besides the main move 3...a6. First, there is 3...Nf6 - the Berlin Defense, which is the second most popular line. Former world champion Vladimir Kramnik boosted its popularity by beating Garry Kasparov in the world championships in London @@StartBracket@@2000@@EndBracket@@ with this tenacious line. The Berlin Defense will be covered in Volume 2 of this series, whereas the other main Black's defenses, amongst others: - 3...Nge7 - the Cozio Defense; - 3...g6 - the Smyslov Defense; - 3...Nd4 - the Bird Defense; -3...d6 - the Steinitz Defense; - 3...f5 - the Schliemann Defense, and; - 3...Bc5 - the Classical Defense will be covered in Volume 3. This will give you a complete repertoire in the Spanish Opening. }
3... a6
{ This is the so-called 'Morphy Defense'. There is instant tension on the board, as our opponent challenges our bishop to make up its mind. The most common move is 4.Ba4, after which the opening will branch into countless variations like the Chigorin, Breyer, Ragozin and Marshall. Black will find his move 3...a6 useful in all of these variations, as he can chase the bishop from a4 with tempo, unpinning himself in the process while also taking space on the queenside. However, completely different positions occur after our move in this course: 4. Bxc6, aka the Ruy Lopez: Exchange Variation. At the same time, uncompromising and attacking players, such as the world champions Bobby Fischer and Garry Kasparov, as well as the current elite player Shakhriyar Mamedyarov from time to time let off steam in this very entertaining line. }
4. Bxc6
{ Black can take back with either the b-pawn or d-pawn, but only the last move has gained popularity as after 4...bxc6 he faces a hard time completing his development.   4.Ba4  The main concept of Morphy's Defense materializes when White falls for the 'Noah's Ark Trap'. This happened in 1929 when Steiner got ambushed in his game against Capablanca, but the current elite grandmaster Nepomniachtchi was similarly caught in it in a recent online game.  4...d6  5.d4  b5  6.Bb3  exd4  7.Nxd4  Nxd4  8.Qxd4  c5!  All of a sudden, White's bishop is caught after c5-c4.  9.Qd5  threatening Qxf7+  Be6  10.Qc6+  The check will not help Black.  10...Bd7  11.Qd5  c4  0-1, @@StartBracket@@55@@EndBracket@@ Nepomniachtchi, I @@StartBracket@@2784@@EndBracket@@ - Demchenko, A @@StartBracket@@2641@@EndBracket@@ chess.com INT 2020 }
4... dxc6
{ The contours of the RLE position are there. White gave up his light-squared bishop and the bishop pair, leaving Black with doubled c-pawns and behind in development. White has many options here. Lasker's main choice was 5. d4, but 5. d3 and 5. Nc3 have also been tried, remaining flexible and not committing the king to g1 yet. }
5. O-O
{ The most ambitious move! White stays flexible, keeping open the options of: 1. d3 or d4, 2. whether the knight should be moved to d2, c3 or a3. The American world-class grandmaster Robert Byrne named 5.O-O is after the Dutch IM John Barendregt, who played this move a couple of times in the 60's. White has already castled while Black's pieces are all on the back rank. Moreover, Black must make an important choice as to how to protect his central pawn since White has renewed the threat of Nxe5 after castling. }
5... Bd6
{ Considering the current theory, 5.. Bd6 is one of the strongest and most popular response for Black here. Contrary to all the modern and odd-looking Queen moves @@StartBracket@@5..Qd6, 5..Qf6 and 5.. Qe7@@EndBracket@@, this healthy developing move with the bishop has its roots all way back in 1867, when Scottish Chess master George Henry Mackenzie served himself of this move obtaining an equal game @@StartBracket@@see below@@EndBracket@@. Given its solid reputation, the adepts on top level are countless: Carlsen, Aronian, Svidler, Wojtaszek, Vitiugov, Adams, Fressinet and Vidit etc. etc. etc.. Meanwhile, it is GM Jan Gustafsson's recommendation in his lifetime repertoire for Black after 1.e4 e5. }
6. d4 { White opens up the center and develops a dangerous initiative. } 6...
exd4 7. Qxd4
{ The queen is attacking the g7-pawn, as a result of which Black cannot move his knight out. }
7... f6
{ Blocking the diagonal, Black is now ready for Ne7 and Ng6, and evt. Be6. Black is very flexible, as he can switch plans of short and long castling. }
8. Be3
{ The bishop is positionally better placed on e3, compared to fianchettoing it on b2. From e3 it reaches both flanks. }
8... Ne7 9. Nbd2
{ This is the right square for the knight. It goes to c4 from where it hits Black d6-bishop. }
9... Be6 { Temporarily preventing the White knight from moving to c4. } 10. Qc3
{ A delicate move. The queen makes place for the knight and prevents any tactical threats such as ...Bxh2. }
10... Qd7
{ Throughout the latest years this move gained more followers as compared to the other competitor 10... Ng6. Here, I'd like to step off the main paths of 11.Nd4 or 11. Nc4, not merely to surprise our opponent, but because I truly believe in the proposed moves. We arrived at crossroads. As this is one of the most critical positions in the entire Ruy Lopez Exchange Variation, Black's set-up a tough nut to crack. I wanted to provide you with a wide variety of moves and plans which all prove to be very dangerous for Black in my opinion. You can choose between 11.Rad1, 11.a4 and 11.Rfd1. }
11. Rfd1
{ A strong idea, as White plays a useful move waiting which side Black chooses. }
11... Ng6 { Black is deferring his choice. } 12. Nd4 O-O-O
{ Ahh.. his Royal Highness opts for the queenside after all. } 13. f3
{ It's always a joy for the eyes to see such a strong pawn chain reaching to the center. ce again, Black has plenty of choice in picking a move or plan. The most characterizing plans and positions for both sides are picked in my analysis below.   13.N2b3  I don't believe that this move can give White the advantage.  13...Bxb3   13...Ne5  would have been a good alternative.  14.f3  avoiding any Ng4's in the near future.  14...b6 !  complicated play ensues. I couldn't find an advantage here for White.  14.Qxb3  Bf4  15.Rd2  Bxe3  This only helps White.  16.Qxe3  c5  carelessly played by Black, but he was already a bit worse.  17.Nb3  +=  1/2-1/2 @@StartBracket@@66@@EndBracket@@ Kovalenko, I @@StartBracket@@2657@@EndBracket@@ - Matlakov, M @@StartBracket@@2714@@EndBracket@@ Minsk 2017 }
13... Qf7
{ 13...h5  going out on a long journey in his endeavor to harm the king's position.  14.a4  h4  15.b4  This quick and dangerous attack seems to me as the most promising continuation.  15...h3   15...Qe7  16.b5  Bb4  17.Qb2  And Black has to prove something to stay in the game, as taking on a6/ c6 and c3 are major threats.  16.g3  Evidently, we keep the character of the position closed on the kingside.  16...Be5  17.N2b3  Black is urged to move its queen.  17...Qf7  18.b5 !  Now it's our time for some demolition work.  18...cxb5  19.axb5  Bxb3  20.cxb3  The attack looks smashing, but that is beyond the next move.  20...Rd6  21.bxa6  bxa6  With a sequence of accurate moves, Black is still in the game. A long struggle lies ahead of us, but White has the better chances. }
14. Nxe6
{ Good timing to take just now on e6. Nc4 is no longer possible, and Black is losing a move by our delayed taking @@StartBracket@@Qd7-f7xe6@@EndBracket@@. }
14... Qxe6 15. Nc4 { The best square for the knight, covering d6 and e5. }
15... Ne5 16. Nxd6+ { We all know that RB vs RN favors the B-side. } 16... Rxd6
17. Rxd6 Qxd6 18. a4
{ White is going to fix Black's kingside pawns, not letting him advance his pawns with b6 and c5. }
18... Rd8
{ 18...b6  won't help Black.  19.a5  Of course, White doesn't let Black play a5 and c5. }
19. a5 { The b7 and a6 pawn are fixed now. } 19... h5
{ This is a critical position, and hopefully in the future it will be a tabiya and starting point for plenty of interesting games to be played at. }
20. Rf1 g5
{ Likewise, Black pursues fixing our @@StartBracket@@e.g. kingside@@EndBracket@@ pawns.   20...h4  21.h3 !?  Is another key idea for White in these kinds of positions. White will break open the kingside with force. By preparing this with h3, the king can hide on h2.  21...g5  22.f4 !  gxf4  Black wants to keep his knight on e5.  23.Rxf4  ±  White is on top as h4 and f6 are weak pawns.   20...Ng6  21.Qc5  Qxc5  22.Bxc5  h4  23.Be3  += }
21. Qc5 { I see this move as the most dangerous for our opponent. } 21... Qxc5
{ 21...Qe6 ?  is bad, on the account of  22.Qa7 } 22. Bxc5 Rd2
{ 22...Ng6  prevents Be7 and evt. Bxf6.  23.Rc1  This weird looking move is protecting c2 meanwhile preparing the king's advance to the center.  23...Kd7  24.Rd1+  Ke8  25.Rxd8+  Kxd8  26.Kf2  and White has all chances to win this ending. He is practically a pawn up here, due to the bad double c-pawn. }
23. Be7 { Black cannot afford to give up on the pawn on f6. } 23... Nd7 24. e5
{ A beautiful move, breaking down Black's pawns. } 24... fxe5 25. Bxg5 Rxc2 26.
g4
{ The point behind White's play! We give up another pawn on b2, but the connected pawns will be unstoppable. }
*

