12. Nb3
{ sidestepping the main line after 12.Nd4. As Black's position is a tough nut to crack, I'd suggest deviating from the main theory to confuse our opponent. }
12... Bg4
{ Notwithstandingt the fact that, there are 0 games in the database to be found with 12... Bg4, this is a serious attempt for Black in the quest for equality. Black should see that Nc5 is not dangerous for him. }
13. Bc5 O-O-O 14. Bxd6 cxd6
{ The problem in this position is that White cannot drive the bishop off with h3 since he has to take into account Nf4. }
15. Rd2
{ Currently, White is ready to move the f3-knight to make the g4-bishop look stupid.   15.h3 ?!  Nf4  Black is fine here since White should better not take on g4.  16.Rd2  Stopping Ne2+.  16...Nxh3+  17.gxh3  Bxh3  18.Nfd4  Qg4+  19.Qg3  The upcoming ending is fine for Black. He gained too many pawns for the exchange and is better.  19...Qxg3+  20.fxg3  Bxf1  21.Kxf1  Black is slightly better here, but White should be able to hold. }
15... Bxf3 16. Qxf3 Rhe8 17. Rdd1
{ Though the position may be close to equal, Black’s problem concerning the backward d-pawn remains unsolved. White paves the way for the knight to c4: Black is not yet out of danger. }
17... Re5 { Preparing both e5 and Rde8. } 18. Nd2
{ Again, Black cannot rid himself of the d6-pawn by playing d6-d5. After 19.Nc4, Black is losing material. }
18... Qf7 19. b3
{ Renewing the threat and parrying Qxa2. White prepares for the knight leap to c4. }
19... d5 20. c4
{ Hitting d5 while the Black king is still slightly exposed on c8. } 20... d4
{ Now Black may find himself in trouble. } 21. Qg3 { Preparing for f4. } 21...
c5 22. f4 Ree8 23. Rb1
{ Black will be tested to the bone, since after b4 we develop a dangerous attack on the king. }
