{ This direct move, attacking e4 has merely appeared in this position. } 15. f3
{ A main pillar of our strategy in this line. White is fortifying his center, before undertaking ensuing operations on the queenside @@StartBracket@@by means of a minority pawn attack@@EndBracket@@. }
15... Bc5
{ A non-obvious move, as - seemingly - Black's queen is in danger on the d-file currently. }
16. Qc3
{ Stabilizing the pivotal point on d4, whereas asking the bishop to choose colour: should he remain active on b6 or retreat to f8? }
16... Bf8
{ It's more likely that your opponent doesn't want to retreat his bishop, but stay active on the a7-g1 diagonal. }
17. Ne2 Qf7 18. Qb3 { once again, we are aiming for a queen ending. } 18...
Qxb3 19. axb3
{ Of course, in these kinds of positions, there are plenty of possible continuations for Black. We pick one of Black's best and see what plans White can demonstrate for an advantage. }
19... Bd6 20. Ng3 Bxg3
{ This is an extra possibility for Black, which he doesn't have after 20.Nd4. }
21. hxg3 a5
{ Immediately utilizing the time to move his pawn majority forward. } 22. g4 h6
{ to stop g5. } 23. Kf2 b6 24. Bd4
{ White places his bishop on c3, stopping the advance of the pawns by keeping an eye on a5. Moreover, he makes place for the king on e3. Gradually White will improve his pieces, and then, he sets off the march of his kingside soldiers. }
24... c5 25. Bc3 Kb7 26. Rxd8 Rxd8 27. Ke3
{ Before undertaking further action, we should improve on our king. } 27... Rd7
28. f4
{ also, here, White's pawns look more dangerous than his opponent's! I like a lot the harmony between White's pieces. Besides, we own the benefit of the RB vs RN material balance. There's no punishment in playing this position with White. }
*

