{ In the following line, please turn off your engine and try to understand White's strategy. }
22. Ne3 b5
{ Though Black's block of pawns - this time with a double on the b-file instead of the c-file - looks sturdy, he will find it difficult to create something real. }
23. h4 h5
{ Black is intending to stop White's majority. It's instructive how White acts now. }
24. g4
{ With the aim of dispersing the Black pawn block, creating solitary pawn islands. }
24... hxg4 25. Nxg4
{ Though White's pawns are not connected anymore, White managed to create the threat of Nxf6. }
25... f5 26. exf5 gxf5
{ The pawn has been lured forward, where it becomes a prey for the knight. }
27. Ne3 f4 28. Ng2
{ Exemplary for White's successful strategy. He will win f4 and has managed free passage for his f- and h-pawn. }
