{ sidestepping the main line after 12.Nd4. As Black's position is a tough nut to crack, I'd suggest deviating from the main theory to confuse our opponent. }
12... Bxb3
{ This panicking move happened twice in practice is the only move played so far in this position. Black players well prepared will likely come up with improvements fighting for equality. }
13. Qxb3 { Preventing short castling, attacking b7. } 13... O-O-O 14. Nd4 Rhe8
{ This direct move, attacking e4 has merely appeared in this position. } 15. f3
{ A main pillar of our strategy in this line. White is fortifying his center, before undertaking ensuing operations on the queenside @@StartBracket@@by means of a minority pawn attack@@EndBracket@@. }
15... Bc5
{ A non-obvious move, as - seemingly - Black's queen is in danger on the d-file currently. }
16. Qc3
{ Stabilizing the pivotal point on d4, whereas asking the bishop to choose colour: should he remain active on b6 or retreat to f8? }
16... Bb6 17. Kf2 Qf7 18. Qb3
{ Though Stockfish is not convinced yet of White's advantage, Lc0 starts to rejoice in the position. }
18... Ne5 19. Qxf7 Nxf7 20. Nf5
{ Releasing the tension, aiming for exchanges. } 20... g6 21. Bxb6 gxf5 22.
Rxd8+ Rxd8 23. Be3
{ Of course, from e3 the White bishop controls the 'entire' board. } 23... fxe4
24. fxe4
{ We don't care about the isolation of e4. Instead, we should focus on the f6- and h7-pawn. A rook shift by Rf1-f3-h3 may win the h7-pawn. Then we start running with our h-passed pawn. And where are Black's passers? I can't see them. }
24... Re8 25. Ke2
{ We reach an ending in which White has the better pawn structure. He will get serious winning chances after getting 2 vs 1 on the kingside. }
*

