5... Bd6 6. d4 exd4 7. Qxd4
{ The queen is attacking the g7-pawn, as a result of which Black cannot move his knight out. }
7... f6 8. Be3 Ne7 9. Nbd2 Be6
{ Temporarily preventing the White knight from moving to c4. } 10. Qc3 Qd7 11.
Rad1 Ng6 12. Nb3 O-O-O
{ hasn't been played yet, but is an interesting alternative. And ultimately fit for the daredevils amongst our opponents. }
13. Na5 { is resulting in very sharp lines, after } 13... Bh3
{ A stunning move. White cannot take here: Black's three pieces @@StartBracket@@QB&N@@EndBracket@@ would make White's king shiver.   13...Bg4 !?  14.Qb3  Hitting b7.  14...b6  15.Nc4  Bxf3  16.Nxd6+  cxd6  17.gxf3  with chances for both sides. }
14. Ne1
{ White had to choose out of 2 main options: 14.Ne1 and 14. Qb3. The latter one leads to very interesting positions in which everything could happen.   14.Qb3 !?  leads to the next forced line, after  14...b6  15.Bxb6 !?  Qg4  16.g3  Bxf1  17.Rxf1  White would be ill-advised to take on c7, after Bf1-b5 @@StartBracket@@preventing Qb7+@@EndBracket@@!  17...cxb6  18.Qxb6  Kd7  despite being a rook down, the position is very unclear and needs to be tested in practice @@StartBracket@@also because of the many interesting sidetracks for both sides@@EndBracket@@. White intends another attacking piece @@StartBracket@@N@@EndBracket@@ to join the battle after Nd4. }
14... Bg4
{ The idea behind this manoeuvre Bh3-Bg4, is that White can better not allow 15. f3, Bxh2+ 16.Kxh2 Qxd1 17.fxg4 Ne5! when Black is better.   14...Bxh2+  15.Kxh2  Qxd1  16.gxh3  Rhe8  17.Qb4  the endings arising after Qd6+, are slightly preferable for White. }
15. Qb3
{ We should stay calm and when the moment arrives, go for our own chances. }
15... b5
{ An ugly and non-appealing move, but it seems to hold for Black.   15...b6 !?  16.Qd3 !?  hitting a6.  16...Bxh2+ !  17.Kxh2  Also here, Black can't take on d1 because of Qxa6 with a mate.  17...Qxd3  18.Rxd3  Be2 !!  a very difficult move to find for our opponent. All the other moves lead to an advantage for White.  19.Rxd8+  Rxd8  20.Rh1  bxa5  21.Kg3  The king is perfectly placed on g3 and Black's extra pawn doesn't really count because of his shattered pawn formation.  21...h6  22.Nf3  Even though the position is balanced, I don't mind making a gamble here with this line for White. It's unlikely that Black would find all these artificial moves, whereas even here White pulls the Nf3-d4-f5 card out of his sleeve. }
16. Rd2
{ a cold-blooded response, leading to double-edged positions. For the Black player, who should prove something to stay in the game, the following line seems far-fetched: }
16... Rhe8 17. h3 Be6
{ 17...Bxh3 !?  is possible here. Most important you should remember, is that we don't take the bishop here since Black's attack would become too powerful. Instead  18.Qc3 !  going for our own chances. }
18. Qc3 { White is attacking the weak pawn on c6. } 18... c5
{ the only move keeping Black in the game. The point is that we cannot take on c5, losing a rook after Bxh2+. }
19. e5 { luring the knight to e5. } 19... Nxe5
{ After  19...fxe5  20.Bxc5  Black's position is falling to pieces. This is showing how fragile Black's position is. }
20. Bxc5
{ This move is possible now. The knight on e5 - blocking the d6-bishop - impedes the discovered check after Bh2+. }
20... Qe7 21. Rxd6 Rxd6
{ We are not obliged to raise the pressure of the pin yet. } 22. Nf3
{ the resulting positions are unclear. } *

