{ Depriving our opponent of his two bishops. In the meantime, in the battle of e6, we create free passage for the knight to c5. }
16... b6 17. Bxe7 Qxe7
{ In for a penny, in for a pound. Most likely, our enemy intends to stick to his plan of bringing his knight to the blockade square on e6. }
18. a4 { Of course, we are heading for the king! } 18... Nf8 19. Nb4
{ Mayday, mayday. How can Black protect his queenside? } 19... Kb7 20. a5
{ White is in time with his attack. } 20... Ne6 21. axb6
{ Naturally, opening the a-file for the attack. } 21... cxb6 22. Nxd5 Rxd5 23.
Nc4
{ Where one knight goes, the other comes. Black can no longer clean house. }
23... Qc5+ 24. Kh1 Nxf4 25. Ra1
{ And now that the dust has settled, and Black won a pawn, it is us pulling the strings. The attack on the vulnerable Black king, open a-file strong passed e-pawn and the square on d6 @@StartBracket@@for the knight@@EndBracket@@ make Black's position utterly inconvenient. }
