[White "9. 5...Bg4, 6...Bh5 - the Pin Variation I"]
[Black "5â¦Bg4 6.h3 Bh5, The Pin Variation I: Introduction"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5
{ This is the Ruy Lopez aka the Spanish Opening. Black has a wide range of responses he can choose from, amongst others besides the main move 3...a6. First, there is 3...Nf6 - the Berlin Defense, which is the second most popular line. Former world champion Vladimir Kramnik boosted its popularity by beating Garry Kasparov in the world championships in London @@StartBracket@@2000@@EndBracket@@ with this tenacious line. The Berlin Defense will be covered in Volume 2 of this series, whereas the other main Black's defenses, amongst others: - 3...Nge7 - the Cozio Defense; - 3...g6 - the Smyslov Defense; - 3...Nd4 - the Bird Defense; -3...d6 - the Steinitz Defense; - 3...f5 - the Schliemann Defense, and; - 3...Bc5 - the Classical Defense will be covered in Volume 3. This will give you a complete repertoire in the Spanish Opening. }
3... a6
{ This is the so-called 'Morphy Defense'. There is instant tension on the board, as our opponent challenges our bishop to make up its mind. The most common move is 4.Ba4, after which the opening will branch into countless variations like the Chigorin, Breyer, Ragozin and Marshall. Black will find his move 3...a6 useful in all of these variations, as he can chase the bishop from a4 with tempo, unpinning himself in the process while also taking space on the queenside. However, completely different positions occur after our move in this course: 4. Bxc6, aka the Ruy Lopez: Exchange Variation. At the same time, uncompromising and attacking players, such as the world champions Bobby Fischer and Garry Kasparov, as well as the current elite player Shakhriyar Mamedyarov from time to time let off steam in this very entertaining line. }
4. Bxc6
{ Black can take back with either the b-pawn or d-pawn, but only the last move has gained popularity as after 4...bxc6 he faces a hard time completing his development.   4.Ba4  The main concept of Morphy's Defense materializes when White falls for the 'Noah's Ark Trap'. This happened in 1929 when Steiner got ambushed in his game against Capablanca, but the current elite grandmaster Nepomniachtchi was similarly caught in it in a recent online game.  4...d6  5.d4  b5  6.Bb3  exd4  7.Nxd4  Nxd4  8.Qxd4  c5!  All of a sudden, White's bishop is caught after c5-c4.  9.Qd5  threatening Qxf7+  Be6  10.Qc6+  The check will not help Black.  10...Bd7  11.Qd5  c4  0-1, @@StartBracket@@55@@EndBracket@@ Nepomniachtchi, I @@StartBracket@@2784@@EndBracket@@ - Demchenko, A @@StartBracket@@2641@@EndBracket@@ chess.com INT 2020 }
4... dxc6
{ The contours of the RLE position are there. White gave up his light-squared bishop and the bishop pair, leaving Black with doubled c-pawns and behind in development. White has many options here. Lasker's main choice was 5. d4, but 5. d3 and 5. Nc3 have also been tried, remaining flexible and not committing the king to g1 yet. }
5. O-O
{ The most ambitious move! White stays flexible, keeping open the options of: 1. d3 or d4, 2. whether the knight should be moved to d2, c3 or a3. The American world-class grandmaster Robert Byrne named 5.O-O is after the Dutch IM John Barendregt, who played this move a couple of times in the 60's. White has already castled while Black's pieces are all on the back rank. Moreover, Black must make an important choice as to how to protect his central pawn since White has renewed the threat of Nxe5 after castling. }
5... Bg4
{ This is the most challenging move we can face. Our opponent pins our knight and is currently not willing to retreat without a punch! As an immediate consequence of this move, White's aggression in the center with d2-d4 with which he endeavours to grab the initiative is no longer possible. Since after h2-h3, Black can keep the pin intact with the aggressive h7-h5 or Bg4-h5. The first game played was from 1870 after which Black didn't fully exploit this plan and retreated his bishop to d7 after h3. }
6. h3
{ White doesn't give Black time to consolidate with Bd6 - protecting e5 - and consecutively Ne7 and Ng6.   6.d3  Bd6  here Black finds time to defend the pawn. The oldest game in the Pin-variation, proceeded as follows:  7.Be3  Ne7  8.Nbd2  O-O  9.c3  Ng6  10.h3  Bd7  11.d4  when Black is fine, though White has a slight pull. ½-½ @@StartBracket@@24@@EndBracket@@ Paulsen, L - Minckwitz, J Baden-Baden 1870. }
6... Bh5
{ This move involves a pawn sacrifice after 7. g2-g4, as Black has to abandon the pin, thereby releasing the tension. }
7. g4
{ White accepts the challenge and unpins himself. The move g2-g4 will give Black serious counterchances against the White king. Despite all this, it's worth it, as White will be rewarded with a tasty central pawn on e5. }
7... Bg6 8. Nxe5
{ Let's take stock of the position. We have won one of Black's central pawns, hence he should aim to create counterplay at our weakest spots. Most notable is White's weakened kingside after g2-g4. Crawling under the skin of our opponent, we might guess his plan now: long castling and opening the h-file with h7-h5. }
8... Qh4
{ 8...Bd6  this move might come too early for Black, as his king is still in the middle of the board.  9.Nxg6  hxg6  So the h-file is opened. Let it be..  10.Qf3  Defending our h3-pawn.  10...Qh4  Being down on development, White is suddenly calling the shots with..  11.e5  !  11...Bc5  12.Kg2  h3 is defended, after which action will be taken in the center.  12...O-O-O  13.c3  White is strengthening his center with d2-d4 on the next move. }
9. Qf3 f6
{ Our opponent forces us to take on g6 when his rook on h8 becomes active. White doesn't really have a choice, because we cannot keep the h-file closed anyhow,   9...Bd6  The difference with 8..Bd6, is that we have the extra option of playing d4. This is beneficial to us, as the h-file remains closed for the moment.  10.d4  Bxe5  11.dxe5  White gets a doubled pawn in the center. The assessment on this position once more depends integrally on whether Black can initiate an attack.  11...h5  12.Nc3  A remarkably cold-blooded response to Black's aggression on the h-file.  12...hxg4  13.Qxg4  Giving up a pawn on h3 but relying on our strong center.  13...Qxh3  14.Qxh3  Rxh3  15.f3  ! A sound positional move. The pawn forms a hedge on the white squares in the center. }
10. Nxg6 { This move is kind of forced. } 10... hxg6 11. Kg2
{ I believe it's worth it to spend a move on the defense of h3. However, sacrificing the h3-pawn with 11.d3, trusting in our strong center, is worth considering as well. }
11... g5
{ Also from a strategic point of view a useful move, Black fixes h3. But he also vacates g6 for the knight. }
12. d3
{ Functional and aesthetically pleasing. The pawn phalanx c2-d3-e4 is White's pride and joy. Black controls the semi-open d- and e-file, but hits a wall here. }
12... Ne7 { The knight’s route has been disclosed } 13. Rh1 Qh7
{ Compared to the d4-variation, when the queen had a clear target, this move now sorts less effect as our pawn on d3 defends e4.   13...O-O-O  is another move order compared to our main line. Black can still determine where to place the queen.  14.Be3  Kb8  Prophylaxis against Qf5 +.  15.Nd2  Ng6  16.Qf5  ! Like in the main line, this move harasses Black's set-up aiming to obtain counterplay. }
14. Kf1
{ The king is crossing over to a safer side of the board. The route which is to be taken with the king is g2-f1-e2, from where the White central pawns provide cover. }
14... O-O-O
{ 14...Ng6  ? Bad timing, as after  15.Qf5  ! The knight is pinned, whereas the king is stuck on e8. }
15. Be3
{ White has built up an impenetrable fortress. The Bishop takes in a positionally sound placement. }
15... Kb8
{ Prophylaxis against future queen checks on f5, in case the knight on e7 would be moving. }
16. Nd2 Qg8
{ So far we followed the main line and the important game: 1-0 @@StartBracket@@49@@EndBracket@@ So, W @@StartBracket@@2650@@EndBracket@@ - Kolev, A @@StartBracket@@2604@@EndBracket@@ Philadelphia 2012. Now I'd like to come up with an improvement over Wesley So's 17.Nc4.   16...Ng6  17.Qf5  ! The Black knight is annoyingly pinned. Black can't book any real progress while still being a pawn down. And, to make matters worse, White doesn't stay sitting on the fence. With the idea a4, Ra3, Rb3 he is changing roles from being a defender to attacker.  17...Bd6  Black dives in the hole of f4.  18.Nc4  Bf4  So far the game: 1/2-1/2 @@StartBracket@@37@@EndBracket@@ Koelber, D @@StartBracket@@2141@@EndBracket@@ - Schieder, A @@StartBracket@@2191@@EndBracket@@ Austria 2020.  19.a4  !! Surprisingly, because of the king on f1 and the undeveloped rooks, White suddenly goes for the attack! The point is that the closed character of the position allows him so.  19...Qh6   19...Bxe3  Was played in a recent correspondence game.  20.fxe3  ! Covering f4, not allowing Nf4. White is on top. ½-½ @@StartBracket@@29@@EndBracket@@ Aggarwal, V @@StartBracket@@1922@@EndBracket@@ - Ciocan, A @@StartBracket@@1548@@EndBracket@@ chess.com INT 2020   20.Qc5  Bxe3  21.fxe3  Nh4  22.Ke2  Rhe8  23.Qb4  g6  24.Na5  +- }
17. e5
{ The square on e4 is vacated for the knight!  1-0 @@StartBracket@@22@@EndBracket@@ Szabo, V 2386 - Szabo, M 2232 LSS email 2011. }
*

