{ Again using the fact that the Black king is still on e8. } 12... Nd5
{ A magnificent countertrick. Can you discover why White cannot take on d6 now?   12...Bxe5 ?  This is bad due to the pin on the e-file.  13.Re1  Nd7  14.d4  White simply wins a piece. }
13. d4 Be7 14. Nc3
{ was an improvement over Magnus's opponents play.   14.Qg3 ?!  is less convincing, due to  14...Qh7  15.c4 ?!  Black was already fine, but c4 is really asking for troubles.  15...Nb4  16.Na3  O-O-O  Every move now contains a threat. From this we may deduce that White created to many weaknesses.  17.Be3  Nd3  Now the knight attacks b2, meanwhile it is on his way to f4.  18.Rab1  g5  The 'Mozart of chess' got plenty of compensation and went on to win in 0-1 @@StartBracket@@31@@EndBracket@@ Bogner, S @@StartBracket@@2409@@EndBracket@@ - Carlsen, M @@StartBracket@@2548@@EndBracket@@ Gausdal 2005. }
14... Nb4 15. Bf4 { White lets the smooth development of pieces prevail. }
15... O-O-O 16. Rad1 Nxc2 { The audacious knight is on a risky undertaking. }
17. d5
{ White grabs the initiative here. After the inevitable exchange of pawns, the knight on d5 is too powerful to handle. On top of that, c7 will be an easy target for an assault. }
