{ h3 is defended, after which action will be taken in the center. } 12... O-O-O
13. c3 { White is strengthening his center with d2-d4 on the next move. } 13...
Be7 14. d4
{ The pawn chain reaches from b2 all the way to e5. Black has to fight it, valuable time which is used by White for the developing of the knight. }
14... f6
{ Of course, a logical pawn move to obstruct our pawn chain. However, after fxe5, Black leaves weaknesses behind. }
15. Nd2 { On its way to e4. } 15... fxe5 16. dxe5
{ Hence, the knight will feel like a million bucks on e4 and the pawns on g6 and g7 are left to their fate and White is still a pawn up. Thus, there can be only one conclusion: White is much better. }
