8... Qh4 9. Qf3 Bd6
{ The difference with 8..Bd6, is that we have the extra option of playing d4. This is beneficial to us, as the h-file remains closed for the moment. }
10. d4 Bxe5 11. dxe5
{ White gets a doubled pawn in the center. The assessment on this position once more depends integrally on whether Black can initiate an attack. }
11... h5 12. Nc3
{ A remarkably cold-blooded response to Black's aggression on the h-file. }
12... hxg4 13. Qxg4
{ Giving up a pawn on h3 but relying on our strong center. } 13... Qxh3 14.
Qxh3 Rxh3 15. f3
{ A sound positional move. The pawn forms a hedge on the white squares in the center. }
15... O-O-O 16. Kg2
{ We improve our king's position. Black cannot yet double on the h-file now that the knight blocks the d8-rook. }
16... Rh5 17. Bf4 Ne7 18. Rh1
{ White is enjoying the better position as his center is powerful and his doubled pawn more influential. In the long run we are aiming for f3-f4-f5. }
