19... Qh6 20. Qc5 Bxe3 21. fxe3 Nh4 22. Ke2
{ White can play it safe, relocating his king to the queenside, e.g. after Ke2-d2-c3. This is possible because of the closed center, now that White has the block of pawns on c2-d3-e4-e3 and there are no breaks available for Black. Having said that, there is even no immediate need to evacuate the king; we could just as well launch an attack by means of the pawn advance  b4 to b5, or play Qb4 and Na5 immediately. }
22... Rhe8 23. Qb4 { White intends Na5, threatening mate on b7. } 23... g6 24.
Na5
{ White will take on b7 next with the queen, or, if not allowed, with the knight on c6. }
