6... Bh5
{ This moves involves a pawn sacrifice after 7.g2-g4, as Black should abandon the pin, thereby he releasing the tension. The other uncompromising moves are: 6..Bh5 and 6..h5, all leading to erratic positions. }
7. g4 { White accepts the tasty central pawn on e5. First he unpins himself. }
7... Bg6 8. Nxe5
{ Let's take stock of the position. We have won a central pawn of Black, hence he should aim to create counterplay at our weakest spots. Most notable is White's weakened kingside after g2-g4. Crawling under the skin of our opponent, we might guess his plan now: long castling and opening the h-file with h7-h5. }
8... Ne7
{ was played recently in a correspondence game, and leads to razor-sharp play. }
9. d3 h5
{ Grabbing the pawn comes against a price. Black will launch an offense on our weak king. }
10. g5 f6
{ Black, castling long, already tries to open as much as possible the character of the position. }
11. gxf6 gxf6 12. Nxg6 Nxg6 13. f4
{ This takes away squares for Black's attacking pieces, meanwhile White will find it easier - with this opening of files after f4 - to cover the squares around his king. }
13... Qd7
{ Here, I would like to propose to you the following novelty: 14.Kh2 instead of 14.f5. After 14.f5, as exemplified in the correspondence game below, White gives the knight a nudge, helping it in the direction of our king. Some nasty tricks, like Nxd3, will be possible. }
14. Kh2
{ The knight is not that strong on g6 yet, while we step off the g-file and protect h3.   14.f5  O-O-O !  15.Kh1  15. fxg6 Qxh3 is dangerous.  15...Rg8  16.Be3  Nh4  I don't like this position for White. The h4-knight is becoming unpredictable and coming our way!  17.Qxh5  Ng2  18.Bf2  Nf4  19.Qf3  Nxd3 !  Other moves, like Qh7, were also playable for Black.  20.cxd3  Qxd3  leads to double-edged play after 21.Nd2. Please notice that White cannot take on d3, because of Rxd3 with the mating threat of 21... Rxh3. 0-1 @@StartBracket@@43@@EndBracket@@ Vorontsov, G @@StartBracket@@1867@@EndBracket@@ - Hjorth, J @@StartBracket@@1812@@EndBracket@@ ICCF 2020 }
14... O-O-O 15. Be3 { It's highly time for some consolidating moves! } 15... f5
{ Black is aiming to open the position up because of our vulnerable king. } 16.
Rg1 Qf7
{ After the interesting alternative 16... Qe6!?, we play 17.Nd2, maintaining the center. }
17. e5 Bh6 18. Qf3
{ White intends to move his knight towards e2 in order to protect his weak f4-pawn. }
18... Qe6
{ White can't move his knight to d2 or c3, because of Nxe5, fxe5, Qxe5+, when the bishop is hanging. }
19. d4 c5 20. c3
{ Maintaining the pawn chain in order. Of course, Black has serious compensation in this complicated and theoretically relevant line. Notwithstanding, he should prove his counterplay and we get our chances to after cxd4, cxd4 when the c-file will be opened for our rook. }
20... Ne7 21. Nd2 { 21.dxc5 ?  is too dangerous, due to  21...Rd3 } 21... cxd4
22. cxd4
{ The opening of the files is not without risk for our adversary either. }
22... Nd5 23. Nb3
{ Our plan is plain and simple. 24. Rac1 and evt. Nc5 if our opponent lets us. Though the position is double-edged, I wouldn't mind playing White. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "10. 5...Bg4, 6...Bxf3 - the Pin Variation II"]
[Black "5â¦ Bg4 6.h3 Bxf3, The Pin Variation III: Introduction"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5
{ This is the Ruy Lopez aka the Spanish Opening. Black has a wide range of responses he can choose from, amongst others besides the main move 3...a6. First, there is 3...Nf6 - the Berlin Defense, which is the second most popular line. Former world champion Vladimir Kramnik boosted its popularity by beating Garry Kasparov in the world championships in London @@StartBracket@@2000@@EndBracket@@ with this tenacious line. The Berlin Defense will be covered in Volume 2 of this series, whereas the other main Black's defenses, amongst others: - 3...Nge7 - the Cozio Defense; - 3...g6 - the Smyslov Defense; - 3...Nd4 - the Bird Defense; -3...d6 - the Steinitz Defense; - 3...f5 - the Schliemann Defense, and; - 3...Bc5 - the Classical Defense will be covered in Volume 3. This will give you a complete repertoire in the Spanish Opening. }
3... a6
{ This is the so-called 'Morphy Defense'. There is instant tension on the board, as our opponent challenges our bishop to make up its mind. The most common move is 4.Ba4, after which the opening will branch into countless variations like the Chigorin, Breyer, Ragozin and Marshall. Black will find his move 3...a6 useful in all of these variations, as he can chase the bishop from a4 with tempo, unpinning himself in the process while also taking space on the queenside. However, completely different positions occur after our move in this course: 4. Bxc6, aka the Ruy Lopez: Exchange Variation. At the same time, uncompromising and attacking players, such as the world champions Bobby Fischer and Garry Kasparov, as well as the current elite player Shakhriyar Mamedyarov from time to time let off steam in this very entertaining line. }
4. Bxc6
{ Black can take back with either the b-pawn or d-pawn, but only the last move has gained popularity as after 4...bxc6 he faces a hard time completing his development.   4.Ba4  The main concept of Morphy's Defense materializes when White falls for the 'Noah's Ark Trap'. This happened in 1929 when Steiner got ambushed in his game against Capablanca, but the current elite grandmaster Nepomniachtchi was similarly caught in it in a recent online game.  4...d6  5.d4  b5  6.Bb3  exd4  7.Nxd4  Nxd4  8.Qxd4  c5!  All of a sudden, White's bishop is caught after c5-c4.  9.Qd5  threatening Qxf7+  Be6  10.Qc6+  The check will not help Black.  10...Bd7  11.Qd5  c4  0-1, @@StartBracket@@55@@EndBracket@@ Nepomniachtchi, I @@StartBracket@@2784@@EndBracket@@ - Demchenko, A @@StartBracket@@2641@@EndBracket@@ chess.com INT 2020 }
4... dxc6
{ The contours of the RLE position are there. White gave up his light-squared bishop and the bishop pair, leaving Black with doubled c-pawns and behind in development. White has many options here. Lasker's main choice was 5. d4, but 5. d3 and 5. Nc3 have also been tried, remaining flexible and not committing the king to g1 yet. }
5. O-O
{ The most ambitious move! White stays flexible, keeping open the options of: 1. d3 or d4, 2. whether the knight should be moved to d2, c3 or a3. The American world-class grandmaster Robert Byrne named 5.O-O is after the Dutch IM John Barendregt, who played this move a couple of times in the 60's. White has already castled while Black's pieces are all on the back rank. Moreover, Black must make an important choice as to how to protect his central pawn since White has renewed the threat of Nxe5 after castling. }
5... Bg4
{ This is the most challenging move we can face. Our opponent pins our knight and is currently not willing to retreat without a punch! As an immediate consequence of this move, White's aggression in the center with d2-d4 with which he endeavours to grab the initiative is no longer possible. Since after h2-h3, Black can keep the pin intact with the aggressive h7-h5 or Bg4-h5. The first game played was from 1870 after which Black didn't fully exploit this plan and retreated his bishop to d7 after h3. }
6. h3
{ White doesn't give Black time to consolidate with Bd6 - protecting e5 - and consecutively Ne7 and Ng6.   6.d3  Bd6  here Black finds time to defend the pawn. The oldest game in the Pin-variation, proceeded as follows:  7.Be3  Ne7  8.Nbd2  O-O  9.c3  Ng6  10.h3  Bd7  11.d4  when Black is fine, though White has a slight pull. ½-½ @@StartBracket@@24@@EndBracket@@ Paulsen, L - Minckwitz, J Baden-Baden 1870. }
6... Bxf3
{ The other uncompromising moves are: 6... Bh5 and 6... h5, all leading to erratic positions. }
7. Qxf3
{ The idea of taking on f3 was employed in the games of Mamedyarov and Kamsky in a blitz and rapid game, respectively. Concerning Black's strategy, it should come as a surprise to White, who expects the more common moves 6... h5 or 6... Bh5, in order to keep the tension on the board aiming for sharp and double-edged positions. This line can become dangerous for White as he doesn't pay attention to Black's ideas of long castling starting a kingside attack throwing his pawns forward. }
7... Qd7
{ This move is the most in the spirit of the Pin-Variation - Bxf3, and was played recently by top GM's Mamedyarov and Harikrishna. Black shows his true intentions: castling long and throwing his g- and h-pawns forward! }
8. d3
{ A new idea popularized by 'Shakh' in 2006. When Mamedyarov plays a new opening idea, it can never be too peaceful, can it? }
8... O-O-O
{ So Shakh gives a twist to the - at first sight - harmless-looking line of 6...Bxf3. Long castling makes the position suddenly very sharp. }
9. Nd2
{ We shall not break our habit, and go on with the same thing we are always doing: Nb1-d2-c4! }
9... f6 { Don't be misled, this quiet move is calm before the storm! } 10. Nc4
{ The knight can support the attack with b4 and a4, but keeps a defensive eye - after a future Ne3 - as well. }
10... h5
{ This game was seen in 0-1 @@StartBracket@@40@@EndBracket@@ Nataf, I @@StartBracket@@2559@@EndBracket@@ -Mamedyarov, S @@StartBracket@@2646@@EndBracket@@ Warsaw 2005, and found a lot of followers afterwards. This game went on with Qe3 and f4, leading to unclear positions. Therefore, I'd like to come up with another plan. }
11. Be3
{ We should not leave one stone unturned, if we get the chance to set out an attack of our own. }
11... g5
{ Black's configuration is dedicated to this attack on our king. It's unlikely he would change plans and go for something else than g7-g5-g4. }
12. a4 g4 { With great force, Black tries to open the lines on the kingside. }
13. Qg3
{ The queen is keeping track of the h3-pawn. Black is at crossroads: shall he take on h3, allowing the exchange of queens, or will he support the attack with Nh6, allowing White to close the position? }
13... Nh6
{ 13...gxh3  This is the other move popular among the Black players. Notwithstanding, I can't get a hold on it as White is simply better in the ensuing ending.  14.Qxh3  White is slightly better here due to his better structure. }
14. h4
{ White closes the kingside. Since White's pieces are pointed at the e5, pawn, Black should give up - anyway temporarily - on his attacking aspirations. }
14... Kb8
{ Here, White can prepare his attack of b2-b4 with Rab1, which was seen in practice. However, I'd rather recommend the immediate: }
15. b4
{ The minority attack against Black king's pawns is very promising. He can take the pawn, but this will merely speed our attack up as the b-file will be opened for our heavy pieces. ½-½ @@StartBracket@@38@@EndBracket@@  Geier, T 2220 -Parmet, D 2375 ICCF email 2015. }
*

