{ White doesn't give Black time to consolidate with Bd6 - protecting e5 - and consecutively Ne7 and Ng6.   6.d3  Bd6  here Black finds time to defend the pawn. The oldest game in the Pin-variation, proceeded as follows:  7.Be3  Ne7  8.Nbd2  O-O  9.c3  Ng6  10.h3  Bd7  11.d4  when Black is fine, though White has a slight pull. ½-½ @@StartBracket@@24@@EndBracket@@ Paulsen, L - Minckwitz, J Baden-Baden 1870. }
6... Bxf3
{ The other uncompromising moves are: 6... Bh5 and 6... h5, all leading to erratic positions. }
7. Qxf3
{ The idea of taking on f3 was employed in the games of Mamedyarov and Kamsky, in resp. a blitz and rapid game. Concerning Black's strategy, it should come as a surprise to White, who expects the more common moves 6...h5 or 6...Bh5, in order to keep the tension on the board aiming for sharp and double-edged positions. This line can become dangerous for White if he doesn't pay attention to Black's ideas of long castling starting a kingside attack throwing his pawns forward. }
7... Nf6
{ The knight is on its way to d7, from where it defends the pivotal point e5. }
8. d3
{ White resumes his general set-up: pawns on white squares, moving the knight of b1 out as fast as possible. }
8... Be7
{ 8...Bc5  This move doesn't make much sense, as he should retreat after  9.Bg5  Be7  when Black loses valuable time. }
9. Nd2
{ As seen in more of our lines, the knight's route is Nb1-d2-c4, and evt. to e3. }
9... O-O 10. Nc4
{ Our opponent should now waste time on the defense of the e5-pawn. } 10... Nd7
11. Qg3
{ Not merely hitting e5, but as well making place for f2-f4, after which the White bishop engages the pawn on c7. }
11... Bh4
{ Deflecting the queen for her main task: attacking e5. At the same time, Black defuses the attack on c7 after f2-f4 and Bxf4. }
12. Qg4 { Not blocking the f-pawn, keeping the option of f2-f4. } 12... Bf6 13.
Bd2 { The rooks are connected, meanwhile the Bishops may be placed to c3. }
13... b5 14. Ne3
{ The knight is very flexible on e3. It can evt. be moved to f5 or g4. } 14...
g6 15. a4
{ White is better here: he can double his rooks on the a-file, exerting pressure on both flanks. }
