7... Qd7
{ This move is the most in the spirit of the Pin-Variation - Bxf3, and was played recently by top GM's Mamedyarov and Harikrishna. Black shows his true intentions: castling long and throwing his g- and h-pawns forward! }
8. d3
{ A new idea popularized by 'Shakh' in 2006. When Mamedyarov plays a new opening idea, it can never be too peaceful, can it? }
8... O-O-O
{ So Shakh gives a twist to the - at first sight - harmless looking line of 6..Bxf3. Long castling makes the position suddenly very sharp. }
9. Nd2
{ We shall not break our habit, and go on with the same thing we are always doing: Nb1-d2-c4! }
9... f6 { Don't be misled, this quiet move is the calm before the storm! } 10.
Nc4 g5
{ There are a lot of similarities with the 10... h5 line of course. Especially after 11.b4. Albeit White gets now the opportunity to block the pawns with 11. Qh5. }
11. b4
{ White chooses here a set-up without Be3. It's a highly interesting alternative to our main line here. }
11... Bxb4 { This is very dangerous now, as the next line will illuminate. }
12. Rb1 Bc5 13. Be3 Bxe3 14. Qxe3
{ Black finds himself in serious trouble because of the threats @@StartBracket@@1@@EndBracket@@ Qa7, and @@StartBracket@@2@@EndBracket@@ Na5. }
