{ 1/2-1/2 @@StartBracket@@29@@EndBracket@@ Radjabov,T @@StartBracket@@2729@@EndBracket@@ - Harikrishna,P @@StartBracket@@2674@@EndBracket@@ Cap d'Agde 2006 }
9... h5 10. Nc4 g5 11. a4
{ 11.Be3  aiming for a transposition after 11..0-0-0 12. a4. However, Black has a mysterious move which offers him decent prospects.  11...Qe6 !  Postponing or refraining from castling, not giving White the opportunity for a queenside attack.  12.a4  Ne7  13.b4  Ng6  ⇆ }
11... O-O-O
{ 11...g4  12.Qg3  O-O-O  13.f4 !  exf4  14.Bxf4  White is slightly better here.   11...Qe6 !?  I think this novelty for Black, not deciding yet whether castling is the right thing to do, is best. The queen defends f6, preparing Ne7.  12.Bd2  Ne7  13.Ne3 !  To stop g5-g4.  13...O-O-O  14.b4  Since Black has lost valuable time after Qe6, the queenside attack should be promising.  14...b6  Trying to keep the queenside closed. After 15.b5, cxb5 16.axb5, Black has this time a6-a5 at his disposal.  15.Rfb1  Kb7  16.Kf1  The king finds a safe haven on f1, and evt. when necessary, on e2. I believe White is a bit better due to his better structure. }
12. Qe3 { Stepping out of g5-g4, threatening Qa7. } 12... Kb8 13. b4
{ Let's just give credit to Naiditsch here. Please pay attention to his way of playing. }
13... g4 14. h4 { Sure, this is a main theme here - keeping the gates closed. }
14... Bh6 15. Qe1 { White intends b4-b5, take take take, and then Qa5. } 15...
Bxc1 16. Qxc1 Ne7 17. b5 { This move is just unstoppable. } 17... cxb5 18. axb5
Qxb5 { 18...axb5  19.Qa3 !  with forceful attacking prospects. } 19. Qa3 Nc8
20. Rfb1 Qc6 21. Na5
{ Winning material and not much later the game. 1-0 @@StartBracket@@35@@EndBracket@@ Naiditsch,A @@StartBracket@@2626@@EndBracket@@ - Harikrishna,P @@StartBracket@@2719@@EndBracket@@ Biel 2020 }
