h5
{ This game was seen in 0-1 @@StartBracket@@40@@EndBracket@@ Nataf, I @@StartBracket@@2559@@EndBracket@@ -Mamedyarov, S @@StartBracket@@2646@@EndBracket@@ Warsaw 2005, and found a lot of followers afterwards. This game went on with Qe3 and f4, leading to unclear positions. Therefore, I'd like to come up with another plan. }
11. Be3
{ We should not leave one stone unturned, if we get the chance to set out an attack of our own. }
11... g5
{ Black's configuration is dedicated to this attack on our king. It's unlikely he would change plans and go for something else than g7-g5-g4. }
12. a4 g4 { With great force, Black tries to open the lines on the kingside. }
13. Qg3
{ The queen is keeping track of the h3-pawn. Black is here at crossroads: shall he take on h3, allowing the exchange of queens, or will he support the attack with Nh6, allowing White to close the position. }
13... Nh6 14. h4
{ White closes the kingside. Since White's pieces are pointed at the e5 pawn, Black should give up - anyway temporarily - on his attacking aspirations. }
14... Kb8
{ Here, White can prepare his attack of b2-b4 with Rab1, which was seen in practice. However, I'd rather recommend the immediate: }
15. b4
{ The minority attack against Black king's pawns is very promising. He can take the pawn, but this will merely speed our attack up as the b-file will be opened for our heavy pieces. }
15... Bxb4
{ If our opponent had the iron nerves of the engine, he could go for this crucial line. }
16. Rab1 c5 17. Rfc1
{ Only an engine can find such thrilling moves. The patience practiced by White after sacrificing a pawn is admirable. White is aiming for c3, to resume the attack on the b-file. The bishop on b4 is in trouble and has nowhere to go. }
17... Qxa4
{ A move of a daredevil; I can't imagine any human without any background knowledge would go for this line with Black. }
18. Ra1
{ 18.c3 ?  Strange enough, this is a blunder.  18...Ba3  19.Ra1  All seems fine for White: isn't he 'just' winning a piece?  19...Rxd3 !  BAMMM!! The rook's invasion comes as a shock to us. Mayday, mayday for the knight on c4.  20.Nxa3  Qxe4  Out of the blue, Black obtained a winning position according to the engine. Black won already plenty of pawns for the piece, as his threat consisting of Nf5 and g3 is indefensible for White, whose pieces are totally disorganized. }
18... Qd7 19. c3 { Aren't we just winning a piece? } 19... Qxd3
{ Yes, but Black is winning a lot of pawns. } 20. cxb4 Qxe4
{ In comparison to the 18.c3-line here above, there is no rook on d3 which makes it possible @@StartBracket@@and necessary@@EndBracket@@ to prevent the knight leap to f5. }
21. Bxh6 Rxh6 22. bxc5
{ When White can move his queen out to c3 or b3, he is simply better. } 22...
Rd3 23. Ne3
{ When Black finds all of these moves, leading to this position, he would still be in the game @@StartBracket@@½-½ @@StartBracket@@38@@EndBracket@@ Geier, T @@StartBracket@@2220@@EndBracket@@ - Parmet, D @@StartBracket@@2375@@EndBracket@@ ICCF email 2015@@EndBracket@@. Even though White's position should - practically speaking - be easier to play. His next move will be Rc4, to chase the queen away from her dominant site. }
