4. Bxc6
{ Black can take back with either the b-pawn or d-pawn, but only the last move has gained popularity as after 4...bxc6 he faces a hard time completing his development.   4.Ba4  The main concept of Morphy's Defense materializes when White falls for the 'Noah's Ark Trap'. This happened in 1929 when Steiner got ambushed in his game against Capablanca, but the current elite grandmaster Nepomniachtchi was similarly caught in it in a recent online game.  4...d6  5.d4  b5  6.Bb3  exd4  7.Nxd4  Nxd4  8.Qxd4  c5!  All of a sudden, White's bishop is caught after c5-c4.  9.Qd5  threatening Qxf7+  Be6  10.Qc6+  The check will not help Black.  10...Bd7  11.Qd5  c4  0-1, @@StartBracket@@55@@EndBracket@@ Nepomniachtchi, I @@StartBracket@@2784@@EndBracket@@ - Demchenko, A @@StartBracket@@2641@@EndBracket@@ chess.com INT 2020 }
4... dxc6
{ The contours of the RLE position are there. White gave up his light-squared bishop and the bishop pair, leaving Black with doubled c-pawns and behind in development. White has many options here. Lasker's main choice was 5. d4, but 5. d3 and 5. Nc3 have also been tried, remaining flexible and not committing the king to g1 yet. }
5. O-O
{ The most ambitious move! White stays flexible, keeping open the options of: 1. d3 or d4, 2. whether the knight should be moved to d2, c3 or a3. The American world-class grandmaster Robert Byrne named 5.O-O is after the Dutch IM John Barendregt, who played this move a couple of times in the 60's. White has already castled while Black's pieces are all on the back rank. Moreover, Black must make an important choice as to how to protect his central pawn since White has renewed the threat of Nxe5 after castling. }
5... Bg4
{ This is the most challenging move we can face. Our opponent pins our knight and is currently not willing to retreat without a punch! As an immediate consequence of this move, White's aggression in the center with d2-d4 with which he endeavours to grab the initiative is no longer possible. Since after h2-h3, Black can keep the pin intact with the aggressive h7-h5 or Bg4-h5. The first game played was from 1870 after which Black didn't fully exploit this plan and retreated his bishop to d7 after h3. }
6. h3
{ White doesn't give Black time to consolidate with Bd6 - protecting e5 - and consecutively Ne7 and Ng6.   6.d3  Bd6  here Black finds time to defend the pawn. The oldest game in the Pin-variation, proceeded as follows:  7.Be3  Ne7  8.Nbd2  O-O  9.c3  Ng6  10.h3  Bd7  11.d4  when Black is fine, though White has a slight pull. ½-½ @@StartBracket@@24@@EndBracket@@ Paulsen, L - Minckwitz, J Baden-Baden 1870. }
6... h5
{ The bishop won't budge an inch... bad news for us! At present, this move is maybe the most popular in tournament practice. And rightly so, we should not let Black complete his development with Ng8-e7-g6 and Qf6, otherwise, we are fighting windmills. }
7. d3
{ In case you would prefer to have rest or want to go to the bar, you can make a draw with 7.c3. The first gentleman's agreement which was made in this way, goes way back to 1966.   7.c3  This move implies a draw offer.  7...Qd3   7...Qf6  !? Unfortunately for the rest seekers, Black can avoid the draw.  8.d4  !? Fortunately for us, there is an appropriate reply to Black's aggression.  8...Bxf3  9.Qxf3  Qxf3  10.gxf3  exd4  11.cxd4  O-O-O  Hitting d4, but we can easily protect our center.  12.Be3  White has the slightly preferable position. Eventually, he can increase the pressure along the g-file.  8.hxg4  hxg4  Yes, the h-file is open. Now, where can our knight go to?  9.Nxe5  Bd6  And in almost all cases, the White players enter the forced line of Nxd3 leading to a perpetual check.  10.Nxd3  Bh2+  11.Kh1  Black has nothing better than the threefold repetition of moves.  11...Bg3+  = }
7... Qf6
{ Former world champion Alexander Alekhine was the first who made the Black line flourish with this strong follow-up. }
8. Nbd2
{ A solid move. The knight defends f3 and can join the defensive forces.   8.Be3 !?  is another popular line, but after  8...Bxf3  Black grabs his chance to damage the White pawn structure.   8...Ne7  9.Nbd2  g5 !?  Alekhine was very clear about his intentions.  10.d4  Ng6  11.Bxg5  Qg7 !  12.hxg4  hxg4  13.Nh4  Nxh4  14.Bxh4  Rxh4  15.g3  Rh8  16.Kg2  O-O-O !  Fighting on two fronts. White cannot take on e5, because of Qg5 @@StartBracket@@losing the knight@@EndBracket@@. 0-1 @@StartBracket@@39@@EndBracket@@ Szwarcman, L - Alekhine, A Petrograd 1916.  9.Qxf3  Qxf3  10.gxf3  White gets a doubled pawn as well.  10...Bd6  Our opponent is first developing his bishop, and only then moving his knight out to g6.  11.Nd2  Like our opponent, we take the long route d2-c4 instead of c3.  11...Ne7  12.Rfb1  Ng6   12...f5  Be aware that our precious bishop will not be locked in after f4!  13.b4  Besides the quest for space on the queenside, White anticipates on the threat of f4, with Bc5.  13...a5   13...f4  14.Bc5  When the status quo does not change much.  14.a3  O-O  15.Nc4  Personally, I like White's position. His pieces work harmoniously together, and his pawns on White are well placed. 1-0 @@StartBracket@@40@@EndBracket@@ Kasimdzhanov, R @@StartBracket@@2652@@EndBracket@@ - Adams, M @@StartBracket@@2731@@EndBracket@@ Tripoli 2004 in the model games section.  13.b4  White is expanding on the queenside, trying to create open files and space for his pieces.  13...Nf8  ! A nice maneuver to optimize the position of the knight.  14.a4  Ne6  Optimal play in this variation by our opponent. The knight couldn't wish for a better square than e6.  15.c3  Nevertheless, White has the slightly favorable chances here. He has more space on the queenside and can look out for a break by means of b4-b5 together with Nc4. His king is best placed on e2. }
8... Ne7
{ The knight is on his road to g6.. and eventually h4. White has to watch out!   8...g5  For the opponents with an aggressive style, this line may suit well. Notwithstanding, White can steer the game in the direction he prefers.  9.Nc4  !  9...Bxf3  Of course, we should swap the queens here in order to avoid being overrun.  10.Qxf3  Qxf3  11.gxf3  f6  12.h4  ! breaking up Black's pawn chain. After gxh4, White can follow up with f3-f4. }
9. Re1
{ At first sight, this move may seem inexplicable in such a sharp position, since there is a piece hanging! In the following part, we will see how useful Re1 can become in a defensive perspective. Sometimes the king can escape via f1 and e2, and sometimes the knight on d2 can help to set up a block on the h2, after hxg4, hxg4 and then Nh2 and Ndf1.   9.Nc4  !? This is a straightforward attempt to reach the ending, perfect for those amongst us who want to reach a playable position with slightly favorable odds without knowing to much theory. In this particular line, applied by several GM's amongst them Igor Glek who scored 2, 5 out 3 here, White menaces to take on g4 followed by Bg5, hence Black cannot enforce his assault with Ng6.  9...Bxf3  kind of forced.  10.Qxf3  Qxf3  11.gxf3  Ng6  The two most serious moves here are 12.Rd1 and 12.Be3.  12.Rd1  O-O-O   12...Bd6  13.Kf1  The king should be moved asap to e2.  13...c5  14.a4  a5  15.c3  Ke7  16.Be3  Rhd8  The White player, Arkadij Naiditsch, got the upper hand. More moves lead to a better position, but he chooses the most convincing one.  17.Nxd6  !  17...cxd6  18.d4  ! White's bishop will become a strong piece, harassing Black on the Black squares and casting a shadow on the knight. 1-0  @@StartBracket@@48@@EndBracket@@ Naiditsch, A @@StartBracket@@2685@@EndBracket@@ - Caruana, F @@StartBracket@@2662@@EndBracket@@ Novi Sad 2009  13.a4  c5  14.Kf1 !  First our pieces should be placed well, before we undertake further action. 1-0 @@StartBracket@@50@@EndBracket@@ Guseinov, G @@StartBracket@@2664@@EndBracket@@ -Robson, R @@StartBracket@@2667@@EndBracket@@ chess.com INT 2019 }
9... Ng6 10. d4
{ The main move, played over 1400 times, and essential in order to obtain 'something'. When Black takes on d4, and then e4-e5, White will find it possible to take on g4.   10.hxg4  ? This is premature - Nd2-f1 will not save White, as Black has another card up his sleeve.  10...hxg4  11.Nh2  Bc5  ! Another attacker scatters all White's hopes.  12.Re2  Rxh2  ! The threats across the h-file are becoming irresistible. White has lost the battle.  13.Kxh2  Qh4+  ! First the Queen, then the rook  14.Kg1  O-O-O  ! And there is no defence possible against Rh8. This line is very important to get a hold on, in order to dodge the various Black traps. }
10... Nf4
{ This knight move looks threatening, but White can repulse the attack.   10...Bd6  !? Is another main option for Black, but it has gone a bit out of fashion lately.  11.hxg4  hxg4  12.Nh2  Rxh2  ! now that f2 is unguarded, Black strikes hard on h2. Keep in mind that Black will let his rook rapidly join the attack after O-O-O.  13.Qxg4  ! The point!   13.Kxh2  ? This is too dangerous for us.  13...Qxf2  13...Qh4   13...Rh4  14.Qf5  ! Black has a wide range of options. His main moves are 14. .Rf4, 14..e:d4 and 14..Ne7, but in each of these cases we won't let the queen's exchange slip away.  14.Qxh4  Rxh4  15.Nf3  The knight occupies a perfect spot on f3.  15...Rh8   15...Rh5  16.Be3  The best move here. White finalizes his development and fortifies his center.  16...O-O-O  17.g3  ! A prophylactic move. Besides giving his king air, he controls now f4 limiting the g6-knight's options.  16.Be3  Sustaining the center, completing the development. 1-0 @@StartBracket@@21@@EndBracket@@ 42 Nicklich, W - Wachsmuth, D DDR 1989. After }
11. dxe5
{ These kinds of positions we should treat with the utmost care and we need eyes in the back of our head, as each misstep could become fatal to us. Thus, try to learn the following lines by heart, and in the end, you will be ultimately rewarded with a pleasant and risk-free ending which you can convert into something tangible. From this point we have two interesting options: @@StartBracket@@A@@EndBracket@@ 11. dxe5 and @@StartBracket@@B@@EndBracket@@ 11.hxg4.   11.hxg4  A change of air might be good to all of us.  11...hxg4  We should not bend the rules; when we try to keep our knight incautiously with 12.Nxe5, we will be mated in a horrific way on the h-file. Therefore we should give up on the piece under the most beneficial circumstances.  12.g3  !   12.Nxe5  ?? Is a terrible mistake.  12...Qh4  Mate is inevitable.  12...gxf3  13.Qxf3  White is ready to take on f4, Black can't yet set up the battery on the h-file.  13...Ne6  14.dxe5  Qh6   14...Qxe5  We don't have to worry anymore that the queen will reach h2 easily.  15.Nb3  ! Be alert on any knight invasions on d4!  15...Bd6  16.Kg2  O-O-O  17.Qf5  White consolidated and went on to win in 1-0 @@StartBracket@@53@@EndBracket@@ Solak, D @@StartBracket@@2635@@EndBracket@@ - Das, S @@StartBracket@@2371@@EndBracket@@ Dubai 2014  15.Nb3  We should genuinely keep an eye on d4, not permitting Ne6-d4!  15...g5  !? This is by far the most popular move in this position.  16.Be3  Bg7  Mostly played, hitting e5. It's time we show our cards here.   16...Qh3  !? Is a good alternative.  17.Qg2  Qh7  18.Nd4  g4  19.Nxe6  fxe6  20.Rad1  The position is double-edged here. Black's king is still in the center.  17.Kf1  Bxe5  18.c3  Solid as a rock. }
11... Qg6
{ It seems that Black's assault bears fruit. After Bxh3 or Nxh3, the Black queen will invade on g2 with - likely - a mate. To make matters worse, hxg4 will merely strengthen Black's attack after hxg4, Nh2 and g3!   11...Qe6  Is a serious alternative but rarely played.  12.Nb3  ! The best, leading to a favorable position for White.  12...Rd8  13.Bd2  We reached an extremely double-edged position here, not for the faint-hearted. White is threatening here 13.Nbd4 undoing the pin, hitting the f4-knight, when Black cannot take the knight 13...Rxd4 because of 14.Nxd4, when the Black queen would be hanging.  13...Bxh3  !  14.Ng5  !  14...Qg6  15.Qf3  ! Are you still with me? So many pieces are hanging! Let's ponder them all one-by-one.  15...Qxg5  16.Bxf4  Qg4  17.Kh2  ! White intends to force Black to take on f3, by playing Be3 on the next move.  17...Qxf3  18.gxf3  This pawn block in the center guarantees us the advantage. }
12. Nh4
{ The only way out for White, but a convenient one..   12.hxg4  ? Once again White can't be advised to take the bishop.  12...hxg4  !  13.Nh2  In one move, White's defenses are set and done.  13...g3  ! But we are lacking time..  14.fxg3  Qxg3  -+ Simultaneously menacing to strike on g2 and h2. Black reached a winning position. }
12... Bxd1
{ The only move.   12...Qg5  is a mistake, as White can let his other pieces join.  13.Ndf3  Bxf3  Be alert on the mating threat as Nxh3.  14.Qxf3  For Black, there is not much to do against Bxf4.  14...Qxh4  15.Bxf4  White obtained a close to winning position. }
13. Nxg6 Nxg6 14. Rxd1
{ Now that queens have been swapped, Black takes unavoidably on e5, and the matters have calmed down, White can claim the better pawn structure and thereby, the advantage. }
14... O-O-O
{ Black first wants to move the king from the center, and only then take on e5.   14...Nxe5  ?!  15.f4  ! Whilst the king is stuck on e8, White undertakes action in the center. And why shouldn't he use his pawn majority? }
15. e6
{ Before unpinning himself, White throws the cat amongst the pigeons. The concept of giving this pawn up in order to inflict as much as possible damage to Black's structure, can be considered a 'desperado'. }
15... fxe6
{ Aren't we chess players herd animals? The vast majority opts for this continuation, whereas 15..f6 is not demonstrably worse.   15...f6  !? Black is keeping his structure intact. ½- @@StartBracket@@18@@EndBracket@@ ½ 31 Mosrati, N 2308- Idrees, M 2381 ICCF email 2018. }
16. Re1 { This unpinning is necessary for further development. } 16... Ne5
{ The knight feels like 'the king of the world' on e5, but that's of a temporary nature as White will bash his head in when he gets the chance.   16...Bc5  Now Black allows the white knight to f3.  17.Nf3  ! The knight controls important square e5. On the next move he will go to g5. }
17. Nb3
{ Black has the slightly more active pieces, but White will very soon settle the score concerning development when he can move his bishop out. What really counts is the preferable pawn structure. }
17... Be7
{ 17...Nc4  Black's knight is hindering White's development. 1-0 @@StartBracket@@41@@EndBracket@@ Lehtinen, P @@StartBracket@@2229@@EndBracket@@ - Laine, E @@StartBracket@@2183@@EndBracket@@ ICCF email 2014 }
18. Bd2 { The bishop will be elegantly placed on c3. } 18... g5
{ Black launches a counter offense meanwhile hindering the f2-f4 advance. } 19.
Bc3
{ Black cannot play the more logical looking Bf6, due to Nc5! The knight is attacking the weak e6 pawn which needs to much care. }
19... Bd6 20. Rad1
{ The last piece has been brought to an active position. Please don't reinvent the wheel because GM Solak has paved for us the way: 1-0 @@StartBracket@@48@@EndBracket@@ Solak,D @@StartBracket@@2628@@EndBracket@@ - Adams,M @@StartBracket@@2744@@EndBracket@@ Reykjavik 2015 See here }
*

