{ White doesn't give Black time to consolidate with Bd6 - protecting e5 - and consecutively Ne7 and Ng6.   6.d3  Bd6  here Black finds time to defend the pawn. The oldest game in the Pin-variation, proceeded as follows:  7.Be3  Ne7  8.Nbd2  O-O  9.c3  Ng6  10.h3  Bd7  11.d4  when Black is fine, though White has a slight pull. ½-½ @@StartBracket@@24@@EndBracket@@ Paulsen, L - Minckwitz, J Baden-Baden 1870. }
6... h5
{ The bishop won't budge an inch... bad news for us! At present, this move is maybe the most popular in tournament practice. And rightly so, we should not let Black complete his development with Ng8-e7-g6 and Qf6, otherwise, we are fighting windmills. }
7. c3
{ This move implies a draw offer, as after 7..Qd3  there follows a forced sequence of moves. }
7... Qf6 { Unfortunately for the rest seekers, Black can avoid the draw. } 8.
d4 { Fortunately for us, there is an appropriate reply to Black's aggression. }
8... Bxf3
{ White menaced to take on g4, so Black is kind of forced to release the tension. }
9. Qxf3 Qxf3 10. gxf3
{ Allowing doubled pawns, but maintaining his strong center. } 10... exd4 11.
cxd4
{ Here, I'd rather have my pawns doubled on the f-file than on the c-file. White has potential in the center and it is Black who has to prove that he is not worse. }
11... O-O-O { Hitting d4, but we can easily protect our center. } 12. Be3 Ne7
{ Obviously, g6 is the best square for the knight, eventually heading for f4 or h4. }
13. Kh1 Ng6 14. Nc3
{ Though it may not be much, I prefer the White pieces. He has a nice block of pawns in the center.. }
14... Bd6 15. Rg1
{ And White can use the semi-open g-file. The position should be difficult deal with for Black, as White can exert a nagging pressure on him. For instance, the game could continue... }
15... Rh7 16. Rad1 Nh4 17. f4 Re8 18. a3 f6 19. Rd3
{ White is slightly better because of his strong center and pressure along the g-file. }
*

