{ In the meantime, we are familiar with the aggressive and promising plan concerning b4, a4 and b5. }
12... O-O-O 13. b4
{ The pawn rush by means of a4 and b5, will cause chaos and despair to Black. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "11. 5...Bg4, 6...h5 - the Pin Variation III"]
[Black "7...Qf6, 8. Be3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5
{ This is the Ruy Lopez aka the Spanish Opening. Black has a wide range of responses he can choose from, amongst others besides the main move 3...a6. First, there is 3...Nf6 - the Berlin Defense, which is the second most popular line. Former world champion Vladimir Kramnik boosted its popularity by beating Garry Kasparov in the world championships in London @@StartBracket@@2000@@EndBracket@@ with this tenacious line. The Berlin Defense will be covered in Volume 2 of this series, whereas the other main Black's defenses, amongst others: - 3...Nge7 - the Cozio Defense; - 3...g6 - the Smyslov Defense; - 3...Nd4 - the Bird Defense; -3...d6 - the Steinitz Defense; - 3...f5 - the Schliemann Defense, and; - 3...Bc5 - the Classical Defense will be covered in Volume 3. This will give you a complete repertoire in the Spanish Opening. }
3... a6
{ This is the so-called 'Morphy Defense'. There is instant tension on the board, as our opponent challenges our bishop to make up its mind. The most common move is 4.Ba4, after which the opening will branch into countless variations like the Chigorin, Breyer, Ragozin and Marshall. Black will find his move 3...a6 useful in all of these variations, as he can chase the bishop from a4 with tempo, unpinning himself in the process while also taking space on the queenside. However, completely different positions occur after our move in this course: 4. Bxc6, aka the Ruy Lopez: Exchange Variation. At the same time, uncompromising and attacking players, such as the world champions Bobby Fischer and Garry Kasparov, as well as the current elite player Shakhriyar Mamedyarov from time to time let off steam in this very entertaining line. }
4. Bxc6
{ Black can take back with either the b-pawn or d-pawn, but only the last move has gained popularity as after 4...bxc6 he faces a hard time completing his development.   4.Ba4  The main concept of Morphy's Defense materializes when White falls for the 'Noah's Ark Trap'. This happened in 1929 when Steiner got ambushed in his game against Capablanca, but the current elite grandmaster Nepomniachtchi was similarly caught in it in a recent online game.  4...d6  5.d4  b5  6.Bb3  exd4  7.Nxd4  Nxd4  8.Qxd4  c5!  All of a sudden, White's bishop is caught after c5-c4.  9.Qd5  threatening Qxf7+  Be6  10.Qc6+  The check will not help Black.  10...Bd7  11.Qd5  c4  0-1, @@StartBracket@@55@@EndBracket@@ Nepomniachtchi, I @@StartBracket@@2784@@EndBracket@@ - Demchenko, A @@StartBracket@@2641@@EndBracket@@ chess.com INT 2020 }
4... dxc6
{ The contours of the RLE position are there. White gave up his light-squared bishop and the bishop pair, leaving Black with doubled c-pawns and behind in development. White has many options here. Lasker's main choice was 5. d4, but 5. d3 and 5. Nc3 have also been tried, remaining flexible and not committing the king to g1 yet. }
5. O-O
{ The most ambitious move! White stays flexible, keeping open the options of: 1. d3 or d4, 2. whether the knight should be moved to d2, c3 or a3. The American world-class grandmaster Robert Byrne named 5.O-O is after the Dutch IM John Barendregt, who played this move a couple of times in the 60's. White has already castled while Black's pieces are all on the back rank. Moreover, Black must make an important choice as to how to protect his central pawn since White has renewed the threat of Nxe5 after castling. }
5... Bg4
{ This is the most challenging move we can face. Our opponent pins our knight and is currently not willing to retreat without a punch! As an immediate consequence of this move, White's aggression in the center with d2-d4 with which he endeavours to grab the initiative is no longer possible. Since after h2-h3, Black can keep the pin intact with the aggressive h7-h5 or Bg4-h5. The first game played was from 1870 after which Black didn't fully exploit this plan and retreated his bishop to d7 after h3. }
6. h3
{ White doesn't give Black time to consolidate with Bd6 - protecting e5 - and consecutively Ne7 and Ng6.   6.d3  Bd6  here Black finds time to defend the pawn. The oldest game in the Pin-variation, proceeded as follows:  7.Be3  Ne7  8.Nbd2  O-O  9.c3  Ng6  10.h3  Bd7  11.d4  when Black is fine, though White has a slight pull. ½-½ @@StartBracket@@24@@EndBracket@@ Paulsen, L - Minckwitz, J Baden-Baden 1870. }
6... h5
{ The bishop won't budge an inch... bad news for us! At present, this move is maybe the most popular in tournament practice. And rightly so, we should not let Black complete his development with Ng8-e7-g6 and Qf6, otherwise, we are fighting windmills. }
7. d3 Qf6
{ Former world champion Alexander Alekhine was the first who made the Black line flourish with this strong follow-up. }
8. Be3
{ This is another popular line for White. Clearly, White is happy to place his bishop on this central square. }
8... Bxf3 { Black grabs his chance to damage the White pawn structure. } 9.
Qxf3 Qxf3 10. gxf3
{ White gets a doubled pawn as well, and the position looks equal, but I truly believe the position is easier to play for White. Especially the expansion on the queenside is something Black must endure. }
10... Bd6
{ Our opponent is first developing his bishop, and only then moving his knight out to g6. }
11. Nd2
{ Like our opponent, we take with the knight the long route, d2-c4 instead of c3. }
11... Ne7 12. Rfb1 Ng6
{ 12...f5  Be aware that our precious bishop will not be locked in after f4!  13.b4  Besides the quest for space on the queenside, White anticipates on the threat of f4, with Bc5.  13...a5   13...f4  14.Bc5  When the status quo does not change much.  14.a3  O-O  15.Nc4  Personally, I like White's position. His pieces work harmoniously together, and his pawns on White are well placed.  15...axb4  16.axb4  b5   16...Rxa1  The pawn on b4 can be considered as a Greek gift.  17.Rxa1  Bxb4  18.Rb1 !  Instead White is aiming for the b7-pawn.   18.Nxe5 ??  Would be a comic mistake, after  18...Bc3  18...Bd6  19.Rxb7  Ng6  20.Bg5  The Black knight can now be taken on both h4 or f4. White is better due to his better pawn structure and more active pieces.  17.Na5  Ra6  18.c4 !  Kasimdzhanov is further expanding on the queenside.  18...Ng6  19.Kf1 !  The king should be moved to the centrum!  19...Rfa8  20.Bd2  fxe4  21.fxe4  Be7  With the following move, Kasimdhzanov closes the character of the position. White gained plenty of space, while Black can barely move.  22.c5  Though the computer only assess White's advantage so small that we need a magnifying glass to reveal it, I believe that White possesses a pleasant position and that Black is already in a squeeze, 1-0 @@StartBracket@@40@@EndBracket@@ Kasimdzhanov, R @@StartBracket@@2652@@EndBracket@@ - Adams, M @@StartBracket@@2731@@EndBracket@@ Tripoli 2004. }
13. b4
{ White is expanding on the queenside, trying to create open files and space for his pieces. }
13... Nf8 { A nice maneuver to optimize the position of the knight. } 14. a4
{ Thus, White managed to build up an initiative on the queenside. A piece of advice: don't be misled by the far too negative interpretation of certain engines like SF. With confidence we can rely on the ideas from the very strong GM Kasimdhzanov in his game against Adams, supported by engine analysis of Leela. }
14... Ne6
{ Optimal play in this variation by our opponent. The knight couldn't wish for a better square than e6. }
15. c3 f6 16. Kf1
{ It is noteworthy that White's knight doesn't yet pick a square  (b3 or c4)  and leaves Black in confusion for the moment. This way he keeps all the options open. }
16... Kf7
{ After Solak's 17.a5, White is slightly better. However, I'd prefer to go in a different direction by aiming for the b4-b5 break. }
17. Nc4
{ 17.a5  White fixes the pawn majority on the queenside.  17...Rhd8  18.Nb3  Intending d4.  18...Be7  19.Ke2  g6  20.d4  led to a slightly preferable position for White in: ½-½ @@StartBracket@@36@@EndBracket@@ Solak, D @@StartBracket@@2641@@EndBracket@@ - Tari, A @@StartBracket@@2593@@EndBracket@@ Khanty-Mansiysk 2017 }
17... Be7 { Making space along the d-file and preventing 18.Nxd6. } 18. Na5
{ How is Black going to protect his b7-pawn? } 18... Rab8
{ This is rather passive. } 19. Rd1
{ The threat is more dangerous than its execution! By moving the rooks to d1 and b1, White combines the ideas of b5 and d4. }
19... g6 20. Rab1
{ White is intending to push b5, creating open files for his rooks. } 20... f5
{ White's play is kind of provocative, as he practices loads of patience. The Black player may find it difficult to sit on the fence and undertakes action. However not visible yet, the e5-pawn can become vulnerable now. }
21. b5 axb5 22. axb5
{ We are following one sample line to illuminate White's strategy in these kind of positions. No doubt, there are interesting alternate ideas for our opponent. }
22... c5
{ 22...cxb5  Can't be approved here, even if it involves our opponent, as the e5-pawn becomes immensely weak.  23.Rxb5  It's clear that White made significant progress here.  23...b6  24.Nc6  White is winning a pawn and - likely - the game. }
23. b6 { With great force, opening the b-file. } 23... c6
{ 23...cxb6 ?  24.Nc4  The e5-pawn is a matter of concern for Black.  24...Kf6  25.exf5  First we open the position, before we enter Black's position.  25...gxf5  26.Rxb6  Bd8  White would like to give his active strategy, an appropriate follow-up.  27.Bg5+ !!  Now the rook is not obliged to retreat.  27...Kxg5  28.Rxe6  White's position is much better here. Black should be worried about his king, the disharmony between his pieces, and his scattered pawns. }
24. Ke2 { Step-by-step, we improve our position across the entire board. }
24... Kf6 25. Ra1
{ White has a lasting advantage, with a clear plan to gradually build up the tension on the a-file by means of Nc4 and Ra7. }
*

