7. d3 Qf6
{ Former world champion Alexander Alekhine was the first who made the Black line flourish with this strong follow-up. }
8. Nbd2
{ A solid move. The knight defends f3 and can join the defensive forces. } 8...
g5
{ For the opponents with an aggressive style, this line may suit well. Notwithstanding, White can steer the game in the direction he prefers. }
9. Nc4 Bxf3
{ Of course, we should swap the queens here in order to avoid being overrun. }
10. Qxf3 Qxf3 11. gxf3 f6 12. h4
{ breaking up Black's pawn chain. After gxh4, White can follow up with f3-f4. }
12... gxh4 13. Kg2
{ in line with Gustafsson's lifetime repertoire 1.e4 e5, I consent that White has the slightly favorable odds here.   13.f4  this is the main line, played over approximately a hundred times.  13...b5  14.Na5  exf4  15.Bxf4  leads to unclear play. 1-0 @@StartBracket@@43@@EndBracket@@ Naiditsch, A @@StartBracket@@2684@@EndBracket@@ - Mons, L @@StartBracket@@2464@@EndBracket@@ Germany 2016 }
13... Ne7 14. f4 b5 15. Na5
{ White's pawn structure is compact, whereas Black has to deal with several 'pawn islands'. }
15... exf4 16. Bxf4 Rg8+ 17. Kh3
{ White has the better structure and Black has to keep his numerous weak pawns together. He can push things his way by means of Bh2/ Be3 and f4, evt. f5. }
