7. d3 Qf6
{ Former world champion Alexander Alekhine was the first who made the Black line flourish with this strong follow-up. }
8. Nbd2 Bd6 9. d4
{ White can engage in an aggressive encounter to test the opponent to the maximum.   9.Nc4  This leads to favorable R@@StartBracket@@R@@EndBracket@@ B vs R@@StartBracket@@R@@EndBracket@@N endings, and is as a consequence, a sound alternative to 9.d4 - a line which requires some knowledge.  9...Bxf3  10.Qxf3  Qxf3  11.gxf3  Ne7  12.f4 !  We get rid of our doubled pawns.  12...exf4  13.Nxd6+  Black as well, but what counts is what is left on the board.  13...cxd6  14.Bxf4  O-O-O  15.Be3  f5  16.f3 !  White has the better pawn structure and splendid - in its flexibilty - bishop. }
9... Ne7
{ Mayday, mayday! The knight is heading for g6 and evt. h4/f4 or e5.   9...exd4 ??  is a horrific mistake with Black's king still on the e-file.  10.e5 !  It makes a huge difference with or without a knight on e7.  10...Bxe5  What else?  11.Re1  is winning for White. }
10. dxe5 { Immediate action was required. } 10... Bxe5 11. Nc4
{ The ensuing positions are slightly favorable for White, after the simplification Bxf3, Qxf3 and gxf3. }
11... Rd8 12. Qe2
{ This position ocurred twice in practice in the games of Gharamian. } 12...
Ng6 13. hxg4 { Yes! We can take! } 13... hxg4 14. Ncxe5
{ The only move, but a good one.   14.Nfxe5  Qh4  15.f4  this doesn't help White out this time, because of  15...g3  when the mate on h1 is inevitable. }
14... Nxe5 15. Ng5 { On - almost- each and every move of Black, we go f2-f4. }
15... Qh6 16. f4
{ White created an escape square on f2 for the king, whereas g3 can be met by Nh3.1-0 @@StartBracket@@35@@EndBracket@@ Gharamian,T @@StartBracket@@2412@@EndBracket@@ - Robin, S @@StartBracket@@2231@@EndBracket@@ Chartres 2005 }
16... gxf3
{ 16...Qh1+  Doesn't yield Black anything.  17.Kf2  g3+  18.Ke1  We are simply a piece up. As it seems, Black's attack is not without risk. }
17. Nxf3
{ The queen is being attacked, so it leaves our opponent without much choice.. }
17... Qh1+ 18. Kf2
{ We can praise the miraculous escape f2-f4! There's a thin line between victory and defeat. }
18... Ng4+ 19. Kg3 { Time for Black to throw in the towel. } *

