Ne7
{ The knight is on his road to g6 and eventually h4. White has to watch out! }
9. Nc4
{ This is straightforward attempt to reach the ending, perfect for those amongst us who won't to reach a playable position with slightly favorable odds without knowing too much theory. In this particular line, applied by several GM's @@StartBracket@@amongst them Igor Glek who scored 2, 5 out 3 here@@EndBracket@@, White menaces to take on g4 @@StartBracket@@followed by Bg5@@EndBracket@@, hence Black cannot enforce his assault with Ng6. }
9... Bxf3
{ kind of forced.   9...Ng6 ?  The bishop is not till the end of days invincible, on the account of  10.hxg4 !  hxg4  11.Bg5 !  White maintains his extra piece.  11...Qe6  12.Nh2  being much better. }
10. Qxf3 Qxf3 11. gxf3 Ng6
{ The two most serious move here are 12.Rd1 and 12.Be3. } 12. Rd1 Bd6 13. Kf1
{ The king should be moved asap to e2. } 13... c5 14. a4 a5 15. c3 Ke7 16. Be3
Rhd8
{ The White player, Arkadij Naiditsch, got the upper hand. More moves lead to a better position, but he chooses the most convincing one. }
17. Nxd6 cxd6 18. d4
{ White's bishop will become a strong piece, harassing Black on the Black squares and casting a shadow on the knight. }
18... b6 19. Ra3
{ All part of Naiditsch's plan: the tension is being raised on Black's structure. }
19... f6 20. Rb3 Rab8 21. Rb5
{ In several moves, Black's position deteriorated severely. White can at any time open the position with b2-b4 when Black remains with a weak b6 @@StartBracket@@and d6@@EndBracket@@ pawn }
21... h4
{ 21...Nf8 ?!  This is not the most accurate move, played by the American superstar.  22.dxe5  dxe5   22...fxe5  is not possible, due to  23.Bg5  23.Rxd8  Kxd8  24.Bxc5  1-0 @@StartBracket@@48@@EndBracket@@ Naiditsch, A @@StartBracket@@2685@@EndBracket@@- Caruana, F @@StartBracket@@2662@@EndBracket@@ Novi Sad 2009   But also after }
22. Ke2 { White has a dream position. } *

