8. Nbd2
{ A solid move. The knight defends f3 and can join the defensive forces. } 8...
Ne7
{ The knight is on his road to g6 and eventually h4. White has to watch out! }
9. Re1
{ At first sight, this move may seem inexplicable in such a sharp position, since there is a piece hanging! In the following part, we will see how useful Re1 can become in a defensive perspective. Sometimes the king can escape via f1 and e2, and sometimes the knight on d2 can help to set up a block on the h2, after h:g4, hxg4 and then Nh2 and Ndf1.   9.hxg4 ?  comes too early for White, as after  9...hxg4  10.Nh2  Qh4  White cannot yet move his d2-knight to f1 in order to protect the h2-knight meanwhile blocking the h-file. This will be different after Re1, when Nd2-f1 will be possible. }
9... O-O-O { Now White can take on g4! } 10. hxg4 hxg4 11. Nh2
{ when it appeared that the f1 square can be utilized for the d2-knight. Black will not overcome his material deficiency. }
11... Qh4
{ The two key ideas of White's defense show themselves:  (1)  Taking on g4, and  (2)  moving the other knight to f1. }
12. Ndf1
{ Maybe even simpler is  12.Qxg4+  , exchanging queens and remaining a piece up. }
