{ Is another main option for Black, but it has gone a bit out of fashion lately. }
11. hxg4 hxg4 12. Nh2 Rxh2
{ now that f2 is unguarded, Black strikes hard on h2. Keep in mind that Black will let his rook rapidly join the attack after O-O-O. }
13. Qxg4 { The point! } 13... Rh4 14. Qf5
{ Black has a wide range of options. His main moves are 14...Rf4, 14...exd4 and 14...Ne7, but in each of these cases we won't let the queen exchange slip away. }
14... Ne7
{ allows a weakening of the structure. Something we cannot let pass!   14...exd4  15.Nf3  Rh7  16.Bg5 !  Qxf5  17.exf5+  Ne7  18.Bxe7  Bxe7  19.Nxd4  White is slightly better, as Black can't unpin himself in a comfortable manner.   14...Rf4  15.Qxf6  Rxf6  16.Nf3  Clearly, White is doing fine here.  16...Re6  17.g3  White is aiming for the 3 vs 2 majority on the kingside after Kg2 and dxe5. }
15. Qxf6 gxf6 16. Nf3 { The knight takes in a perfect spot. } 16... Rh5 17. Be3
{ This position was played 6 times, with overall good results for White. The game could continue   17...O-O-O  From here only in a couple of moves White obtained a large advantage.  18.g3  Rdh8  19.Kg2  Ng6  20.Rh1  Rxh1  21.Rxh1  Rxh1  22.Kxh1  White is already much better here in this BN vs BN ending. The doubled pawns are just too bad.  22...Nf8  23.Kg2  Nd7  24.Nh4  b5  25.Kh3 !?  25...a5  26.Kg4  Nf8  27.c3  Ne6  28.Kf5  1-0 @@StartBracket@@28@@EndBracket@@ Givon, A @@StartBracket@@2340@@EndBracket@@ - Stamnov, A @@StartBracket@@2184@@EndBracket@@ Plovdiv 2012    28.Kf5  Black resigned here, as after  28...exd4  29.Bxd4  Nxd4+  30.cxd4  Be7  31.f4  is a cheerless position for the Black player. }
