13. Qxg4 { The point! } 13... Qh4 14. Qxh4 Rxh4 15. Nf3
{ The knight occupies a perfect spot on f3. } 15... Rh5 16. Be3
{ The best move here. White finalizes his development and fortifies his center. }
16... O-O-O 17. g3
{ A prophylactic move. Besides giving his king air, he controls now f4 limiting the g6-Knight's options. }
17... exd4
{ 17...f5 ?!  Black uses a battering ram, but all the pawn exchanges only make White's task easier.   If  17...f6  , not giving up the center,  18.Kg2  +/= when White gets ready to use his king in the ending.  18.exf5  Rxf5  19.Kg2  Rdf8  20.Nxe5  Nxe5  21.dxe5  Bxe5  22.c3  and White went on to win. His majority on the Kingside will soon be set in motion. Please see the game: 1-0 @@StartBracket@@41@@EndBracket@@ Magem Badals, J @@StartBracket@@2535@@EndBracket@@ - Khalifman, A @@StartBracket@@2660@@EndBracket@@ New York 1998, CBM 064 Wedberg, T }
18. Bxd4
{ after this exchange of central pawn, White owns the majority on the Kingside which will be profitable for him in the far ending. }
18... f6 { White shouldn't worry about Rdh8. His king is perfectly fine. } 19.
Kg2
{ A useful move in the ending. The king changes colour from a defending to an attacking piece. }
19... Re8 20. Nd2
{ The knight jumps to c4, whereas - when the time is right - White will set his majority in motion by means of f2-f4. White is better here. }
