12. g3 gxf3 13. Qxf3
{ White is ready to take on f4, Black can't yet set up the battery on the h-file. }
13... Ne6 14. dxe5 Qh6 15. Nb3
{ We should genuinely keep an eye on d4, not permitting Ne6-d4! } 15... Qh2+
{ This merely helps the king in the right direction. } 16. Kf1 Bc5 17. Rd1
{ 17.Nxc5 ??  Nd4  The knight covers e2, subsequently Black menaces Qh1+.  18.Qg2  Qh1+  19.Qxh1  Rxh1+  The king has to be moved to g2, when the rook on e1 is lost. }
17... Bxf2 18. Qxf2 { White has to survive some checks. } 18... Qh1+ 19. Ke2
Qxe4+ { Now no longer Rh2 is a threat and White can develop his bishop. } 20.
Be3 Qxc2+ 21. Rd2 Qc4+ { Crisscrossing the board, the checks come to an end. }
22. Kf3 Rh5
{ 1-0 @@StartBracket@@65@@EndBracket@@ Barbalic, Z @@StartBracket@@1979@@EndBracket@@ - Vajas, S ICCF email 2011 }
23. Qe2 Rf5+ 24. Bf4
{ Black's position is hopeless as he is a piece down. Please notice that after the queen's exchange, g5 doesn't win a piece on account of Ke4 @@StartBracket@@trapping the rook@@EndBracket@@. }
24... Rxf4+ { Yes, but now Black is a full rook down. } 25. gxf4 Qxf4+ 26. Kg2
Qg5+ 27. Kf1
{ White can secure his king by the interposing of the queen or rook on the second rank. }
