dxe5
{ These kinds of positions we should treat with utmost care and we need eyes in the back of our head, as each misstep could become fatal to us. Thus, try to learn the following lines by heart, and in the end, you will be ultimately rewarded with a pleasant and risk-free ending which you can convert into something tangible. }
11... Qe6 { Is a serious alternative, but rarely played. } 12. Nb3
{ The best, leading to a favorable position for White.   12.Ng5  Bxd1  13.Nxe6  Nxe6  Black's knight is very dominant on e6.  14.Rxd1  O-O-O  =∞  White's pieces are not coordinating and e5 will be lost after g5 and Bg7. Black is fine here. }
12... Rd8 13. Bd2
{ We have reached an extremely double-edged position here, not for the faint-hearted. White is threatening Nbd4 next, undoing the pin and hitting the f4-knight, when Black cannot take it with ...Rxd4 because of Nxd4, when the Black queen would be hanging. }
13... Bxh3 14. Ng5
{ 14.gxh3  cannot be recommended, because of  14...Qg6+  when White will be mated. }
14... Qg6 15. Qf3
{ Are you still with me? So many pieces are hanging! Let's ponder them all one-by-one. }
15... Rxd2 { If  15...Bxg2  still  16.Qxf4 } 16. Qxf4
{ when Black loses his bishop or rook. } *

