9... Ng6 10. d4
{ The main move, played over 1400 times, and essential in order to obtain 'something'. When Black takes on d4, and then e4-e5, White will find it possible to take on g4. }
10... Nf4
{ This knight move looks threatening, but White can repulse the attack. } 11.
dxe5
{ These kinds of positions we should treat with utmost care and we need eyes in the back of our head, as each misstep could become fatal to us. Thus, try to learn the following lines by heart, and in the end, you will be ultimately rewarded with a pleasant and risk-free ending which you can convert into something tangible. }
11... Qg6
{ It seems that Black's assault bears fruit. After Bxh3 or Nxh3, the Black queen will invade on g2 with - likely - a mate. To make matters worse, hx g4 will merely strengthen Black's attack after hxg4, Nh2 and g3! }
12. Nh4
{ The only way out for White, but a convenient one...   12.hxg4 ?  Once again White can't be advised to take the bishop.  12...hxg4 !  13.Nh2  In one move, White's defenses are set and done.  13...g3 !  But we are lacking time..  14.fxg3  Qxg3  -+  Simultaneously menacing to strike on g2 and h2. Black has reached a winning position. }
12... Qg5 { is a mistake, as White can let his other pieces join. } 13. Ndf3
Bxf3 { Be alert on the mating threat as Nxh3. } 14. Qxf3
{ For Black, there is not much to do against Bxf4. } 14... Qxh4 15. Bxf4
{ White obtained a close to winning position. } *

