12. Nh4 { The only way out for White, but a convenient one.. } 12... Bxd1
{ The only move. } 13. Nxg6 Nxg6 14. Rxd1
{ Now that Queens have been swapped and the matters have calmed down, White can claim the better pawn structure, and thereby, the advantage. }
14... Nxe5 15. f4
{ Whilst the king is stuck on e8, White undertakes action in the center. And why shouldn't he use his pawn majority? }
15... Bc5+ 16. Kf1
{ 16.Kh1 ?  would have been a terrible mistake, after  16...Ng4  17.hxg4??  hxg4# }
16... Nd7 17. Nf3
{ White has full control over the squares e4, d4, d5 and e5. He develops naturally, easily finding the best places for his pieces. }
17... Nf6
{ Black wants to move his knight to e4 and evt. g3, but White pulls a rabbit out of his head. }
18. f5
{ In the spirit of this opening! Next Bc1-f4 will come, hitting c7 and taking in an active position. }
18... O-O
{ Black couldn't take on e4, as the knight would be pinned after Re1. } 19. e5
{ Let's make hay while the sun is shining! } 19... Ne4 20. Bf4
{ White fully exploited his central pawns and took the lead on the board. } *

