{ The bishop won't budge an inch... bad news for us! At present, this move is maybe the most popular in tournament practice. And rightly so, we should not let Black complete his development with Ng8-e7-g6 and Qf6, otherwise, we are fighting windmills. }
7. d3 Qf6
{ Former world champion Alexander Alekhine was the first who made the Black line flourish with this strong follow-up. }
8. Nbd2
{ A solid move. The knight defends f3 and can join the defensive forces. } 8...
Ne7
{ The knight is on his road to g6 and eventually h4. White has to watch out! }
9. Re1
{ At first sight, this move may seem inexplicable in such a sharp position, since there is a piece hanging! In the following part, we will see how useful Re1 can become from a defensive perspective. Sometimes the king can escape via f1 and e2, and sometimes the knight on d2 can help to set up a block on the h2, after hxg4, hxg4 and then Nh2 and Ndf1. }
9... Ng6 10. d4
{ The main move, played over 1400 times, and essential in order to obtain 'something'. When Black takes on d4, and then e4-e5, White will find it possible to take on g4. }
10... Nf4
{ This knight move looks threatening, but White can repulse the attack. } 11.
dxe5
{ These kinds of positions we should treat with utmost care and we need eyes in the back of our head, as each misstep could become fatal to us. Thus, try to learn the following lines by heart, and in the end, you will be ultimately rewarded with a pleasant and risk-free ending which you can convert into something tangible. }
11... Qg6
{ It seems that Black's assault bears fruit. After Bxh3 or Nxh3, the Black queen will invade on g2 with - likely - a mate. To make matters worse, hx g4 will merely strengthen Black's attack after hxg4, Nh2 and g3! }
12. Nh4 { The only way out for White, but a convenient one.. } 12... Bxd1
{ The only move. } 13. Nxg6 Nxg6 14. Rxd1
{ Now that Queens have been swapped and the matters have calmed down, White can claim the better pawn structure, and thereby, the advantage. }
14... O-O-O
{ Black first wants to move the king from the center, and only then take on e5. }
15. e6
{ Before unpinning himself, White throws the cat amongst the pigeons. The concept of giving this pawn up in order to inflict as much as possible damage to Black's structure, can be considered a ' desperado' . }
15... fxe6
{ Aren't we chess players herd animals? The vast majority opts for this continuation, whereas 15... f6 is not demonstrably worse. }
16. Re1 { This unpinning is necessary for the further development. } 16... Ne5
{ The knight feels like 'the king of the world' on e5, but that's of a temporary nature as White will bash his head in when he gets the chance. }
17. Nb3
{ Black has the slightly more active pieces, but White will very soon settle the score concerning development when he can move his bishop out. What really counts is the preferable pawn structure. }
17... Be7 18. Bd2 { The Bishop will be elegantly placed on c3. } 18... g5
{ Black launches a counter offense meanwhile hindering the f2-f4 advance. } 19.
Bc3
{ Black cannot play the more logical looking Bf6, due to Nc5! The Knight is attacking the weak e6 pawn which needs to much care. }
19... Bd6 20. Rad1 { The last piece has been brought to an active position. }
20... g4
{ Black is knocking at the gates, but White stays calm and with the following move he simplifies the position. }
21. Nc1 { The Knight is on its way to d3. } 21... gxh3 22. Nd3
{ The knight on e5 couldn't stay forever on its throne. Momentarily White gives up a pawn, which will be regained with interest later. }
22... Nxd3 23. Rxd3 { The rook on h8 is hanging, so Black cannot take on g2. }
23... Rhf8
{ If  23...h2+  24.Kh1  Rhf8  , hitting  f2  , but the White rook can keep everything protected with  25.Re2  and White can look forward to a very convenient ending due to Black's shattered structure. }
24. Rxh3
{ Hitting h5. Black can no longer safeguard this pour lonesome soul. Solak converted his advantage in a persistent manner against Adams. For more see the model game Solak-Adams }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "12. 5...f6 - the Classical Variation"]
[Black "5â¦ f6: Introduction"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5
{ This is the Ruy Lopez aka the Spanish Opening. Black has a wide range of responses he can choose from, amongst others besides the main move 3...a6. First, there is 3...Nf6 - the Berlin Defense, which is the second most popular line. Former world champion Vladimir Kramnik boosted its popularity by beating Garry Kasparov in the world championships in London @@StartBracket@@2000@@EndBracket@@ with this tenacious line. The Berlin Defense will be covered in Volume 2 of this series, whereas the other main Black's defenses, amongst others: - 3...Nge7 - the Cozio Defense; - 3...g6 - the Smyslov Defense; - 3...Nd4 - the Bird Defense; -3...d6 - the Steinitz Defense; - 3...f5 - the Schliemann Defense, and; - 3...Bc5 - the Classical Defense will be covered in Volume 3. This will give you a complete repertoire in the Spanish Opening. }
3... a6
{ This is the so-called 'Morphy Defense'. There is instant tension on the board, as our opponent challenges our bishop to make up its mind. The most common move is 4.Ba4, after which the opening will branch into countless variations like the Chigorin, Breyer, Ragozin and Marshall. Black will find his move 3...a6 useful in all of these variations, as he can chase the bishop from a4 with tempo, unpinning himself in the process while also taking space on the queenside. However, completely different positions occur after our move in this course: 4. Bxc6, aka the Ruy Lopez: Exchange Variation. At the same time, uncompromising and attacking players, such as the world champions Bobby Fischer and Garry Kasparov, as well as the current elite player Shakhriyar Mamedyarov from time to time let off steam in this very entertaining line. }
4. Bxc6
{ Black can take back with either the b-pawn or d-pawn, but only the last move has gained popularity as after 4...bxc6 he faces a hard time completing his development.   4.Ba4  The main concept of Morphy's Defense materializes when White falls for the 'Noah's Ark Trap'. This happened in 1929 when Steiner got ambushed in his game against Capablanca, but the current elite grandmaster Nepomniachtchi was similarly caught in it in a recent online game.  4...d6  5.d4  b5  6.Bb3  exd4  7.Nxd4  Nxd4  8.Qxd4  c5!  All of a sudden, White's bishop is caught after c5-c4.  9.Qd5  threatening Qxf7+  Be6  10.Qc6+  The check will not help Black.  10...Bd7  11.Qd5  c4  0-1, @@StartBracket@@55@@EndBracket@@ Nepomniachtchi, I @@StartBracket@@2784@@EndBracket@@ - Demchenko, A @@StartBracket@@2641@@EndBracket@@ chess.com INT 2020 }
4... dxc6
{ The contours of the RLE position are there. White gave up his light-squared bishop and the bishop pair, leaving Black with doubled c-pawns and behind in development. White has many options here. Lasker's main choice was 5. d4, but 5. d3 and 5. Nc3 have also been tried, remaining flexible and not committing the king to g1 yet. }
5. O-O
{ The most ambitious move! White stays flexible, keeping open the options of: 1. d3 or d4, 2. whether the knight should be moved to d2, c3 or a3. The American world-class grandmaster Robert Byrne named 5.O-O is after the Dutch IM John Barendregt, who played this move a couple of times in the 60's. White has already castled while Black's pieces are all on the back rank. Moreover, Black must make an important choice as to how to protect his central pawn since White has renewed the threat of Nxe5 after castling. }
5... f6
{ From a historical perspective, 5...f6 is Black's main move. For example, Fischer encountered this move in all of his RLE games. Black's plan is plain and simple: 5...f6 guards the central e5-pawn, after which it is no longer dependent of the protection of one the pieces. }
6. d4
{ Theoretically, this move is considered as the only move for White to play for an advantage. White opens the position as Black is heavily underdeveloped. }
6... exd4
{ The contours of the structure present themselves to us. White obtained a 4 vs 3 pawn majority on the kingside. Black is saddled up with two doubled pawns on the c-file, which he should make count on the queenside. This is a difficult task to conduct, as he c-pawns are slow and immobile and - in many lines - can become weak.   6...Bg4  A popular move throughout time amongst the Black players.  7.c3  !? White's most well-known follow up here is 7. dxe5. However, this move maintains the central pawns and keeps the tension alive. The 'RLE-connoisseur' Azeri GM Guseinov played plenty of games here, with great success.  7...Bd6   7...Qe7  Another very plausible line for Black, with the obvious idea of castling long.  8.dxe5  In order not to get pinned along the d-file, the time is right to take on e5.  8...fxe5  Another reason of 8. dxe5 comes apparent. Black can no longer castle long.  9.h3  Asking the bishop for his intentions.  9...Bh5  10.Na3  As we have seen in so many lines, White moves his knight to c4.  10...Nf6  11.Nc4  Black has to start thinking about solving problems against Nxe5.1-0 @@StartBracket@@15@@EndBracket@@ 40 Guseinov, G 2666- Naroditsky, D 2621 chess. com INT 2020  8.Nbd2  Multifunctional, as the knight protects f3 and can go to c4.  8...Ne7  9.h3  I would like to stress once more the importance of this move. We take space from our opponent on the kingside, asking the bishop what route he takes.  9...Bh5   9...Be6  is another route. Guseinov played here an interesting game highlighting our trumps in this position.  10.dxe5  White is creating one more pawn weakness in his enemy's camp.  10...fxe5  The pawn on e5 is all alone and dependent on the defence of the pieces.  11.Ng5  Bg8   11...Qd7  was tried by GM Jumabayev against Guseinov, but quite convincingly White got the better chances after  12.Nxe6  Qxe6  13.Qg4  Offering the exchange of queens, is a common theme in the RLE. White is better because of his better structure. 1-0 @@StartBracket@@15@@EndBracket@@ 69 Guseinov, G 2646 - Jumabayev, R 2612 Riadh 2017  12.Qh5+  ! It seems that Black's set-up with 11...Bg8 is too slow.  12...Ng6  13.Ndf3  ! Black faces - here already on move 13 - a tough defence.  13...Qf6  14.Nh4  Black can't impede White causing further damages to his pawn structure. 1-0 @@StartBracket@@17@@EndBracket@@ 63 Guseinov, G 2621 - Abasov, N 2516 Shamkir 2014  10.dxe5  Bxe5  11.Qb3  ! Hitting the pawn on b7 and in the meantime, Black cannot castle.  11...Qc8  12.Nxe5  fxe5  Two main factors make that the assessment of this position is in White's favour: 1 the Black king in the centre, and 2 the weak pawn on e5.  13.f4  ! White decides to attack the king.  13...Bf7  What else since Black could not castle.  14.Qb4 !  Once again, Black's castling is complicated. 0-1 @@StartBracket@@17@@EndBracket@@ 38 De la Villa Garcia, J 2496 -Marin, M 2597 Benasque 2010 }
7. Nxd4 c5
{ This can be considered as the best move for Black. Due to the open character of the position and his poor king position, Black desires rather sooner than later to swap the queens. Detrimental effects to this move are that c5 can be engaged as a target, while the d5-square comes free for White's knight.   7...Ne7  The whole line seems quite scary for Black.  8.Nc3  Ng6  9.Be3  Bd6  By far Black's most popular move. Not surprisingly, 9...Bc5 hasn't been tried yet in practice. Surprisingly, the discovered attacks with the d4-knight don’t really seem to work and Black is only slightly worse.  10.Nf5  ! White is not afraid of getting doubled pawns - giving Black no air to breathe.  10...Bxf5  11.exf5  White's f5-pawn is actually quite strong. It wouldn't look bad for White if he had a piece on e6. As the ensuing lines show, White has a very pleasant position. }
8. Nb3
{ Another often played move here is 8. Ne2. The knight on b3 is momentarily well placed: it hits c5 and eventually can harass Black's queenside pawns by means of Na5. }
8... Qxd1 { Black is doing well to exchange the queens. } 9. Rxd1
{ Despite the fact that the queens are off the board, Black can't afford one small misstep here because he has fallen way behind in development. }
9... Bd7
{ Black wants to castle long, so he blocks the d-file with his bishop.   9...Bg4  For a certain period and from the moment it became fashion, this was the way to go for Black, deviating from the main path after 10...Bd7 and 11..0-0-0.  10.f3  Be6  For some time, in the heydays of this line, many Black players considered provoking f2-f3 an improvement over their position. Indeed, after c4 Black can instantly give a check on c5 or pin the knight. On the other hand, White would like to place his pawn on any occasion on f3, so he spares time.  11.Bf4  I believe that 11.Bf4 is the strongest finalizing the development meanwhile attacking c7, but 11.Nc3 is neither without venom. When Black is doesn't know his theory well, he may be busted.   11.Nc3  A very interesting alternative to our main line, used once by Mamedyarov! Black should be well in his theory, otherwise his game can quickly collapse.  11...Bd6  12.Be3  Eagerly White tries to find an opening in Black's position.  12...b6  13.a4  White is intending a5, to make Black stagger.  11...c4  !? In the given situation, the knight's best place is on d4, which enables Black to castle.  12.Nd4  Black can pin the knight in two ways, nevertheless 0-0-0 is the only played move here.  12...O-O-O  13.Nc3  The rooks are connected again.  13...Bf7   13...Bc5  14.Be3  White can quite easily finish his development with Kf2, reaching perfect harmony between his pieces. 0-1 @@StartBracket@@22@@EndBracket@@ 40 Fressinet, L 2581- Rausis, I 2525 France 2001   13...Rxd4  This gives White some extra options. I believe this is the worst amongst Black's 3 options of Bf7, Bc5 or Rxd4.  14.Rxd4  Bc5  15.Ne2  ! White is enabled to regroup the knight from c3 to d4.  14.Kf2  Ne7  15.Be3  Anticipating on Ng6 and Bc5. Besides, the f4 square is vacated for a knight or a pawn.  15...h5  16.Rd2  Ng6  17.Rad1  White maintains a small but lasting advantage. Please have a look in the model game section for: 1-0 60 Rozentalis, E 2592 - Bojkov, D 2553 Queenstown 2012. }
10. Nc3
{ White's next moves will be Bf4, Nd5 and - if he is permitted to - a4-a5. }
10... O-O-O 11. Bf4
{ Black finds it hard to complete development. The moves 11...Bd6, 11...Nh6 and 11...Ne7 don't work since c5 is hanging. }
11... Be6
{ The only move that keeps Black in the game. The other moves 11...g5 and 12...Be6, are considerably less convincing. 11...Re8 appeared in one of the most ancient games of this line: Dutch IM John Barendregt played it in 1961. His opponent, who had to do without the current theory, chose a normal looking move. It was the beginning of a crushing defeat and a short game of merely 21 moves. Hence, the Ruy Lopez Exchange Variation can be hazardously risky for Black, even after the exchange of queens! By trial and error, the Black players figured out how they should hold the position.   11...Re8  ? This appeared twice in - respectively - 1960 and '61, in the games of the Dutch IM Barendregt, after whom the RLE-line 5. 0-0 has been named by Robert Byrne.  12.Nd5 !  Black suddenly finds himself in trouble. How should he defend his c7-pawn?   11...g5  is not without risk.  12.Bg3  Be6  applying the same idea as in our main line.  13.Rxd8+  Kxd8  14.Rd1+  Kc8  15.Nd5  What can be done in the defence of the c7-pawn; Black is forced to give up on his bishop pair by taking on d5.  15...Bxd5  16.Rxd5  b6  17.Rd1  Ne7  18.Nd2  Nc6  19.Nf1  !? The knight is on its way to f5 and White retains the better odds. }
12. Rxd8+ Kxd8
{ Black's position looks ugly, as he is so underdeveloped, and stuck with doubled pawns. Nonetheless, this is the most relevant position in the entire Ruy Lopez Exchange Variation. Black's position is resilient and White's main threat Nd5 can be dealt with...Bxd5. }
13. Rd1+ Kc8 14. Nd5
{ The key idea in this line. White attacks the undefendable pawn on c7. Black can't do more than to give up his bishop pair to save his weak pawn. }
14... Bxd5
{ 14...c6  Allows a beautiful mate, but can't be recommended  15.Nb6 } 15. Rxd5
b6
{ We reached the tabiya of the Ruy-Lopez Exchange Variation. The main line is 16. Rd1, but White can as well improve his knight's position first. }
16. Nd2
{ White can't break through, notwithstanding the fact that he enjoys the stronger pawn structure. It's time to regroup the pieces, before moving the kingside pawns forward. Take notice of the great model game Kovacevic-Tosic @@StartBracket@@SRB-Ch, 2013 @@StartBracket@@1-0@@EndBracket@@@@EndBracket@@. here }
