{ From a historical perspective, 5... f6 is Black's main move in theory. For example, Fischer encountered this move in all of his RLE games . Black's plan is plain and simple: 5... f6 guards the central e5-pawn, after which it is no longer dependent of the protection of one the pieces. }
6. d4
{ Theoretically, this move is considered as the only move for White to play for an advantage. White opens the position while Black is heavily underdeveloped. }
6... Bg4
{ A popular move throughout time amongst Black players. Black pins the knight and increases the tension in the center. }
7. c3
{ White's most well-known follow up here is 7. dxe5. Magnus Carlsen @@StartBracket@@who else?@@EndBracket@@ decreased my interest for this line. He defeated Kamsky in convincing style   7.dxe5  Qxd1  8.Rxd1  fxe5  9.Rd3  Bd6  10.Nbd2  Nf6  11.Nc4  O-O  12.Nfxe5  Be2  13.Re3  Bxc4  14.Nxc4  Ng4  15.Re2  Bxh2+  16.Kf1  Rae8  17.Nd2  Rd8  18.f3  Bg3  19.Kg1  Ne5  20.b3  Ng6  21.Nf1  Be5  when Black was winning material Kamsky, Gata @@StartBracket@@2741@@EndBracket@@ - Carlsen, Magnus @@StartBracket@@2862@@EndBracket@@ Sinquefield Cup 1st Saint Louis, 13.09.2013. However, this move maintains the central pawns and keeps the tension alive. The 'RLE-connoisseur' Azeri GM Guseinov played plenty of games here, with great success. }
7... Qe7
{ Another very plausible line for Black, with the obvious idea of castling long. }
8. dxe5
{ In order not to get pinned along the d-file, the time is right to take on e5. }
8... fxe5
{ Another reason of 8. dxe5 comes apparent. Black can no longer castle long. }
9. h3 { Asking the bishop for his intentions. } 9... Bh5 10. Na3
{ As we have seen in so many lines, White moves his knight to c4. } 10... Nf6
{ Now Black for the moment keeps the option open of castling long and attacks e4.   After  10...Rd8  11.Qe2  Qe6  12.Nc2  Nf6  13.Ne3  Bc5  14.Nf5  followed by g4, White takes the lead. }
11. Nc4 { Black should do something against Nxe5. } 11... Qe6
{ An interesting attempt of the Black player. For the sake of creating attacking chances for himself, he sacrifices a pawn.  11...Nd7  may well be a good alternative for Black.  12.Na5  Rb8 !  A difficult move to find, but not for the correspondence player!: 1/2-1/2 @@StartBracket@@19@@EndBracket@@ Valak, A @@StartBracket@@2423@@EndBracket@@- Silva, R @@StartBracket@@2373@@EndBracket@@ ICCF email 2011   11...Nxe4  is simply bad, due to  12.Re1  when White is winning. }
12. Ncxe5 Bd6
{ Black's compensation seems to be more than enough, however White pulls a card out of his sleeve. }
13. Qb3
{ Offering the exchange of queens, thereby reducing the tension on the knights. }
13... Qe7 { Black cannot avoid the exchange of queens, because of } 14. Qxb7
{ Black has no time to take on e5. } 14... O-O 15. Nxc6
{ Again Black is kept busy - since his queen is under siege now, he should  (temporarily)  leave his attacking aspirations. }
15... Qxe4 16. Re1
{ Once more, we don't give Black the space to attack our king. } 16... Qd5 17.
Qb3
{ After the exchange of queens, we remain material up. After  17...Bxf3  18.gxf3  the swap of queens is still on the menu. }
