Bb4
{ Black quickly develops while trying to do harm to white's pawn structure. }
10. Nce2 { White doesn't let Black damage his pawns. } 10... O-O
{ White wants to use squares d2 and e1, so.. } 11. c3 Bd6 12. Nf5
{ Black doesn't enjoy taking on f5. He would surrender his bishop pair and allow a weak square on e6. }
12... Re8 13. Qb3+ Kh8
{ Unfortunately for our opponent, he can't develop with 13...Be6?, as we are hungry for a pawn with  (14.Qxb7.) }
14. Neg3
{ On the next move, we follow up with 15.Rad1 and possibly 16.Bc5. Black has no choice and should quickly encounter the mighty knights. }
14... Bxg3 15. Nxg3 b6
{ A well-known strategy in these positions: placing the pawns on the colour of the opposing bishop. }
16. Qc2
{ The queen on b3 has served her purpose, while - now - on c2, she protects e4. }
16... Qe7 17. c4
{ White is engaging with the similar strategy of placing the pawns on the colour of the opposing bishop. His own bishop becomes more mobile in the meantime. }
17... c5 18. f3 { Fortifying the center and resuming conducting his plan. }
18... Ne5 19. b3
{ The pawn wedges are a nuisance for the Black bishop. Everywhere it goes, its range is blocked. }
19... Be6
{ White has placed his pawn perfectly; they are almost all on light squares restricting his opponent's bishop. Now he regroups his knight. }
20. Ne2
{ White regroups the knight in the direction of d5: the balance is clearly in White's favor. It's hard to give Black any good advice here. }
20... Bg8 21. Nc3
{ Hitting the square d5. Once again, White's pawn structure makes it so that he has the better odds   21.Nc3  c6  avoids Nd5 but creates a new target..   21...Rad8  22.Rad1  h6  23.Rfe1  Qf8  24.Nd5  Bxd5  25.cxd5  And White obtained a large advantage. His pawn structure is better as is his bishop to the knight.  22.Na4 !  Yes! The pawn on b6 is now under fire.  22...Rab8  23.Rad1  and White takes the lead on the open file. Black hands are tied to the defence of the weak b6 pawn. }
