4... dxc6
{ The contours of the RLE position are there. White gave up his light-squared bishop and the bishop pair, leaving Black with doubled c-pawns and behind in development. White has many options here. Lasker's main choice was 5. d4, but 5. d3 and 5. Nc3 have also been tried, remaining flexible and not committing the king to g1 yet. }
5. O-O
{ The most ambitious move! White stays flexible, keeping open the options of: 1. d3 or d4, 2. whether the knight should be moved to d2, c3 or a3. The American world-class grandmaster Robert Byrne named 5.O-O is after the Dutch IM John Barendregt, who played this move a couple of times in the 60's. White has already castled while Black's pieces are all on the back rank. Moreover, Black must make an important choice as to how to protect his central pawn since White has renewed the threat of Nxe5 after castling. }
5... f6
{ From a historical perspective, 5... f6 is Black's main move in theory. For example, Fischer encountered this move in all of his RLE games . Black's plan is plain and simple: 5... f6 guards the central e5-pawn, after which it is no longer dependent of the protection of one the pieces. }
6. d4
{ Theoretically, this move is considered as the only move for White to play for an advantage. White opens the position while Black is heavily underdeveloped. }
6... exd4
{ The contours of the structure present themselves to us. White obtained a 4 vs 3 pawn majority on the kingside. Black is saddled with two doubled pawns on the c-file, which he should make count on the queenside. This is a difficult task to conduct, as the c-pawns are slow and immobile and - in many lines - can become weak. }
7. Nxd4 c5
{ This can be considered as the best move for Black. Due to the open character of the position and his poor king position, Black desires rather sooner than later to swap the queens. Detrimental effects to this move are that c5 can be engaged as a target, while the d5-square comes free for White's knight. }
8. Nb3
{ Another often played move here is 8.Ne2. The knight on b3 is momentarily well placed: hitting c5 and - evt. - it can harass Black's queenside pawns by means of Na5. }
8... Qxd1 { Black is doing well to exchange the queens. } 9. Rxd1
{ Albeit that the queens are off the board, Black can't afford one small misstep here because he has fallen way behind in development. }
9... Bg4
{ For a certain period and from the moment it became fashion, this was the way to go for Black, deviating from the main path after 10..Bd7 and 11..0-0-0. }
10. f3 Bd7 11. Bf4 O-O-O 12. Nc3 c4
{ 12...Be6  13.Rxd8+  Kxd8  14.Rd1+  Kc8  15.Nd5  Bxd5  16.Rxd5  b6  ½-½ @@StartBracket@@52@@EndBracket@@ Oleksienko, M @@StartBracket@@2525@@EndBracket@@ - Socko,B @@StartBracket@@2637@@EndBracket@@ Rijeka 2010. This is a transposition after the main line without the moves 9... Bg4 10. f3 included. Since White intends to play f2-f3 anyway, this is a better version. }
13. Na5 Bc5+ { 13...b5  14.Nd5  Bc5+  is a transposition to our main line. }
14. Kh1
{ White's main choice here is  14.Kf1  but the king will be exposed to all kind of checks, for instance after  b5  15.Nd5  Ne7  16.Bxc7  Nxd5  here becomes clear that Bxd8 is not possible, due to Ne3+.  17.Rxd5  Kxc7  18.Rxc5+  Kb6 !  On this occasion the Black king is not insecure at b6 at all!  19.b4  cxb3  20.Nxb3  Be6  is unclear. }
14... b5 { The only way to protect b5. } 15. Nd5
{ As seen so often in the RLE-lines: the c7-pawn can be considered Black's Achilles heel. }
15... Ne7 { Relying on a tactical idea. } 16. Bxc7
{ 16.Nxc7 ??  is a mishit, after  Bb6 ! } 16... Nxd5 17. Bxd8
{ A serie of moves with mass exchanges takes place. } 17... Ne3 18. Nb7
{ You will be amazed, but this move appeared 20 times in practice! } 18... Nxd1
{ 18...Kxb7  is losing, due to  19.Rxd7+  Kc6   19...Kc8 ?  20.Rc7+  +-  20.Rc7+ !  Kd6  21.Rc8 !!  after Kd7, the c5-bishop will be taken, whereas White threatens a discovered check now. }
19. Nxc5 Nf2+
{ 19...Nxb2  20.Ba5 !  Na4  21.Nxa4  bxa4  22.Rd1  Despite the fact of the opposite coloured bishops ending, with the rooks on the board there is plenty to play for. White dominates here. }
20. Kg1 Nxe4 { a desperado in its purest form. } 21. Nxe4 Rxd8
{ Is this a draw? Definitely not, as the following game shows. } 22. Rd1 Kc7
23. Nc5
{ White has much better ending due to his better king and Black's weak queenside pawns. }
23... Bc8 24. Rxd8 Kxd8 25. Kf2 Ke7 26. Ke3 Kd6 27. Kd4
{ Clearly, White's king prevails, as does his knight. Black is facing hard times in the joyless ending. Please see the following game shows how quick things could go downhill for our poor opponent.   27...g5  28.g3  h6  29.a4  Kc6  30.a5  Kd6  31.Ne4+  Ke6  32.Nc5+  Kd6  33.f4  gxf4  34.gxf4  Bf5  35.Nxa6  Bxc2  36.Nb4  Bd1  37.Nd5 !  the pawn on f6 or b5  (after Nc3)  is going to fall.  Bf3  38.Nxf6  Ke6  39.Ne4  Kf5  40.Nd6+  Kxf4  41.Nxb5  Kg4  42.Nd6  Ba8  43.Kxc4  Kh3  44.b4  Kxh2  45.b5  h5  46.Nf5  1-0 @@StartBracket@@46@@EndBracket@@ Orlov, A @@StartBracket@@2520@@EndBracket@@ - Zajogin,A @@StartBracket@@2400@@EndBracket@@ Germany 2008. }
*

