12... O-O-O 13. Nc3 { The rooks are connected again. } 13... Rxd4
{ This gives White some extra options. I believe this is the worst amongst Black's 3 options of Bf7, Bc5 or Rxd4. }
14. Rxd4 Bc5 15. Ne2 { White is enabled to regroup the knight from c3 to d4. }
15... Bf7 16. Be3 Ne7 { Even here, the rook is pinned. } 17. Kf2
{ This move is anyhow on our agenda, as the king move contributes to the reinforcement of the pawn majority. Now Black is forced to take our rook otherwise we will move it. }
17... Bxd4 18. Bxd4
{ The bishop finds his perfect spot on c3, from where it puts pressure on the f6 and g7 block of pawns @@StartBracket@@e.g. after g4 and g5 - as in the model game Fressinet-Rausis@@EndBracket@@. }
