{ White's most popular option, played over 120 times, containing a trick to exchange one of the bishops. }
14... Rxd1+ 15. Rxd1 g6 { This causes the by Nf5 provoked weakening. } 16. Nd4
{ The move g7-g6 restricts the only light-squared bishop on the board. Moreover, the Black squares and f6 specifically, are weak  (er)  . The provocation of 14.Nf5 has paid out! }
16... Bc5 17. Be3
{ Not solely unpinning, meanwhile applying a tactical concept of which we are aware now. }
17... Ne7 18. Nf5
{ Offering the exchange of the bishops. In case Black accepts the invitation, he will have trouble to protect the pawn and/or square on f6. }
18... Bxe3+
{ Giving up the bishop pair, is not something Black is striving for. } 19. Nxe3
Rd8 { Comprehensibly, our opponent wants to fight the d-file. } 20. Rxd8+
{ Notwithstanding the previous note, we are glad to swap the pieces. As shown in the modelgames and examples from the introduction, due to our favorable pawn structure we maintain all chances on a good outcome. }
20... Kxd8 21. Ng4
{ White's position has improved considerably. The provocation of Nf5, g7-g6, resulted into a weakness consisting of the pawn on f6. White is superior on the black squares and will try to capitalize on this and his pawn majority on the kingside. }
