12. Nd5 { How should Black defend his c7-pawn? } 12... Rxe4 13. Bxc7 Ne7 14.
Nc3 { After the rook moves, our bishop can retreat. } 14... Rc4 15. Bg3
{ The Black squares have been weakened. The cavalry is ready to make use of these holes in Black's position. }
15... Be6
{ 15...Bc6  16.f3 !  does not help Black either.  16...Nf5  17.Bf2  The rook is totally misplaced, and on the next move comes Na5. }
16. Rd6 Bf5
{ Black's position is hopeless here in the game: 1-0 @@StartBracket@@42@@EndBracket@@ Benjamin, J @@StartBracket@@2585@@EndBracket@@- Rowley, R @@StartBracket@@2375@@EndBracket@@ Philadelphia 1993. White could improve here with the following sequence of moves. }
17. Re1
{ White obtained 2 powerful rooks on the open files. Black is facing the impossible task of completing his development. }
17... Bxc2 18. Na5
{ The knights have become a scourge for the pitiful Black player. } 18... Rd4
19. Rb6 { Hitting b7. } 19... Rd7 20. Rc1 { Our new target is the pawn on c5. }
20... Bd3 21. Na4
{ Black is defenseless against all the threats coming his way. } *

