{ applying the same idea as in our main line. } 13. Rxd8+ Kxd8 14. Rd1+
{ Black should retreat to c8, since the c7-pawn needs protection. } 14... Kc8
15. Nd5
{ What can be done in the defence of the c7-pawn? Black is forced to give up on his bishop pair by taking on d5. }
15... Bxd5 16. Rxd5
{ Black still does not have the time to develop his pieces. This time it's the pawn on c5 which needs guidance. }
16... b6 17. Rd1
{ The rook conducted its task on d5 and there are no breakthroughs..so, let's return. }
17... Ne7 18. Nd2 Nc6 19. Nf1
{ The knight is on its way to f5, retaining the better odds.   The following moves  19.Nc4  h5  appeared in  Malisauskas, V @@StartBracket@@2530@@EndBracket@@ - Smyslov, V @@StartBracket@@2550@@EndBracket@@ Tallinn 1996 1/2-1/2 @@StartBracket@@51@@EndBracket@@, but was not changing the course of the game much due to White's superior pawn structure. }
