{ Black finds it hard to complete its development. The moves 11..Bd6, either Nh6, or 11..Ne7 @@StartBracket@@c5 is hanging@@EndBracket@@ and are out of the question now. }
11... Be6
{ The only move that keeps Black in the game. The other moves 11.. g5 and 12.. Be6, are considerably less convincing. 11..Re8 appeared in one of the most ancient games of this line: Dutch IM John Barendregt played it in 1961. His opponent, who had to do without the current theory, chose a normal looking move. It was the beginning of a crushing defeat and a short game of merely 21 moves. Hence, the Ruy Lopez Exchange Variation can be hazardously risky for Black, even after the exchange of queens! By trial and error, the Black players figured out how they should hold the position. }
12. Rxd8+ Kxd8
{ Black's position looks ugly, as he is so underdeveloped and in the meantime he is stuck with a double pawn. Nonetheless, this is the most relevant position in the entire Ruy Lopez Exchange Variation. Black's position is resilient and White's main threat Nd5 can be dealt with by Bxd5. }
13. Rd1+ Kc8 14. Nd5
{ The key idea in this line. White attacks the undefendable pawn on c7. Black can't do more than to give up his bishop pair to save his weak pawn. }
14... c6 { Allows a beautiful mate, but can't be recommended } 15. Nb6# *

