{ The contours of the RLE position are there. White gave up his light-squared bishop and the bishop pair, leaving Black with doubled c-pawns and behind in development. White has many options here. Lasker's main choice was 5. d4, but 5. d3 and 5. Nc3 have also been tried, remaining flexible and not committing the king to g1 yet. }
5. O-O
{ The most ambitious move! White stays flexible, keeping open the options of: 1. d3 or d4, 2. whether the knight should be moved to d2, c3 or a3. The American world-class grandmaster Robert Byrne named 5.O-O is after the Dutch IM John Barendregt, who played this move a couple of times in the 60's. White has already castled while Black's pieces are all on the back rank. Moreover, Black must make an important choice as to how to protect his central pawn since White has renewed the threat of Nxe5 after castling. }
5... f6
{ From a historical perspective, 5...f6 is Black's main move. For example, Fischer encountered this move in all of his RLE games. Black's plan is plain and simple: 5...f6 guards the central e5-pawn, after which it is no longer dependent of the protection of one the pieces. }
6. d4
{ Theoretically, this move is considered as the only move for White to play for an advantage. White opens the position as Black is heavily underdeveloped. }
6... exd4
{ The contours of the structure present themselves to us. White obtained a 4 vs 3 pawn majority on the kingside. Black is saddled up with two doubled pawns on the c-file, which he should make count on the queenside. This is a difficult task to conduct, as he c-pawns are slow and immobile and - in many lines - can become weak.   6...Bg4  A popular move throughout time amongst the Black players.  7.c3  !? White's most well-known follow up here is 7. dxe5. However, this move maintains the central pawns and keeps the tension alive. The 'RLE-connoisseur' Azeri GM Guseinov played plenty of games here, with great success.  7...Bd6   7...Qe7  Another very plausible line for Black, with the obvious idea of castling long.  8.dxe5  In order not to get pinned along the d-file, the time is right to take on e5.  8...fxe5  Another reason of 8. dxe5 comes apparent. Black can no longer castle long.  9.h3  Asking the bishop for his intentions.  9...Bh5  10.Na3  As we have seen in so many lines, White moves his knight to c4.  10...Nf6  11.Nc4  Black has to start thinking about solving problems against Nxe5.1-0 @@StartBracket@@15@@EndBracket@@ 40 Guseinov, G 2666- Naroditsky, D 2621 chess. com INT 2020   8.Nbd2  Multifunctional, as the knight protects f3 and can go to c4.  8...Ne7  9.h3  I would like to stress once more the importance of this move. We take space from our opponent on the kingside, asking the bishop what route he takes.  9...Bh5   9...Be6  is another route. Guseinov played here an interesting game highlighting our trumps in this position.  10.dxe5  White is creating one more pawn weakness in his enemy's camp.  10...fxe5  The pawn on e5 is all alone and dependent on the defence of the pieces.  11.Ng5  Bg8   11...Qd7  was tried by GM Jumabayev against Guseinov, but quite convincingly White got the better chances after  12.Nxe6  Qxe6  13.Qg4  Offering the exchange of queens, is a common theme in the RLE. White is better because of his better structure. 1-0 @@StartBracket@@15@@EndBracket@@ 69 Guseinov, G 2646 - Jumabayev, R 2612 Riadh 2017  12.Qh5+  ! It seems that Black's set-up with 11...Bg8 is too slow.  12...Ng6  13.Ndf3  ! Black faces - here already on move 13 - a tough defence.  13...Qf6  14.Nh4  Black can't impede White causing further damages to his pawn structure. 1-0 @@StartBracket@@17@@EndBracket@@ 63 Guseinov, G 2621 - Abasov, N 2516 Shamkir 2014   10.dxe5  Bxe5  11.Qb3  ! Hitting the pawn on b7 and in the meantime Black cannot castle.  11...Qc8  12.Nxe5  fxe5  Two main factors make that the assessment of this position is in White's favour: 1 the Black king in the centre, and 2 the weak pawn on e5.  13.f4  ! White decides to attack the king.  13...Bf7  What else since Black could not castle.  14.Qb4 !  Once again, Black's castling is complicated. 0-1 @@StartBracket@@17@@EndBracket@@ 38 De la Villa Garcia, J @@StartBracket@@2496@@EndBracket@@ -Marin, M @@StartBracket@@2597@@EndBracket@@ Benasque 2010 }
7. Nxd4 c5
{ This can be considered as the best move for Black. Due to the open character of the position and his poor king position, Black desires rather sooner than later to swap the queens. Detrimental effects to this move are that c5 can be engaged as a target, while the d5-square comes free for White's knight.   7...Ne7  The whole line seems quite scary for Black.  8.Nc3  Ng6  9.Be3  Bd6  By far Black's most popular move. Not surprisingly, 9..Bc5 hasn't been tried yet in practice. Surprisingly, the discovered attacks with the d4-knight don’t really seem to work and Black is only a slightly worse.  10.Nf5  ! White is not afraid of getting doubled pawns - giving Black no air to breathe.  10...Bxf5  11.exf5  White's f5-pawn is actually quite strong. It wouldn't look bad for White if he had a piece on e6. As the ensuing lines show, White has a very pleasant position. }
8. Nb3
{ Another often played move here is 8. Ne2. The knight on b3 is momentarily well placed: it hits c5 and eventually can harass Black's queenside pawns by means of Na5. }
8... Qxd1 { Black is doing well to exchange the queens. } 9. Rxd1
{ Albeit that the queens are off the board, Black can't afford one small misstep here because he has fallen way behind in development. }
9... Bd7
{ Black wants to castle long, so he blocks the d-file with his bishop.   9...Bg4  For a certain period and from the moment it became fashion, this was the way to go for Black, deviating from the main path after 10..Bd7 and 11..0-0-0.  10.f3  Be6  For some time, in the heydays of this line, many Black players considered provoking f2-f3 an improvement over their position. Indeed, after c4 Black can instantly give a check on c5 or pin the knight. On the other hand, White would like to place his pawn on any occasion on f3, so he spares time.  11.Bf4  I believe that 11.Bf4 is the strongest finalizing the development meanwhile attacking c7, but 11.Nc3 is neither without venom. When Black is doesn't know his theory well, he may be busted.   11.Nc3  A very interesting alternative to our main line, used once by Mamedyarov! Black should be well in his theory, otherwise his game can quickly collapse.  11...Bd6  12.Be3  Eagerly White tries to find an opening in Black's position.  12...b6  13.a4  White is intending a5, to make Black stagger.  11...c4  !? In the given situation, the knight's best place is on d4, which enables Black to castle.  12.Nd4  Black can pin the knight in two ways, nevertheless 0-0-0 is the only played move here.  12...O-O-O  13.Nc3  The rooks are connected again.  13...Bf7   13...Bc5  14.Be3  White can quite easily finish his development with Kf2, reaching perfect harmony between his pieces. 0-1 @@StartBracket@@40@@EndBracket@@ Fressinet, L @@StartBracket@@2581@@EndBracket@@- Rausis, I @@StartBracket@@2525@@EndBracket@@ France 2001    13...Rxd4  This gives White some extra options. I believe this is the worst amongst Black's 3 options of Bf7, Bc5 or Rxd4.  14.Rxd4  Bc5  15.Ne2  ! White is enabled to regroup the knight from c3 to d4.  14.Kf2  Ne7  15.Be3  Anticipating on Ng6 and Bc5. Besides, the f4 square is vacated for a knight or a pawn.  15...h5  16.Rd2  Ng6  17.Rad1  White maintains a small but lasting advantage. Please have a look in the model game section for: 1-0 @@StartBracket@@60@@EndBracket@@ Rozentalis, E @@StartBracket@@2592@@EndBracket@@ - Bojkov, D @@StartBracket@@2553@@EndBracket@@ Queenstown 2012. }
10. Nc3
{ White's next moves will be Bf4, Nd5 and - if he is permitted to - a4-a5. }
10... O-O-O 11. Bf4
{ Black finds it hard to complete its development. The moves 11..Bd6, either Nh6, or 11..Ne7 c5 is hanging and are out of the question now. }
11... Be6
{ The only move that keeps Black in the game. The other moves 11.. g5 and 12.. Be6, are considerably less convincing. 11..Re8 appeared in one of the most ancient games of this line: Dutch IM John Barendregt played it in 1961. His opponent, who had to do without the current theory, chose a normal looking move. It was the beginning of a crushing defeat and a short game of merely 21 moves. Hence, the Ruy Lopez Exchange Variation can be hazardously risky for Black, even after the exchange of queens! By trial and error, the Black players figured out how they should hold the position.   11...Re8  ? This appeared twice in - respectively - 1960 and '61, in the games of the Dutch IM Barendregt, after whom the RLE-line 5. 0-0 has been named by Robert Byrne.  12.Nd5 !  Black suddenly finds himself in trouble. How should he defend his c7-pawn?   11...g5  is not without risk.  12.Bg3  Be6  applying the same idea as in our main line.  13.Rxd8+  Kxd8  14.Rd1+  Kc8  15.Nd5  What can be done in the defence of the c7-pawn; Black is forced to give up on his bishop pair by taking on d5.  15...Bxd5  16.Rxd5  b6  17.Rd1  Ne7  18.Nd2  Nc6  19.Nf1  !? The knight is on its way to f5, remaining the better odds. }
12. Rxd8+ Kxd8
{ Black's position looks ugly, as he is so underdeveloped and in the meantime he is stuck with a double pawn. Nonetheless, this is the most relevant position in the entire Ruy Lopez Exchange Variation. Black's position is resilient and White's main threat Nd5 can be dealt with by Bxd5. }
13. Rd1+ Kc8 14. Nd5
{ The key idea in this line. White attacks the undefendable pawn on c7. Black can't do more than to give up his bishop pair to save his weak pawn. }
14... Bxd5
{ 14...c6  Allows a beautiful mate, but can't be recommended  15.Nb6 } 15. Rxd5
b6
{ We reached the tabiya of the Ruy-Lopez Exchange Variation. The main line is 16. Rd1, but White can as well improve his knight's position first. }
16. Nd2
{ White can't break through, notwithstanding he enjoys the stronger pawn structure. It's time for the regrouping of the pieces, before moving the kingside pawns forward. For all of the key ideas how to proceed here with White, please take notice of the next strong model games in the following, starting of Kovacevic-Tosic @@StartBracket@@SRB-Ch, 2013 @@StartBracket@@1-0@@EndBracket@@@@EndBracket@@. }
