[White "12. 5...f6 - the Classical Variation"]
[Black "16. Nd2 Model Game"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5
{ This is the Ruy Lopez aka the Spanish Opening. Black has a wide range of responses he can choose from, amongst others besides the main move 3...a6. First, there is 3...Nf6 - the Berlin Defense, which is the second most popular line. Former world champion Vladimir Kramnik boosted its popularity by beating Garry Kasparov in the world championships in London @@StartBracket@@2000@@EndBracket@@ with this tenacious line. The Berlin Defense will be covered in Volume 2 of this series, whereas the other main Black's defenses, amongst others: - 3...Nge7 - the Cozio Defense; - 3...g6 - the Smyslov Defense; - 3...Nd4 - the Bird Defense; -3...d6 - the Steinitz Defense; - 3...f5 - the Schliemann Defense, and; - 3...Bc5 - the Classical Defense will be covered in Volume 3. This will give you a complete repertoire in the Spanish Opening. }
3... a6
{ This is the so-called 'Morphy Defense'. There is instant tension on the board, as our opponent challenges our bishop to make up its mind. The most common move is 4.Ba4, after which the opening will branch into countless variations like the Chigorin, Breyer, Ragozin and Marshall. Black will find his move 3...a6 useful in all of these variations, as he can chase the bishop from a4 with tempo, unpinning himself in the process while also taking space on the queenside. However, completely different positions occur after our move in this course: 4. Bxc6, aka the Ruy Lopez: Exchange Variation. At the same time, uncompromising and attacking players, such as the world champions Bobby Fischer and Garry Kasparov, as well as the current elite player Shakhriyar Mamedyarov from time to time let off steam in this very entertaining line. }
4. Bxc6
{ Black can take back with either the b-pawn or d-pawn, but only the last move has gained popularity as after 4...bxc6 he faces a hard time completing his development.   4.Ba4  The main concept of Morphy's Defense materializes when White falls for the 'Noah's Ark Trap'. This happened in 1929 when Steiner got ambushed in his game against Capablanca, but the current elite grandmaster Nepomniachtchi was similarly caught in it in a recent online game.  4...d6  5.d4  b5  6.Bb3  exd4  7.Nxd4  Nxd4  8.Qxd4  c5!  All of a sudden, White's bishop is caught after c5-c4.  9.Qd5  threatening Qxf7+  Be6  10.Qc6+  The check will not help Black.  10...Bd7  11.Qd5  c4  0-1, @@StartBracket@@55@@EndBracket@@ Nepomniachtchi, I @@StartBracket@@2784@@EndBracket@@ - Demchenko, A @@StartBracket@@2641@@EndBracket@@ chess.com INT 2020 }
4... dxc6
{ The contours of the RLE position are there. White gave up his light-squared bishop and the bishop pair, leaving Black with doubled c-pawns and behind in development. White has many options here. Lasker's main choice was 5. d4, but 5. d3 and 5. Nc3 have also been tried, remaining flexible and not committing the king to g1 yet. }
5. O-O
{ The most ambitious move! White stays flexible, keeping open the options of: 1. d3 or d4, 2. whether the knight should be moved to d2, c3 or a3. The American world-class grandmaster Robert Byrne named 5.O-O is after the Dutch IM John Barendregt, who played this move a couple of times in the 60's. White has already castled while Black's pieces are all on the back rank. Moreover, Black must make an important choice as to how to protect his central pawn since White has renewed the threat of Nxe5 after castling. }
5... f6 6. d4 exd4 7. Nxd4 c5
{ As came forward in the theory section, Black - being behind in development - aims for the exchange of queens. }
8. Nb3 Qxd1 9. Rxd1 Bd7 10. Nc3 O-O-O 11. Bf4
{ White follows our main line here. As we have seen so far, Black has to do something against the threat of Nd5. }
11... Be6
{ When our mind is blank, we could consider the fact that this is our opponent's best try as a miracle. After all, he is so much down on development and nonetheless, he allows Rxd8. }
12. Rxd8+ Kxd8 13. Rd1+ Kc8
{ Imperceptibly, Black's position is impenetrable. It's hard to find an entrance somewhere. }
14. Nd5
{ As a result, we attempt to create the most favorable circumstances for the ending. Black has to make a concession of giving up his bishop pair. }
14... Bxd5 15. Rxd5 b6
{ We reached the tabiya of the Ruy-Lopez Exchange Variation. The main line is 16. Rd1, but White can as well improve his knight's position first. In order to get a hold on how to handle these types of positions, please study thoroughly the following plans of this model game. From this starting point, you can find more interesting games in this model game chapter }
16. Nd2 Ne7 17. Rd3 Nc6 18. c3
{ White wants to avoid an uninvited guest after 18..Nb4/d4. } 18... Nd8
{ This knight manoeuvre is cumbersome and causes a loss of time. It was better to set the pawns in motion after Be7  and b5. }
19. h4
{ On the contrary, White doesn't hesitate and sets his main force in motion. }
19... Ne6 20. Bh2
{ In my opinion, the following set-up with the bishop on  e3  - a sound central place - could have been be preferred:  20.Be3  h5  21.g3  g6  22.Kg2  Be7  23.b3  when White is ready to march forward with his pawns. However, this odd-looking bishop position doesn't spoil anything: Black can't play Bd6 and likewise White is ready for f2-f4. }
20... Be7 21. Kf1 Re8 22. f4 Bf8 23. Re3
{ 23.f5  This move may well come to early, as it is devaluing the pawn majority on the kingside by giving himself a backward pawn on e4.  23...Nd8  24.b3  Nf7  the knight is on its way to d6, where it is taking the pawn on e4 under siege. }
23... b5 24. b3
{ Stopping the Black avalanche meanwhile avoiding any exchanges of the  (doubled)  pawns. In this way, for Black it's hard to exploit his queenside majority. }
24... g6 25. Ke2 Bh6 26. g3
{ White is stabilizing his kingside pawns and restricting the mobility of his opponent's pieces. One may wonder how our bishop got on h2. Despite this flaw in White's mobility of his piece@@StartBracket@@s@@EndBracket@@, White only has to move his king to f3 before he can set his pride and joy in motion. }
26... Kd7 27. Rd3+ Kc6 28. Kf3 { White is ready now to play g4. } 28... Bf8 29.
Bg1
{ White understands now that the bishop could have been better placed on e3. It's a loss of time, but Black cannot take profit of it.   29.g4  might come too early, because of  29...Bd6  30.Bg3  h6  when Black is intending to create the e5-square by playing g5. }
29... Bd6 30. Be3
{ Once again now that the pawn on f4 is guarded, White is ready for g2-g4. }
30... h5 31. Bf2
{ 31.c4 !?  Could have been played in order to fix the Black pawn on c5.  White is not yet ready for   31.g4 ?!  hxg4+  32.Kxg4  as after  32...Ng7  with the idea of f5, Black gets active piece play c.q. a satisfactory position. }
31... Nf8
{ Black's options are limited; he faces a difficult position. All he can do is wait and avoid creating a weakness. }
32. Nf1 { The knight is played too e3, where it can go to d5. } 32... Nd7 33.
Rd1 { A rule of thumb in the ending is 'Do not hurry'. } 33... Nb6
{ Black can't sit on the fence but feels tempted to activate his piece. In fact, the knight should have been reserved for the defense of the weak kingside. }
34. Ne3 c4
{ We concluded already that the Black player applied the wrong strategy. And now comes the decisive mistake. }
35. bxc4 bxc4
{ Black created the opposite he was striving for. He aimed for active counterplay but is stuck with a weak c-pawn.   Neither to be advised, was  35...Nxc4  since after  36.Nxc4  bxc4  37.Rd4  how should the pawn be defended? For instance,  37...Kb5  38.Rd5+  Kc6  39.Ra5  Kb7  40.Bd4  Rf8  41.f5 !  shattering the Black pawn structure.  After  41...gxf5  42.Rxf5  it's time to disengage from battle. The contest is over.   Notwithstanding the aforementioned line, Black could have saved the game by means of:  35...Bc5!!  Black will obtain counterplay across the a-file.  36.cxb5+  axb5  37.Rd2  Ra8  38.g4  Bxe3  39.Bxe3  Nc4  when Black is active enough to claim equality. ⇆ }
36. g4
{ The right time to act! Black's knight and bishop are too far away from their defenseless pawns. }
36... hxg4+ 37. Nxg4 { Black's pawns are defenseless. } 37... Nd7 38. Ne3
{ More ways lead to Rome. After   38.Bd4  Rf8  39.Ne3  White obtains a big advantage as the pawn on c4 is lost. }
38... Nc5 39. Rd4
{ Holding on to the pawn on e4, incarcerating the c4-pawn. The rest is a matter of technique. }
39... g5 { An act of desperation to get some counterplay. } 40. hxg5 fxg5 41.
f5 { The two connected pawns are just too strong. } 41... Rh8
{ The rook is activated along the h-file. But too little, too late: White's pawns cannot be stopped. }
42. Nxc4 Rh3+ 43. Kg4
{ Aesthetically White plays the perfect game. He doesn't lose sight of the harmony between his pieces. }
43... Rh2 44. Bg3 Bxg3 45. Kxg3 Rc2 46. Ne5+ Kb7 47. Rc4
{ White is not giving ground - not an inch! The ensuing rook sacrifice wins a pawn, but loses the game. }
47... Rxc3+ 48. Rxc3 Nxe4+ 49. Kh2
{ After  49...Nxc3  the knight is losing track of the f-pawn as  50.f6!  will unequivocally lead to promotion. 1-0 @@StartBracket@@49@@EndBracket@@ Kovacevic, A @@StartBracket@@2571@@EndBracket@@ - Tosic, M  @@StartBracket@@2412@@EndBracket@@ Vrnjacka Banja 2013. }
