1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5
{ This is the Ruy Lopez aka the Spanish Opening. Black has a wide range of responses he can choose from, amongst others besides the main move 3...a6. First, there is 3...Nf6 - the Berlin Defense, which is the second most popular line. Former world champion Vladimir Kramnik boosted its popularity by beating Garry Kasparov in the world championships in London @@StartBracket@@2000@@EndBracket@@ with this tenacious line. The Berlin Defense will be covered in Volume 2 of this series, whereas the other main Black's defenses, amongst others: - 3...Nge7 - the Cozio Defense; - 3...g6 - the Smyslov Defense; - 3...Nd4 - the Bird Defense; -3...d6 - the Steinitz Defense; - 3...f5 - the Schliemann Defense, and; - 3...Bc5 - the Classical Defense will be covered in Volume 3. This will give you a complete repertoire in the Spanish Opening. }
3... a6
{ This is the so-called 'Morphy Defense'. There is instant tension on the board, as our opponent challenges our bishop to make up its mind. The most common move is 4.Ba4, after which the opening will branch into countless variations like the Chigorin, Breyer, Ragozin and Marshall. Black will find his move 3...a6 useful in all of these variations, as he can chase the bishop from a4 with tempo, unpinning himself in the process while also taking space on the queenside. However, completely different positions occur after our move in this course: 4. Bxc6, aka the Ruy Lopez: Exchange Variation. At the same time, uncompromising and attacking players, such as the world champions Bobby Fischer and Garry Kasparov, as well as the current elite player Shakhriyar Mamedyarov from time to time let off steam in this very entertaining line. }
4. Bxc6
{ Black can take back with either the b-pawn or d-pawn, but only the last move has gained popularity as after 4...bxc6 he faces a hard time completing his development.   4.Ba4  The main concept of Morphy's Defense materializes when White falls for the 'Noah's Ark Trap'. This happened in 1929 when Steiner got ambushed in his game against Capablanca, but the current elite grandmaster Nepomniachtchi was similarly caught in it in a recent online game.  4...d6  5.d4  b5  6.Bb3  exd4  7.Nxd4  Nxd4  8.Qxd4  c5!  All of a sudden, White's bishop is caught after c5-c4.  9.Qd5  threatening Qxf7+  Be6  10.Qc6+  The check will not help Black.  10...Bd7  11.Qd5  c4  0-1, @@StartBracket@@55@@EndBracket@@ Nepomniachtchi, I @@StartBracket@@2784@@EndBracket@@ - Demchenko, A @@StartBracket@@2641@@EndBracket@@ chess.com INT 2020 }
4... dxc6
{ The contours of the RLE position are there. White gave up his light-squared bishop and the bishop pair, leaving Black with doubled c-pawns and behind in development. White has many options here. Lasker's main choice was 5. d4, but 5. d3 and 5. Nc3 have also been tried, remaining flexible and not committing the king to g1 yet. }
5. O-O
{ The most ambitious move! White stays flexible, keeping open the options of: 1. d3 or d4, 2. whether the knight should be moved to d2, c3 or a3. The American world-class grandmaster Robert Byrne named 5.O-O is after the Dutch IM John Barendregt, who played this move a couple of times in the 60's. White has already castled while Black's pieces are all on the back rank. Moreover, Black must make an important choice as to how to protect his central pawn since White has renewed the threat of Nxe5 after castling. }
5... f6 6. d4 exd4 7. Nxd4 c5 8. Nb3 Qxd1 9. Rxd1 Bd7 10. Bf4 O-O-O 11. Nc3 Be6
12. Rxd8+ Kxd8 13. Rd1+ Kc8 14. Nd5 Bxd5 15. Rxd5 b6 16. Rd1
{ White couldn't make real progress here. There weren't any holes available for his pieces to intrude, so that means White is going to regroup now. }
16... Ne7 17. Kf1
{ We can't say whether 17.Kf1 or 17.Nd2 is best in the given situation, as both pieces need to bo replaced.   17.Nd2 !?  Nc6  18.c3  Be7  19.Nc4  Re8  20.f3  Bd8  21.Ne3  Quite often the knight is well placed on the central square of e3.  21...Ne5  22.Bxe5 !?  Remarkably, White gives up his bishop for the knight.  22...Rxe5  23.Kf2  This is an improvement over the game. The king should be mobilised at first.  It's instructive to see we should take into account the opponent's piece play. The game went   23.c4  g6  24.g4  c6  25.Kf2  Bc7  26.Ke2  Re7  White's pawns ought to be standing on the Black squares to restrict the opponent's bishop, not on the White squares.  27.h3  Be5  As a result, Black's bishop became very mobile.  28.b3  The bishop is very flexible and Black is ok. ½-½ @@StartBracket@@62@@EndBracket@@ Hrivnak,V-Cervenka,I Bardejov 1981  23...g6  24.b3 !  After Black's b5, we will not allow c4.  24...Re7   24...Re8  25.g3  Be7  26.f4 !  26...Bd6  27.Kf3  White will continue gaining space on the kingside, and has a very promising position.  Or maybe even stronger   27.Nd5 !  27...Rxe4  28.Nxf6  Re7  29.c4 !  The bishop doesn't look too happy on d6. His own pawns are blocking him.  29...Rf7  30.Ne4  Kd7  31.Kf3  ±  Step-by-step, White is improving his position, and has every chance of winning.  25.g3  Our main trump - the kingside pawns - are now set in motion. Side by side, and preferably on the Black squares.  25...Rd7  In my sample line, Black opts for clarification by the exchange of rooks.  26.f4  26...Rxd1  27.Nxd1  b5  Currently, there comes to light why White played b3 on the 24th move. By c3-c4, the c5 pawn will be fixed on c5, restricting the scope of Black's bishop. In the meantime, the White pawn phalanx h2-g3-f4 makes the bishop's life even harder.  28.c4 !  In this sample line, White obtained a winning position. The Black pawn on c5 is fixed, and practically speaking, White is pawn up due to his pawn majority on the kingside. ½-½ @@StartBracket@@28@@EndBracket@@ Hrivnak,V-Cervenka,I Bardejov 1981 }
17... Nc6 18. Ke2 Be7 19. Be3
{ Firstly Smeets controls d4 before he moves his knight to the promised land. }
19... g5
{ This may well be a weakening of the kingside pawns, and in particular square  f5  . After  19...h5  20.f4  g6  21.c3  White still rejoices at his better prospects due to his pawn majority. }
20. Nd2 { The knight is on its way to f5. } 20... Nd4+
{ In my opinion this is a dubious plan. Black will remain with pawns on Black squares - the same colour as his bishop. }
21. Bxd4 cxd4 22. Nf1 { We know the drill. } 22... c5 23. Ng3 Bd6 24. Nf5
{ The knight reached its destination. The next step is to open a file for the rook. }
24... Be5
{ The bishop can't be pleased. The configuration of his pawns put on the same colour entails that he can barely move. }
25. g3
{ Black couldn't change the character of the position by playing d3+. After c:d3, B:b2, Rb1 will be lost. }
25... Kb7 26. b3 { White anticipates on the Black pawns rolling forward. }
26... h5 27. Rf1 g4 28. h3 { White can enter Black's position on the h-file. }
28... b5 29. Rh1
{ Now that the Black rook has to give up on the h-file, things are starting to look bad for him. }
29... Rg8 30. hxg4 hxg4 31. Nh6 { The pawn cannot be saved anymore. } 31... Re8
{ 31...Rd8  Black's counterplay can't be initiated, as it comes too late.  32.Nxg4  c4  33.bxc4  bxc4  34.f4  d3+  35.cxd3  cxd3+  36.Kd2  White would be winning here. }
32. Nxg4 f5 { Of course, this won't save Black. } 33. exf5
{ The f-pawn is too strong and there aren't ways to equalize for Black. Best he can do now is taking a sole pawn on g3. }
33... Bxg3+ 34. Kf3 Bd6 35. Rh6
{ White takes the lead, his pieces are more active than Black's ones. } 35...
Rd8 36. Ke4 { White's pieces are working well together. } 36... Kb6 37. Ne5
{ The twofold Dutch champion is settling on e5. } 37... Kc7 38. f4
{ The knight is settled for once and for all on e5. White's pieces are controlling the board. }
38... Bf8
{ This move is simply losing a pawn, but it was hard to give Black any good advice. }
39. Rxa6
{ This rapid-duel on the hightest Dutch level came to an end. White's initiative is too powerful, meanwhile he is a pawn up. 1-0 @@StartBracket@@39@@EndBracket@@ Smeets,J @@StartBracket@@2515@@EndBracket@@-L'Ami,E @@StartBracket@@2516@@EndBracket@@ Schagen 2005. We have learnt from this game how to possibly hit Black's weak kingside after the dubious g7-g5. Placing the knight on f5 and opening the h-file was part of White's play. }
