5... f6 6. d4 exd4 7. Nxd4 c5 8. Nb3 Qxd1 9. Rxd1 Bd7 10. Nc3 O-O-O 11. Bf4 Be6
12. Rxd8+ Kxd8 13. Rd1+ Kc8 14. Nd5 Bxd5 15. Rxd5 b6 16. Nc1
{ Besides 16. Nd2 and 16. Rd1, the text move is another way to regroup the pieces. }
16... Ne7 17. Rd2 c4
{ With 17..c4 Black attempted to gain sufficient counterplay in Filippov, A  (2644)  -Khamrakulov,D  (2445)  Osh 2013 1-0  (38)  , which is best under the given circumstances. See the main game below. We see in the game Talla-Palecek, that when Black is refraining from this counteraction, he can wander off quite soon. However, White can much easier create a passed pawn than Black and we are playing for two results.   17...Ng6  18.Bg3  c4  19.Ne2  Bc5  20.Kf1  Re8  21.f3  Nf8  22.Bf2  Bb4  23.Rd1  Rd8  24.Rxd8+  Kxd8  25.Be3  Bd6  26.g3  Be5  27.Nd4 !  Kd7  28.f4 !  Forcing the exchange of the bishop.  28...Bxd4  29.Bxd4  Ne6  30.Be3  The remaining ending is no picnic for Black.  30...Nd8  31.f5  Nc6  32.Ke2  Nb4  33.Kd2  c5  34.Bf4  Nc6  35.c3  b5  36.g4 !  White is showing his true colours: the main strength - the majority - is set in motion.  36...Nd8 ?  The fatal mistake.  37.e5  fxe5  38.Bxe5  g6  39.fxg6 ?!  The advance of the king @@StartBracket@@Ke3-Ke4-Kd5@@EndBracket@@ would have assured the win. The advance of the king  @@StartBracket@@Ke3-Ke4-Kd5@@EndBracket@@ would have assured the win.  39...hxg6  40.h4  Ke6  41.Bg7  Kf7  42.Bh8  Ne6 ?  Nc6 and Kg8, Kf7 attacking the bishop would have been a strong defense. Once the bishop doesn't cover e5 anymore, Ne5 would have guaranteed sufficient counterplay. Nc6 and Kg8, Kf7 attacking the bishop would have been a strong defense. Once the bishop doesn't cover e5 anymore, Ne5 would have guaranteed sufficient counterplay.  43.Ke3  g5  44.hxg5  Nxg5  45.Be5  Kg6  46.Bf4  Nh3  47.Kf3  Ng1+  48.Kf2  Nh3+  49.Kg3  Ng1  50.Be3  1-0 @@StartBracket@@50@@EndBracket@@ Talla,V @@StartBracket@@2476@@EndBracket@@-Palecek,P @@StartBracket@@2252@@EndBracket@@ Banska Stiavnica 2010. }
18. Ne2 Nc6 19. Nd4
{ White opts for a RB vs RB ending maintaining winning chances and putting his faith in the pawn majority on the kingside. White could as well keep the knights on the board, going on with Kf1 and f3 etc. }
19... Nxd4 20. Rxd4 b5
{ This is not a modelgame as the previous examples in this specific line. But it reveals that the Black double pawns can better be stopped in an early phase @@StartBracket@@e. g., by b3@@EndBracket@@. Here White's majority is counterweighed against Black's. }
21. Kf1 Be7 22. Rd5 g6 23. Ke2 Rd8 24. Rxd8+ Kxd8 25. g4
{ White is fixing the pawn @@StartBracket@@f6@@EndBracket@@ on the colour of his own bishop: a recurring theme. }
25... Kd7 26. Bg3 g5 27. f4 gxf4 28. Bxf4 a5 29. e5
{ After the exchange, White is closer to the creation of a strong far passed pawn on the kingside. }
29... a4 30. Ke3 Ke6 31. Ke4 { Still, Black is not out of danger. } 31... c6
32. Bg3
{ White's position is technically speaking not winning. But the Black player - under pressure - blundered here. }
32... Bd8
{ 32...fxe5  33.Bxe5  c5  Is fine for Black, as a consequence of the far pushed pawns on the queenside. White cannot prepare h4, since Black will play Bf6.  34.Bg3  Bf6  35.b3  cxb3  36.cxb3  axb3  37.axb3  now that the double pawn is off the board, there is no reason to think that White is better. }
33. Bh4
{ But here, things are different: Black cannot allow a pawn ending in which White gets the far passed pawn on the kingside. }
33... Ba5
{ Avoiding the lost pawn ending, White is winning a pawn because of the pin. }
34. Bxf6 Bd2 35. h4 { Black cannot carry the weight of the loss of the pawn. }
35... c5 36. g5 b4 37. h5 { The pawns can't be stopped. } 37... b3 38. cxb3
{ Black resigned, as after  38.cxb3  axb3  39.axb3  cxb3  40.g6  hxg6  41.hxg6  c4  42.g7  Kf7  43.e6+  Kg8  44.e7  Black can no longer stop promotion. Filippov, A  (2644)  -Khamrakulov,D  (2445)  Osh 2013 1-0  (38)  . }
