[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "13. Exercises"]
[Black "Kasparov, Garry vs. Andersen, Morten"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "7r/1kp5/p1pb3p/4p1p1/4P3/4BP2/PPR2P1P/6K1 w - - 0 20"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ This position, bearing all the characteristics of the RLE - the doubled c- and f-pawns and the frequently occurring rook with the same coloured bishops endings, are typical for these endings. Try to find out where Black is the weakest, and come up with a strong plan. }
20. Kg2
{ Right! The king, being an attacking force in the ending, can be manoeuvered to f5 or h5 in order to attack the weak Black pawns. }
20... Rg8 21. Kg3
{ Under no circumstances Black can allow the king's invasion. } 21... h5
{ Our opponent abruptly called our king's invasion to a halt. } 22. h4
{ One way or another we should find a passage way for our king in order to attack the kingside pawns. }
22... gxh4+
{ 22...g4  was a more tenacious defense, though White could have kept the pressure on after  23.f4 !  exf4+  24.Bxf4  Be7  25.e5  c5  26.Re2  pushing the pawn forward, and when the position is fit, we could try to capitalize on the e-pawn by means of Bg5. }
23. Kxh4
{ We can consider our king as a full-fledged member of our attacking forces. Imagine the situation arising after the exchange of rooks here, Black will find it impossible to defend both of his pawns on h5 and e5. }
23... Rf8 24. Kxh5 Rxf3 25. Rc1
{ The sequence of exchanges turned out to be beneficial for White. The e5-pawn is isolated and easy to attack by means of Kh5-g4/g6-f5, followed up by Be3-d2-c3. }
25... Rf8 26. Kg6
{ The white king found a new target: the fixed pawn on e5. The only thing is that the black rook cuts off the f-file. }
26... a5 27. b3 Rf3
{ Did Kasparov make the wrong route with his king? It looks a bit lost on g6 and it is difficult to make progress here. }
28. Kg5
{ Kasparov switches to another plan, moving his king to g3 to free his bishop in order to attack Black's pawns on e5 and a5. Moreover the blockade will be lifted and the pawns will be evt. set in motion. }
28... Rf8 29. Kg4 Re8 30. Rc4 { The new target is the lonely pawn on a5. }
30... Rf8 31. Kg3
{ The bishop is no longer bound to the defense of the f2-pawn, and can move freely in the assault on the pawns on a5 and e5. }
31... Rg8+ 32. Kf3 Rh8 33. Ke2 Ra8 34. Ra4 Ka6 35. Bd2 Kb5
{ All Black's hands are tied. } 36. Be3 c5 37. Kd3 c4+
{ Black's hands were tied, but was this panicking including a pawn sacrifice, necessary?   37...Re8  38.Bd2  Ra8  39.Bc3  Ra6  was no fun for Black either. Nonetheless it won't be easy for White to break the defensive line. }
38. Rxc4 Rf8 39. Ke2 c5 40. Bd2 Rf7 41. a4+
{ The pawn on a5 is fixed on a Black square. } 41... Kb6 42. Rc3 Kc6 43. Rf3
Ra7 { 43...Rxf3  44.Kxf3  is lost for Black. White will win a5 or e5. } 44. Kd3
Rd7 45. Kc4
{ The light suares are unmistakingly weak, and may well serve as intruding squares for the White king. }
45... Bc7 46. Rf6+ { Step by step, Black is being pushed back. } 46... Kb7 47.
Be3 { Now that the second pawn falls, Black's position is lost. } 47... Rd1 48.
Bxc5 Rc1+ 49. Kb5 Re1 50. Rf7 Kc8 51. Kc6 Bd8 52. Rf8 Rc1 53. Re8
{ The pawns are falling like flies. Black resigned. } *

