{ Imagine for a moment that you are superstar Shakhriyar Mamedyarov, with a never ending and strong desire for a win. With this in mind, try to find White's best move. }
18. b4
{ That's the idea behind White's initial timid play! With great force, White opens up the Black pawn structure. }
18... axb4 19. a5
{ Blowing up Black's pawn chain, meanwhile opening the lines around his king. }
19... bxa5 20. Bxc5
{ Black's position falls apart, whereas his pieces are not yet developed. }
20... Nh6 21. Rxa5 Rhe8 22. Bb6 Rd6
{ 22...Rd7  is also losing, because of  23.Nc4 !  Bxc4  24.Rc5+  Kb7  25.Rxd7+  Kxb6  26.Rxc4  when Shakh is simply the exchange up. }
23. Nc4 { with devastating effect, the knight joins the play. } 23... Bxc4
{ 23...Rc6  24.Rdxd5  Rxc4  25.Ra8+  White will be an exchange up, which shouldn't cause Mamedyarov any problems converting...unless he would have a total offday, being sick and tired. }
24. Rxd6 Re1+ 25. Kf2 Re2+ 26. Kg3
