[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "14. Model Games"]
[Black "Lasker, Emanuel vs. Capablanca, Jose Raul, 1914"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5
{ This is the Ruy Lopez aka the Spanish Opening. Black has a wide range of responses he can choose from, amongst others besides the main move 3...a6. First, there is 3...Nf6 - the Berlin Defense, which is the second most popular line. Former world champion Vladimir Kramnik boosted its popularity by beating Garry Kasparov in the world championships in London @@StartBracket@@2000@@EndBracket@@ with this tenacious line. The Berlin Defense will be covered in Volume 2 of this series, whereas the other main Black's defenses, amongst others: - 3...Nge7 - the Cozio Defense; - 3...g6 - the Smyslov Defense; - 3...Nd4 - the Bird Defense; -3...d6 - the Steinitz Defense; - 3...f5 - the Schliemann Defense, and; - 3...Bc5 - the Classical Defense will be covered in Volume 3. This will give you a complete repertoire in the Spanish Opening. }
3... a6
{ This is the so-called 'Morphy Defense'. There is instant tension on the board, as our opponent challenges our bishop to make up its mind. The most common move is 4.Ba4, after which the opening will branch into countless variations like the Chigorin, Breyer, Ragozin and Marshall. Black will find his move 3...a6 useful in all of these variations, as he can chase the bishop from a4 with tempo, unpinning himself in the process while also taking space on the queenside. However, completely different positions occur after our move in this course: 4. Bxc6, aka the Ruy Lopez: Exchange Variation. At the same time, uncompromising and attacking players, such as the world champions Bobby Fischer and Garry Kasparov, as well as the current elite player Shakhriyar Mamedyarov from time to time let off steam in this very entertaining line. }
4. Bxc6
{ Black can take back with either the b-pawn or d-pawn, but only the last move has gained popularity as after 4...bxc6 he faces a hard time completing his development.   4.Ba4  The main concept of Morphy's Defense materializes when White falls for the 'Noah's Ark Trap'. This happened in 1929 when Steiner got ambushed in his game against Capablanca, but the current elite grandmaster Nepomniachtchi was similarly caught in it in a recent online game.  4...d6  5.d4  b5  6.Bb3  exd4  7.Nxd4  Nxd4  8.Qxd4  c5!  All of a sudden, White's bishop is caught after c5-c4.  9.Qd5  threatening Qxf7+  Be6  10.Qc6+  The check will not help Black.  10...Bd7  11.Qd5  c4  0-1, @@StartBracket@@55@@EndBracket@@ Nepomniachtchi, I @@StartBracket@@2784@@EndBracket@@ - Demchenko, A @@StartBracket@@2641@@EndBracket@@ chess.com INT 2020 }
4... dxc6
{ The contours of the RLE position are there. White gave up his light-squared bishop and the bishop pair, leaving Black with doubled c-pawns and behind in development. White has many options here. Lasker's main choice was 5. d4, but 5. d3 and 5. Nc3 have also been tried, remaining flexible and not committing the king to g1 yet. }
5. d4
{ The line recommended in this course is 5.0-0 and is considered as the only move in the struggle for an advantage. 5.d4 is aiming - without further ado - for reaching a 4 vs 3 pawn majority on the kingside. }
5... exd4 6. Qxd4 Qxd4 7. Nxd4
{ Lasker holds two cards here: his better pawn structure and his lead in development. }
7... Bd6 8. Nc3 Ne7 9. O-O O-O 10. f4
{ The second world champion presumably believes that a slow approach starting with f3, doesn't encounter the two bishops of his opponent sufficiently. Placing a pawn on the colour of his own bishop involves a risk though. }
10... Re8 11. Nb3 { Stepping out of the danger zone after evt. Bc5 or c5. }
11... f6
{ A common Black theme: by f6, Black is counterbalancing the e4/f4 pawn force of White. }
12. f5
{ According to Kasparov: 'Under the classical rules of the Steinitz positional school this move has to be damned. White gets a weak pawn on e4, Black a stronghold on e5, with a devaluation of White's pawn advantage on the kingside - too many negative points for just one move. But Lasker's eagle eye had seen much further.' The eye pointed at the weak square on e6, meanwhile cramping Black's position by the far pushed f-pawn. It may well be that the older and cunning Lasker, in the aftermath of his career, was calling on the overconfidence of his youthful opponent, who didn't sense the approaching danger in time. }
12... b6 13. Bf4 Bb7
{ Strangely enough, Capablanca was better off keeping his doubled c-pawns by  13...Bxf4 !  14.Rxf4  c5  15.Rd1  Bb7  Black managed to reactivate his bishop without further ado.  16.Kf2   16.Rd7  Rac8  and with Bc6 or Nc6-e5 to follow.  16...Rad8  17.Rxd8  Rxd8  18.Ke3  Nc6 !  An active plan of Black comprises of besieging the e4-pawn. The knight is on its way to d6.  19.h3  Ne5  White should act against the threat of Nc4+.  20.Nd2  Re8  21.Rf1  Nf7  22.g4  Of course, White tries to create something real out of his pawn majority, so he sends his troops forwards.  22...Nd6  23.Kf4  b5  when Black obtained sufficient counterplay. }
14. Bxd6 cxd6 15. Nd4
{ This move was missed by Capablanca when he played 13...Bb7. } 15... Rad8
{ Capablanca finds it difficult to admit his error on the 13th move. Instead, he'd be better off doing so with 15...Bc8.   15...Bc8  According to Kasparov, Black can maintain the balance here.  16.Rad1   16.g4 !  However, I believe that this move, which hasn't been mentioned by Kasparov, still offers the better odds to Lasker.  16...c5  17.Nde2  Bb7  18.Nf4  The knight on f4 is excellently placed, keeping an eye on e6 and d5.  16...c5  17.Ne6  Bxe6  18.fxe6  Is the pawn on e6 strong or weak?  18...Rad8  19.Nd5  Nc6 !  was Kasparov's explication of Black's tenacity in this position, as after  20.e7  Rb8 !  Black is holding.   20...Nxe7 ?  White would be winning material.  21.Nc7  Rf8  22.Ne6  when one of the two rooks will be taken. }
16. Ne6 Rd7 17. Rad1 Nc8
{ Capablanca asserted after the game: ' I was now at the point of playing c6-c5, to be followed by ...d6-d5, but suddenly I became ambitious.' Kasparov agrees with this after 17.. c5 18. g4, witness the fact that Black can break free with d6-d5, but misses a devious, little pawn move.   17...c5  18.g4  d5  19.Nxd5  Nxd5  Indeed, Black would be fine after exd5 Bxd5  20.c4 !!  This move was missed in Kasparov's analysis. Capablanca would be helpless against cxd5 }
18. Rf2 b5 19. Rfd2 Rde7 20. b4
{ Lasker is grabbing important space, as well on the queenside. } 20... Kf7 21.
a3 Ba8
{ The biggest ordeal for Lasker in the struggle for a full point, would be after the exchange sacrifice of Rxe6, as claimed by Capablanca and Kasparov. }
22. Kf2 Ra7 23. g4 h6 24. Rd3 a5
{ Black's plan of opening the a-file will backfire. } 25. h4 axb4 26. axb4 Rae7
{ Capablanca's hesitant attitude illuminates the failure of his defensive set-up. }
27. Kf3 Rg8 28. Kf4 g6 29. Rg3 g5+
{ 29...gxf5  30.exf5  would make Black's defensive task even more difficult, as White will now put his c3-knight on e4 and follow up with g4-g5. }
30. Kf3 Nb6 31. hxg5 hxg5 32. Rh3 { The invasion operation via h7 commenced! }
32... Rd7 33. Kg3 Ke8 34. Rdh1 Bb7
{ All of White's pieces are splendidly placed, except for one piece.. } 35. e5
{ The victorious breakthrough, as Capa's already cramped position is about to collapse when the c3-knight enters his position via e4. }
35... dxe5 36. Ne4 Nd5 37. N6c5
{ There were more ways to Rome, such as 37.Rh8, but this move wins an exchange. But now Black is helpless against the threat Nd6+. }
37... Bc8 { After  37...Rdg7  38.Nd6+  , Black is losing his bishop. } 38. Nxd7
Bxd7 39. Rh7 { The rest is a piece of cake for the old fox. } 39... Rf8 40. Ra1
Kd8 41. Ra8+ Bc8 42. Nc5
{ As mentioned by Kasparov, Capablanca was dejected by this terrible loss. Capablanca wouldn't dare any longer to play 3..a6 against Lasker in their match for the World Championships seven years later. Notwithstanding, Capablanca asserted after the game: 'It has been wrongly claimed that 12.f5 wins the game, I would like nothing better than to have such a position again.' The bottom line of this game should be that Black should have undertaken immediate action after his move, creating counterplay against the pawn on e4. By his wait-and-see approach Lasker's strategy restricting Black's minor  (light-squared)  pieces and occupying e6, paid off. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "14. Model Games"]
[Black "Fischer, Robert James vs. Portisch, Lajos, 1966"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5
{ This is the Ruy Lopez aka the Spanish Opening. Black has a wide range of responses he can choose from, amongst others besides the main move 3...a6. First, there is 3...Nf6 - the Berlin Defense, which is the second most popular line. Former world champion Vladimir Kramnik boosted its popularity by beating Garry Kasparov in the world championships in London @@StartBracket@@2000@@EndBracket@@ with this tenacious line. The Berlin Defense will be covered in Volume 2 of this series, whereas the other main Black's defenses, amongst others: - 3...Nge7 - the Cozio Defense; - 3...g6 - the Smyslov Defense; - 3...Nd4 - the Bird Defense; -3...d6 - the Steinitz Defense; - 3...f5 - the Schliemann Defense, and; - 3...Bc5 - the Classical Defense will be covered in Volume 3. This will give you a complete repertoire in the Spanish Opening. }
3... a6
{ This is the so-called 'Morphy Defense'. There is instant tension on the board, as our opponent challenges our bishop to make up its mind. The most common move is 4.Ba4, after which the opening will branch into countless variations like the Chigorin, Breyer, Ragozin and Marshall. Black will find his move 3...a6 useful in all of these variations, as he can chase the bishop from a4 with tempo, unpinning himself in the process while also taking space on the queenside. However, completely different positions occur after our move in this course: 4. Bxc6, aka the Ruy Lopez: Exchange Variation. At the same time, uncompromising and attacking players, such as the world champions Bobby Fischer and Garry Kasparov, as well as the current elite player Shakhriyar Mamedyarov from time to time let off steam in this very entertaining line. }
4. Bxc6
{ Black can take back with either the b-pawn or d-pawn, but only the last move has gained popularity as after 4...bxc6 he faces a hard time completing his development.   4.Ba4  The main concept of Morphy's Defense materializes when White falls for the 'Noah's Ark Trap'. This happened in 1929 when Steiner got ambushed in his game against Capablanca, but the current elite grandmaster Nepomniachtchi was similarly caught in it in a recent online game.  4...d6  5.d4  b5  6.Bb3  exd4  7.Nxd4  Nxd4  8.Qxd4  c5!  All of a sudden, White's bishop is caught after c5-c4.  9.Qd5  threatening Qxf7+  Be6  10.Qc6+  The check will not help Black.  10...Bd7  11.Qd5  c4  0-1, @@StartBracket@@55@@EndBracket@@ Nepomniachtchi, I @@StartBracket@@2784@@EndBracket@@ - Demchenko, A @@StartBracket@@2641@@EndBracket@@ chess.com INT 2020 }
4... dxc6
{ The contours of the RLE position are there. White gave up his light-squared bishop and the bishop pair, leaving Black with doubled c-pawns and behind in development. White has many options here. Lasker's main choice was 5. d4, but 5. d3 and 5. Nc3 have also been tried, remaining flexible and not committing the king to g1 yet. }
5. O-O
{ The most ambitious move! White stays flexible, keeping open the options of: 1. d3 or d4, 2. whether the knight should be moved to d2, c3 or a3. The American world-class grandmaster Robert Byrne named 5.O-O is after the Dutch IM John Barendregt, who played this move a couple of times in the 60's. White has already castled while Black's pieces are all on the back rank. Moreover, Black must make an important choice as to how to protect his central pawn since White has renewed the threat of Nxe5 after castling. }
5... f6 6. d4 exd4 7. Nxd4
{ Likewise the previous model game Lasker-Capablanca  (1914)  , Fischer holds two cards here: his better pawn structure and his lead in development. }
7... c5 8. Nb3 Qxd1 9. Rxd1 Bd6 10. Na5
{ The knight on a5 is a thorn in the eye for Black. } 10... b5
{ The most natural reply of Portisch, not allowing the knight to c4. Since the pawn on b7 is no longer under attack, he can move his c8-bishop. }
11. c4 { The c5-pawn is fixed. White can follow up with Be3, Nb1-d2-b3. } 11...
Ne7 12. Be3 f5
{ Another possibility was  12...Rb8  , but this prophylactic move comprises its drawbacks: Fischer will opt for another route for the knight, by  13.Nd2 !  when the knight is heading to b3, from where it attacks c5. }
13. Nc3 f4
{ The pawn on  b5  can't easily be protected with  13...Bd7  , because of  14.Nb7 ! }
14. e5
{ We all know Fischer's reputation: 'retreating' is a verb which isn't embedded in his system. He opens the position while Black is not yet mobilised. }
14... Bxe5 15. Bxc5 Bxc3 16. bxc3
{ The position suddenly features an open character. Black should do something against the threat of Re1. }
16... Ng6 { Necessary, but allowing an uninvited guest to c6. } 17. Nc6 Be6 18.
cxb5 axb5 19. Na7
{ An artistic move of Fischer, on a7 the knight hits the pawn on b5 the hardest. }
19... Rb8
{ Two alternatives were: 19..Bc4 and 19..Bd7, but they both lead to much worse positions. For instance,  19...Bc4  20.a4  bxa4  21.Rxa4  Be6  22.Ra6  Kf7  23.Rc6  the peculiar position of the knight on  a7  entails that the pawn on  c7  is defenseless.   Or  19...Bd7  Who traps who? The Black bishop the White knight, or vice versa?  20.Rd2 !  when no more explanation is required. }
20. Rdb1 { The pawn can't be protected any longer. } 20... Kf7
{ A temporary reprieve would be  20...Bd7  21.a4 !  c6  22.axb5  cxb5  23.c4  and here, beyond any doubt, the pawn will be lost. }
21. Nxb5 Rhd8 22. Rb4 Bxa2 23. Nxc7 Rbc8 24. h4
{ I find this a typical Fischer move, never giving his opponent a moment of rest. White menaces to take on a2, since he created an escape square for the king. }
24... Rd2 25. Bb6 f3 26. Be3
{ 26.Nb5  intending Bd4 and h5, was a strong alternative. } 26... Re2 27. Nb5
{ with the double threat of Nd6 and Nd4  @@StartBracket@@incarcerating the e2-rook@@EndBracket@@. }
27... Ra8 28. h5
{ 28.Nd4  would have been sufficient for the win, but Fischer wants to gain victory in style. }
28... Ne5 29. Rf4+ Ke7 30. Rd1
{ It appears that the king is caught in the middle of the board. } 30... Rc8
{ 30...fxg2  would have led to a picturesque mate:  31.Bc5+  Ke6  32.Nc7 } 31.
Re4 Kf6 32. Rd6+ { Fischer's play doesn't need any further explanation. } 32...
Kf5 33. Rf4+ Kg5 34. Rxf3+
{ 34.Rxf3+  Kxh5  35.Rf5+  Kg4  36.Rg5+  Kh4  37.Rd4+  is mate on the next move. }
*

