[White "14. Model Games"]
[Black "Fischer, Robert James vs. Unzicker, Wolfgang, 1970"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5
{ This is the Ruy Lopez aka the Spanish Opening. Black has a wide range of responses he can choose from, amongst others besides the main move 3...a6. First, there is 3...Nf6 - the Berlin Defense, which is the second most popular line. Former world champion Vladimir Kramnik boosted its popularity by beating Garry Kasparov in the world championships in London @@StartBracket@@2000@@EndBracket@@ with this tenacious line. The Berlin Defense will be covered in Volume 2 of this series, whereas the other main Black's defenses, amongst others: - 3...Nge7 - the Cozio Defense; - 3...g6 - the Smyslov Defense; - 3...Nd4 - the Bird Defense; -3...d6 - the Steinitz Defense; - 3...f5 - the Schliemann Defense, and; - 3...Bc5 - the Classical Defense will be covered in Volume 3. This will give you a complete repertoire in the Spanish Opening. }
3... a6
{ This is the so-called 'Morphy Defense'. There is instant tension on the board, as our opponent challenges our bishop to make up its mind. The most common move is 4.Ba4, after which the opening will branch into countless variations like the Chigorin, Breyer, Ragozin and Marshall. Black will find his move 3...a6 useful in all of these variations, as he can chase the bishop from a4 with tempo, unpinning himself in the process while also taking space on the queenside. However, completely different positions occur after our move in this course: 4. Bxc6, aka the Ruy Lopez: Exchange Variation. At the same time, uncompromising and attacking players, such as the world champions Bobby Fischer and Garry Kasparov, as well as the current elite player Shakhriyar Mamedyarov from time to time let off steam in this very entertaining line. }
4. Bxc6
{ Black can take back with either the b-pawn or d-pawn, but only the last move has gained popularity as after 4...bxc6 he faces a hard time completing his development.   4.Ba4  The main concept of Morphy's Defense materializes when White falls for the 'Noah's Ark Trap'. This happened in 1929 when Steiner got ambushed in his game against Capablanca, but the current elite grandmaster Nepomniachtchi was similarly caught in it in a recent online game.  4...d6  5.d4  b5  6.Bb3  exd4  7.Nxd4  Nxd4  8.Qxd4  c5!  All of a sudden, White's bishop is caught after c5-c4.  9.Qd5  threatening Qxf7+  Be6  10.Qc6+  The check will not help Black.  10...Bd7  11.Qd5  c4  0-1, @@StartBracket@@55@@EndBracket@@ Nepomniachtchi, I @@StartBracket@@2784@@EndBracket@@ - Demchenko, A @@StartBracket@@2641@@EndBracket@@ chess.com INT 2020 }
4... dxc6
{ The contours of the RLE position are there. White gave up his light-squared bishop and the bishop pair, leaving Black with doubled c-pawns and behind in development. White has many options here. Lasker's main choice was 5. d4, but 5. d3 and 5. Nc3 have also been tried, remaining flexible and not committing the king to g1 yet. }
5. O-O
{ The most ambitious move! White stays flexible, keeping open the options of: 1. d3 or d4, 2. whether the knight should be moved to d2, c3 or a3. The American world-class grandmaster Robert Byrne named 5.O-O is after the Dutch IM John Barendregt, who played this move a couple of times in the 60's. White has already castled while Black's pieces are all on the back rank. Moreover, Black must make an important choice as to how to protect his central pawn since White has renewed the threat of Nxe5 after castling. }
5... f6 6. d4 exd4 7. Nxd4 Ne7 8. Be3 Ng6 9. Nd2 Bd6 10. Nc4 O-O 11. Qd3 Ne5
12. Nxe5 Bxe5 13. f4
{ Suetin  @@StartBracket@@quoted from Kasparov on My Great Predecessors@@EndBracket@@ notes the fear everyone had facing Fischer aka 'The Fischer-fever'. Restricting the bishops. It is typical of Fischer that he is not concerned about opposite coloured bishops and the further simplification of the position. In our time there is perhaps no one else who so believes in the accumulation of small advantages.' @@StartBracket@@Suetin@@EndBracket@@ }
13... Bd6
{ The line given by Kasparov showing White's edge:   13...Bxd4  14.Bxd4  Be6  15.f5  Bf7  16.Qc3  Qd7   16...b6 !?  might have been an improvement over Kasparov's line - chasing, without further ado, White's bishop from the long diagonal.  17.Qe3  making place for the bishop on c3.  17...c5  18.Bc3  but White is still clearly better as he will resume his attack by e4-e5.  17.e5  fxe5  18.Bxe5  Bd5  19.Qg3  when the opposite-coloured bishops would merely help White's attack. }
14. f5
{ Kasparov on Fischer - My Great Predecessors IV: 'Restricting the c8-bishop - Lasker's ideas are still alive and triumphing!', referring to Lasker's victory against Capablanca in 1914, also in the RLE and also covered in our model games section. }
14... Qe7 15. Bf4 Bxf4 16. Rxf4 Bd7 17. Re1 Qc5
{ Both players are shuffling their pieces to more active places. Fischer prepares for the break in the center, whereas Unzicker is merely stopping him from executing his plan.   17...c5  was another common configuration of the pieces for Black in the RLE. But here he cannot level the position either.  18.Nf3  Bc6  19.Qc4+ !  Driving the king off to the corner.  19...Kh8  20.Nh4  With the dreadful mating idea of Ng6+ and Rh4 mate. }
18. c3 Rae8 19. g4
{ Of course, White shouldn't be afraid to use his majority. } 19... Qd6 20. Qg3
Re7 21. Nf3 c5 22. e5
{ 22.g5  would have been a sound alternative.  22...Kh8  23.Kf2  Clearing the g-file for the artillery. }
22... fxe5 23. Rfe4 Bc6
{ In the game Unzicker sits on the fence, giving carte blanche to Fischer.  Instead, this was the time to undertake countermeasures with   23...g6 !  24.Rxe5  Rg7 !  Due to the threat of gxf5, White should take on g6.  25.fxg6  Rxg6  But now the pawn on g4 is left alone.  26.h3  h5 !  optimally making use of the 2 pins. The position gets an open character, in which the White king is not secure either. }
24. Rxe5 Rfe8 25. Rxe7 Rxe7 26. Ne5
{ Fischer is digging in on e5. The knight is terrifically powerful here! }
26... h6
{ 26...Bd5  Better according to the engines, but who would be able to play such a cold-blooded reply under such a hazardous circumstances?  27.b3  b5  28.g5  White's dominant position and accompanying threats should become overwhelming for any Black player.   26...Qd5  only threatens one check on h1. White is in no need to draw his troops back.  27.g5 ! }
27. h4 Bd7 { Keeping an eye on f5, thereby indirectly avoiding g5. } 28. Qf4
Qf6 29. Re2 Bc8 30. Qc4+ { Steering the game to the ending. } 30... Kh7 31. Ng6
{ The knight is a thorn in the flesh for Black. } 31... Rxe2 32. Qxe2 Bd7
{ 32...Qd6  was a better attempt to stay in the game. Anyway, Fischer should take into account Qg3+ and cannot freely move his queen behind the enemy lines @@StartBracket@@i.e. e7 or e8@@EndBracket@@. }
33. Qe7
{ Flawlessly capitalizing on its majority: the resulting ending is won for Fischer. }
33... Qxe7 34. Nxe7
{ Fischer's knight is invincible, keeping the king in the corner. } 34... g5
35. hxg5 hxg5 36. Nd5
{ Despite the material balance, in a higher sense the outcome of the game has already been decided. White's protected passed pawn on f5 is just too strong. }
36... Bc6 37. Nxc7
{ The inevitable is taking place, the downfall of Black's position. } 37... Bf3
38. Ne8 { Indirectly, Fischer is protecting his pawn on g4. } 38... Kh6 39. Nf6
Kg7 40. Kf2 Bd1
{ 40...Kxf6  is lost because of the protected passed pawn on f5.  41.Kxf3 } 41.
Nd7
{ Fischer's refined technique does even not allow his opponent to take the pawn back on g4. }
41... c4
{ 41...Bxg4  42.f6+  Kg8  43.f7+ !  Kxf7  44.Ne5+  winning a piece and the game. }
42. Kg3 *

