{ The contours of the RLE position are there. White gave up his light-squared bishop and the bishop pair, leaving Black with doubled c-pawns and behind in development. White has many options here. Lasker's main choice was 5. d4, but 5. d3 and 5. Nc3 have also been tried, remaining flexible and not committing the king to g1 yet. }
5. O-O
{ The most ambitious move! White stays flexible, keeping open the options of: 1. d3 or d4, 2. whether the knight should be moved to d2, c3 or a3. The American world-class grandmaster Robert Byrne named 5.O-O is after the Dutch IM John Barendregt, who played this move a couple of times in the 60's. White has already castled while Black's pieces are all on the back rank. Moreover, Black must make an important choice as to how to protect his central pawn since White has renewed the threat of Nxe5 after castling. }
5... Qe7 6. d4 exd4 7. Qxd4 Bg4 8. Bf4 Bxf3 9. gxf3 Nf6 10. Nc3 Nh5 11. Bg3 Rd8
12. Qe3 Nxg3 13. hxg3 Qc5 14. Rad1 Qxe3 15. Rxd8+ Kxd8 16. Rd1+ Kc8 17. fxe3 g6
18. e5 Bg7 19. f4
{ Let's take stock of the position. White set up a mass of pawns within small territory. The e4-square can be used for the knight from where it can be deployed for further undertakings via c5, g5 or f6. Last but not least, the Black king is cut off from the kingside. }
19... f6 20. exf6 Bxf6 21. e4
{ There comes the next footsoldier on its way to e5. The pawn wedge g3-f4-e5 makes it the case that the bishop is about to be degraded. }
21... h5 22. Kg2
{ Of course, White is trying to keep the coordination between his pieces intact. }
22... Bxc3
{ 22...Be7  23.Kf3  a5  24.e5  Rf8  25.Ke4  is not a position for which Black can be admired for. }
23. bxc3 b5 24. e5 { White's pawns are further on the way than Black's. } 24...
a5 25. Kh3
{ The king determines the ourcome of the game. The route h4-g5 lies open and there is nothing the world champion could do. }
25... b4 26. Kh4 { There is no need to react. } 26... Re8 27. Kg5 Re6 28. Kh6
{ A marvellous final chord of the game. The king's route is via g5-h6-g7 and f7. }
