[Black "Vallejo Pons, Francisco vs. Sasikiran, Krishnan, 2009"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5
{ This is the Ruy Lopez aka the Spanish Opening. Black has a wide range of responses he can choose from, amongst others besides the main move 3...a6. First, there is 3...Nf6 - the Berlin Defense, which is the second most popular line. Former world champion Vladimir Kramnik boosted its popularity by beating Garry Kasparov in the world championships in London @@StartBracket@@2000@@EndBracket@@ with this tenacious line. The Berlin Defense will be covered in Volume 2 of this series, whereas the other main Black's defenses, amongst others: - 3...Nge7 - the Cozio Defense; - 3...g6 - the Smyslov Defense; - 3...Nd4 - the Bird Defense; -3...d6 - the Steinitz Defense; - 3...f5 - the Schliemann Defense, and; - 3...Bc5 - the Classical Defense will be covered in Volume 3. This will give you a complete repertoire in the Spanish Opening. }
3... a6
{ This is the so-called 'Morphy Defense'. There is instant tension on the board, as our opponent challenges our bishop to make up its mind. The most common move is 4.Ba4, after which the opening will branch into countless variations like the Chigorin, Breyer, Ragozin and Marshall. Black will find his move 3...a6 useful in all of these variations, as he can chase the bishop from a4 with tempo, unpinning himself in the process while also taking space on the queenside. However, completely different positions occur after our move in this course: 4. Bxc6, aka the Ruy Lopez: Exchange Variation. At the same time, uncompromising and attacking players, such as the world champions Bobby Fischer and Garry Kasparov, as well as the current elite player Shakhriyar Mamedyarov from time to time let off steam in this very entertaining line. }
4. Bxc6
{ Black can take back with either the b-pawn or d-pawn, but only the last move has gained popularity as after 4...bxc6 he faces a hard time completing his development.   4.Ba4  The main concept of Morphy's Defense materializes when White falls for the 'Noah's Ark Trap'. This happened in 1929 when Steiner got ambushed in his game against Capablanca, but the current elite grandmaster Nepomniachtchi was similarly caught in it in a recent online game.  4...d6  5.d4  b5  6.Bb3  exd4  7.Nxd4  Nxd4  8.Qxd4  c5!  All of a sudden, White's bishop is caught after c5-c4.  9.Qd5  threatening Qxf7+  Be6  10.Qc6+  The check will not help Black.  10...Bd7  11.Qd5  c4  0-1, @@StartBracket@@55@@EndBracket@@ Nepomniachtchi, I @@StartBracket@@2784@@EndBracket@@ - Demchenko, A @@StartBracket@@2641@@EndBracket@@ chess.com INT 2020 }
4... dxc6
{ The contours of the RLE position are there. White gave up his light-squared bishop and the bishop pair, leaving Black with doubled c-pawns and behind in development. White has many options here. Lasker's main choice was 5. d4, but 5. d3 and 5. Nc3 have also been tried, remaining flexible and not committing the king to g1 yet. }
5. O-O
{ The most ambitious move! White stays flexible, keeping open the options of: 1. d3 or d4, 2. whether the knight should be moved to d2, c3 or a3. The American world-class grandmaster Robert Byrne named 5.O-O is after the Dutch IM John Barendregt, who played this move a couple of times in the 60's. White has already castled while Black's pieces are all on the back rank. Moreover, Black must make an important choice as to how to protect his central pawn since White has renewed the threat of Nxe5 after castling. }
5... Bd6 6. d4 exd4 7. Qxd4
{ The queen is attacking the g7-pawn, as a result of which Black cannot move his knight out. }
7... f6 8. Be3 Ne7 9. Nbd2 Be6
{ Temporarily preventing the White knight from moving to c4. } 10. Qc3 Ng6 11.
Nd4 Qe7 12. Nxe6
{ In this Mackenzie-variation after 5..Bd6, I recommend you to play here 12.a3. For the ones who want to try their luck in the ending, this is a sound alternative. }
12... Qxe6 13. Qb3
{ White is clear in his intentions: he goes for the queen swap to enter the ending with a 4 vs 3 pawn majority on the kingside. }
13... Qxb3 14. axb3 O-O-O 15. Rfd1 Rhe8 16. f3 f5
{ White's center is under siege when Black reached his momentum.  Playing securely and harmoniously, Vallejo Pons finds a way to get out of the pressure.   16...h5  this can be considered the most popular choice. In the ensuing part, we are following MVL in his game against Wen  (Biel 2012)  , maximizing full pressure on his opponent.  17.g3  Ne5  18.Kg2  g5  19.Bd4  g4  20.f4  Nd7  21.Bc3  Bc5  22.Re1  Nb6  23.Ra5 !  Meanwhile we are familiar with this positional plan like the palm of our hand.The rook is activated along the 5th rank. Unfortunately, with brilliant play Black can hold his position.  23...Bd4 !?  Even stronger was   23...Nd5 !  Making use of the d5- square in a handy way: the knight is all of a sudden developed whereas it seemed prospectless on b6.  24.Nf1  Bb6  25.Raa1  Nxc3  26.bxc3  Rd7  27.Re2  f5 !  28.e5   28.Rae1  Rxe4  29.Rxe4  fxe4  30.Rxe4  Rd1  is dangerous for White.  Kd8 !  the king is on its way to e6, from where his royal highness blocks the e-pawn. Black is no longer in any danger here.  24.Bxd4  Rxd4  25.Re2  Rd5 !  Super defending by Black. Unfortunately, it doesn't change the balance as White remains on top due to his favorable pawn structure.  26.Ra1  Rd6  White is slightly better here, and could raise the tension by means of 27. h3 1/2-1/2 @@StartBracket@@42@@EndBracket@@ }
17. g3 { The pawn restricts the Black knight and bishop. } 17... Rd7 18. Kf1
{ Bringing the king one step closer to the center. } 18... Ne7 19. Bf2
{ White's piece play is very compact. } 19... Rf8 20. f4
{ Closing the f-file, making Black's previous rook move pointless. } 20... fxe4
21. Nxe4
{ After a tough struggle, the Spanish GM managed to get the better of his opponent. The knight is magnificently placed on e4 and White's majority commence to pose ominous dark clouds above the Black position. }
21... Nf5 { The knight looks well placed on f5, but.. } 22. Rd3
{ White slowly prepares for the advance of the pawns. First, he has to improve the placement of his pieces. }
22... h5 { This blockade will not hold forever. } 23. Re1
{ Completely in line with one ought to play such a positions. White is making move-by-move positionally progress by compact piece play. }
23... b6
{ Finally, Black is capable of creating a force of his own. On the next move he wants to move his c-pawn to c5. }
24. Nxd6+
{ In endgames, there are often more open lines. In such cases, the bishop  (and rook)  is usually stronger than the knight  (and rook)  . }
24... Nxd6 25. b4
{ Meticulously manoeuvring on both flanks: c5 has been made impossible. } 25...
Rf5 26. Re6
{ 'Don't bother knocking', is what Sasikiran may have thought here. } 26... g5
27. Be3 Rdf7 28. Kg2
{ Undeniably, White made progress, although your engine may have its own ' thoughts'. }
28... Nc4
{ 28...gxf4  29.Bxf4  doesn't seem like an appealing option for a down-to-earth, thirteen-in-a-dozen chess player of flesh and blood, since the knight starts wandering on the board leaving his post on d6. }
29. fxg5 Nxe3+ 30. Rdxe3 Rxg5 31. R6e5
{ Because of the material balance one is inclined to consider this position as equal. In fact, Black is close to being lost due to White's possibilty of rapidly creating a passer. }
31... Rff5 32. Rxf5 Rxf5 33. h4
{ Suddenly the position becomes critical, now that White intends g4, hxg4 and Kg3, creating a passed h-pawn. }
33... c5 34. bxc5 Rxc5 35. c3 Rb5 36. Re2 Kd7 37. g4 hxg4 38. Kg3 Rd5 39. Kxg4
Rd1 40. h5 Rh1
{ The last move before the time-control, and a seemingly logical one - bringing the h-pawn to a halt.   40...Rg1+ !  This was the way to go! The king is lured to the h-file.  41.Kf5  Rh1  42.Kg6  Rg1+  43.Kf6  Rf1+   43...Rh1 ??  44.Re5 !  Again, White is building a bridge on the 5th rank.  44.Kg6  Rg1+  45.Kh7  a5 !  46.h6  a4  When Black is in time with his counterplay on the queenside. }
41. Re4
{ Building a bridge on the 4th rank, was most likely what Sasikiran had missed. }
41... Rg1+ 42. Kh4 Rb1 43. h6 Rxb2 44. Kg3
{ Surprisingly moving the king away from the pawn and backwards. The underlying idea is that h2 is no longer available for the Black rook. }
44... Rb5 45. h7 Rg5+ 46. Rg4 Rh5 47. Rh4 Rxh7 48. Rxh7+ Kd6 49. Kf4 c6 50. Rh5
b5 51. Ke4 Kc7 52. c4 *

