{ This is the so-called 'Morphy Defense'. There is instant tension on the board, as our opponent challenges our bishop to make up its mind. The most common move is 4.Ba4, after which the opening will branch into countless variations like the Chigorin, Breyer, Ragozin and Marshall. Black will find his move 3...a6 useful in all of these variations, as he can chase the bishop from a4 with tempo, unpinning himself in the process while also taking space on the queenside. However, completely different positions occur after our move in this course: 4. Bxc6, aka the Ruy Lopez: Exchange Variation. At the same time, uncompromising and attacking players, such as the world champions Bobby Fischer and Garry Kasparov, as well as the current elite player Shakhriyar Mamedyarov from time to time let off steam in this very entertaining line. }
4. Bxc6
{ Black can take back with either the b-pawn or d-pawn, but only the last move has gained popularity as after 4...bxc6 he faces a hard time completing his development.   4.Ba4  The main concept of Morphy's Defense materializes when White falls for the 'Noah's Ark Trap'. This happened in 1929 when Steiner got ambushed in his game against Capablanca, but the current elite grandmaster Nepomniachtchi was similarly caught in it in a recent online game.  4...d6  5.d4  b5  6.Bb3  exd4  7.Nxd4  Nxd4  8.Qxd4  c5!  All of a sudden, White's bishop is caught after c5-c4.  9.Qd5  threatening Qxf7+  Be6  10.Qc6+  The check will not help Black.  10...Bd7  11.Qd5  c4  0-1, @@StartBracket@@55@@EndBracket@@ Nepomniachtchi, I @@StartBracket@@2784@@EndBracket@@ - Demchenko, A @@StartBracket@@2641@@EndBracket@@ chess.com INT 2020 }
4... dxc6
{ The contours of the RLE position are there. White gave up his light-squared bishop and the bishop pair, leaving Black with doubled c-pawns and behind in development. White has many options here. Lasker's main choice was 5. d4, but 5. d3 and 5. Nc3 have also been tried, remaining flexible and not committing the king to g1 yet. }
5. O-O
{ The most ambitious move! White stays flexible, keeping open the options of: 1. d3 or d4, 2. whether the knight should be moved to d2, c3 or a3. The American world-class grandmaster Robert Byrne named 5.O-O is after the Dutch IM John Barendregt, who played this move a couple of times in the 60's. White has already castled while Black's pieces are all on the back rank. Moreover, Black must make an important choice as to how to protect his central pawn since White has renewed the threat of Nxe5 after castling. }
5... f6 6. d4 exd4 7. Nxd4
{ Likewise the previous model games Lasker-Capablanca  (1914)   and Fischer-Unzicker  (1970)  , Rozentalis holds two cards here: his better pawn structure and his lead in development. }
7... c5 8. Nb3 Qxd1 9. Rxd1 Bg4
{ Up to some point, this was a very fashionable line. As comes forward in the theoretical section, 10..Bd7 is Black's main move. }
10. f3 Be6 11. Bf4 c4 12. Nd4 O-O-O 13. Nc3
{ Not fearing ghosts, since after  13...Bc5  White calmly replies with  14.Be3  . }
13... Bf7 14. Kf2 Ne7 15. Be3
{ Anticipating Ng6 and Bc5. Besides, the f4 square is vacated for a knight or a pawn. }
15... h5 16. Rd2 Ng6 17. Rad1 Ne5 18. a3 g6 19. Nde2
{ Also  19.h3 !?  was worth a try. White protects the g4 square and wants to resume with f4. }
19... Rxd2 20. Rxd2 Bg7 21. Nf4 Re8 22. Nfd5 Nd7 23. Bf4 c6
{ A slight and important weakening of the Black's pawn structure, as now the Black squares  (e.g. d6)  become more vulnerable. More and more, it gradually contributes to White's positional advantage. }
24. Ne3
{ 24.Nc7  Rd8  25.Na8  Black can handle this threat with the plain and simple  25...b5 !  But not   25...Bf8 ??  26.Na4 !  White is winning here.  26...b5  27.N4b6+  Kb7  28.Rxd7+  Rxd7  29.Nxd7 }
24... b5 25. Bd6 Nf8 26. Bb4 Ne6 27. Ne2
{ The knight is heading for d4 or f4. From this moment on, Black loses the thread of the game. }
27... Bh6 28. g3 { Taking control over f4, preparing for f4. } 28... Ng5 29.
Nf4 { 29.Rd6  doesn't win material, because of  29...Re6 } 29... Ne6 30. Nxe6
Bxe6 31. f4
{ Despite Black's bishop pair, White is calling the shots. White is moving his majority forward, in the meantime excluding the bishop on h6 from its range. }
31... Rd8 32. Rxd8+ Kxd8 33. c3
{ The Black pawn majority has been blocked, and the bishop on h6 is out of play. }
33... Kd7 34. Nc2 h4 35. Bc5
{ The first concrete problems are there. The a6-pawn is going to be attacked. }
35... a5 36. a4
{ The RLE-specialist is showing his refined endgame technique. Unexpectedly, he engages his opponent on the queenside! }
36... hxg3+ 37. hxg3 Kc7 38. Nd4 Bd7 39. Kf3 f5
{ Comprehensibly, the Bulgarian GM does not want White to execute his plan below with g4 and f5. However, allowing a passed e-pawn, is not very attractive either.   39...Kb7  Black cannot sit and wait, as the following line illustrates:  40.g4  Kc7  41.Be7  Bg7  42.f5 !  g5  43.e5 !  fxe5  44.Ne6+  Bxe6  45.fxe6  The bishop on h8 is doomed, as his squares to move to are limited. The king is going to pick him up on the way Kf3-e4-f5-g6-h7. }
40. e5 Bg7 { The last piece which can be improved is the king. } 41. Kg2
{ The king is invading along the flank. } 41... Bh6 42. Kh3 Kb7 43. Kh4 Ka6
{ 43...Kc7  doesn't make a real difference.  44.e6  Be8  45.Nf3  Kb7  46.Ne5  Kc7  47.Nf7 !  clearing the path for the king via g5.  47...Bg7  48.Kg5  The invading is just too much to handle for White. }
44. Bd6
{ 44.e6  with the similar idea as just mentioned, is maybe even easier for victory. }
44... Kb7 45. Bc5 Ka6 46. e6 Be8
{ The most obvious winning plan hasn't changed. } 47. e7 Kb7 48. Nf3 Kc7 49.
Ne5 g5+
{ Understandably, Black wishes to punch back. Only here it helps White.   49...Kb7  would have been more resilient. }
50. fxg5 Bg7 51. Nf3 Kd7 52. Bd4 Bxd4 53. Nxd4 Kxe7 54. Nxf5+
{ The rest is a matter of technique. Especially for the specialist GM Rozentalis, this is not a big deal. }
54... Kf8 55. Nd6 Bd7 56. g6 Ke7 57. g7 Be6 58. Nf5+ Kf6 59. g4 bxa4 60. Kh5 *

