{ This is the so-called 'Morphy Defense'. There is instant tension on the board, as our opponent challenges our bishop to make up its mind. The most common move is 4.Ba4, after which the opening will branch into countless variations like the Chigorin, Breyer, Ragozin and Marshall. Black will find his move 3...a6 useful in all of these variations, as he can chase the bishop from a4 with tempo, unpinning himself in the process while also taking space on the queenside. However, completely different positions occur after our move in this course: 4. Bxc6, aka the Ruy Lopez: Exchange Variation. At the same time, uncompromising and attacking players, such as the world champions Bobby Fischer and Garry Kasparov, as well as the current elite player Shakhriyar Mamedyarov from time to time let off steam in this very entertaining line. }
4. Bxc6
{ Black can take back with either the b-pawn or d-pawn, but only the last move has gained popularity as after 4...bxc6 he faces a hard time completing his development.   4.Ba4  The main concept of Morphy's Defense materializes when White falls for the 'Noah's Ark Trap'. This happened in 1929 when Steiner got ambushed in his game against Capablanca, but the current elite grandmaster Nepomniachtchi was similarly caught in it in a recent online game.  4...d6  5.d4  b5  6.Bb3  exd4  7.Nxd4  Nxd4  8.Qxd4  c5!  All of a sudden, White's bishop is caught after c5-c4.  9.Qd5  threatening Qxf7+  Be6  10.Qc6+  The check will not help Black.  10...Bd7  11.Qd5  c4  0-1, @@StartBracket@@55@@EndBracket@@ Nepomniachtchi, I @@StartBracket@@2784@@EndBracket@@ - Demchenko, A @@StartBracket@@2641@@EndBracket@@ chess.com INT 2020 }
4... dxc6
{ The contours of the RLE position are there. White gave up his light-squared bishop and the bishop pair, leaving Black with doubled c-pawns and behind in development. White has many options here. Lasker's main choice was 5. d4, but 5. d3 and 5. Nc3 have also been tried, remaining flexible and not committing the king to g1 yet. }
5. O-O
{ The most ambitious move! White stays flexible, keeping open the options of: 1. d3 or d4, 2. whether the knight should be moved to d2, c3 or a3. The American world-class grandmaster Robert Byrne named 5.O-O is after the Dutch IM John Barendregt, who played this move a couple of times in the 60's. White has already castled while Black's pieces are all on the back rank. Moreover, Black must make an important choice as to how to protect his central pawn since White has renewed the threat of Nxe5 after castling. }
5... Be6 6. Nxe5 Qd4 7. Nf3 Qxe4 8. Ng5 Qf5 9. Nxe6 fxe6 10. d3 Nf6
{ 10...O-O-O  Black is showing his cards. by way of the open d- and f-file his intention is to create active piece play.  11.Be3 !  It has not been played frequently, but it's useful to place the Black bishop offside. In other words, we ought to avoid situations in which the Black bishop comes to c5.  11...Re8  This is a mysterious move of the engine. I think that White enjoys a small but stable plus here.  12.Qe2  Nf6  13.Nd2  Is the set-up we are aiming for. For the further part, Rozentalis shows us the way. }
11. Nd2 O-O-O 12. Qe2 Bd6 13. Nc4
{ Always pleasant to have the option of taking the bishop off the board. On the other hand, the knight set his sights on e5. }
13... e5
{ There is no need for panic-stations, but we should not allow e5-e4. } 14. f3
{ Preventing e5-e4 meanwhile fixing the pawn on e5. } 14... Rhe8 15. Bd2
{ White has a free rein, using this fact to mobilize his forces hitting e5. }
15... Bc5+ 16. Kh1 Nh5
{ The knight is not welcome and Rozentalis should avoid letting him go to f4. }
17. g3 Nf6 { The knight returns as his role was outplayed on h5. } 18. Rae1 h5
19. Bc1 { Assumingly, with the intention of 20.b3 and 21.Bb2 engaging on e5. }
19... Bd6 20. Qe3
{ One of the common theme recurring in the RLE. The Qe3-a7 idea is a nuisance for the Black side. }
20... Bb4 21. Rd1 b5
{ Probably better for Black was  21...Kb8  22.a3  Bf8  23.Rde1  , but also here White is better due to his tension on the weak pawn  e5  . }
22. Nd2
{ From d2 the knight has excellent prospects, as it can be directed to e4 or b3-c5/a5. In the meantime, the queen is lurking to invade on a7. }
22... Nd5
{ Can we jump in or should we refrain from such a daring undertaking? } 23. Qa7
{ Yes, we can! } 23... Nb6
{ This is the point of Black's last moves. He endeavours to trap the queen. We should be vigilant and avoid any imprisonments by a shortage of fresh air. }
24. Ne4
{ The 'cunning old fox' Rozentalis has the ability to look beyond the horizon, foreseeing that his queen can't be trapped when he opens the d-file.   24.Qxa6+ ??  This would turn out disastrously for us, because of  24...Kd7 !  After Ra8 our queen is locked up. }
24... Kd7
{ Of course, White shouldn't jeopardize his queen: the time to act is now! }
25. d4 Ra8 26. Qb7 Nd5
{ White is not losing his queen, after  26...Reb8  27.dxe5+ !  when the king moves a step aside, White can escape by Qxc6.  27...Nd5  28.Rxd5+  cxd5  29.Qxd5+  The poor king remains a matter of concern for Black. And to make matters worse for him, there is nothing to compensate for that! }
27. dxe5 Rab8
{ 27...Reb8  doesn't allow the queen's escape Qb7-a7-d4 @@StartBracket@@like in the game@@EndBracket@@, but will not help him either, because of  28.Rxd5+ !  when the queen is stronger than ever. }
28. Qa7
{ The military journey undertaken by the queen sorted effect: time to sail home with the loot. }
28... Ra8 29. Qd4 Ba5 30. c4
{ Of course, as many as possible lines should be opened, now that the king is lacking shelter. }
30... bxc4 31. Qxc4 Bb6 32. Nc3
{ The killer shot, as Black should give on his last hope - the knight kept the position closed. Now the king won't be able to find shelter. }
32... Qe6 33. f4
{ AFter  33.Nxd5  cxd5  34.Rxd5+  White is winning without too many difficulties. However, against  33.f4  with the idea of 34.f5 is neither a defense. }
33... Red8 34. f5
{ Black resigned, as he cannot take on e5 due to Nxd5, cxd5, Rxd5+ winning the queen. }
*

