{ The contours of the RLE position are there. White gave up his light-squared bishop and the bishop pair, leaving Black with doubled c-pawns and behind in development. White has many options here. Lasker's main choice was 5. d4, but 5. d3 and 5. Nc3 have also been tried, remaining flexible and not committing the king to g1 yet. }
5. O-O
{ The most ambitious move! White stays flexible, keeping open the options of: 1. d3 or d4, 2. whether the knight should be moved to d2, c3 or a3. The American world-class grandmaster Robert Byrne named 5.O-O is after the Dutch IM John Barendregt, who played this move a couple of times in the 60's. White has already castled while Black's pieces are all on the back rank. Moreover, Black must make an important choice as to how to protect his central pawn since White has renewed the threat of Nxe5 after castling. }
5... Bg4
{ This is the most challenging move we can face. Our opponent pins our knight and is currently not willing to retreat without a punch! As an immediate consequence of this move, White's aggression in the center with d2-d4 with which he endeavours to grab the initiative is no longer possible. Since after h2-h3, Black can keep the pin intact with the aggressive h7-h5 or Bg4-h5. The first game played was from 1870 after which Black didn't fully exploit this plan and retreated his bishop to d7 after h3. }
6. h3
{ White doesn't give Black time to consolidate with Bd6 - protecting e5 - and consecutively Ne7 and Ng6.   6.d3  Bd6  here Black finds time to defend the pawn. The oldest game in the Pin-variation, proceeded as follows:  7.Be3  Ne7  8.Nbd2  O-O  9.c3  Ng6  10.h3  Bd7  11.d4  when Black is fine, though White has a slight pull. ½-½ @@StartBracket@@24@@EndBracket@@ Paulsen, L - Minckwitz, J Baden-Baden 1870. }
6... h5
{ The bishop won't budge an inch... bad news for us! At present, this move is maybe the most popular in tournament practice. And rightly so, we should not let Black complete his development with Ng8-e7-g6 and Qf6, otherwise, we are fighting windmills. }
7. d3 Qf6
{ Former world champion Alexander Alekhine was the first who made the Black line flourish with this strong follow-up. }
8. Nbd2 Ne7 9. Re1 Ng6 10. d4 Nf4 11. hxg4
{ We saw in the theoretical section that is our second choice after 11.dxe5. Also here, White can play for the advantage. }
11... hxg4 12. g3 gxf3 13. Qxf3 Ne6 14. dxe5 Qxe5 15. Nb3 Bd6 16. Kg2 O-O-O 17.
Qf5
{ Once more, the queen's exchange is the best strategy. Black's attacking aspirations are bashed out and White's endgame prospects are better. }
17... g6 18. Qxe5 Bxe5
{ Solak's position can be preferred as he can set his pawns in motion. Meanwhile, where are Black's pawns? }
19. f4 Bf6 20. e5
{ White's pawn phalanx is impressive and - as a result -Black is forced to retreat. }
20... Be7 21. Be3 c5 22. Rad1
{ White doesn't mind mass exchanges. The king reaches in merely two moves e4, after which the pawns can be pushed forward by g4 and f5. }
22... Rxd1 23. Rxd1 b6
{ The pawn push  23...c4 ?  comes too early, because of  24.Na5 !  The pawn on c4 needs protection.  24...b5  25.Nc6  The invader on c6 makes it the case that Black is gradually closed in, making his position everything but enviable. }
24. c3
{ Sweet prophylaxis preventing the knight's invasion of Nd4. Other moves are less convincing, for example  24.Kf3  Rh2  with counterplay. }
24... a5
{ Also after  24...c4  25.Nd4 !  Nc6 is in the air.  25...Nxd4  26.Bxd4  White has the better prospects because of his pawns. Black cannot give up the h-file, since after  26...Rd8  27.Rh1 !  White takes over the h-file. }
25. Nd2
{ White is not afraid of  25...Rd8  26.Kf3  with 27. Ke2 to follow, he can conveniently unpin himself. }
25... f5
{ Black's desire to block the position on the kingside is comprehensible. } 26.
exf6
{ The play of the expert of the RLE is by the book. White intends to capitalize on his extra pawn on the kingside, so he opens up the position with the 'en passant' move. }
26... Bxf6 27. Ne4 Bg7 28. a4
{ This strategy - repeating itself throughout the entire course - is to block the the pawn majority of the opponent. }
28... Re8
{ Black starts drifting. He has no control over the direction of the game as he lacks any targets. }
29. Kf3 { Solak is experienced enough to realize that he shouldn't hurry. }
29... Rf8 30. Kg4
{ Now with the king on g4, the g6 pawn has definitely become a target. } 30...
Re8
{ Being ignorant to Black's threats on the e-file, would jeopardize our advantage. }
31. Kf3 Rf8 32. Rd5
{ Solak is optimally using the space c.q. available squares which have been granted to him. There is great harmony between the White pieces. }
32... Nd8
{ Worse was  32...c6?  ,from the frying pan into the fire! This move would chase the rook from d5, but would allow access to d6.  33.Rd6  The threats can no longer be parried. }
33. Nd2 Nc6 34. Nc4 Ne7 35. Rd1
{ Finally, the rook has been chased away from d5. But now the invasion along the h-file is looming. }
35... Kb7 36. Rh1 Nf5
{ After the exchange of rooks by  36...Rh8  the extra pawn on the kingside really starts to count. For instance,  37.Rxh8  Bxh8  38.Ke4  Kc6  39.g4!  White has so much to play for, whereas Black can't use his pawn majority.  Bg7  40.f5  gxf5+  41.gxf5  due to the strong f5-pawn, Das would have been on the verge of defeat here. }
37. g4 Nd6
{ The line  37...Nxe3  38.Kxe3  Kc6  won't help Black either, because of  39.Rh7  Rg8  40.Ke4  Black can't stop White from advancing his pawns. }
38. Nxd6+ cxd6 39. Rh7 Rg8
{ 39...Rf7  is dangerous, as Black gets entangled in an eternal pin.  40.c4  Kc6  41.Bd2 !  optimally exploiting the drawbacks of the pin. }
40. f5
{ Once more, White should have fixed Black's pawns with  40.c4 !  Kc6  41.b3  The only way to get out of the misery is,  41...d5  but this also contains its flaws after  42.f5 !  gxf5  43.gxf5  d4  44.Bf4 !  building a mating net around Blacks king. }
40... Kc6
{ Not to be recommended was  40...gxf5  since it allows a pin, after  41.Bh6 ! }
41. fxg6 Be5 42. Ke4 Rxg6 43. g5
{ Despite Solak's small inaccuracy on the 40th move, he still has every chance of winning. }
43... Rg8 44. Re7 Rh8 45. g6 Rh3
{ Enduring a long period being under pressure, Black succumbs.   A better attempt was  45...Rh2  46.Kf5  Rg2  47.Bg5  Rf2+  48.Ke4  Rg2  still fighting for the draw. }
46. Bg5 Rg3 47. Rxe5
{ Trusting on the g-pawn, now that the bishop sets up a blockade on the g-file. }
47... dxe5 48. Kf5 Rf3+ 49. Kxe5 Rf8 50. c4
{ Showing no mercy on his poor opponent, who is suffocated since he can barely move. }
50... Kd7 51. g7 Rg8 52. Kf6 Ke8 53. Bh6
{ Black is in Zugzwang. After Kd7, Solak would have decided the game with Kf7. }
