[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "14. Model Games"]
[Black "Solak, Dragan vs. Adams, Michael, 2015"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5
{ This is the Ruy Lopez aka the Spanish Opening. Black has a wide range of responses he can choose from, amongst others besides the main move 3...a6. First, there is 3...Nf6 - the Berlin Defense, which is the second most popular line. Former world champion Vladimir Kramnik boosted its popularity by beating Garry Kasparov in the world championships in London @@StartBracket@@2000@@EndBracket@@ with this tenacious line. The Berlin Defense will be covered in Volume 2 of this series, whereas the other main Black's defenses, amongst others: - 3...Nge7 - the Cozio Defense; - 3...g6 - the Smyslov Defense; - 3...Nd4 - the Bird Defense; -3...d6 - the Steinitz Defense; - 3...f5 - the Schliemann Defense, and; - 3...Bc5 - the Classical Defense will be covered in Volume 3. This will give you a complete repertoire in the Spanish Opening. }
3... a6
{ This is the so-called 'Morphy Defense'. There is instant tension on the board, as our opponent challenges our bishop to make up its mind. The most common move is 4.Ba4, after which the opening will branch into countless variations like the Chigorin, Breyer, Ragozin and Marshall. Black will find his move 3...a6 useful in all of these variations, as he can chase the bishop from a4 with tempo, unpinning himself in the process while also taking space on the queenside. However, completely different positions occur after our move in this course: 4. Bxc6, aka the Ruy Lopez: Exchange Variation. At the same time, uncompromising and attacking players, such as the world champions Bobby Fischer and Garry Kasparov, as well as the current elite player Shakhriyar Mamedyarov from time to time let off steam in this very entertaining line. }
4. Bxc6
{ Black can take back with either the b-pawn or d-pawn, but only the last move has gained popularity as after 4...bxc6 he faces a hard time completing his development.   4.Ba4  The main concept of Morphy's Defense materializes when White falls for the 'Noah's Ark Trap'. This happened in 1929 when Steiner got ambushed in his game against Capablanca, but the current elite grandmaster Nepomniachtchi was similarly caught in it in a recent online game.  4...d6  5.d4  b5  6.Bb3  exd4  7.Nxd4  Nxd4  8.Qxd4  c5!  All of a sudden, White's bishop is caught after c5-c4.  9.Qd5  threatening Qxf7+  Be6  10.Qc6+  The check will not help Black.  10...Bd7  11.Qd5  c4  0-1, @@StartBracket@@55@@EndBracket@@ Nepomniachtchi, I @@StartBracket@@2784@@EndBracket@@ - Demchenko, A @@StartBracket@@2641@@EndBracket@@ chess.com INT 2020 }
4... dxc6
{ The contours of the RLE position are there. White gave up his light-squared bishop and the bishop pair, leaving Black with doubled c-pawns and behind in development. White has many options here. Lasker's main choice was 5. d4, but 5. d3 and 5. Nc3 have also been tried, remaining flexible and not committing the king to g1 yet. }
5. O-O
{ The most ambitious move! White stays flexible, keeping open the options of: 1. d3 or d4, 2. whether the knight should be moved to d2, c3 or a3. The American world-class grandmaster Robert Byrne named 5.O-O is after the Dutch IM John Barendregt, who played this move a couple of times in the 60's. White has already castled while Black's pieces are all on the back rank. Moreover, Black must make an important choice as to how to protect his central pawn since White has renewed the threat of Nxe5 after castling. }
5... Bg4
{ This is the most challenging move we can face. Our opponent pins our knight and is currently not willing to retreat without a punch! As an immediate consequence of this move, White's aggression in the center with d2-d4 with which he endeavours to grab the initiative is no longer possible. Since after h2-h3, Black can keep the pin intact with the aggressive h7-h5 or Bg4-h5. The first game played was from 1870 after which Black didn't fully exploit this plan and retreated his bishop to d7 after h3. }
6. h3
{ White doesn't give Black time to consolidate with Bd6 - protecting e5 - and consecutively Ne7 and Ng6.   6.d3  Bd6  here Black finds time to defend the pawn. The oldest game in the Pin-variation, proceeded as follows:  7.Be3  Ne7  8.Nbd2  O-O  9.c3  Ng6  10.h3  Bd7  11.d4  when Black is fine, though White has a slight pull. ½-½ @@StartBracket@@24@@EndBracket@@ Paulsen, L - Minckwitz, J Baden-Baden 1870. }
6... h5
{ The bishop won't budge an inch... bad news for us! At present, this move is maybe the most popular in tournament practice. And rightly so, we should not let Black complete his development with Ng8-e7-g6 and Qf6, otherwise, we are fighting windmills. }
7. d3 Qf6
{ Former world champion Alexander Alekhine was the first who made the Black line flourish with this strong follow-up. }
8. Nbd2 Ne7 9. Re1 Ng6 10. d4
{ White can't let Black play Nf4 unhindered, so he must take action now. For all the tactical intricacies after hxg4  and/or exd4 please have a look at the theoretical section - Chapter 11. }
10... Nf4 11. dxe5 Qg6
{ White still can't be advised to take on g4, whereas Black sets the queen on us - more specifically on g2. }
12. Nh4
{ Fortunately, we can liquidate into the ending to avert the dangers against our king. }
12... Bxd1 13. Nxg6 Nxg6 14. Rxd1 O-O-O 15. e6
{ Before unpinning himself, White throws the cat amongst the pigeons. The concept of giving this pawn up in order to inflict as much as possible damage to Black's structure, can be considered a ' desperado'. }
15... fxe6
{ Aren't we chess players herd animals? The vast majority opts for this continuation, whereas 15..f6 is not demonstrably worse. }
16. Re1 { This unpinning is necessary for the further development. } 16... Ne5
{ The knight feels like 'the king of the world' on e5, but that's of a temporary nature as White will bash his head in when he gets the chance.   16...Bc5?!  Now Black allows the white knight to f3.  17.Nf3 !  The knight controls important square e5. On the next move he will go to g5. }
17. Nb3
{ Black has the slightly more active pieces, but White will very soon settle the score  @@StartBracket@@concerning development@@EndBracket@@ when he can move his bishop out. What really counts is the preferable pawn structure. }
17... Be7 18. Bd2 { The bishop will be elegantly placed on c3. } 18... g5
{ Black launches a counter offense meanwhile hindering the f2-f4 advance. } 19.
Bc3
{ Black cannot play the more logical looking Bf6, due to Nc5! The knight is attacking the weak e6 pawn which needs a lot of care. }
19... Bd6 20. Rad1 { The last piece has been brought to an active position. }
20... g4
{ Black is knocking at the gates, but White stays calm and with the following move he simplifies the position. }
21. Nc1
{ The knight is on its way to  d3  . After  21.hxg4  hxg4  here Black obtains dangerous counterplay against White's king along the h-file. Please note that we can not give up our strong bishop. }
21... gxh3 22. Nd3
{ The knight on e5 couldn't stay forever on its throne. Momentarily White gives up a pawn, which will be regained with interest later. }
22... Nxd3 23. Rxd3 { The rook on h8 is hanging, so Black cannot take on g2. }
23... Rhf8
{ After  23...h2+  24.Kh1  Rhf8  Black is hitting f2, but the White rook can keep all the kids @@StartBracket@@c.q. pawns@@EndBracket@@ together.  25.Re2 !  Solidity above all other things! Black's pawn structure is shattered and White can look forward to a highly convenient ending. }
24. Rxh3 { Hitting h5. Black can no longer safeguard this pour lonesome soul. }
24... Bc5
{ ..but Adams strikes back on f2. The pawn can merely be defended with Rf3, as on both Re2 or Rf1 Black takes on f2. }
25. Rf3
{ In case of  25.Rf1  Bxf2+  26.Rxf2 ??  White could have avoided heavy material losses moving the king to h1.  26...Rd1+  suddenly it's Black who is winning. }
25... Rxf3 26. gxf3 Rg8+ 27. Kf1 h4 28. Bf6
{ 28.Bd2 !  This is a novelty over the game @@StartBracket@@Bf6@@EndBracket@@ and a possible improvement over the game.  28...h3  29.Ke2  e5  30.Be3  Bd6  31.Rh1  Rh8  32.Kf1  If the White king arrives on h2, a difficult ending awaits Black. }
28... h3 29. Ke2 Rg6 30. Bh4 Bd6
{ 30...Rh6 ?!  31.Bg3  31...Bd6  32.f4  Solak would find a way to get his king nearer to the h-pawn. }
31. Rh1 b5
{ Adams was probably not sensing the danger coming his way.   31...Be5 !  was called for, as after  32.b3  h2 !  White can't make real progress with his king due to the threat of Rg6-g1. For instance,  33.Kf1   33.Ke3 ??  can't be recommended, because of  33...Rg1  Kd7  with a draw as the most probable outcome. }
32. Ke3
{ Things have become gloomy for Black, since he cannot prevent f3-f4 any longer. }
32... Rh6 33. Bg5 Rh5 34. f4
{ At this very moment, White gains the momentum as the passage of the king towards the h-pawn has been cleared. }
34... e5 35. Kf3 { If there were any doubts, the pawn on h3 is lost. } 35...
exf4 36. Kg4
{ Solak rightly goes first for the dangerous h-pawn. The f-pawn is lost anyway. }
36... Rh8 37. Rxh3
{ Now Black is stuck with weak similar-square-coloured pawn as his bishop's. }
37... Rg8 38. Kf5
{ The king is a major asset in the ending. White prepares for the advance of the e-pawn. }
38... c5
{ White can't take the pawn as he loses a piece after  39.Bxf4  ,  Rf8+  . }
39. Bf6
{ Naturally, White wants to push his e-pawn. Alertness is required though.   39.e5 ??  Bxe5  when the pawn is lost. }
39... c4 40. Rh8
{ Simplifying matters, after which Black cannot hope on any counterplay at all. }
40... Rxh8 41. Bxh8
{ The f-pawn will be lost, leaving White with two massive connected passed pawns. }
41... Bc5 42. f3 Be3 43. Ke6
{ The activity of the kings makes the difference in this ending. 43.Be5 with the idea taking on f4 is winning as well. }
43... Bc1 44. Kf7
{ The king is perfectly positioned for the advance of the e-pawn. } 44... a5
45. Bg7 a4 46. e5 Bxb2 47. e6 Ba3
{ Unfortunately for Black  47...Bxg7  48.e7  leads to promotion. } 48. Bf8
{ Clearing the path for the e-pawn, not allowing Black to swap his bishop for the e-pawn. Adams feeling hopeless, resigned. 1-0 @@StartBracket@@48@@EndBracket@@ Solak,D @@StartBracket@@2628@@EndBracket@@-Adams,M  @@StartBracket@@2744@@EndBracket@@ Reykjavik 2015 }
