[Round "?"]
[White "14. Model Games"]
[Black "Naiditsch, Arkadij vs. Svidler, Peter, 2019"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5
{ This is the Ruy Lopez aka the Spanish Opening. Black has a wide range of responses he can choose from, amongst others besides the main move 3...a6. First, there is 3...Nf6 - the Berlin Defense, which is the second most popular line. Former world champion Vladimir Kramnik boosted its popularity by beating Garry Kasparov in the world championships in London @@StartBracket@@2000@@EndBracket@@ with this tenacious line. The Berlin Defense will be covered in Volume 2 of this series, whereas the other main Black's defenses, amongst others: - 3...Nge7 - the Cozio Defense; - 3...g6 - the Smyslov Defense; - 3...Nd4 - the Bird Defense; -3...d6 - the Steinitz Defense; - 3...f5 - the Schliemann Defense, and; - 3...Bc5 - the Classical Defense will be covered in Volume 3. This will give you a complete repertoire in the Spanish Opening. }
3... a6
{ This is the so-called 'Morphy Defense'. There is instant tension on the board, as our opponent challenges our bishop to make up its mind. The most common move is 4.Ba4, after which the opening will branch into countless variations like the Chigorin, Breyer, Ragozin and Marshall. Black will find his move 3...a6 useful in all of these variations, as he can chase the bishop from a4 with tempo, unpinning himself in the process while also taking space on the queenside. However, completely different positions occur after our move in this course: 4. Bxc6, aka the Ruy Lopez: Exchange Variation. At the same time, uncompromising and attacking players, such as the world champions Bobby Fischer and Garry Kasparov, as well as the current elite player Shakhriyar Mamedyarov from time to time let off steam in this very entertaining line. }
4. Bxc6
{ Black can take back with either the b-pawn or d-pawn, but only the last move has gained popularity as after 4...bxc6 he faces a hard time completing his development.   4.Ba4  The main concept of Morphy's Defense materializes when White falls for the 'Noah's Ark Trap'. This happened in 1929 when Steiner got ambushed in his game against Capablanca, but the current elite grandmaster Nepomniachtchi was similarly caught in it in a recent online game.  4...d6  5.d4  b5  6.Bb3  exd4  7.Nxd4  Nxd4  8.Qxd4  c5!  All of a sudden, White's bishop is caught after c5-c4.  9.Qd5  threatening Qxf7+  Be6  10.Qc6+  The check will not help Black.  10...Bd7  11.Qd5  c4  0-1, @@StartBracket@@55@@EndBracket@@ Nepomniachtchi, I @@StartBracket@@2784@@EndBracket@@ - Demchenko, A @@StartBracket@@2641@@EndBracket@@ chess.com INT 2020 }
4... dxc6
{ The contours of the RLE position are there. White gave up his light-squared bishop and the bishop pair, leaving Black with doubled c-pawns and behind in development. White has many options here. Lasker's main choice was 5. d4, but 5. d3 and 5. Nc3 have also been tried, remaining flexible and not committing the king to g1 yet. }
5. O-O
{ The most ambitious move! White stays flexible, keeping open the options of: 1. d3 or d4, 2. whether the knight should be moved to d2, c3 or a3. The American world-class grandmaster Robert Byrne named 5.O-O is after the Dutch IM John Barendregt, who played this move a couple of times in the 60's. White has already castled while Black's pieces are all on the back rank. Moreover, Black must make an important choice as to how to protect his central pawn since White has renewed the threat of Nxe5 after castling. }
5... Qf6 6. d4 exd4 7. Bg5 Qd6 8. Nxd4 Be7
{ Because of this model game from Black's end, we don't play the most obvious move 9. Bxe7, but instead 9. Be3 @@StartBracket@@see chapter 6@@EndBracket@@. It seems natural to take on e7, as Black is rid of his main force: the bishop pair. But as we all know, Svidler is of the not easy to catch sort. }
9. Bxe7 Nxe7 10. Nc3 Bd7 11. Nde2 O-O-O 12. Qc1
{ 12.Qxd6  cxd6  solving Black's doubled pawns, doesn't bring White anything but a draw. }
12... Ng6
{ At first, Svidler uses prophylactical means against White's pawn majority. }
13. Qe3 Kb8
{ Of course not allowing an uninvited guest after Qe3-Qa7.   13...b6 !?  was possible as well. }
14. Rad1 Qe7 15. f4
{ What else? White should try to exploit his pawn majority. } 15... Bc8
{ The beginning of a strong idea. Svidler blocks the white pawns in the center with f6 , after which he will engage on e4 by hitting it. It's instructive to see how Black can best handle White's pawn majority and improves on Capablanca's play in his famous game against Lasker in 1914  (see the modelgame section)  . }
16. Nc1
{ White's knights look a bit clumsy in their quest looking for a strong square. }
16... Rxd1 17. Rxd1 b6
{ A very important plan of Svidler. Please compare this game with the other model games Lasker-Capablanca, 1914 @@StartBracket@@1-0@@EndBracket@@, and Fischer-Unzicker 1970 @@StartBracket@@1-0@@EndBracket@@ which this position resembles a lot. Undoubtedly, Svidler knew these classical games and understood that he should take immediate countermeasures against White's center. }
18. Nd3 a5
{ Not yet allowing Nd5 as after 18... c5, and avoiding his structure to be fixed by White's b2-b4. Last but not least, Svidler is intending to bring his bishop back into the game, first via the square a6. Later, he can place it along the long diagonal h1-a8.   After  18...h6  intending g5 White strongly plays  19.b4  ∞ }
19. Re1 Ba6 20. Nf2
{ Not a move White is fond to play. The knight doesn't have bright prospects on f2.   After  20.e5  Qe6 !  Black is better because of the blockade on f5.   In the next instructive line Black exerts pressure on White's center so badly, that the latter one collapses.  20.f5  Bxd3 !  21.cxd3  Ne5!  hitting White hard on d3.  22.d4  Nc4! !  23.Qe2  Qb4 !  24.Nd1  Nd6  25.Qf2  Nb5  White couldn't stop the loss of a pawn. }
20... Re8 { Also promising was  20...Qb4 !?  hitting White's weakest spots. }
21. a3 { Rightly so Naiditsch feared a future Qb4. } 21... f6
{ Svidler has brought the central pawns to a halt. } 22. Ne2 Bb7
{ The bishop conducted a fruitful task on a6, now it's time to be moved to the long diagonal. }
23. Ng3 c5
{ Black has a pleasant edge. The pawn on e4 is a matter of constant concern for Naiditsch, whereas there is no way White can one way or the other create a passed pawn on the kingside. The fact is that the heavy pieces don't help White either. Furthermore, Black made already huge progress on the queenside, with his pawns advanced to b6, a5 and c5. }
24. Nf5 Qf7 { The queen's sortie to c4 or a2 is looming. } 25. Rd1 Nf8
{ The beginning of a splendid knight manoeuvre in order to put the screws on e4. }
26. c3 a4 27. h3 Ne6 { All part of the plan: the knight is on its way to d6. }
28. Ng3 Bc6 29. Rd2 Nd8 30. Qd3 Nb7 31. Kh2 Nd6 32. Rd1 h5
{ The final @@StartBracket@@positional@@EndBracket@@ blow. The pressure was piling up on e4, and there is no longer a way to safeguard both this point under siege and the queenside. }
33. Re1 h4 34. Nf1 Qb3
{ Svidler had to be patient, but since all his pieces are perfectly placed now this queen move comes with devastating effects. White collapses. }
35. e5
{ Is also losing a pawn, because of  35.Qb1  Nc4  36.Re2  Nxa3 !  when the b-pawn is pinned. }
35... fxe5 36. fxe5 Qxb2 37. Re2 Qb5 38. Qc2
{ After  38.Qxb5  both Nxb5 or Bxb5 are winning. } 38... Nc4
{ it's surprising how fast White's position is in ruins. Black's strategy of attacking the queenside and center prevailed. Another aspects standing out, are the helpless White knights. }
39. e6 Nxa3
{ Naiditsch resigned. After this game we should be aware of the dangers for White: Black endeavours to block and attack our central pawns, whilst keeping the queens on the board for counterplay. If he can, he puts his queenside forward to grab the initiative on the queenside. }
