[White "14. Model Games"]
[Black "McShane, Luke J vs. Adams, Michael, 2019"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5
{ This is the Ruy Lopez aka the Spanish Opening. Black has a wide range of responses he can choose from, amongst others besides the main move 3...a6. First, there is 3...Nf6 - the Berlin Defense, which is the second most popular line. Former world champion Vladimir Kramnik boosted its popularity by beating Garry Kasparov in the world championships in London @@StartBracket@@2000@@EndBracket@@ with this tenacious line. The Berlin Defense will be covered in Volume 2 of this series, whereas the other main Black's defenses, amongst others: - 3...Nge7 - the Cozio Defense; - 3...g6 - the Smyslov Defense; - 3...Nd4 - the Bird Defense; -3...d6 - the Steinitz Defense; - 3...f5 - the Schliemann Defense, and; - 3...Bc5 - the Classical Defense will be covered in Volume 3. This will give you a complete repertoire in the Spanish Opening. }
3... a6
{ This is the so-called 'Morphy Defense'. There is instant tension on the board, as our opponent challenges our bishop to make up its mind. The most common move is 4.Ba4, after which the opening will branch into countless variations like the Chigorin, Breyer, Ragozin and Marshall. Black will find his move 3...a6 useful in all of these variations, as he can chase the bishop from a4 with tempo, unpinning himself in the process while also taking space on the queenside. However, completely different positions occur after our move in this course: 4. Bxc6, aka the Ruy Lopez: Exchange Variation. At the same time, uncompromising and attacking players, such as the world champions Bobby Fischer and Garry Kasparov, as well as the current elite player Shakhriyar Mamedyarov from time to time let off steam in this very entertaining line. }
4. Bxc6
{ Black can take back with either the b-pawn or d-pawn, but only the last move has gained popularity as after 4...bxc6 he faces a hard time completing his development.   4.Ba4  The main concept of Morphy's Defense materializes when White falls for the 'Noah's Ark Trap'. This happened in 1929 when Steiner got ambushed in his game against Capablanca, but the current elite grandmaster Nepomniachtchi was similarly caught in it in a recent online game.  4...d6  5.d4  b5  6.Bb3  exd4  7.Nxd4  Nxd4  8.Qxd4  c5!  All of a sudden, White's bishop is caught after c5-c4.  9.Qd5  threatening Qxf7+  Be6  10.Qc6+  The check will not help Black.  10...Bd7  11.Qd5  c4  0-1, @@StartBracket@@55@@EndBracket@@ Nepomniachtchi, I @@StartBracket@@2784@@EndBracket@@ - Demchenko, A @@StartBracket@@2641@@EndBracket@@ chess.com INT 2020 }
4... dxc6
{ The contours of the RLE position are there. White gave up his light-squared bishop and the bishop pair, leaving Black with doubled c-pawns and behind in development. White has many options here. Lasker's main choice was 5. d4, but 5. d3 and 5. Nc3 have also been tried, remaining flexible and not committing the king to g1 yet. }
5. O-O
{ The most ambitious move! White stays flexible, keeping open the options of: 1. d3 or d4, 2. whether the knight should be moved to d2, c3 or a3. The American world-class grandmaster Robert Byrne named 5.O-O is after the Dutch IM John Barendregt, who played this move a couple of times in the 60's. White has already castled while Black's pieces are all on the back rank. Moreover, Black must make an important choice as to how to protect his central pawn since White has renewed the threat of Nxe5 after castling. }
5... Bd6 6. d4 exd4 7. Qxd4
{ The queen is attacking the g7-pawn, as a result of which Black cannot move his knight out. }
7... f6
{ Michael Adams tried out several systems against the RLE. Presumably, he will regard the Mackenzie-variation as one of the safest ones. Please have a look at the theoretical section for the ideas of White in order to make our opponent stagger. }
8. Be3 Ne7 9. Nbd2 Be6
{ Temporarily preventing the White knight from moving to c4. } 10. Qc3
{ As we saw before, we should pay heed to the threat of Bxh2+ in case we won't to move our knight to c4. Now White is ready for this move, and on top of that, clears the d-file for the rooks. }
10... Qd7 11. Nc4 Bxc4
{ With a heavy heart, Black is saying goodbye to his bishop pair. } 12. Qxc4
Ng6 13. Rad1 O-O-O
{ Black's position is a very tough nut to crack. In the following part of the game, McShane is patient in order to convert his kingside majority into something tangible. }
14. Nd4 Ne5 15. Qe2
{ White is ready to set his pawns in motion, kicking out the knight of his dominant position on e5. }
15... g6 16. f4 Nf7 17. f5
{ McShane's intentions are clear. He intends to occupy e6 with his cavalry. }
17... Rde8
{ I find this a fascinating defensive idea, in its purest form and simplicity. The English GM anticipates a possible Nf7-d8. I was truly impressed by this calm way of defense, and embedded it in my book about defense: 'Unbeatable'. }
18. Ne6 Qe7
{ A very accurate move. Adams is prepared for repelling the invader with Nd8.   Afer  18...Nd8?  19.e5 !!  White vacates the great blockading square for his knight on e4 and creates an dangerous passed f-pawn.  fxe5  20.Nc5  following up with f6, would give White the edge.  20...Qf7  21.f6  when White got more than sufficient compensation. }
19. Bd4 Nd8
{ Unfortunately for us, we can't maintain our most dominant piece. } 20. Nxd8
Rxd8 21. fxg6 hxg6
{ By the counterattack on h2, White has no time to take on f6. } 22. h3
{ When matters have calmed down, your engine will likely assess this position as balanced. However, there lies a difficult technical task ahead for Adams because of his worse pawn structure. }
22... Bc5 23. Bxc5 Qxc5+ 24. Kh1 Rxd1 25. Qxd1
{ McShane kept his edge consisting of his superior pawn structure. Mickey has to make a tough decision now: how to handle both Qg4+, and Qxg6, as Rxf6? }
25... f5
{ The 'obstinate' engines have - unfortunately - always the final say. Adams should have played:   25...Kb8 !  a very difficult move to find, even for a world class player like Adams. The Black player should have monitored the positions arising where White is @@StartBracket@@after winning f6 and g6@@EndBracket@@ obtaining two connected passed pawns on g2 and h3.  26.Rxf6  Qe5  27.Rxg6  Qxb2  as there remain two heavy pieces on the board, McShane will think twice before he sends his g- and h-pawn forward. }
26. exf5 gxf5 27. Qf3
{ The flaws of 25... f5?, come to light. How should the pawn be protected? }
27... Rf8 28. c3
{ The strong move  28.Qa3 !!  was missed by the English GM. The ensuing rook ending is lost for Black.  28...Qxa3  29.bxa3  Kd7  30.Kh2  when all is set for g2-g4.  30...Ke6  31.g4 !  would have resulted in a very difficult @@StartBracket@@and likely lost@@EndBracket@@ ending for Adams, on the account of White's decisive far passed pawn. }
28... Qd5 29. Qxd5 cxd5 30. g4 { This pin becomes fatal for Black. } 30... Rh8
{ Averting the loss of a pawn, but the ensuing ending is very bad for Black. The g-pawn is hard to stop since Black's king is so far off and cut off. }
31. Rxf5 Rxh3+ 32. Kg2
{ The contours of the playscape become visible. The g-pawn is unstoppable as the Black king is cut off from the f-file. }
32... Rd3 33. g5
{ Without hesitation, the foot soldier is being directed forward. } 33... d4
34. g6
{ Adams comes @@StartBracket@@far@@EndBracket@@ too late with his counterplay. The g-pawn can't be stopped. }
34... Rd2+ 35. Rf2 dxc3 36. g7
{ The promotion can not be stopped, since after  36...Rd8  White plays  37.Rf8  winning the game. }
*

