4. Bxc6
{ Black can take back with either the b-pawn or d-pawn, but only the last move has gained popularity as after 4...bxc6 he faces a hard time completing his development.   4.Ba4  The main concept of Morphy's Defense materializes when White falls for the 'Noah's Ark Trap'. This happened in 1929 when Steiner got ambushed in his game against Capablanca, but the current elite grandmaster Nepomniachtchi was similarly caught in it in a recent online game.  4...d6  5.d4  b5  6.Bb3  exd4  7.Nxd4  Nxd4  8.Qxd4  c5!  All of a sudden, White's bishop is caught after c5-c4.  9.Qd5  threatening Qxf7+  Be6  10.Qc6+  The check will not help Black.  10...Bd7  11.Qd5  c4  0-1, @@StartBracket@@55@@EndBracket@@ Nepomniachtchi, I @@StartBracket@@2784@@EndBracket@@ - Demchenko, A @@StartBracket@@2641@@EndBracket@@ chess.com INT 2020 }
4... dxc6
{ The contours of the RLE position are there. White gave up his light-squared bishop and the bishop pair, leaving Black with doubled c-pawns and behind in development. White has many options here. Lasker's main choice was 5. d4, but 5. d3 and 5. Nc3 have also been tried, remaining flexible and not committing the king to g1 yet. }
5. O-O
{ The most ambitious move! White stays flexible, keeping open the options of: 1. d3 or d4, 2. whether the knight should be moved to d2, c3 or a3. The American world-class grandmaster Robert Byrne named 5.O-O is after the Dutch IM John Barendregt, who played this move a couple of times in the 60's. White has already castled while Black's pieces are all on the back rank. Moreover, Black must make an important choice as to how to protect his central pawn since White has renewed the threat of Nxe5 after castling. }
5... f6 6. d4 Bg4 7. c3
{ White's most well-known follow up here is 7. dxe5. Magnus Carlsen @@StartBracket@@who else?@@EndBracket@@ decreased my interest for this line. He defeated Kamsky in convincing style   7.dxe5  Qxd1  8.Rxd1  fxe5  9.Rd3  Bd6  10.Nbd2  Nf6  11.Nc4  O-O  12.Nfxe5  Be2  13.Re3  Bxc4  14.Nxc4  Ng4  15.Re2  Bxh2+  16.Kf1  Rae8  17.Nd2  Rd8  18.f3  Bg3  19.Kg1  Ne5  20.b3  Ng6  21.Nf1  Be5  when Black was winning material Kamsky, Gata @@StartBracket@@2741@@EndBracket@@ - Carlsen, Magnus @@StartBracket@@2862@@EndBracket@@ Sinquefield Cup 1st Saint Louis, 13.09.2013. However, this move maintains the central pawns and keeps the tension alive. The 'RLE-connoisseur' Azeri GM Guseinov played plenty of games here, with great success. }
7... Qe7
{ Another very plausible line for Black, with the obvious idea of castling long. }
8. dxe5
{ In order not to get pinned along the d-file, the time is right to take on e5. }
8... fxe5
{ Another reason of 8. dxe5 comes apparent. Black can no longer castle long. }
9. h3
{ Asking the bishop for his intentions meanwhile we grab space. In case Black maintains the pin, we can under certain circumstances try to win the e5-pawn after g2-g4. }
9... Bh5 10. Na3
{ As we have seen in so many lines, White moves his knight to c4. } 10... Nf6
11. Nc4 { Black should do something against Nxe5. } 11... Qe6
{ An interesting attempt of the Black player. For the sake of creating attacking chances for himself, he sacrifices a pawn. }
12. Ncxe5 Bd6
{ Black's compensation seems to be more than enough. However, White pulls a trump card from his sleeve. }
13. Qb3
{ Offering the exchange of queens, thereby reducing the tension on the knights. }
13... Qxb3
{ 13...Qe7  Black cannot avoid the exchange of queens, because of  14.Qxb7  Black has no time to take on e5.  14...O-O  15.Nxc6  again Black is kept busy, as his queen is under siege now he should @@StartBracket@@temporarily@@EndBracket@@ leave his attacking aspirations.  15...Qxe4  16.Re1  Once more, we don't give Black the space to attack our king.  16...Qd5  17.Qb3 !  After the exchange of queens, we remain material up. }
14. axb3 O-O 15. g4
{ White is slightly better here. The bishop retreat is not appealing for Black, so he undermines the e5-point. }
15... Rae8 16. gxh5
{ A stunning move would be  16.Ra5 !?  but hey, why wouldn't we make use of the half open a-file if we can.  16...c5  17.gxh5  Bxe5  18.Nxe5  Rxe5  19.f3  Setting up a block in the center. The direct result is that Black's pieces lack flexibilty.  19...Nxh5  20.b4  White is slightly better. }
16... Bxe5 17. Nxe5 Rxe5 18. f3
{ Like we have seen in the 16.Ra5-line, we set up a block in the center. The direct result is that Black's pieces lack flexibilty. }
18... Nxh5 19. Be3 Re6 20. Ra5 Rg6+
{ This perfectly sound move of Naroditsky, is causing him troubles in the ensuing part of the game. It shows us how fragile Black's position is.   20...Nf4  21.Kf2 !?  moving the king to e3. Please note that Black cannot take on h3 yet. }
21. Rg5 Rxg5+ 22. Bxg5
{ A recurring theme is the R&B vs. R&N ending. As we know, the bishop is the preferred sparring partner of the rook in these endings. }
22... h6 23. Be3 Rd8
{ Another logical move on Black's end, but it allows White to consolidate by improving his king's position. As a result, White is much better. }
24. Kf2
{ So, how should Black bring his pawns in motion? After all, his majority should - one way or the other - be used. }
24... Kf7
{ 24...b6  White can fix the pawns now, by  25.b4  using the doubled pawns in our favor: after Ra1 we will thankfully exploit the half open a-file. }
25. b4
{ White's vastly outnumbered pawns on the queenside got a hold on Black's majority. }
25... Rd7 26. Rg1 Nf6 27. Bd4
{ The bishop dominates the board. They say that knights need strongholds in the center..well.. the bishop doesn't mind either! }
27... Nh5 28. Ke3
{ The additional plus of Bd4: creating space for the king on e3. } 28... g5
{ The pawn is no longer under attack, but it can still be easily targeted. }
29. h4
{ The Black g5-pawn kept things together for Black as the g-file remained closed and the f- and e-pawn where blocked. Undermining this point, White is not far off from getting a passed pawn whereas the invasion of the White rook along the g-file is a matter of time. }
29... Kg6
{ Black cannot allow two connected passed pawns; therefore, ...gxh4 is to be rejected. }
30. hxg5 hxg5 31. Be5 { The threat of f3-f4 must be parried now. } 31... Kh6
32. f4
{ Showing understanding. Also this is a recurring topic in the RLE. White is liquidating to the ending, not fearing a draw in the rook ending because of his strong e-passer and the enemy's king being cut off. }
32... gxf4+ 33. Bxf4+ Kh7
{ 33...Nxf4  34.Kxf4  The resulting rook ending is a dead end for Black, especially now that the king is cut off, the e-pawn has free passage.  34...Rd2  35.Kf5  Rxb2  36.e5  Side by side wandering to e8.  36...b6  37.e6  Rf2+  38.Ke5  a5  39.e7  Re2+  40.Kf6  Threatening Rh1 mate.  40...Rf2+  41.Ke6  Re2+  42.Kd7  Time to resign for Black. }
34. Be5
{ Thank you Gadir, with this move you splendidly elucidate my previous comment, why the bishop is better than the knight in such endings. }
34... Re7 35. Bd4
{ Where should the Black knight move to? If you know the answer, please let me know on  in the comments. Because I have no clue. }
35... Re6 36. Rg5 Kh6 37. Rg8
{ Besides the horrible knight, please have a look at the deplorable state of the Black king, which is falling almost off the verge of the board. }
37... Kh7
{ Playing these passive king moves indicates that Black is on the slippery slope. }
38. Rb8
{ With Black's pieces far away, White is after the vulnerable queenside pawns. }
38... b5 39. Ra8 { Time to cash in the chips. } 39... Ng3
{ Sneakily trying to bring the knight into play. Will White dismiss this by taking on a6? }
40. Rh8+
{ Too bad for Black, White didn't. The knight is captured after  40...Kg6  41.Rg8+  . Illustrative about this game was the poor position of Black's king and the superior bishop over the knight. }
*

